text: a : peppery spice with citrusy fruit , somewhat leathery . a : clear golden yellow with a tight white head f : dry , with fruit ( apple/citrus ) and spice up front . o : good interpretation of saison . nice and dry with plenty of character . there 's something tangy tht decreases my overall enjoyment .  tingly in the nose which is common with sour ales but this is n't sour at all t. sweet with dried fruit , malty m. has a biting quality , a bit to carbonated .

the aroma is strong thick sweet and syrupy . including pine , alcohol , vanilla and oak . overall it 's very nice , i 'd like to see how it would do with another year or two to tame the hops down .  very astringent .
the aroma is great , extreamly fresh .  the mouth feel was hindered a bit , as the bottle had n't been sitting in my refrigerator long enough , the ale could have been a little more carbonated .

no head retention or lacing huge oaky , fruitty boozey nose , beautiful t : dryness , raisins , dates , & breadyness with a slight booze presence up front .  taste is light and airy , a tad sweetness is overpowered by barley and water . this stuff does n't dry out the mouth , which is good . then again , that 's because there is nothing in here except water and barley . i will take a soda anyday , but i guess i can see why people trying to quit alcohol but still like a cold `` beer '' here and there will spend money on it .

zero head retention & lacing s : smokeyness & toasty grain , pick up a lot peat & alder once really warm t : roasty & charred malt , dark chcolate & husky smokeyness up front .  its sucks to know that in a different format this could be so much more . body and carb is okay , but by this point i 'm already at the meh stage .

great looking beer .  this is an excellent pilsner . number three on my list , only behind konig and pilsner urquell . just as crisp and refreshing as both of those , but a little lighter in taste and body . very clean , top quality .

a - brilliant copper color with a finger of thick solid off white head .  a surprisingly great beer from a brewing giant . it could have been a little less punishing when guzzled , but hey it 's a dark beer and we are not dealing with coors light here . i think the beer is buitiful to look at , and is rather smooth . but the lable and beer fit perfectly ph

a - extremely dark brown body with a dark brown head to go along with it . the thick and frothy head started out at about 4 inches and ever so slowly faded down leaving a thick humocky topography .  mouthfeel is a little too carbonated and light but i still enjoyed the beer in-spite of those tow minor complaints .
clear dark ruby appearance . creamy , somewhat bubbly , beige head sits on top .  m/d : the mouthfeel is a tad low on this for my liking of an oud brune .
anyways , poured a dark golden body with a white head about three fingers wide . a very easy drinking beer .  the feel in my mouth was medium and it was a bit syrupy .

lighter and brighter looking than i expected , nelson poured without any `` redness '' i typically , and erroneously , associate with rye beers . a clear hay golden hue , with a beautiful cream white head ; excellent retention and lacing .  a watery texture and lighter body than i expected from the nose , with a moderate amount of carbonation .
smell is amazing . has a spicy fruity smell .  the palate is thin but ok .

smell is a rich dark chocolate with some dark roasted coffee . very sweet aroma . taste is more of a dry cocoa , but still chocolaty .  this beer has a lot of flavor for a light . too bad its not a good flavor ! nothing impressive at all here . i 'm not sure what they are putting in this beer but its not worth the 7.99 they are charging for a six pack . i would recommend pabst blue ribbion over this any day !

looks absolutely fantastic , deep impenetrable black body with coffee coloured head , aromas full of coffee and chocolate and heavy dark roast malts with some fruity notes and a little hop .  under carbonated .

smells heavy of cherries , very good smell . taste is just as heavy with the cherries .  the mouthfeel is a bit harsh with the 8.0 % alcohol , but i have found very few tripels that can hide the alcohol content .

nov 12th 08 this ale boasts a golden amber body that supports a proud white head . the apperiance is clear and the head leaves intricut lacing .  it it a bit on the carbonated side , so the mouthfeel is a bit more bland than i had expected .
very inviting , to say the least .  m - the mouth feel is spritzy and aggressive with a dry finish .
this brew pours an opaque black color . the head is large , and fluffy with a color of white speckled with tan .  the mouth fell was a little thin for stout .
wonderful mixed aroma with qualities of malt behind the wonderful saaz hops . this is a really nice beer .  the mouthfeel is thinner when compared with other stouts , merely decent .

the beer was poured into a champagne flute . appearance : this may be the singularly best looking beer i have ever seen in a glass . the head was very tall and proud with an off white coloration . the retention was perfect throughout the consumption of the beer . the carbonation was explosive rolling boiling bubbles .  the mouthfeel is quite thin , verging on watery .
aroma reminded me of strawberry shortcake , but more strongly of strawberry syrup from strawberry ice cream topping .  m - medium body , fair carb , etc .

nice clear copper color with a decent tan head , nice active carbonation , and nice sheets of lace .  smooth , medium body with a palate almost entirely made up of bitter , herbal hops ; perhaps trace notes of biscuity malt can be detected , but they are virtually non-existent . finish is long , dry , and bitter , and leaves you wanting more , which leads to a great level of drinkability , especially for a hophead .

served in a pilsner glass a : pours a deep mahogany color that looks thick . pours with very thick white head and leaves considerable lacing s : very sweet smelling brew possibly of cherries .  the only complaint i have is that the texture left much to be offered . overall i great beer .

no lacing was evident as i drank this aromatic ale . speaking of aroma , this ale wreaks of bourbon and vanilla with some burnt wood smokey notes to finish . close your eyes , or keep them open , and waft a smell and you 'd think you were sniffing a high ball . the flavor is bourbon upfront , charred wood , vanilla and brown sugar .  on my first stop on my michigan beer tour . the grand cru on tap was a very nice start to my tour . the first taste was wonderful , but , the flavor of the beer left my mouth looking for just alittle more .
a beautiful brown with red highlights and a tan head that lasts and sticks .  mouthfeel : low carbonation , light-medium body , slick texture . a bit flat all in all .

can holiday wine cellar escondido , ca a ( surprisingly ) better than average pour ! clear light goldenrod yellow with a large , persistent white head , and lots and lots of spiderweb lacing down the glass .  feel is kinda harsh .

the smell is probably the best part of this beer . sweet and herbal with a touch of honey , hazelnut , citrus of some kind . the finish is very dry . pretty cool beer .  it had a light feel on the palate with mild carbonation .
smell - pretty nice smelling . lots of blueberries as well as some malt .  mouthfeel - rather bubbly , fairly thin .

sugary sweet hoppy aroma . floral and fruity hop presence with strong peachy gummy candy elements and a sweet malt backing .  the feel is smooth , suprisingly light for a beer that seems so heavy . while i feel that this is one of north coast 's better efforts ... though none are really bad , i do wish that it had a bit more body .

a-pitch black , perfect darkness . burnt and bitter , with black licorice .  taste is more of the same ... some wild floral flavors , hints of citrus ... seems like the dominant flavors have switched from the citrus to the floral characteristics . i like it , for sure , but could use some balance . i 'm not a big fan of the bitter taste left in the mouth ... but it 's still plenty drinkable . a definitely above-average ale , but not the best .
nice hop aroma right off the bat . very piney and resiney .  carbonation is a little much in my opinion and cuts down on the smooth/velvety texture .
s - warm citrus and honey . grapefruit . t - grapefruit , seedless rye bread .  m- the weakness of the beer - moderately light body feels a little weak to me . light carbonation does n't add much .

poured a one finger white head that had good retention and lacing . the beer is a nice amber-orange color and is very clear .  had one warm just to see what the flavors were really like , and blllaaahhhh corn up the ying yang ! honestly , if youre going for the light beer on a budget , i 'd go with bud light just because it has no flavor , this is like a bad , adjunct-y lager that 's been in storage for a year . i 'm just wonder if miller has some weird process that makes their beer taste stale , because i notice the exact same thing in mgd , yet not high life , maybe its just the filterization . anyways , about twice as yellow , piss looking as a heineken , yet actually produces a decent mouthful . and the smell seems to get better when there is less of it , so the finish is actually pretty satisfying . overall , decent for why people drink it , but for a light beer , i 'd go with amstel , even for its price .
excellent look - copper color with a big slightly off-white head that leaves excellent lacing . looks as good as a rye beer can .  palate : medium body and higher end carbonation .
pours deep red , with some f*ing amazing head on it .  the mouthfeel is just average . also , carbonation is lacking enough to make this feel sticky .

frickin ' a beautiful . deep and black , medium head of nice and tight dark tan bubbles . no effort required to get it and even going vigorously on the pour it seems like there 's not a crazy amount of head . beautiful .  i picked this lager over the ale 's offered , due to the miserable heat wave here in no . cal . it was an appropriate choice . saaz hops seemed to be prominent with good malt base . a nice refreshing beer . nothing spectacular but very acceptable when in the mood for this style .

a great smelling though ultimately dull witbier .  m-its a little undercarbonated but the balance of the sweetness with the malt and subtle hops make for a relitivly complex october beer . d-easy to drink and very nice to have this time of year , easy to session .

the beer pours a nice orange color , and an aggressive pour yields an initially massive off white head , that fades to a one finger height before lingering . an impressive amount of lacing in generated , almost enough to garner a 5 .  i did notice after a while that it has been pulled from tap that it acquires a lack of a better word , a buttery taste that really dos n't go good with anything . i do like this beer and i 'm not bashing it . the buttery taste in my opinion did not take effect until thirty or so minutes after pour . i do keep some in my fridge . i have shiner before to make burgers with , which turned out great . good beer for beer lovers .
pours dark amber with a large honeycomb coloured head and lots of lacing .  the body becomes thin on the mid palate and that 's my primary complaint .

| 8.0 % abv | 2011 brewer : shmaltz brewing company ( he'brew ) style : american strong ale glass : crystal mug appearance : dazzling orange-amber under light , with a foamy , frothy head .  the mouthfeel is a bit too watery and perhaps a bit chalky .
s- malt . candied sweetness . chocolate with a touch of vanilla .  i wish the carbonation was a little more noticeable in the mouth .

s : the smell is quite amazing and complex in my opinion . there are some light hops initially noticed . overall , it is very pleasant . t : after the very satisfying smell , the taste was sort of a let down .  m - light body , with a carbonation level that is probably too sharp for the style .

crystal clear red-orange body , covered by a huge frothy irish linen colored head , rocky top which rose above the rim . very good lacing . a very vague , almost non-existent aroma , some bread baked much earlier in the day .  the carbonation is heavy and it adds harshness to the palate . medium-full body .

pours a superb color for a `` blueberry stout . really cool stuff . the head does dissapate a little too quickly , but overall this one looks great .  way too thin in the mouthfeel category , however .

brilliant color ! poured fairly rough and produced a solid one-and-a-half-finger head that 's dense and creamy like whipped topping . good retention that went down to a rich layer and left thick patches of lacing .  mouthfeel was moderate , not super heavy or light .
s : bourbon and caramel/toffee smell . t : reminds me of a barleywine with a bourbon shot dropped it in .  the body is pretty light though and clean .
pours a beautiful burnt sunset orange with crystal clarity , finger of foamy head has good retention .  mouthfeel is thin for a stout imo , but not bad .

looks nearly black with about a 3/8 '' caramel colored head from a vigorous pour .  nice chewy mouthfeel , but significantly under-carbonated . the only thing it lacks is carbonation and a decent head .

reviewed 11/21/2009 ( bottle , goblet glass , 53degf , office @ computer after dinner ) : pours a strong purplish red color body , with an average sized dark pink head , lasting .  a rather thin aqueous body with less carbonation than expected , but otherwise nothing wrong with this brew .

its pale golden liquid is filled with lively bubbles cascading to the the bright long lasting white head .  as for the go-down : thin & lightly carbonated , not aggressive but not annoying either & no aftertaste .

the nose is bursting with scents of fresh-squeezed oranges , pineapple , guava . good full-bodied ipa with plenty of carbonation zip . i expected more of a fruity-tasting ipa , but this one is herbal , earthy , and spicy .  m : surprisingly on the more carbonated side with a slight fizzy mouthfeel .

s - smelled like delicious spiced pumpkin pie with clove and spiced apple undertones . this is an excellent beer .  m : sharp carbonation is pretty overpowering , and any refreshing aspects of the smell and taste are lost .

leaves a frothy , massive head of light tan large sized bubbles . opaque and very cloudy dark brown color . good lacing .  out of all of the blueberry beers i have had i would have to say this is probably my favorite . very fruity with a somewhat dry finish to it . the blueberries are definitely the star of the show . overall this is a very drinkable beer and makes a great summer brew .

black with a glorious creamy beige head with great retention and lacing .  bought this over a month to two months a go and decided to give it a go . it is an ipa so it does have a nice bright orange to copper color . the taste and the smell are sweet and fruity , the only bad thing i have to to say about it , is the taste of tea is very lacking . i cant pick it up but , other than that i wish that stone , ishii and baird made this more as a yearly offering , cause its really good

biggish , crusty , light tan head leaves lots of hard , sticky lacing . very pretty .  as readily available as bud , and a whole lot better . a great fall-back session brew , which is good with a meal , or having several at a baseball game .

pours a clear yellow with tons of head and lots of lacing . not typically a fan of the pale yellow look , but this one had an amazing head and great retention .  mouthfeel : the body is oddly thin , and crisp .
great aroma , hope there is more of this in the palate . pretty decent .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and somewhat tannic , but the overall effect is quite interesting .

aroma is very pleasant and soft sweetish malt with mild floral hops , hints of pine , slight citrus , it is a wonderful combination , i spent some time just enjoying the aroma . taste is a bit harsh grassy and sligthly lemony hops ; unfortunately the taste is soon gone and just pleasant and rather long lasting bittery aftertaste remains .  went down smooth with no after taste . not bad , but could include a few more hops to round out the beer . i would recommend even without . it was very good between 45 and 55 degrees .
pours an opaque black with tight tan head .  mouthfeel : a little watery , but not terrible .

poured out of a 16.9 oz bottle into a tulip style glass . i held it up to the sun on my patio and admired it for a few seconds . ( cue music ) there were two inches of white head that led to a nice white cap that never dissipated .  medium thin body manages a bit of creaminess .

s sweet and complex on the nose . honey , orange zest , and chinese 5-spice . touch of clean alcohol and fresh bread . light malt character on the backend coddles a soft alcohol note . the finish carries a rolling bitterness , and the malt that balanced the ending alcohol note slowly fades to give way to a brighter boozyness .  mouthfeel , i would like it have been a bit more carbonated , but it did fine .
smell is fantastic ( i love hops ) .  the mouthfeel is fairly overcarbonated and dry .

really thick almond colored brew , very opaque ; leaves a huge head with thick lacing as it 's poured into a glass .  i 've always liked this beer , and if they beefed up the abv and gave it a little more body , it would be the perfect porter . why grant 's beers share these characteristics i do n't know , but if they ever did beef 'em up a little , they could truly be a contender .

pours out a thickly hazed golden-orange . gigantic , solid off-white head . consistancy and appearance of cotton candy . great looking , but lacking elsewhere .  it was creamy with an average carbonation level and also average alcoholic strength ( 6.0 % abv ) . overall : awful .
the white head is huge and pillowy and leaves wonderful fuzzy navel lacing .  a bit thin , but a very good stout flavor develops in the mouth . i 'd have preferred a bit fuller body .
pours a deliciously cloudy , rich red with a nice thick & dark tan head .  nicely carbonated .

lots of small bubbles , highly carbonated s- big lemon , hay , banana , citrus , and funky notes t- this is super bitter , lots of sulfur/salty qualities on the finish . tons of nondescript bitterness , if only the taste matched the aroma .  the carbonation is nice throughout . thinner than expected also .

smells and tastes of molasses , raisins , brown sugar and bourbon soaked oak barrels . very pungent and boozy in the nose and finish as well .  initial taste of a sparkling mouthfeel with a puckering sour cherries that coat the mouth incredabily . the palate duration is average . medium body .

consumed 2 days later a : poured a deep maroon color with good carbonation and a dirty white head s : caramel .  tart and dry feel , but not overly so . lower carbonation detracts a little , really the only flaw in my mind .

pours pitch black like guinness . smells extremely strong of caramel and a hint of mint ( i 'm thinking of mint chocolate chip ice cream ) .  mouthfeel : surprisingly thin body , full carbonation , fairly thick coat after the swallow .
a - poured completely ink black . appears thick and viscous . a small amount of light brown head formed and receded quickly .  too much carbonation for this style ( -1.0 ) .

pours a cloudy medium orange amber with a nice 2 finger white head that very slowly melts to a craggy , very sticky white lacing .  if i had to log a complaint , it would be that this stout is too thin and less of a cream offering . however , it is full of flavor and easy to drink despite being 6.5 % abv .

the smell is as excepted sweet and more sweet . hints of flowers and something a bit citrusy . wow ! the taste is sooo much bigger than the smell and really does n't do it justice .  m : flat , slick , and that 's it . not quite watery , but pretty close .
exceptional appearance .  it went down smooth with a little bite in the after taste .

pours to a brilliantly clear pale golden , forming a tall soapy `` pure as the blown snow '' white , with excellent retention and lacing . great looking brew .  this is very malty at the opening with a twinge of caramel . upon downing it , the taste resembles a very dark beer . very malty with heavy caramel presence that makes it a bit sweet . it also gives a bitter character that mellows into a sweetened deal . i 'll have to try it from the mug in the near future . it may turn out differently due to more carbonization released , making it less bitter , dare i venture to say . but , straight from the bottle , it is easier to imbibe if you 're used to dark , bitter ales .
pours into a pint glass a translucent straw yellow with a billowing white head and and amazing lacing that last throughout the drink .  light feel with lots of carbonation .

s - smell is phenomenal . right after you uncap it you 're hit with cinnamon and nutmeg and plenty of pumpkin .  mouthfeel is a little bit stingy , but from the carbonation and not the alcohol , otherwise the liquid is the right viscosity and creams up ok on the tongue .

a - hazy , orangish yellow body topped by a huge , rocky head with the most spectacular retention i have ever seen .  m. a little too sticky , it feels syrupy , but without a sweeter taste it fells a little off .

the smell is very strong of nutmeg , cinnamon , pumpkin . this is an excellent pumpkin ale . the scent is so strong you will convince yourself that a pumpkin pie is baking nearby .  wow this has to be one of the worst ideas in beer history . trying to cross a pale ale with a belgian and what you got is something that is a distant cousin to both . instead of leveraging the style 's strengths this beer doubles down on their worst attributes . a very hoppy tatse that fights like a strong ale . not a fun beer and a true shame that it might discredit weyerbacher 's other great beers .

it smells like a beuatiful blend of the ng belgian red cherry aspect and a very nice gueze . well done .  the mouthfeel of the beer was , like most porter and ale styles , very average . however , the mouthfeel did not detract from the overall feel of the beer .
bottle in 16oz.sierra nevada glass leaves a beautiful 3/4 inch head . a-tremendous color , nice floaties , great lacing on the glass .  m - slightly thin and sweet .

this beer poured slow , and was pitch black in color . the head was medium sized , but brown , with small bubbles . looked beautiful !  m/d - mouthfeel is nothing special , the steely hop bite takes a bit away .

a light orangey hue , spewing forth grapefruit and mango goodness with a slight bit of malt . a nice bitter , touch of sweetness and plenty of citrus fruit . pretty tasty , nothing to go too wild over , but enjoyable nonetheless .  ambrosial start , lots of malt , the top skimpy in feel with the finish having a delightful hop spicy bite , the carbonation moderate and the aftertaste droughty and long lasting .

black hole is the visual m.o . the head is mammoth and very interesting . dark mocha color around the bottom near the liquid and a lighter tan color up top . very cool .  rich flavor in a thin body -- well not that thin , but certainly less than most bocks ( not to mention doppels ) .

pours a beautiful dark orange/copper color with a good head retention and lacing . i love the color of this beer .  perfect carbonation but that thin , light mouthfeel is where this beer falls a little flat .

pours a dark brown colour with a frothy thick tan head .  not sure if our north american brethren appreciate this but this is , as far as i can tell the first fairly widely available american style ipa brewed in the uk . the american craft brewing industry which has been accused of being derivative is really starting to influence europe which is great . i am all for my uk brewing industry but i do get a little board of the vast variety of often samey real ale bitters populating manypubs . we definitely have a shortage of hopheads brewing in the uk ! and before anyone shoots me down , greene king ipa is not an ipa ! ! !

although very skunky it smells alot like pot which to me is an awesome characteristic . i am curious if the fermentation process of beck 's involves any hemp but it seem 's unprobable .  flavor is absolutely nothing like an oud bruin .
huge head , somewhat lasting , good lacing , smallish bubbles .  m - medium/light body with little carbonation good with spicy food .

the second the cap is popped , the aromas come rushing out and literally fill the room . it smells like i 'm chopping up fresh oranges and pineapples as i pour this beer ; remarkable ! this beer takes me longer to finish than most dipas this drinkable because i stop to sniff this beer before every sip ! it is not exceptionally bitter but a rather sweet and citrusy ipa . there is n't a lot of malt getting in the way of the hops , hops , hops . a superbly drinkable dipa .  less fizzy than anticipated in the mouth .

pours out an opaque black with shimmering brown at the edge of the glass . thick , creamy , off-white head and thick lacing as well .  had this during o'briens wet hop festival . pours clear orange with a white ring of bubbles . lots of caramel with some tropical hops in the nose . kind of like a fruitcake . earthy , yet citrusy in the taste . bit sweeter than your normal ipa . grapefruit and blood orange . good stuff .
nothing wrong with the way it looks . clear and golden , great head .  the mouthfeel , i was not so impressed with .

appearance - nice copper color , cream colored head holds at a solid cap and laces quite well .  i found that the beer smelled and tasted rather skunky , unlike most other beers that i had tasted and was deeply disappointed by it . it felt ok in the mouth and looked very nice in its green bottle but was not worth my time .
a : this pours a lovely cloudy golden/orange color . a huge foamy head forms and leaves tons of sticky lace down my snifter .  heavy hops , but not totally unbalanced . very quenching .

11.2 oz bottle poured into duvel tulip a : perfect . billowing tan head barely contained in this glass . settles to leave full layer of fine tan lacing . as you sip the soft foam coats the side of the glass in sheets not patches .  m - not as thick as i 'd like it to taste considering how rich the smell is . d - very drinkable , with the lighter mouthfeel it 's easier to forget how much you 've had .

great nose . the taste is n't quite as solid with a less dominant sweetness than the aroma . the nose had me excited , but the taste did n't quite deliver and the mouthfeel was definitely a let down .  thanks to ncvbc for this great extra best by 12/31/08 bottle poured into my sniffer produced a good fingers worth of tan head that turns into a ring of lace around the glass on top of a jet black body aromas of toasted malts , coffee and chocolate with a slight funk ( i 'm glad i am not the only one to pick it up i though my nose was going ) earthiness , sweat malts , light chocolate , molasses good balance of flavors the only real complaint is it is a little thin for a stout good drinkability i could drink a few of these a night easy .

poured into a tulip . the beer pours black with a huge tan head at least three fingers . great retention leaving some sticky lace behind .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with likely carbonation . that , and the over carbonated pour make this beer a something i would not recommend .

produced a huge rocky head that lasts & lasts and when subsides leaves half its mass on the side of the glass ( i did n't mean for that to rhyme , it just worked out that way . ) the aroma is ok , its floral like perfume but not particularly citrusy or piney or any of those typically american hop descriptors .  m : mouthfeel is decent , goes down reasonable smooth even with the slight burning sensation .
pours a nice bright yellow orange with a massive , almost overflowing white head . head sticks around indefinitely as bubbles continually rise in an energetic fashion .  it was a little thin .

has to be one of the better looking beers i have ever poured . university of texas , burnt orange color and beautiful head that was reminiscent of vanilla ice cream on top .  hate to say it , but the bottle/case i have is absolutely awful . other than a hint of coriander spice all i got was an overwelming sourness that made this one of the few i had to pour down the drain . they obviously put wayyy too much orange peel in their mix . if you can get past the sourness it is par for a wit bier course . i 'm hoping this was a bad/expired batch because ... .as far as mill street goes imo , stick to the coffee porter ...

the smell is very good , nice and spicy in a way that is concentrated without being overly intense .  very pleasant indeed . great hop character . this is a fairly balanced ipa . hard to say , it might just be because this particular bottle is more on the room temp side , but i would like more effervescence . a good beer all in all . i will be sure to drink it again , only a little colder and faster . more drinking , less typing ... .
huge deep malty scents , with lots of caramel and toffee and a nixe bit of earthiness , as well .  could use both more body and carbonation .

very strong smells of pineapple and pirate beers waft away from the glass . there is caramel , yeast and citrus along with the sea , like the belgian pirate-themed beers i have tried . cold weather seems to encourage the brewing gene ... slainte .  mouthfeel is pretty good , but a little on the watery side for a chocolate/dessert beer . with the abv at 6 % and the body a little thinner than other chocolate stouts , one could have a couple of these in one night .

the smell is fruity and funky sweet . tons going on here in addition to the funkiness of the brett .  there 's a bit of a hop presence in the finish as a lingering bitterness runs along the side of the tongue . finishes pretty clean , with a little lingering of the hops present , but otherwise very dry . a very drinkable , light beer . perhaps more of a hop presence than other beers like this that i 've had .

the nose was sweet , dominated by roasted malts , chocolate , treacle and burnt toffee , very pleasant indeed .  the flavor too is ever so slight wine barrel aging with a weird and awkward type sour . it 's really off putting . this barrel aging was awful . this beer is weak and severely overrated . it was awful both times .
one of the best smelling beers i have tried .  m - ok and average .
one thing of note on this beer is its beautiful appearence , dark caramel coloring , and nice thick head .  m - lots of carbonation maybe bordering on too much .

a - pours a thick 2 fingers of tan head that sticks around for quite some time .  5/5 m : medium body and smooth . the lighter body makes it sit not-too-heavy , and it would be easy to partake of a few of these on a cold night .

pours a deep , opaque mahogany , almost black . there 's a 3-finger cafe au lait head with a moderate amount of layered lacing .  the carbonation is moderate high . i think it is a bit high for the style but the carbonation does not take anything away from the beer .

very sexy . s - great smell , definitely get a heavy does of burnt chocolate , some roasted coffee and other malts . great example of roasted scents . i would gauge that there was a spectacular effort put into tempering this brew to get these scents from the malts . i like sours but certainly not mixed with this style . very bitter as you will note from almost every review but this one had an almost sour milk character that turned me off during my dinner which was centered around beef .  the first time i had this beer , i distinctly remember it being among the worst i had ever had . apparently my ba colleagues disagree , so i 'm giving it another try . there is some faint grassy hops , but this beer is mostly about the malt character . overall , this is way better than i remember . i might have to make this a regular part of my beer fridge ! or perhaps they had n't figured things out when the brewery was just getting started . glad that there 's another quality beer in e-town .
brilliant light gold with a solid finger and a half of tight foam . excellent retention .  m : medium viscosity , acidic early and slightly syrupy on the palate , with moderate carbonation .
river horse special ale esb pours a deep cloudy gold with a massive pillowy head that took up half the glass .  medium-bodied , maybe just a little bit thin .
a- deep black with a giant tan head . retention is awsome and it laces down the entire glass .  mouthfeel : hoppy and rough , but a bit fuzzy .

my beer poured a dark , murky , opaque mahogany color with a gigantic , creamy tan head that took forever to fade and leaves chunky lacing down the side . my foam looks like a root beer float it is so solid and creamy looking .  mouthfeel : pretty thick and a little syrupy . i 'd actually like a little more carbonation .
pours a fluffy/clingy finger and a half light tan head over a crystal clear dark rust brownish liquid .  small bubbles , slightly thin .
smells very nice . very peppery with spicy yeast , bananas and pineapple .  i think if the mouthfeel was better it would have made a world of difference imo .

appearance : dark for an ipa . really nice lacing smell : bready malts cover the hop aroma which leads to a balanced ipa taste : as i smelled .  cons : the low carbonation level does hurt many factors of the beer , but it is such an exquisitely brewed offering , it 's only a minor issue .

reminded me of candied yams on thanksgiving . almost no hops were detectable and the alcohol was hidden nicely . t : first sip was scrumptious , showcasing much of what i just smelled . unfortunately , as the drinks went by , so did the complexity .  somewhat smooth feel , moderate-medium body for amber , but still feels a little thin .

the smell is a big whack of fresh sweet raspberries . damn , the taste does not live up to the pleasant smell . the alcohol burn is way too strong and blurs out the other flavors that hopelessly tries to emerge .  m : somewhat thick , bread-y . but smooth .
a tall , tan , thick head that lasts .  m - i did n't think the mouthfeel enhanced this brew . too softly carbonated ; not flat , just a bit wimpy .

s - wow , what a blast of aromas : floral notes , pine and citrus smack you in the face . t - it tasted of spicy , piney hops with a sweet , burnt toast maltiness . it is extremely hoppy and fairly easy drinking considering the high abv .  the mouthfeel is a little off , too light and thin .
clean and very good .  m - a bit high on carbonation and thin in body .
a : yellow , straw hues , slightly hazy , enormous whipped meringue head , long lasting retention , nice lacing .  the mouthfeel is thiner but still good .

pours a dark dark brown black sprouting a fluffy sculptured light cream tan color head with microscopic tightly knit bubbles . this beer produces a curious industrial like nose about itits not particularly robust , but to me the low level background radiation is like some synthetic yet curiously copasetic waft stealthily sneaking in upon my nostrils.. the flavor is predominantly malt .  mouthfeel is slightly thin for the style or maybe just thin for how much is going on there ... .like you are expecting more of a stout mouthfeel .

bottle : poured a bright golden color lager with a medium size foamy head with good retention and some great lacing .  the only knock here is that it was a little thin . m = is it possible to be creamy and watery at the same time ?

the nose piques my interest in this brew as the aroma is highly reminiscent of a belgian triple with strong esters of alcohol , yeast , and caramelized sugar . entry is muted until the midtaste takes over by blanketing the tongue with a thick coating of honey . my numbers reflect my overall impression of this brew ... nice appearance , great nose , overpowering honey midtaste & finish .  under carbonated and somewhat thin bodied , there is a coffee flavored finish that is truly amazing .

it 's hard to make a stout i dont enjoy but i am not so sure about this one . the color is most excellent ( pure pitch black ) and it poured with a nice head but unfiortunately it did n't last and left very little lace on the glass .  trying to think of a sweet red wine , not one i can place , but its defintely tannic , bitter and sweet ... the taste is super interesting , not say its good , but interesting . chocolate wine comes to mine , light feel though . what i do know is that 8 months is too long as it totally changes the beer into something new losing almost all stout character .
d : nice big i.p.a. , best smelling i have had yet , very flavorful and the malt has been kept in check and the hops can come right through .  body is very thin for a dipa , medium carbonation .

fairly strong aroma and inviting . t : definitely citrus forward , although the flavors are a bit more muted than the nose lead me to believe .  m : mouthfeel was alright , moderately carbonated and a medium body . nothing too special .

a : pours a bright yellow-orange , cloudy to the point of opaque but with some visible carbonation ; has the usual billowy , long-lasting head of dense white foam which settles to a healthy cap and leaves loads of frothy lacing .  m - very thin body , decent mouthfeel , but not great for the style .

poured a nice golden color with a dense rocky head pronounced piney and citrusy aroma , along with an earthy spice to it . huge hop bouquet . this beer seemed a little thin and light bodied for an ipa .  blue moon gran cru is a great choice for all blue moon fans . tastes similar to blue moon , but with a much bolder taste . its a shame its a limited edition brew , and it was quite pricey as well , but somehting worthy to pick up once to try . appearance : it was the golden color of blue moon , but appered to be unfiltered , but there was much more sediment then most unfiltered beers smell : not a bad smell , but nothing speical either taste : great taste , similar to blue moon , but much stronger , what is there not to love about that
this smells delicious , but the overwhelming tart cherry became a turn off for me .  m - it 's a bit thin for the style .

the smell of this brew is grassy with some minor inclusion of earth and peppery notes . a faint note of funky cheese blends with some vinous aspect of white grape skins . fairly decent across the board but on a day like this , it paled in comparison to some of the other geuze offerings sampled .  m - nothing special . just a regular lager thing .
great smelling brew ! taste is of funky , pungent malts , dark fruits again , plenty of yeast , spices .  m : a bit light in the mouth , but it kind of coats your mouth as well .

the appearance was a perfect deep color with a incredible head .  feels quite creamy at first , almost in a draft-stout kind of way , which struck me as odd . would rather it be crisper and a bit more carbonated , though .

appearance : nice easy lacing with a light head , lively , golden color .  i know some ba 's knock this onw because its not rare or amazing but i love it . if i am in a bar that i do n't think has a lot to choose from sam adams is the first word out of my mouth . its not too expensive and tastes good for what you pay .

a : a much darker brown than most brown ales . poured a thick creamy espresso colored head with good carbonation showing .  m - decent body with a bit more carbonation than i 'd like from this style .

nose is `` oh my fucking god '' chocolate . this smells like a combination of the greatest cup of pure milk chocolate , chocolate milk or hot chocolate with touches of espresso , coffee , dark burnt coffee beans and pure vanilla beans .  the body was light and there was not enough carbonation .

2008 version pours a deep , rich-looking mahogany brown body . hazy . off-white , foamy head slowly fades with nice lacing . good looking smells up front of alcohol and hops .  mouthfeel : medium and semi-smooth . bottom line : this is one of the most bland beers i 've ever had .

enormous thick and lasting beige head , colour is very dark brown , cloudy .  i am starting to view the boston beer co. as a-b or miller taking a stab at the craft market but still wanting to appease the masses rather than being strict to beer styles . a big dissapointment for an apa

hints of orange and lemon dance around the intense aged oak notes , giving this beer an amazingly original and interestingly complex nose . wow . flavor is much as would be expected after the nose . sweetness rivals the heftiest of wheatwine honey-sweetness you 've experienced .  slight hint of the hop flower but the malt dominates , sweet , crisp , fresh and pleasing to the senses with the start lightly sweet , satisfactory malt presence , and top light to middling in feel . this is a style where i like the lighter body , as it lets the flavoring hops shine through , quite quaffable , a damn fine session beer me thinks , and i thank royalt for this bottle .

a - a nice looking beer with a dark brown color reminiscent of a good black coffee or coke . head was a good two fingered tan froth , that retained quite well .  on the thin side , and i dont get much carbonation .

a- pours a light hazed golden yellow color . two finger white head shows medium retention . long webs of lace are all over my glass .  the taste is a bit light for a dunkel but definitely not as light as a typical hefewiezen . there is a malty undertone that one would expect with this type of beer . honestly , i 'm not sure why this beer is n't getting better reviews , i had a weihenstephan dunkel after it and it stood up quite well .
the humble brown has rarely looked so good .  lighter mouthfeel than expected . d - full flavor and light mouthfeel .
nice lacing and strong retention . pretty !  crisp taste - not heavy as expected ... hints of smokey , woody flavors - has the appeal of a coffee porter ... mouthfeel is average .

s-one of the best smelling beers of the tasting , lots of cinnamon with pumpkin and some nutmeg .  s - some grassy hops paired with caramel malt t - slight hop bitterness resolving into some serious roasty malt , but then it 's all gone fairly quickly with just a hint of woody bitterness m - quite light with just a hint of carbonation on the back of the tongue ; the slight bitterness endures for a whlie d - quick drinkable , though the excessive roasty malt will probably get in the way ; little to no alcohol warmth nice drink ; did n't expect it to be as dark as it is - listed as an american porter , but it 's almost a supercharged brown ale .

very nice . t : initial attack is pleasant , pure coffee , but then it turns quite bitter , but not in a hoppy way , more of an unpleasant burnt coffee way .  m full but not as full as i thought that it might be .

- served at cellar temperature appearance : sort of hazy ( unfiltered beer ) golden color with orange highlights . the head is off white and bubbly , like a champagne . cakey top part of the head and lots of sticky lace left on the sides of the glass .  feels thin .
pours a beautiful light honey color , having little to no head kept it from getting a better score .  mouthfeel : i 'm a bit disappointed by the mouthfeel .

allspice cinnamon and nutmeg all very strong a beautiful smelling ! t-the spices hit upfront with an impressive strength .  the head vanished quickly , but the carbonation level remained high . the aroma was overwhelming sour cherries ... mouthwatering sweet aroma that shows a huge proportion of cherries used in this brew . definitely on the sugary sweeter cherry beer side .
pours brown with ruby hints . there are two healthy fingers of head ( boy , is this a live beer ) and the retention and lacing are top notch .  mouthfeel is fullbodied , and slightly cloying .

huge bubbly head .  i think i 'm a bit parial to this beer for 2 reasons . it 's not by any means a `` specialty '' beer , it 's your typical lager and since it 's been around since before any of us were born it 's got a nostalgic feel . excellent beer in my books , average for most .

s - sweet fruit and malt smell with some alcohol .  with the name , you would think that this is an amber with english hops , but the banana fruitiness dominates any other flavors , even the hops disappears under the bananas . this is the mystery of rhodell 's , how can mark produce such great dipas , ipas , imperial stouts , barley wines , german style ales and lagers , but when it comes to scottish ales or amber/red ales , they all have this same . stupid , banana phenol , making them undrinkable . i dont get it .

great clarity , very active , amber color , with a finger of bubbly off white head that fades gradually .  flavor is more of the same with enough body to keep the brew honest . good mix of sweet and bitter and a weaker mouthfeel that allows for more on a warm summer day .

a : pours a one finger head of amazing cream , brilliant thickness , and incredible retention ( over six minutes before i could n't wait any longer ) for the style . incredibly appealing .  yack ! i 've had this lots over the years , but this time it got a major problem with butterscotch . aroma smacks me down wth that butterscotch - ugh . but , somewhere in there is some malt and a little chocolate , good malt . flavor is butterscotch - blaaahh . ca n't finish it . draft lines are clean here too . no more , pleeeeze
pours a dark black color with a large tan head , fades slowly and leaves lots of lacing on the glass .  m-medium bodied with slightly more carbonation than i prefer in a porter .

16 ounce can , best by sept. 29 , 2011 . pours extremely hazy orange amber color with a 1 finger fairly dense off white head with good retention that reduces to a thin lacing cap that lasts .  ) m. ok mouthfeel .

a : i love the look of this beer : extremely dark brown with a huge tight foam head .  mouth feel is thin pretty characteristic of bbc 's beers which makes this a really drinkable session stout with a lot of flavor .

22 oz bottle poured into imperial pint glass a - pours a near black opaqueness with a large 2 inch tan colored head . a good looking beer .  t & m : for a doppelbock a little thinner bodied than is usually expected .

a : clear copper , fluffy white head , good retention and lace .  mouthfeel - this seems a bit watery for my liking , and a bit light too , it does n't take away from the beer too much though luckily , still great . the carbonation seems pretty good , maybe a bit overcarbonated .

heavily hopped with three different american hop varieties , the hop aroma and flavor are citrus-like and pungent . very strong hop aroma - primarily cascade hops , so this e.s.b . 's aroma reminds me of a dry-hopped pale ale in the pacific northwest style . overall , a satisfying ale - not exactly true to its style , but very good nonetheless .  the taste is ok. it seems a little flat coming out of the can compared to the tap . nice clean finish , no lingering aftertaste . definiteley a session beer if drinking from the tap .

on-tap at beachwood bbq , on to the beer : the head retention is great on top this coal black beer . great , thick lacing sticks to the glass .  mouf & gt ; nice , nothing special drinkability & gt ; sure thing

the beer poured into the glass a brilliant clear gold with a thick , dense white head , te head retained well , and when it did recede it left a chunky lace on the side of the glass . a stream of champagne bubbles rise from the bottom , a testament to the carbonation of the bottle conditioned beer .  this is an enjoyable , smooth but tasty strong polish lager . the aroma is fresh , toasty sweet bread , hint of lemon , pine , and rather nice . it has a bit of a czech lager taste to it and the alcohol is essentially unnoticeable . the taste is clearly alcholic , but very smoothly so , with nothing rough opr unpleasant . it has a light caramel quality , bread , and nice , warm spiciness , it 's a bit rasiniy , sweet and spicy with a light bitterness coming to the fore in the finish . it does not taste quite as strong as it is .

poured into a tall hobgoblin tumbler , there is a huge billowing light tan head . very impressive presentation .  in the glass , the elderberry dominates . the taste just off , sour in a nasty way , more like rotten fruit than any sort of pleasant tartness which might be expected from the berries . we gave this a decent try to see if it would get better , but in the end just could n't drink it .

poured out of its short and stubby white painted 11.2oz bottle into a tulip glass . body is dark brown with a monsterous head with great retention that produced lacing throughout the duration of the drink .  this beer tastes like candy hearts mixed with medicine . it smells like sour bubblegum or something to that effect . coloring is actually pink.. which is unusual . definitely trying to appeal to females with the label , but even as a female.. i thought it was gross . that 's all i 'm going to say .

smell : strong spice and citrus , bubble gum taste/mouthfeel : thin but refreshing , banana , spicy hops this witbier was very good . i think the appearance of the beer itself lacks a little but the smell and taste makes up for it .  the largest macro beer in the country is very disappointing . the feel of this beer is somewhat thin but i liked the bock feel that it had .
pours a two finger cream head that fades slowly leaving a good lace . nice crystal clear ruby/amber color .  m : the body is light but sugary and grainy with a moderate carbonation .

2011 bottle poured into a tulip glass . a - an inch of dense cream-colored foam sits atop a beautiful ruby colored ale .  mouth feel was pretty average , smooth , not very complex so i expected a little more from it in that department .
s : crisp aroma with strong malt presence and hints of flowery hoppiness .  seems a bit thin , with very soft carbonation .

aroma is pungent with grapefruit , sharp citric hops , with cloaked , faint suggestions of oranges , apples , and toasty grains .  i feel that it felt a little light on the tongue after it went down .
aroma is wonderful . incredibly intense malt tones and a nice sweetness detected .  m - the mouthfeel is a little light , with little carbonation .
positives : great aroma of sweet chocolate .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with low yet sharp carbonation .
opaque amber-brown pour with a dense , 3-finger white head and tons of lacing .  the mouthfeel is a bit astringent .
good head retention thats lasting the entire beer .  the body is okay for a stout , but is more like a porter .
the beer itself is not opaque and almost black . very nice looking in the glass .  mouthfeel - foam is scarce and small bubbles and light caramel that fades quickly . slightly thin .

into a pint glass , poured a cloudy orange/amber with one finger of white , good retention , and great lacing .  mouth is fairly prickly and somewhat detracts from the tasting . i wish there was a little less carbonation and foam here .
half inch of dense creme colored head . brown in color with an orange glow when held to light . good lacing and a welcomed layer of retention after settling .  m : light bodied and well carbonated .

pretty good lacing , and , overall , a stellar appearance . however , appearance is n't everything .  this is a bad beer . not only that , but its a very overpriced bad beer . it smells like grain , aluminum , and malt liquor , and tastes about the same . there 's a tea-flavor going on in there a bit as well . head was pitiful even though it came from a nitro can . a waste of money . please save your tastebuds and dont buy this garbage for 7.50 a 4-pack .

spectacular retention and thick , chunky lace .  this beer was purchased at cyclone liquors , in ames , iowa . the beer was very dark in color and tasted very well . i drank the beer warm and i think it was a good beer . i would try this beer again if it was presented to me . it had a very nice sweet taste for a german dunkel , which i am not a huge fan of .
pours hazy light brown with some orange tints . great head and great lacing .  mouthfeel starts lite , then fullbodied . alcohol and carbonation are a little over-pronounced .

a : a stunning deep brown near black with cranberry highlights . a inch of toasted head comes after a medium pour . the head slowly fades to an impressive 1/3 inch . lacing on a dark beer ?  mouthfeel : the carbonation seems oddly low , but the body is medium light which gives the beer a little bit of oomph that it needs .

poured in my struise glass the beer looks very nice , dark with a creamy head . it 's a pity that the head disappears after a while .  md-light body and sharp moderate carbonation . foamed pretty good going down the drain .

a : my usual down-the-middle stout pour results in a near-overflow of creamy , frothy , light-brown foam above a midnight-black body . solid retention and some light , fine lacing .  mouthfeel is a bit of a problem for me . the carbonation level is also a factor , making it hard to enjoy in gulps .

a perfect pour into an oversized wine glass with rich deep amber body a tightly formed thick white head , i could not find any reason to not give a perfect score.tropical fruity hops in the nose with a little boozy and caramel sweetness , overripe mango and pineapple on the palate with again some sweetish booze , the malt base is quite dry underneath the hops and sweet booze.a nice dipa , one of the best pours for me ... ever .  the mouthfeel was the only thing that detracted from the beer in my opinion , as i found it to be a little to watery for my personal preference .

great nose on this altbier . very mild fragrance , overall , but perfectly to style . perfect for the cool austin weather this time of year .  mouthfeel is medium thin , with a little less carbonation than i would have liked .

ahhh , nice smoke on the nose ! i love smoke beers and i was really hoping this would have some campfire nose and it does .  while the champagne-like extreme dryness may put off some , i think it makes the beer truly unique and tasty as opposed to unblanced .

smell was very appetizing , a rich sour cherry with a bit of roasted malt . taste was not nearly as robust , pretty much just a strong stout , a nice bit of burnt malt and coffee , coupled with a nice tartness from the cherry , but not nearly as rich and complex as the aroma had me expecting . mouthfeel was very rich and creamy , medium body .  mouth feel : a bit thin on the palet , or maybe the aroma and taste make you expect more in the way of mouth feel .

served up a breathtaking deep copper amber that is crystal clear . the head is slightly off-white and looks superb with tightly packed , shiny bubbles that stick around forever and leave near perfect lace . if this beer tastes nearly as good as it looks i will be most happy .  mouthfeel is a bit of a letdown.. crisp but not as crisp as i had hoped . overall drinkability is good , the taste makes up for what it lacks in mouthfeel .

long trail ale poured copper ; clean & clear , topped by a nice , tall , dense white head .  i can feel it in my cheeks . it does n't have any off aromas specifically , but it definitely has the acidity for it . undrinkable , i 'm pouring it out .

a- a brown amber with a light brown head . good lacing .  the beer must have been very old , but it 's the brewery 's fault for the green bottle . i took one sip and thought of pouring it out , but then realized i could pretend it was really good and get my friend to try it . he promptly ran to the sink to wash his mouth out . yes , it was that bad . unless you 're positive it 's fresh , do n't buy this beer . i have never had a worse experience .

( s ) - very aromatic . very dynamic & layered . again , a good taste that followed suit to the smell . great aroma . lends itself more to a better drinkability score due to a lower abv than alot of strong ales out there ; thicker than most too , but it fits it well . this might benefit from further aging , but its great now .  my first impression was the color . the color was an impressive dark brownish ruby . the smell was sweet malt and fruit . the taste had definite apple/apple peel flavors going on .

( s ) - plenty of rich molasses & raisin with an even richer vanilla & whiskey-like smokiness . ( t ) - just like the smell with a pronounced raisin & cocoa profile .  a : solid black , modest lacing even at the beginning , but once the beer was gone so was the lacing s : malty , chicory , lingers nicely t : dominated by coffee ; bitter stout ; the oak comes through nicely ; not very complex m : casked , so it does n't really buzz in the mouth overall , a really good beer , but not as complex as i was hoping ; still , very worthwhile

draft at teresa 's in wayne , pa pours a very dark brown with foamy tan head that forms a lacing that lasts throught the whole glass .  perhaps another way to explain the feeling would be a textured shandy . noting the high praise this saison received , i have trouble fathoming such a bad experience .
i 'm picking up in floral and citrus . hops linger in the mouth for a couple minutes and slowly fade into a nice , mellow finish .  body seems quite thin for an imperial stout .

think imperial irish dry stout instead of russian imperial stout ... a : bottle opens with a 'gunshot pop '' and pours a dark black with a monstrous 2.5 '' dark tan head . fantastic retention .  mouthfeel - smooth , yet a litle effervescent .
2006 appearance , great head and retention . easy to create head .  m-lots of carbonation -- almost too much actually . a little more watery than you 'd expect .

pours copper hue , with a nice , long lasting , white head and lively carbonation .  again , dried dark fruit seems to be the dominating taste , and as it warms , a sweet cherry-like flavor comes in m : at first i found this beer a bit too prickly and highly carbonated for my liking ; i purposely agitated the beer by swirling and enjoyed it a bit more when carbonation was less severe great beer that i would drink anytime i needed a belgian fix .

the smell is amazing , dense spectrum of aromas floating out of my glass .  the nose is caramely and very malty . a little too carbinated for a traditional barleywine but lines ones gut like the best of the bunch ! being a sucker for barleywines i have to give this beer high remarks .

on tap at the austin ginger man . the aroma had a sweet wheat flavor along with banana , lemony citrus and a moderate clove spiciness . very flavorful and well rounded hefewiezen aroma . i get lots of clove flavor throughout the beer .  a bit watery on the body .

i 'm intrigued by the label that tells me this beer is a mix of young and old ipas aged in french oak ; intrigued because i like hops and like the effect that age can have on hops . i liked the earthy , woody aroma of this ale . i liked how the earthiness and vanilla-oakiness emerged among the caremelly malt and herbal hop flavors .  a bit more body would 've made this an excellent brew .

appearance - 4.5 poured gently into my stange , three fingers of solid , thick , pink head formed over a burgundy-red body that is quite transparent and looks to be highly carbonated . the head retained well and left plenty of lacing .  just the right amount of hops . even though you can taste the fruits and spice , you can also taste the high alc % . drinkability : very drinkable , but if you more than one in a session , watch out : ) overall : a better than average tripel .

appearance tan creamy four finger head on a straight pour . a good looking beer .  not amazing but for everyday you ca n't beat it . its good year round and drinking a bunch of them . it is n't expensive either . amber coloration , ok head and lacing , some hops but mostly malt . not overly heavy but not watery . i know the beer snobs disparage it but it does n't have to be sophisticated to be enjoyed .
smell is pure hops , limes , lemons ... .lemon marange pie ! great brew . memorable !  there is a very little carbonation factor in this beer .
a : pours a cloudy , medium brown color with two fingers of billowy , pale tan head . exceptional retention and lace , vigorous carbonation .  the body is light but somewhat creamy .

first off is 2008 alaskan barley wine . no real visible carbonation because the beer is so cloudy . s - the nose is the best feature of this beer . there are lots of sweet dark fruits much like a dropple bock . could be more complex . t - here this beer takes a turn for the worse .  4.5 m - lacks body . a bit thin but spritzy carbonation .

a- poured a dark black , with a nice head that faded quickly . the head was chocolate brown in color that had minimal lacing . i was very excited to taste based on looks .  mouthfeel is average , with enough body to carry the flavors , but is approaching watery at times .

appearance , beer pours a red golden with a huge pillowy off tan head that lingers and clings to the sides of the glass thickly . big bubbles and small bubbles intermingle making this beer look alive on the pour . the red gold color is more of a ruby when held to the light , this is one impressive looking barleywine .  m. feel is not bad , light crisp well carbonated .
s - ahhhh the wonderful scent of hops on a summer evening .  mouthfeel is a little too weak for my tastes , and is the only fault i can find with this brew .
crowned with a huge , well-retained tan head . very nice appearance .  well , so ... if it 's a barleywine or imperial or whatever , well ... then it 's probably thin on the mouth , eh ?

ca n't really tell the difference between this and the nitro can but i love this stuff . i could drink this stuff all day and night . a true classic !  mouthfeel was a bit thin , but the taste was clean and minty on the tongue .

( s ) - a very fruity aroma with fresh orange peel and lemon . a very vibrant fruit driven profile with hints of a hay/wheat dryness .  actually thought it might be bad but when i drank it there was plenty of carbonation . smell : a toasted malty smell with an almost cardboard smell . taste : very strong toasted smell but more of a bitterness then a sweetness . note : no date on the bottle but wondering if this beer had gone bad . will try another attempt at it but not really looking forward to it .
a : deep brown with a nice fluffy tan head . 2-fingers to start , slowly receding . perfect .  m - pretty watery and thin .

a - giant white lumpy 3 finger head with fantastic retention ! ever-so-slightly hazy straw yellow that 's profusely effervescent .  thanks walter a-a nice rich amber , good head , some lacing that turned into a small bubble ring s-a slight bready smell , some citrus ( makes me think of citra hop ) slight sweetness and then tart t- close to the same as the smell , there is a slight tangyness in the middle of the drink , it 's a good thing m- it 's moderately lively not as much bite and tingle i was expecting , a clean wet finish o/d- overall i really like this , it 's not the craziest ipa but it 's more than just decent , drinkability , i can see myself finishing this growler , this is a tasty beer and one i really like
anyways , into the erdinger glass ... a - really impressed with this head .  decent palate , a little thin like the others in the series , but fairly smooth .
appearance- pours a super light straw yellow with a soft bright white head .  very good . sort of on the thin side , but still ok. a good drinker .

dark brown in color and the tan head retains its character well .  nothing to write home about when it comes to mouthfeel . kind of a club-soda feel to the beer , tingly . though there seems to be a strange `` romanian roulette '' effect where every sixth beer is kinda soapy .

s : this beer smells incredible . huge vanilla aroma that is mixed with a huge coffee aroma .  the wood tannins come across and make this beer texturally difficult . it 's rough and gritty for a mouthfeel .

appears a ruby dark brown with a beige head and lots of thick , sticky lacing .  taste is weak but odd at the same time with a mild rice-sweetness . this is the kind of beer you can share with your friends because most do n't appreciate the imports anyway . i drank plenty of this is my younger days ... when you look up headache in the dictionary it reads `` drink 12 budweisers and take a nap .

at first , the nose was lots of tart apple and/or pears . after the drink sat for a bit the nose became mostly bananas and vanilla .  this is almost as good a stout as they come . i like guinness extra stout better because it has more bitterness . but this stout is smooth and easy to drink with a nice bitterness . if you are looking for a stout to bring to a party this is a good one because it is not too bitter . almost everyone i have served this to has liked it .

incredibly pungent and tropical aroma . the distinct nelson hops really shine here . one of the best aromas i 've ever experienced from any dipa . an absolutely wonderful dipa . honestly , i never expected a dipa this good to come from karl strauss -- count me in as very pleasantly surprised .  ) my only qualm was the the body seemed a little thin .

with a stiff pour , the brew produces a good two finger thick tan head , with a body that is dark ruby red and copper in color , and is well filtered . head retains decently , and lacing lasts pretty well for the style .  mf- raw resinous and sticky , becoming oily , medium carbonation , slightly astringent , dry and grainy in the finish d- well rounded ipa , but not the best around .

fosters lager pours a crystal clear light golden color with a beautiful thick foamy head that rides way above the lip of the glass and stays .  taste : sweet malt , raisins , a lot of sweet nutty flavors like pecans , sour/tart dark cherry flavor , ending with a nutty malt characters mouthfeel : really light body , low carbonation , pretty basic .

exceptional head and lace . big , rough , chunky , substantial lace . impressive to look at and earns full points on that count .  finishes with a sweet malt taste m- medium bodied with decent carbonation , not as full for an octoberfest as i 'd like but still good d- very drinkable and easy to use to introduce others to a seasonal beer

it settles slowly in a dramatically lumpy fashion leaving a tremendous amount of chunky and webby lace .  the taste is awesome m : medium bodied , perhaps a bit too heavy , with decent carbonation , not the best , but is good enough for an apa .

the cascade hop explosion was still there , but i was able to handle it this time around and i really enjoyed it . ruby-amber color , bordering on red . awsome color .  m : not as creamy as the better oatmeal stouts out there . still above average for a dark beer , but expected more from the style .

aroma is quite hoppy , mostly grapefruit , pine , citrus rind . mild buttered bread aroma , some pinneaple , a hint of spiced banana .  magic hat usually disappoints me , not that their brews are n't good , it 's that some of them just are n't tasty- till now . magic hats roxy rolles is right up there with ithaca 's cascazilla and troegs hopback amber . a definite seasonal must have for me . great ! ! !
the color is pitch black . head is large , creamy , and dark tan .  it also takes a hit because while it looks thick , it feels a bit thinner than it should be .

a - pours a beautiful golden/amber with a puffy head which quickly dissolves with lots of lacing s - wow .  in my opinion , flying dog brewery has created a great seasonal , smooth-tasting beer with very little bite or after taste . i would definitely recommend it to any self-respecting beer drinker who might be having an end-of-summer party this or any october .
a- pours a tar-like black with a tan head .  m - a little lighter and sparkly than i 'd like at first ... the more it warms and dies down , the better it gets .
overall : a solid fresh hop pale ale with a really good aroma .  taste : mirrors the smell , but the flavors are weaker than their aroma counterparts because of a thin mouthfeel .

appearance : copper-brown color with a nice 1/2 '' head ; looks great when your pour it smell : not much here , surprisingly ; i sense a little bit of hops and raisins taste : similar ; hops and a raisin sweetness to balance it ; the taste isnt as hoppy as regular arrogant mouthfeel : nice , thick , full-bodied drinability : goes down ok ; you ca n't chug it , but then again you would n't want to this is n't quite as good as regular arrogant , but i 'd like to give this oaked another shot  m -- light carbonation . good body with a lightly soft mouthfeel .

smell : super strong pine , grapefruit , and bitterness warns the tastebuds through the nose what is to come . taste : hearty caramel sweetness with a very strong and biting bitterenss .  the feel is a little odd . it does n't seem to be too carbonated , but the bubbles sting like sprite against your lips .
this brew has a delicious smell of peanut brittle and roasted malts .  malty and corny .

a - pours a gorgeous pure orange color with a nice white dense head . it recedes slowly and it is sticky and very attractive .  medium to thick body , light almost too light level of carbonation with a sweet almost sticky mouthfeel .

a- pretty close to opaque brown/black . head is thick and tan , stays frim at one finger . a couple wisps of lacing . o- it 's a tasty beer but it 's a bit too sweet , yet light , for me to think of it as much above average in the styke .  it 's light on body , and not especially interesting - but as fruit beers go , this was excellent .

a - pours black with a nice light-tan head . looks great . sticks fairly well to the side , just about as good as a porter could .  the last 2/3 of my beer was a bit thin , but this was quite refresing and very easy to drink .
this beer pours a very bright yellow sundrenched tint that just beckons to be drunk .  mouthfeel is a little thin , though .

s - nice ! grapefruit aroma with some hints of pine fill my nose . very attractive flowery hops , with some bready biscuity malt hidden along the way . nice co2 .  m- thin to medium in body . highly attenuated with a soft carbonation .

a : light straw yellow . plenty of carbonation , bone white head with medium to heavy lacing .  overwhelming carbonation cuts through initial malt goodness , temporarily undermining a tasty complex malt profile .

pours cloudy yellow orange with thick creamy foam indefatgiable white foam .  mouthfeel is really my only disappointment , as the beer is overall pretty watery . the body feels thin , as the carbonation is there after pouring , but quickly disappears .
there was very good retention and excellent lacing .  mouthfeel : both the carbonation and body are on the higher end of the light range .

copper color with two fingers of creamy offwhite head that really stands up . leaves nice lacing .  tastes like an aged beer , its very dry and cuvee-like . significant hops.its wierd but it does smell like a barleywine . a bit undewhelming mouthfeel.there was some problem with foam in the taps , and maybe if i had this in the wee hours . still good .
bright yellow and unfiltered with a full white head that leaves nice lace .  it goes down smooth .

black in hue , opaque , it was served with about a fingers worth of beige head , which was surprisingly frothy . subsequent lacing was very prominent , bubbly lace dominated the walls of the glass . the appearance of this beer is near perfect .  this feels thin for some reason . carbonation is good and proper .
smell - aroma was bery pleasing with a definite berry aroma .  has a very light mouth feel , which makes it a more-then-one beer .
appearance : pours orange in color with a huge fluffy white head that stays around for some time . lots of bubbles floating to the top .  medium bodied and dry .

and once i saw the pour of this beer i was highly anticipating excellence . it has an amazing color of a mackintosh red apple that glistens from fresh rain .  smell is a cross between musty and estery at first , then just corn . tastes like corn , but considerably worse than a typical macro . it has some off flavors , that i ca n't really identify . bad .

when you first pour it , it wafts clean fruity and spicy saison notes . put your nose to the glass and everything intensifies going from mouthwatering to mindnumbing .  like cheap malt liquor infused with citrus and nail polish remover .

great looking deep copper-red with a full tan head that receded to a thin layer with great lacing .  presentation 11.2 oz ''ceramic '' bottle with blue foil over the cap no date on bottle . pours with a think creamy head that dissipates as quickly as is rose . light brown with a hind of deep red . a smell of caramel and alcohol , taste is more of the same with a slight earthiness to it . finishes cleanly .

reviewed 12/30/2009 ( bottle ) : pours a very dark almost black color body , ca n't see through at all . big light tan color head , somewhat lasting .  m : medium body with no carbonation . this is pretty much tap water flat . the mouthfeel is sticky with notable warming .

dark brown with a cream coloured head that dies down to a thick head with some great lace .  mouthfeel - the one noticeable drawback to this offering is the lack of carbonation . otherwise it felt very good in the mouth .

a : pours a very dark brown with a billowing fluffy dark tan-ish brown oily head that slowly faded into a thick film leaving a network of sticky lace .  its perfectly balanced and not overly done . m very medium , which i find most all stone beers to be and i dont really complain about . the carbonation is present and isnt overly aggressive or submissive .

s : coffee ice cream cones ? like a joy ice cream cone , and a mild coffee . only beer yet to give me that . m : creamy , creamy and creamy . imperial anyone ? t : i 'll start with a heavy dark chocolate to start .  mouthfeel is ok. fairly light body , more than i 'd think it should be at this abv .

it pours like a big , english old ale . smell- fat and sweet , it 's a beautiful display of wood and chocolate covered cherries ... but more like the liquid that surrounds the cherries . notes of old leatherbound library books and rum soaked dark fruits abound .  m : medium light body with medium high carbonation .

came out a murky amber-gold with a good inch 's worth of head on it . great retention , and perfect lacing rings after each sip . beautiful .  m - a little thinner than i imagined , though based on the aroma , i might have been expecting a double ipa .

a : beautiful beer ! it 's a perfectly clear light amber color topped by a big-bubble , thin but foamy head . lacing is alright , but the beer looks so good it makes up for that in other areas .  light carbonation and light-medium bodied . starts as sour apples becomes more sour like lemon juice , dry finish ; easily the least enjoyed belgian i have had . 750ml bottle - gift from vintage cellars blacksburg , va .
head exhibits very impressive staying power , and impressive lace . color is a beautiful dark and cloudy orange , yellowing around the edges .  had a typical pilsner mouthfeel .

the spices really compliment the berry smell . very unique and inviting . the highlight of this beer is the incredible aroma . t - not quite as impressive as the nose leads to believe .  i sent it back thinking it had gone bad , but the bartender tried it and assured me it was ok. m - average for a macro lager .

amazing mix of bitter hops , tropical fruit , pine , etc , etc . really amazing ! taste follows suit -- -an assault of hops and some light malt . very nice , but nothing i 'd want to have more of one of . had a touch of heat from the 10 % abv on the finish . overall a really good brew -- -glad i tried it finally .  mouthfeel was somewhat on the thin side , but still quite acceptable .
a : pitch black , slightly viscous . excellent head formation and nice lacing . this is how an ais should look in the glass .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with above carbonation .

great bavarian weizen smell of of banana and wheat that unfortunately is not backed up by the flavor which is mildly wheaty with lots of carbonation . this was an ok dunkelweizen but there are much better ones out there .  the taste is fantastic , but the beer is a little thin and a bit hot ; not a good session beer , but great type of brew to have after a long day .
the duchesse . i liked the aroma - sour cherry , tart , musty . i hope it does n't pervade the taste .  mouthfeel is about average for an ipa .

a- pretty beautiful . a reddish amber color , just glowing .  overall , i quite enjoyed this beer . it 's got a fresh and interesting taste that makes it a decent drinking beer . deliciously fruity hops , nice malt sweetness , comes across as quite fresh . noticeable taste of apricots which i quite like makes this distinctive and something i look forward to drinking . disappointing finish however . lots of interesting things happening up front and then nada . nothing really lingers which is a darn shame , 'cause overall this beer is well worth a try . still tasty after each bottle . mmmm .

i 'm pouring this into my hotel low ball/water glass , for what it 's worth . looks like a fine scotch with a bit of bone white head at the top . quite a bit of visible bubbles indicates a good amount of carbonation .  it was n't as smooth as i expected because of a slight chalky feel in the mouth .

poured into a de molen sniffer . smell : great nose , full of dark chocolate , slight sour cherry , bourbon and vanilla taste : great taste as well , this beer is very complex and still very balanced . the smell and taste are wonderful , for me it seems an attempt of the molen to produce their own cuvee delphine from struise .  this feels a bit acidic , but not too much . medium mouthfeel with a dry finish .

& raspberry , great if weird scents going on here ... t : raspberry , plums , figs , & strawberry jam verging om pop tart filling , very weird , plus leafy hops up front .  light bodied though , almost watery . in a way this is an ipa-light - some similar desirable flavors and aromas , but less bitterness , less alcohol , and lighter bodied .

aroma is really nice for a bourbon-barrel stout ... vanilla , sweetish milk chocolate , with an underlying fruitiness from the barrel . very tasty stuff ...  m : lightly carbed , thin , slightly oily , tannic finish .
a velvety mouth feel , really enjoyable .  it is light bodied and enjoyable . it has a light hops aroma and a light bodied feel to it .
smells of raisins and roast malt and a little chocolate , very nice .  m : mouthfeel is a bit thin , considering how robust the initial flavor is .
this beer is absolutely stunning , sharp ruby red . it 's a really great looking winter brew .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and resinous , this is really the only fault i can find .

aroma is the highlight of this beer big sweet candy sugars dancing with plums , liquorish and cherries . very inviting aroma on this one . mouthfeel is a big medium with nice medium carbonation , which is nice as too many of these brews are over carbonated .  mouthfeel is the only real negative to this one , medium bodied and a bit thinner than i 'd like .
beautiful , beautiful honey color with a thick , but not creamy , head .  mouthfeel was ok ; about the same as urquell .
