aromas of tart cherries right off the bat mixed with nicely roasted malts and a woody bourbon aroma as well . i really enjoy the tart cherry integration .  nice flavors , with a nice two-row malty sweetness and a huge piney and slight citrusy hop flavor that is very much in front ; good overall , but very unbalanced , even considering the style . goes down fine , but there is quite a bit of hop scratchiness .

the smell is quite good : belgian yeast funk , candi sugar , orange peel and coriander . it has more of the belgian yeast aroma than most wit brews . not as heavy on the orange peel and coriander as most wits ; which i find to be a good thing .  m -- slightly too watery , does n't really coat the mouth like i would hope but it washes down clean with no bad lingering tastes d -- this is it here , i think this is the beer i would use to introduce someone new to ipa 's .

fantastic looking beer .  from the perfume river in vietnam ( no really , that 's what the label says ) , on to the beer : poured into a mug , it 's a clear yellow color with a soda-like head . this flavors in the beer do n't meld together well for me . there 's more cooked corn , a mild astingency , and a straightforward bitterness that battle each other for supremecy . even at ice cold , it took some work for me to stomach this beer . round off the edges and we might have something more tolerable .

i 'll tell you that the smell is freaking awesome . have n't tasted the beer yet , but smells of good things to come ... here we go . s - freaking awesome . especially since i considered this some bland , flavored light beer t - nice .  decent carbonation , a little thin on the malt profile for the style .
the hop aroma is like sticking your nose in a bag of cascade hops and taking a deep breath .  m-a bit watery for my tastes but the taste makes you forget about it being slightly thin .

a : orangey amber cloudy beer with a huge 3 finger cappucino head that settles to peaks and valleys veery slowly , great lace throughout .  m/t : light to medium body , watery and a good amount of carbonation . however with the light body , low bitterness and virtually zero aftertaste , i could session this beer .
appearance : this beer is magical . a perfect brown head sits upon a black body , grabbing the glass and not letting go as i drink .  mouthfeel medium body for the style with sharp carbonation .

many thanks to drweizen for sending this in his shipment of holiday beers ... the beer is quite carbonated ( with a slow pour , i got half head ! ) and leaves a gorgeous lace pattern on my glass .  mouthfeel : there is a lot of bitterness .

bought this one on a whim , the fz album cover made it too good to pass up . beer advocate describes this as a doppelbock . ) poured a beautishus deep copper , malty nose , and nice lacing as i emptied the glass .  nice carbonation , but this comes off as a little thin . this should be more drinkable considering its thin body , but as this is a stout , the thin body is a bit of a turn off .
this bock pours perfectly with a tight forming bright white head that stays around for a good duration .  the mouth feel is heavy with a decent amount of carbonation .
poured nice gold color with a generous stiff white head .  mouthfeel : slighty watery good .

appearance : pours a perfectly clear , deep yellow body with a tall , bubbling , white head . looks nice .  m-explosive carbonation . tough to gauge the feel over the bubbles . a bit too carbonated for me .
pours a dark black color with a thin brown head .  first pull provided a mouthfeel that was a little more smooth than i would have expected , just short of creamy .

appearance - ruby/amber with a light brown head . alcohol is very present , almost like a rum in the presentation .  very good light lager . hints of barley and hops , with a smooth slightly dry aftertaste . this brew had a short lived white foamy head and lower than normal carbonation . i would highly recommend this to any light beer drinker .

the smell is great . as a chocolate lover , i really like this . smells like straight up melted chocolate . but this is really good if you like chocolate . next time i will pair it with some raspberries or strawberries , or make a damn milkshake out of it .  it is a little bit sweet on the tongue . i could stand it to be a little bit more dry .

the appearance is still wonderful , rich , creamy and delightful , although you get less of the wonderful spectacle of the bubbles gently settling on the surface .  beer/brewery - old fezziwig ale/boston beer company ( samuel adams ) city/state- boston , massachusetts style winter warmer abv 5.9 % ibu 27 date 10 dec 2011 serving type 12 oz bottle glassware pub glass appearance mahogany in color with a thin head with a brownish white color aroma- fruity and winter spices , all spice , clove and nutmeg i think taste pumpkin pie without the pumpkin , a lot of clove , also has a bit a of a bitter ( non hop ) after taste mouthfeel very light and bland ob feeling conclusion other than the after taste this is a great christmas beer , not quit a winter warmer as they abv is a little low , but still a good flavor to think of around christmas .

poured from a growler into a pint glass . pours a deep , clear ruby-brown with wonderful garnet highlights when held to the light . a fat , frothy head of light tan foam shows marvelous retention , holding tight throughout and lasting to the finish , grabbing tightly to the walls of the glass , leaving behind thick , bubbly curtains of lace as the glass empties .  mouthfeel the beer is slick on the tongue with strong carbonation . the body is a little lacking , medium-light .

bottled 10/31/11 a : pours jet black with a nice finger high layer of dark mocha head that laces the glass nicely .  s : candied pineapple , yeast , and hops well balanced t : a typical ipa taste with accents of pineapple ; yeasts and hops , well balanced m/d a bit thin , carbonation too small and too much , abv on the high side and quite noticeable good beer
very nice looking beer .  the mouthfeel was medium with a syrupy sweetness on the palate .

pours a lovely shiny ruby colour , rich and clear . head is beige , nice and dense and retaining thin crown . lace is good and sticky . looks wonderful .  it must be said that this beer is a bit astringent on the palate and a bit thinner than i would have liked , but it is still rather drinkable .

a- pours a deep oily black with a three finger tall foamy brown head that has incredible retention ( after 5 minutes there 's still a finger worth left ) .  feel left me a bit disappointed , however , as it was thin -- too thin for this big of flavor .

- this beer had a very exceptional appearance and a weathered pumpkin smell . very inviting beer , although there was something `` left on the field '' as the beer entered my mouth .  on tap this poured as a golden straw colored ale , clear and bright with less than an inch of head . there is an apparent hoppy aroma that followed with a similarly dominant slight-hoppy taste followed by the expected bitters - very tasty . i stopped with one . not to discount its drink-ability , there are just several others i wish to try .
poured from a 12oz bottle , into a 16oz glass mug , color was a beautiful hazy golden , with a huge 3 finger+ fluffy head .  the only thing i was not pleased with with this beer was the mouthfeel .
s - classic belgiun smell.. sweet dark fruits.. caramel and brown sugar . t - pretty bland and tart .  the beer is a bit too thin for my tastes but is a good sessionable beer .

s : it smells great . fresh , crisp , hints of the hoppiness of an ipa . mf : very interesting and different . overall : very interesting and complex beer .  good carbonation and medium bodied . flavor is spicy , yeasty , hints of sweetness that gets buried by the yeast . lingering yeasty aftertaste .

makes an excellent appearances , pours a cloudy rich amber with a large foamy tan head with good retention and lots of sticking .  lively carbonation is a bit excessive , but the body is quite smooth .

this beer looks wonderful . a beautiful mahogany red , cloudy and rich topped with two and a half fingers of rich foam . the beer leaves textbook rings down the glass as you drink it ( rather quickly ) .  mouthfeel : medium body , a bit chalky , tingly carbonation and a dry finish .
poured into a goblet , revealing huge tan head , barely any body . lots of head .  quite thin in my mouth .

a - beautiful hazy orange , loads of carbonation , four fingers of fluffy head with good retention . very little lacing .  it states `` the deep coffee flavors are created naturally during the brewing process by dark roasted malts . '' then later it notes `` stout brewed with coffee . anyway , i 'll refer to this as a steady drinking stout because of its thinness , otherwise it 's pretty enjoyable . not particulary complex but enjoyable taste of roasted malt with coffee . abv seems pretty low as i had two with no noticable effects .

it has a great thick fluffy dark mocha colored head perched upon a jet black body . the head was still present a good 5 minutes after pouring .  thanks jpm30 . clearly sour taste that sweetens as you drink it . vineous and slightly rich , wood only detactable before the taste buds are overpowered.. great after salty fish . a slightly milder alternative to a cantillon , overpowering the mouth but not for the entire day .

as others may have observed , this is more like `` pumpkin pie ale '' than `` pumpkin ale '' . picture a nut brown ale , with a pumpkin flavor , and the nose of cinnamon & nutmeg and you have this one .  the motuhfeel is moderately carbonated and slightly watery .
really delightful . very nice aroma sits about halfway between a brown ale and a porter .  m- the mouth feel is a bit overly carbonated , yet not thin .

per label `` a kicked up version of our popular wee heavier '' , i had the pleasure of trying that brew a few years back while in asheville and i have to say i liked that one better.poured into a 22oz nonic a deep amber/brown with a pillowey 2 finger light beige head atop that settled ever so slowly into a frothy mass leaving broken rings of lace behind , from there down hill.muted aromas slight brown brown sugar and fruit but it doesnt show thru enough , flavors stay with that theme very light with some malt tilted sweetness like brown sugar and raisin but its really light and watery tasting in my mind.hmm kind of a clunker here was expecting much more from a pretty good small brewery in western carolina .  apricots . hops undetectable above the jaw-clenching , eye-squinching , head-shaking sourness . awful . ugh . otherwise , it defintely seems to be beer , ( if in no way resembling any version of a contemporary pa ) , but with a sour and bitter fruitiness that pervades , annoys , and overwhelms . the originally enticing head cashed in early and diminished to virtual non-existence before i gave up trying to like this one ; very little lacing to wash out of the glass . wo n't drink the other two in the sampler , did n't finish this one , and opened a sn celebration ale to get the taste out of my mouth .

s : wow , this beer smells amazing . whiskey and bourbon dominate the nose . i could literally sit here and smell this beer for the 15 minutes and be perfectly happy .  m : thin mouthfeel with moderate carbonation .

topped with a frothy and creamy mocha colored head . looks pretty damn tasty .  start is lightly sweet , the top skeletal in feel , the finish lightly carbonated , hops shy in their spiciness , a bit medicinal , dry aftertaste , quite drinkable but a touch different than my normal american over the top beers , and frankly scarlet i dont give a damn , im ready for a change .

exquisite in appearance !  it has little to no head on it with a soft pour . this beer has a good balance of spices that is not overpowering . the aftertaste is mellow . this is one of the darker ales that i have drank but all in all i would give it another try . especially on a snowy winter day .

sweet malts , wheat , maple syrup , and barrel aged booze in the nose . wheat & sweet malts with a hoppy backbone . boozy on the way down , leaving your throat tingly .  m - not much fizz , easy drinking if you like it .
s : the best smelling coffee oatmeal stout i 've smelled to date .  mouthfeel is a bit gassy .

s- nice nutty aromas , butterscotch , caramel , high end rum notes . this makes me smile . t- starts out a nice light dry chocolate , some nutty notes , light caramel , and some light dry hoppiness on the clean finish .  there is little ( hardly any ) carbonation here , and the mouthfeel really does n't pack a punch at all .

sampled on 4-7-09 pours a clear deep red/brown , with a huge , foamy , clingy , off-white head that leaves crazy thick lacing .  mouthfeel is probably the most disappointing aspect of this otherwise excellent beer ; the carbonation promised by the head largely disappeared , leaving a slick , full bodied beer with very light carbonation . a nice , sharp bite of carbonation would have been welcome in this case , drying out the finish nicely , but that does n't happen here .
s- smells of coffee , hint of chocolate , a little sweet . enticing .  m : a little thin in body d : good .

t - while the aroma is astounding , the taste does not do the aroma justice . it 's one of my top 5 ipa 's , i 'd say , but compared to the outstanding aroma , the taste is considerably less in amplitude .  m - fairly thin body and medium carbonation . nothing special on the mouthfeel .
bottle : poured a clear golden color ale with a big foamy head with good retention and good lacing .  m - thought it was a little flat , but not bad .
bottle poured into a glass a : a rich and frothy off white head with great lacing and retention .  carbonation is a little light though .

s - toffee , cocoa powder , nutty , then as it warms sweet citrus oil , green pine needles . slabs of caramel mix with alcohol vapors and fill the glass with a robust sweetness . t - starts with a mix of semi/sweet chocolate , sweet toffee malt , then an undertow of hops rush in with mint and citrus . the aroma is so good it 's hard to explain .  m : not too bad , there was a little bit of body .
2003 : nice heavy white head tops the cloudy golden hue .  my only complaint with this beer is that it is a little thin .
the head is quite impressive , off white in color , composed of thousands and thousands of tiny bubbles .  body is not as full as i would like , but this is one heck of a tasty beer .

serving type : 16oz bottle appearance : pours a darker cloudy orange colour w/ a 1 finger head . plenty of lacing the whole time while drinking .  a soft , almost too light mouthfeel and a little weak carbonation , the only appearent downside of this brew in my opinion .
pours a nice dark brown/black with a quarter inch head , typical for founders stuff .  i wish the mouthfeel had a bit more viscosity ... .but i say that about every stout .

thick , oily black pour unleashes a magnificent tan head that just stays and stays , eventually forming a thick collar that remains til the end . crusty lace coats my glass .  m - heavy , with little carbonation .
smell : bacon ! ! again with bacon smelling rauchbiers . i love it ! ! but , it 's a bit weak .  m - at times , a bit of a metallic feel to the beer .

smells of rich dark roast , light coffee , fruity yeast and light alcohol . when cold , all i could taste were roasted flavors , a sharp carbonation , and a woody , slightly smokey hop flavor , maybe chinook .  m - surprisingly , its a bit thin and lacks carbonation .

summit horizon red : a : appearance is exceptional , great amber-red color to it with exceptional clarity ! nice 1 '' head that develops yet depletes half-way through .  a little weak in the feel . tons of carbonation couldn'tmake up for the watery texture .

the beer poured real nice , big fluffy head , nice maroon color , excellent carbonation , it was a real treat to see after installing a new air conditioner .  sort of thin . inoffensive , but it really does n't do much for me .
smell : varies as it warms : bacon , chocolate , hickory , raisin , wood and more ... taste : dope .  m : a bit thin d : incredibly drinkable .

a - pours very dark red , foams high but dissipates quickly . has a very nice cream/coke fizz coloured head and a great ruby red hue in light . very attractive beer .  mouthfeel was a bit thick , and it was not quite as carbonated as i would have liked .
has a mashed ripe banana smell with sprucey / piney notes .  slightly sour , a bit thin , highly carbonated . quite drinkable .

poured a deep dark reddish-brown into my guinness pint glass , and the tan head reached the top . beautiful .  fairly thin and smooth , mild to medium bodied . breckenridge definitely delivers a vanilla porter as i would expect a vanilla flavored porter to be . i suggest toning down the roasted barley and focusing more on bittering hops .
acidic and fruity nose . fun berry aromas . the nose was the best part of this beer .  mouthfeel is not too bad , sharpness coming more from the carbonation than hops .

the sweet smelling belgian malts are very nice . the flavor starts out very well .  m- light to medium , smooth but still missing a little depth here . d- this is n't what i was expecting , but the hops hit me huge here .

when i went to smell the aromas , i was very impressed with the assumed banana and clove . they were very prominent and defined ... i couldnt wait to taste ( damn it has a strong aroma that belies its appearance .  bittersweet finish . kind of think and syrupy on the palate .

appearance : pours into an allagash tulip a slightly hazy pale gold with a huge , fluffy , white , large-bubbled head . an insane stream of bubbles rockets up through the beer keeping the head constantly refreshed .  mouthfeel : pretty heavy for a porter but very drinkable even in the heat .

the aroma is very nice , a heady mixture of malt , honey and alcohol . unfortunately the flavor does n't come close to fulfilling the promise in the aroma . the body is carbonated with a rather lager-ish character .  mouthfeel was a little thin , that 's my only complaint .

a : lovely dark red-brown , nearly opaque , with an antique-white froth that 's thin but resilient .  ginger is one of my favorite flavors . this beer has a wonderful ginger taste , which is exactly what i would expect from a beer with this name . further , there is a decent bitterness & a slight sweetness as well . i 'm not a huge fan of spiced beers normally , but this one is really nice . recommended .
brilliantly clear , tawny copper hue . pitted , steadfast ivory white head . persistent , massed lace trails .  mouthfeel - thin , a decent and sturdy body , carbonation is average .

s : strong and good balance of malt/hops in the nose . sweet and bitter , but not bittersweet .  body is medium , and perhaps errs to light every once in a while , which does n't help the flavours as much as it could .

the aroma was like a big hop garden bouquet with a little sugared pixie dust spread all over . i was ready for the taste and ready to be blown away , but was not .  mouthfeel is a bit light , to me , for the style , though it seems appropriate for the flavors that this beer brings to the palate .

the aromas are divine : brandied , sour apples , an array of raw and roasted nuts , oranges , vanilla and pepper . on the palate it was metallic and struggled to deliver the promise of the nose . still , bright , sweet green strawberry and caramel curled in and out of the perfectly flat liquid . apparently this beer was not out of date , as there have been many other reviews this year for examples this old . a shame .  m - moderate carbonation , medium bodied .

pours the color of any other well crafted imperial stout , pitch black but with an impressive mocha colored inch of foam on top . the head displayed some excellent retention and a creamy layer of bubbles from the cask treatment .  m- it is a thicker , heavy beer , with sweet taste .
s - the aroma is pretty impressive , and accurately captures the smells and intricacies of apple pie .  feel is thin bodied overall , but well bodied for the style .

lively . golden with a dense creamy head ... after all it is the cream of manchester ... a nickname i 've never felt comfortable with .  i always look forward like most do the annual stone anniversary brews.poured a rich deep amber with a tight and sticky one finger off white head , big hops in the nose with a mix pine and herbal/leaf , there is a gummy , fruity-like sweet note as well.the mouthfeel is a bit sharp i will say it crashes down the gullett at first , it does begin to smooth out after a few sips but still seems a bit harsh.no holds barred hops hit the palate up front with big pine and big herbalness , a healthy does of sweeter alcohol gives a slight burn along with a bit of dark fruit.very good but seems like it something that should sit for awhile , still another fine one from stone .
the chocolate yeti has perfect color in both the body of the beer and the frothy dark brown head .  first sip reveals a much thinner body than i expected and average carbonation .

i smell a fruity and floral characteristic along with a strong citrusy hop overtone . this is a classic ipa and the brewers knew what they were doing with this batch .  if you aerate the beer in your mouth , it really releases the co2 . it would do well as a beer to server with medium to strong cheese .

poured this brew into a la chouffe glass , just like the last tasting . makes lots of bright white foam , and has a hazy golden colored body .  got this in an abita variety pack ... would be a great session beer if i had the quantity . in general , the abita 's have a really clean taste , little aftertaste ... is that the spring water that it talks about on the cap ? a good dark ale , malt flavor is tasty . pretty brown color . smell is very pleasing .

the smell is great . smell of very fresh hops in something that promises to be potent . very weak . can taste the massive carbonation as if it was campaign , not beer . very fresh .  it 's got a little bit of a piney finish that 's quite refreshing . maybe closer to watery , but not bad . d- very drinkable esb .

a floral citrus smell hits you hard with a smell of some sweetness to it that seems to be hiding in this hoppy beer . mouthfeel- a good amount of carbonation to it between medium to heavy in its feel , about average in my opionion drinkability-is n't the best but with conditioning you can become very use to it and then it becomes very appealing . just brilliant .  i also find it a little thin .
pours straw yellow , with little head . ruby red grapefruit dominates the smell . very bright citrus , little malt .  mouthfeel is a little bit thin .

the head falls to an island of loose bubbles , a ring , and dusting that leaves spots of lacing.. mind blowing aroma . orange , mango , papaya , grapefruit , pineapple ... candied hops ! sweet and floral , it tickles my nose and begs to be tasted . i taste tropical fruits , with lots of green and white pepper , it is earthy and reminds me of kind-buds .  m- smooth , but a tad thin . carbonation is good , as is the thoroughly smooth finish with a tad of warmth .
smells exactly like strawberry jam with a very subtle hint of tartness .  it has a pretty high carbonation .

pours a deep orange copper hue into my chalice glass with an off white head forming thick and even with fine detailed lacing .  a delightful golden color graced by a pale yellow head . i did n't get much lacing , but i believe that was due to a freshly-washed glass ( served at a bar ) . nice hops come through in this one . it is a little bitter and spicy , but also has some good vanilla and tones of malt . not the most fantastic example of its style , but tasty and very drinkable .

drank on-tap at hot tomato 's , new haven , ct poured a hazy amber with a two-finger , bubbly , white head that left huge ridges of lacing all the way down the glass .  mouth feel is reasonably rich .

poured from a liter swingtop bottle into a snifter a= pours a thick black color with a nice one finger brown head that lasts suprisingly long with amazing lacing . s= huge hop notes which is amazing as well as a prominent coffee smell .  this is a seasonal brew , do n't know if it is offered everywhere or if it was given adequate time to chill before serving so i 'll reserve final judgment for later .

a : pours a light golden with a couple fingers of dense white head that reduced very slowly into a thick frothy head . beautiful rings/sheets of lacing left with every sip .  it 's ok. mouthfeel is a little heavy .
wow . the nose was so great . what happened ?  feel is a bit coarse , but just a bit .
a- pours dark clear gold-yellow with a white and beautiful head . big carbonation , looks fantastic .  carbonation was fairly low , with thin to medium body .

overall really nice aroma . first sip is a mix of caramel and toasted malts with a touch of fruitiness .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin , spicy , moderately dry , and has a distinct saison flavor in the aftertaste .
an absolutely gorgeous looking beer !  mouthfeel is poor due to the overdone carbonation .

the appearance is the best part about this beer . pours badass and the head stays with it the whole time of drinking .  drink this on tap at city beverage in durham . i like the color and mouthfeel , though a bit thin for a heavy beer aroma is slightly sweet and complex spices taste is toasted barley , spices , and slight caramel with little head . drinks easy for a heavy beer

aromas were fantastic : bready , citrus-fruit and cloves were wonderfully balanced . it was not too strong , but the aromas were apparent .  mouthfeel was medium with a mild lager sweetness accompanied by loads of off flavors , including apples and grapes .

s : perfumy nose ( muscat ? ) with grapes and chamomile flowers , pungent , with hints of honeysuckle . t : there is a belgian yeasty estery upfront which is nice . after that the grapes really come out , particularly the gewurztraminer which i 'm a fan of since i love alsatian whites . but anyways , it 's a fun beer to delve into , tasty for sure . a marriage of northern french wine and belgian beer , it makes perfect sense .  the mouthfeel is a bit watery and cool in texture , it goes down nicely and is a little bit better than water .

smell is nice ! !  the only thing that could be improved on this beer is the mouthfeel . a bit light for my tastes , but like i said it has incredible drinkability without making you get too full too quick .

best by date of 5/3/11 a : standard pour yields a billowy 2.5 finger light creamsicle colored head with very good retention . lacing is patchy and spotty with nice cling .  mouthfeel is a bit watery not much body to it , but on a hot day like today , i could take plenty of these guys down .

attractive , crystal clear dark bronze hue . topped by a thick , fluffy head that recedes into a persistent one fingered layer .  it 's almost too sticky and thick to be pleasureable , kind of like a toned-down bourbon county stout . i 'm not a big fan of the finish , which comes off like sweet wort of a stout ( oily and a bit thin ) . m : very thick , with some relief , but then a lingering silkiness .

simply beautiful cascading action that lasts for over a minute ! superb tan head retention that is not going away at all !  m : finish stays around for quite a while , almost too long , really coats the mouth .

smells wonderful ! t - flavor is a bit subdued , really disappointing after such an amazing nose . more tart cherry , with flavors of brown sugar , vinegar , tobacco , and high quantities of oak .  thin on mouthfeel medium orangish-amber with a 1 finger offwhite head that leaves a respectable amount of lacing . taste : broad caramel maltiness with a warming alcohol changes over to a restrained english hop bitterness . notes : a nice esb , although the abv is much higher than say , honker 's ale . drinkability ranks fairly high but the alcohol content is above that of a session beer .
nose is superb -- very much pumpkin pie . delicious and a new pumpkin ale favorite !  pretty average mouthfeel overall .
this stinks like simcoe , cascade , and centennial - if i recall . good shit .  carbonation a little higher than i expect in the style but still manages to be exceptionally drinkable .
a - golden yellow with a huge , chunky white head . excellent retention ang big chunky lace up and down the glass . beautiful beer .  the mouthfeel is where this beer kind of fell apart for me .

big flowery hops dominate the aroma , but it 's not a hop wallop , and it has a bit of sugary/caramel sweetness backing it up . the more i smell the more i like . has a kind of dessert-y lure to it . decent stuff , but it did n't deliver what the looks and smell promised .  i purchased this beer in a mix and match pack at the recommendation of the guy working at the liquor store = error . the look of the beer was clear and it drank smooth , but it was accompanied by the 'sour beer face . ' the taste was a combination of failure and shame ( with a hint of fruit ) all leading to the grand finale of a quick pour into the drain .

very strong baking chocolate smell - the kind that smells delicious but is really dry and ends up too bitter when you taste it . what a deceptive beer - first you notice it because it is a ris in a can , then it looks and smells great , and then it just lets down big time in the taste .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with low carbonation and somewhat thin , disappointing .

a : red-brown , fluffy off-white head , awesome retention and lace !  mouth : such a light and watery mouthfeel that it becomes distracting pondering the feel when you should be appreciating the tastes . drink : the nearly too-light mouthfeel is redeemed by the drinkability of this brew .
a - has two full fingers of ultra-fine reddish-tan head . what a beauty !  m - smooth going down , a bit thin , finishes dry .
pours a bright orange color , slightly carbonated , with a thick pillowy off-white head .  the mouhtfeel was light and lacked body .

poured into an imperial pint glass , formed a 1 1/2 '' tan head over the slightly cloudy dark reddish amber brew . frothy head lasts and lasts , with plenty of dwelling lace .  m : starts off creamy , but i 'm pretty quickly struck by how watery this is . the carbonation is decent , but i find this surprisingly thin .

poured almost pitch black , good size tan foamy head that diminished to a tan creamy collar that held the sides of the glass all the way down .  it is about a medium mouthfeel , with almost no carbonation .

a - clear ruby brown with a thick white head that has excellent retention and fairly decent lacing .  the palate is bland , sweet , and clean . the strongest aspect of this beer is its mouthfeel , it is medium , sturdy carbonation , very basic but appropriate .

this ones a nice deep brown color with a big fluffy tan head and pretty amazing lacing .  m : lighter than it should be and very creamy and smooth , decent carbonation . f : long creamy chocolate vanilla smoothness .

a clear copper colour with a 2 finger head of foam . it 's ok , especially during the hot days of summer . head retention turns out to be excellent as is the lacing .  rated as a stout the mouthfeel is a bit thin , the carbonation is a bit high , and the finish is a bit less than one would expect .

well it was a damn fine pour in to the imperial pint glass right to the top a deep clear copper , with a quick to vanish one finger head.somewhat downhill from there i have to say aromas of hard water and fruit but light and that clear/green bottle skunk but i wont hold it against the actual beer itself.flavors are ok it has the english fruitiness a touch of brown sugar and iron but not much hop presence just a light herbal note in the finish after a few sips.quite light for a 6.5 % alc beer goes down easily just nothing to make u want more , a decent beer none the less to be had .  the body is medium with decent carbonation .
s : smell of yeast and coriander that gives way to banana . t : taste not as complex as the smell , but still pleasing .  m : a bit thin , i was kind of expecting it to be a bit more viscous .

location cellar 70 serving 22oz the scent of this piva is spot on and really is inviting . i have n't had any other coffee stouts , so i am by far means an expert .  the mouth was a bit oily but not unpleasantly so .

a : this dark lager poured a beautiful clear amber color that showed off a ton of carbonation . i was extremely impressed by the appearance of this beer .  mouthfeel medium full for the style with carbonation that is a bit too strong for my taste .

i 've always put off reviewing this thinking perhaps i 'm not getting it at it 's freshest , but it is perpetually average so here we go ... start with the positive.. good looking beer .  picked up a few of these `` oil cans '' at a local liquor mart . this is the only place i 've seen them . i like the regular fosters occasionally , and have fond memories of it from various parties and times in life . after looking at the color , noticed that the can said `` caramel coloring added , '' so nothing real to go by there . i liked this , i guess , but the drinkablility was hampered by a fakey sort of bitterness that did n't hold a candle to the fuller 's and young 's of the world . kind of caught in my throat . i pick up the regular if it 's on special , but for a real bitter , this ai n't it .
appearance & gt ; lovely golden amber hue . lively .  kind of leaves your mouth feeling very acidic .
pours a clear amber/brown , huge thick off white head forms , great retention , excellent lacing .  a little too thick on the tongue , but nice .

very nice start of a semi-grainy and fully malted pilsner barley . delicious .  im stoked i can try a beer from this brewery even tho it is a collaboration but ive got nothing but good things to say about mikkeller and heard good reviews on these other two so looking forward to it , it pours a very light honey hue with decent carbonation that leaves a one finger head with sporadic lacing , the aroma is floral hops , apricot , bananna and a nice belgian yeasty aroma too , it has an average mouthfeel for the style almost syrupy and has tastes of yeasty bread , citrus and of course a pleasant floral hop finish with the alcohol well hidden , this is definately an easy beer to drink and if it didnt cost $ 18 ( aus ) i could drink it all night .

canned on 10/26/2011 a : pours a deep , clear ruby color with a finger of thick light tan colored head .  this has the syrupy goodness of the 90-minute , but with an added syrupiness ... robust and smooth , like a desert sauce , you could pour this over a bowl of vanilla ice cream instead of a caramel sauce , with its own french vanilla creaminess ... the only thing that detracts here is an odd light metallic twinge at the finish that didnt seem to fit . otherwise , this is a beaut of a big beer with a light profile .

smell : delicious and complex . truly a melange of different aromas . coffee bean , caramel , toffee , chocolate . wonderfully palatable . drinkability : very drinkable . excellent complexity of flavors .  m- just average .

s : roasted malt is very prevalent and dominates right away . lots of great stuff going on in the aroma . t : as in the nose , sweet roasted malt is the main characteristic .  m - very carbonated , to the point that it almost stings on the way down .

loving the smell ... sweet oats , grain . - wonderful zingy porter ... nice bitter earthy hop.. and a backdrop of sweet oats and chocolate malt ... a very pleasant and drinkable porter .  the mouthfeel has a strange little zing that seems inappropriate for the style .
pours a clear orange , chunks , one of the coolest looking heads ever , kind of a reverse cascading tan , head goes fast , some lace .  more carbonation would go a long way .
appearance : good frothing and great head retention , the pale amber hue shows an active carbonation and a brilliant clarity .  the taste is also fresh but a with bit of watery mouthfeel .
lovely auburn red color blows me away .  m : medium to light body with medium to low carbonation . would have preferred a bigger body by far .
1pt 9oz flip top bottle - 5.4 % abv c : pours a nice hazy golden sunflower color with a lot of head and substantial visible carbonation .  m_slightly below medium bodied and very effervescent .
a beautiful , reminiscent of the normal guinness cream top decks this dark copper colored beer . blanket lacing .  m : very smooth , but seems pretty thin in terms of the body of the beer .

this is one of the best smelling beers i have ever had .  i was not a big fan of the mouthfeel of this one . i 'm all for thick imperial stouts , but somehow this one was much more syrupy than i liked , it felt a little to sticky sweet in my mouth .

poured with a firm sturdy , foamed up head .  with all of the flying dog beers this one has the most bitter taste . yet it does remind me of my earlier beer brewing expreriences ! i always enjoyed the yeasty taste and smell of beer . and this one really has that aroma . flying dog is a great brewery that is slowly becoming a well known micro all over the country ! this only means that they will be bought out by a mega brewery or they will change their formulation all together !

aroma vomits forth ripe , rich fruits . raisin paste and juicy plum notes jump out of the glass from a distance . the slightest hint of raw cocoa beans top off this exotic nasal medley . still , tastewise , there are better dubbels . it 's no 12 , but it 's a solid beer wrapped in an exquisite package . worth a try , glad i did .  mouthfeel is off a little bit , maybe undercarbonated .

pours a honey golden hue , translucent and bright , with generous white head . lots of lacing and creamy goodness on the head . only negative is that it is incredibly watery & light .  m - thinner body , bubbly from both the carbonation the spice .

s - a fantastic aroma of lemony citrus and wheat with pale malts and a light bouquet of floral hops . the thing that totally makes the aroma is the wonderful funk from the brett yeast . tiny fruit esters of mango and pineapple from the yeast also play a small but delicious role . very complex and inviting . t - a bright sour funk bursts across the tongue right away bringing with it that barnyard and horse-blanket that is so good . it 's definitely a lively beer . d - i 'm really happy i 'm sharing this cause a 750 ml to myself would be devastating for two reasons ; a ) to my sobriety , and b ) to my taste-buds .  mouthfeel is surprisingly tingly and sharp from the tiny carbonation and i suspect a hop i ca n't discern in either the aroma or taste . mouthfeel is unfortunately a little weak and thin for style to my mind .
dark , but clear with ruby/purple highlights . fine beige foam , really sticky with sheets of bubbles coating the glass . good head retention too .  a little thin .

smell : extremely tart , cherries , acid , mushroom , funk/barn/horseblanket , leather and oak taste : extremely sour , i could n't get the taste of this one out of my mouth till dinner the next day . similar to the smell , vinegar , lots of must/mold , leather , oak , and sour/tart cherries .  the mouth feel is medium bodied , smooth yet singular . a light presence of the carbonation followed by some bitterness .

what a crazy story ... a - a tall pour creates totally huge cascading that ends in a three+ finger head with awesome retention .  this is a man 's beer . none of this flowery wine swilling critique lingo . light color , smell and mouth feel , who really cares . outstanding dry & hoppy flavor without sweetness . when bought in the 30 pack , cost is about 50 cents each . the best macro being produced !
coffee dominates the nose and overpowers the other smells that are underneath . nevertheless , the smell is very enticing .  body was very light and thin .
12oz bottle - 2006 edition pours a clear mahogany brown with rich ruby highlights .  4.5/5 m : crisp , medium body .
smell : funky dog , tart , lemon , peach . mouthfeel : medium body and medium-high carbonation overall : nice to try , but unbalanced .  m - medium body , not a lot of carbonation .

a : gorgeous crystal clear orange amber with a tall white head that falls to a lacy white ring s : althought this beer has a reputation for a huge citrous presence , i am not getting a lot of that - hops seem more grassy and muted more than anything else t : relatively malty balance for an ipa - hops are coming through at the end with some grapefruit and a clean bitter finish m : med-full mouthfeel and just a bit warm - especially warm for the style o : i 'm really wondering how what i 'm drinking matches up to what i 've read about this beer - the comments and reviews by others seem all over the map ( cloudy vs clear , hoppy vs malty , big vs little etc ) .  a really really long aftertaste in the nose .

a - pours a gorgeous bright and translucent dark copper color with some nice golden and slight amber hints . very good retention . almost perfect looking beer .  this beer has a flavor i really like m- pretty thin and bubbly , almost reminds me of a bmc feel o- one of my favorite tasting pale ales .

probably one of the more amazing lager aromas , it 's truly crisp and fresh , i could smell it all day . the flavours are light , but the aromas quite amazing . indeed overall this beer is much better than even most european lagers .  a good beer . comes in a .33ml brown bottle , part of a 6 pack sampler from brouwerij van steenberge . a sweet and dark beer , where hops has taken a back seat to the malt profile . not light , but not heavy either . give it a try .

reviewed 1/8/2008 ( bottle ) : pours a golden somewhat cloudy yellowish color . big foamy frothy white head with good lacing .  mouthfeel is a bit fizzy , and another beer where bottle-conditioning would have a positive impact .
a very nice looking beer .  mouthfeel : typical red stickyness drinkability : i love this beer .

app : deep amber clear . very thick fluffy white head w/lace .  ripped some cd 's with itunes and did n't pay much attention to the rest of the beverage until i listened to `` parachute woman '' by the stones and realized my head was already buzzing , hey , is this really 7.0 abv ? even though lent is over , i could subsist on this brew until easter , especially if it is cold and damp outside , but it 's not , it 's warm and sunny , and i have to plant some hostas and spread some weed-n-feed . in theory this beer will go well with my lunch of cold leftover spring rolls ( heresy !

lovely , bright cherry red color ... head is large at first , simmers down quickly ... aroma : mmmmm ... .complex ! quite a rich and invigorating aroma , i postpone consumption to prolong my time drinking it deep into the nose ... really nice !  the body is sufficient to carry the 10 percent alcohol which is impressive by itself . some spicy notes and an effervescent type of feel to it .

head clumping is visible and the head retention is well overall . moderate lacing and pretty clear .  tastes like , yeah , tart blueberries ( probably artificial blueberries ) . just sweet & weird & sweet ... really tough to finish one . much like a cheap , too-tart wine cooler .
clear brown color with a strong pillowy off-white head .  the mouthfeel is a little thin but the taste lingers and somehow gets better after the beer passes through my esophagus .
a : light brown pour with a good light tan head that leaves lace on the glass after about 1-2 fingers of head .  mouthfeel is medium with more carbonation that i expected due to no head showing up .

very pleasant aroma t- a slight fruitiness with a hint of caramel . slight hoppiness , intially good , but after taste left something to be desired m- slightly heavy , definately not light .  texture is smooth but only slightly fizzy , leaving a slightly sweet fruity finish .

500 ml bottle this gluten free beer poured a clear , golden color with fizzy carbonation and good , white foam that persisted , clung to the glass , and left lacing .  mouthfeel : thin yet flavorful .

poured an opaque ink jet black with a nice khaki head with good lacing .  i 've been waiting to try this one for some time now and it was well worththe wait ! i could smell it 's fruity aroma as soon as i opened the bottle , it has a nice dark cloudy amber color to it that is topped with a nice thick head . it goes down very smooth and just warms up your mouth , and you can really taste the spices in it .

pours a deep brown , transparent with an off white head . huge head that sticks to the glass and remains about and inch thick . tight head , quite beautiful .  is this someones idea of a joke ? rotten peaches with a kick of dirty feet is not something i prefer in my beer . sour an nasty , she be . i should have know by the pour , cider apple yellow fizzy white head . cripe , im glad i only got 2 bottles of this overpriced ( $ 2.50 a pop ) sour peach soda geez , only 4.5 % . i would have kicked myself in the sack for buying this , but im no longer that agile .

ahh , the smell makes up for the poor visual aspect ... it is phenomenal ! nonetheless , this is an outstanding nose . barrel aging is very evident upon tasting , as is the alcohol . to me , it almost seems like a tripel and a half , as it needs a bit more body-adding malts and the alcohol is a bit rough ... but that is being a bit picky , i am very glad i brought this out for my 500th .  slightly under carbonated for my taste but not really a flaw .

4.5 s : dry hopping has done wonders . tons of mango . after that comes pineapple , grapefruit , and orange . balancing maltiness with caramel and breadiness from the yeast . 3.5 d : decent , but nothing special .  the carbon dioxide is rich but not too aggressive .

the smell is perfect , like cranberries , very tart and almost bitter . you can really smell this all the way up your nose .  mf : relatively light body with medium to high carbonation . would like a little more body , but the flavor more than makes up for it .

bottle from the lcbo the 2008 vintage has held its own agaist the 2007. black with a lovely tan head .  t/m - dense oak , leather , wet hay and barnyard notes , freshly cut grass maybe some dark fruits like apricot and/or figs ; short-lived citrus hops up front and a cloyingly long , drying finish . almost reminds me of dry vermouth . the mossy barnyard notes developed nicely . d - the drying effect would probably limit me to just one of these , a nicely developed saison for spring and summer .

smell - a wonderful yeast or dough or wheat smell dominates , with orange or another citrus fruit tagging along . irresistibly smooth finish , tastes much the way it smells although the wheat is less noticeable .  mouthfeel was the only thing i was n't too keen on- felt a little spritzer-ish .

top of the line nose on this one , just fantastic . my first impression was damn ! the consensus was this was an excellent beer , & there was a marked difference once it warmed - a collection of `` yeah , it 's ok '' changed to `` damn , this is good '' after 10-15 minutes . really glad i got to try this one , thanks again tucker !  mouthfeel is a little light for a beer this big , but that would likely improve with age . carbonation is a tad too prickly for my personal tastes .
thick foamy tan head that lasted pretty well , and nice lacing .  more watery flavored than i expected from this ... very light mouthfeel .
poured a beautiful amber color . wonderful lacing . just a beautiful beer .  mouthfeel is light and carbonation fades to almost flat .

the aroma shows some nice complexity of aged bourbon , madeira , charred wood , vanilla & plum with some rich chocolate & caramel touched by just a hint of spicy , floral hops . very nice ! the flavor starts off with some grainy sweetness with a solid caramel character , but gives way to an edgy underlying bitterness that creates a fruity , off-dry , boozy/winey finish .  mouthfeel : light/ medium body with excessive carbonation that somewhat hinders the flavor .

smells of cinnamon rolls , predominant oak , very bready , some dark fruits , raisins in particular , some bourbon , unbelievably complex . tastes of sweet caramel breadiness with dark fruit undertones . a nice wave of breadiness follows with something slightly funky , cheesy almost . almost no carbonation , nice sweet mouthfeel , alcohol is scary hidden . a very interesting beer , lots of complexities . that said , i was blown away by the different flavors that passed over my tongue with every sip , one after another , incredibly complex . a very sweet beer and a treat , careful of the alcohol , dangerously hidden .  mouthfeel features more carbonation than i 'd like for a big beer like a barleywine .
i love the appearence of this beer , the deep dark color and the nice tan foamy head make for an inviting glass .  the mouthfeel is decent , but could be a bit more robust to support the flavors .

this is a really great nose . tastes not quite as good as it smells , but still solid . smells great and is solid all around - worth a shot .  a wonderful beer . one i have had before , and thought it would be great for the new year . it 's dark brown hue and brownish colored head was delightful . the taste of cocoa and hops pleased my nose . the roasted flavors were soothing , but left a little bit of an after taste .

pours crystal clear orange-amber color with a dense 2 finger off white head with great retention that reduces to a fairly thick lacing cap that lasts the entire glass .  medium bodied , highly carbonated .

good strength and good harmony between the components . the nose is awesome , but that 's the only thing that is .  rolling carbonation augments the already full feel making seem more boisterous than perhaps it is . carbonation is too much for me .

appearance : pours a beautiful hazy dark amber color with a finger of foamy off white head that leaves a little bit of lacing and good retention .  m - light bodied , not overly carbonated , clean finish , mild fruity aftertaste fades quickly .
this smells amazing . brings back memories of the cherry topping my mother used to make to go along with her cheese blintzes .  mouthfeel is a little too tingly for me with the carbonation .
the aroma is strong and super sweet . at the end is a nice hint of the wood . the finish is wood and alcohol . overall , this was ok. its very similar to the utopias to me .  sticky mouthfeel .

looks beautiful and inviting !  the feel is the only drawback here . it was rather light in body , and thin feeling . carbonation was adequate , but it just lacked that `` near medium '' that i would expect from a dipa .

smells awesome ; there 's an herbal hoppiness with orange/tangerine notes , some slight pine , and lots of biscuit/nutty malt with an undertone of sweet caramel . it finishes with a clean bitterness and biscuity malt .  it was barely palatable : very little carbonation - full of sour , gone-bad notes .
billowy white rocky head . decent bubbling .  m - this is like any cheaply made micro lager in japan .
pours a deep golden yellow with an inch or so of resilient white foam . offers good retention and sticky lacing .  m- low carbonation and very low mouthfeel .

the appearance was impressive , very black with a nice brown head .  t : bitter chocolates and cold black coffee .mmmmm m : a bit thin in the mouthfeel , slight warming in the finish which i found dry .

there was also a good bit of effervesence in a brew that was a beautiful golden-yellow color . there was decent head retention throughout and the `` belgian lace '' that was left behind was beautiful .  12 oz bottle poured into weizen glass , only glass i could get at my buddy 's house a : great pale golden color , light head with decent retention , great clarity s : great floral aromas t : not a pale ale that is actually an ipa , not overly bitter and slight maltiness m : good carbonation , could be a little thinner o : great pale ale , not just a copy of other american pale ales .
the aroma is deliciously hoppy with some citrus notes .  m & d - the brew is a tiny bit watery , the doughy character is a tiny bit too small , and so the mouthfeel is n't as full as i 'd expect .
if you like that sort of thing , then here is your poison . the color was very pleasant , very nice eye-candy .  the mouthfeel was a bit unimpressive too light in my opinion .

s - full of fruity aromas : grapefruit , cantaloupe , and oranges . some sweet foral scents as well .  despite the nearly opaque black color , the flavor of this one is surprisingly light . there are sweet malt notes , a delicious fruitiness and some fairly rich yeasty , estery notes . i keep over-looking this brewery , but every time i try one of their beers im usually pretty impressed . this particular beer is tasty , refined and very drinkable . recommended .

appearance : as poured the beer is clear copper/bronze color with a `` white head that soon recedes to a thin patch of foam , a ring around the glass and some thick foam sticking to the sides of the glass .  m- the mouthfeel is a little lighter than expected , almost watered down .

my mouth is watering s - super floral , i do n't even need to put my nose that close to get wonderful citrus and pine notes t - a bit sweet to me . m - sweetness sticks a the tongue to much , leaves a sugary oily aftertaste , decent carbonation o - a good ipa , but not the best  mouthfeel- medium body with very little carbonation .
pours beautifully , flat opaque black with a thick chocolate milk-colored head that dissipated but not too quickly .  mouthfeel : a bit thin and watery .

one of the prettiest looking beers i 've seen , a reddish cloudy haze glows from within , with a pink thick bubbly head .  chocolaty to dark brown in appearance with a light head . great smell of toffee , roasted barley . taste conjures up images of coffee shops , candy stores , with the roasted barley presence as well as that bitter coffee taste , balanced by sweet toffee notes and a hint of hops . great tasting beer . my first milk stout , and it did n't disappoint .

devastatingly attractive . dried herb in color . brilliant nose . obviously aged and incredibly smooth on the palate but the cellaring destroyed the hop presense .  m - it drys out in the mouth a little too quickly for me .
pretty impressive for what i 'm reviewing as a wee-heavy .  could use more carbonation .

a : this is a very beautiful looking beer . the head is absolutely amazing , with perfect color and form . the color is a very dark brown or black , depending on how much light is on it .  mouthfeel : a little thin , medium body , low carbonation , medium flavor . underwhelming mouth .
nose is a sweet mix of yeasty malt with creamy fresh fruity notes , almost mellon like .  there was a very light mouthfeel , but an extremely dry , crisp finish .

aroma is very intriguing . predominantly grapefruit , but there 's a real presence of orange fragrance in the vein of an orange-scented candle from one of those ( apologies for the terminology here ) `` girlie '' stores . very interesting . light citrus flavor upfront .  mouthfeel is grainy and oily , body is medium to thin , carbonation is sharp .
this beer poured a cloudy deep gold that bordered on light amber . it 's pure white head was thick and rich , solid lacing adorned the glass .  feel is also a bit thin and fizzy .
poured a nice orange/golden color with a very large bubbly head which remained for a long time and left average lacing . an excellent looking beer .  light body with a very active carbonation .
aroma is amazing ; quite flowery , tangy , fruity , with some yeast and a perfume presence .  m : fairly thick , carbonation seems a tad high .

head is a bright off white , watery and light , not much retention or lacing ... outstanding aroma , very funky floral muskyness , some nice brett ... taste has some nice things going , this is a musky sour brett saison , not sweetness , makes no bones about it . crushable musky saison , well worth trying .  i had this beer at the great waters facility as we stop in often . i try to take notes on the beers i try but sometimes forget . the attack was very smooth and there was a sweet and smooth flavor with faint hops character at the finish . i do n't think i have had any cask beers at great waters that i did n't like .
appearance is flawless . it 's a very dark ruby with a billowing pillow of foam and great lacing .  m : average , carb . levels are good .

appearance - deep red , 3 fingers of head which reduced .  i 'm not getting much in the way of bitterness anywhere here , which combines with a medium thin body to provide very little in the way of a finish .

it 's unfortunate that such an incredible looking beer would have so little else working for it . appearance - dark , brooding .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied to me . could be a little thicker on the tongue .
rgc pours a deep red-cognac color with generous carbonation and a settling tan head .  thin bodied , and just sufficient carbonation , but i suspect the growler is at fault much more than the beer .

appearance : pours a slightly hazy ruby-brown with an inch of foamy off-white head on top . head is slow to settle leaving behind a nice lace along the glass . aroma : bottle depicts oranges , though the aroma is more a tart cherry with some hints of sweetness .  all of the good notes that a belgian has , with some american notes such as a much higher rate carbonation , more citric fruitiness . the high carbonation almost makes me question whether or not it 's natural , but i doubt stone would rape this brew with added co2 like the macros do .

i thought is was a hefe at first , but upon tasting , i was corrected . smells of a crisp hop dryness and mandarin orange . the hops carry over in to the taste but it is backed by an odd cheerios like grain .  very basic but very good m= average carbonation and average weight .

smell- figs ! drinkability- deciptively drinkable , i could finish up this bottle in a hurry and then find out that it 's 10 % abv afterward . nice .  the mouthfeel is a little lacking in carbonation too .
it looks like a very refreshing and tasty beer . crystal clear straw colored beer , again looks very refreshing .  mouthfeel is medium bodied . lots of carbonation , almost too much .

it pours a beautiful clear coppery-brown with just a little head .  had to give it the maximum points for appearance , because even out of an imported bottle , it looks just right . comes in with an alcohol bite that 's almost like an imperial . pertty nice taste , though , and if you had some , i would n't refuse .

smell : lovely aroma of apples , pears , and light citrus - notably grapefruit . slightly sour smell comes in at the end . a very sour character shows up that is a bit cloying , then the beer finishes strong and unpleasantly bitter .  it is medium-bodied with soft carbonation and seems perhaps more watery than i 'd expect . it leaves the mouth feeling a bit astringent .

s - sweet hop delight . much stronger hop aroma than doppelbocks i have had before . earthy hop aroma with a very sweet scent as well .  m : a little bit thinner than expected , medium-light bodied with low carbonation , lightly creamy .
there is tons of lacing as well . this beer is a very pretty one .  m - a little water , but it goes down smoothly d - this is a really good beer .
huge tan head after a normal pour , looks very nice .  mouthfeel if very alive and crisp at first sip . maybe a bit overpowering on the carbonation .
s - very nice . sweet . i like it a lot . very different than most beers of this style .  m - a little watery for the style , but not objectionable .

a big fluffy ice cream scoop of a head , eventually smooths out to about a quarter inch . for a lager this is a very good looking beer .  t - again , bicuit and nut . nice and malty , virtually no hop bite , but tasty none the less . d - i have had this a ton in the past , but i only just got around to getting another one for the purposes of reviewing .

exceptional smell of toffee , caramel , nutty . wanted to eat something that smelled like this . slightly bitter note on the nose . sweet with a more bitter nutty taste .  mouthfeel is smooth , crisp and almost watery , with medium carbonation and a medium body .

excellent . sweet and sour fruits cominate the taste , but caramel malts creep slowly in , along with alcohol , honey , and even some wood . the feel ends up pleasantly sweet and smooth .  mouthfeel too prickly and astringent but medium body is appropriate for style .

absolutely amazing grapefruit , lemon , and orange aroma . also has a touch of sweet toffee and vanilla . this was a beautiful hazy golden pour , with typical cask frothy head . very well balanced flavor , then a wonderful dry bitter finish . this is an amazing brew , and the cask only adds to it .  best as it warmed , when the malt flavors of chocolale and toffee become a bit more complex and the mouthfeel seems fuller .

looked great on the pour . hazy apricot with a thin wispy head .  it 's viciously acidic , but tasty . i like acidic ... i 'll drink straight malt vinegar . this is fizzy alcoholic pomegranate juice with nothing to resemble beer to my palate . i would n't hold `` not tasting like beer '' against a legitimate ale beverage , which i 'm sure this is , except that i like beer , and i do n't like this .

pours a deep amber ruby body with a nice modest off white head . smells of a massive combination of strong barley wine and oak . there 's flavors of raisons , plums and caramel on the nose with lots of vanilla and toasted notes from the oak . bourbon and dark fruit play out initially .  the beer poured hard but the carbonation ended up being low and the mouthfeel medium .

aroma : it has that rare smell that is as full and alluring as you 'd hope it would taste : banana bread , roasted chestnuts , cloves , hints of chocolate , estery and phenolic notes . the finish is very clean , with lingering bits of pepper and chalky dark chocolate . mouthfeel : it has a very smooth feel even though the carbonation is quite prickly . the dark malts give it a fuller and more flavorful character than most saisons , although incorporating them also reduces the peppiness and refreshment of a traditional saison . would i get it again ? : yes . it 's a solid beer , and though not the pinacle of its style , a welcome alternative to traditional saisons . bottled : february 25 , 2011 served : may 6 , 2011 price = $ 8.99 at whole foods ( nyc ) additional notes : - international bitterness units : 30 - malt : pilsner , rye , crystal rye , black malt - hops : pilgrim , saaz  i almost gag every time i take a sip of this . tastes like day-old miller high life with some bread , chocolate , and coffee mixed in . it looks like cola , and at first it smells like oh , say , a bottle of old milwaukee . if only it tasted even half as good as old milwaukee . please , for your own sake , stay away .
black with a solid 1 finger tan head with excellent retention and lacing .  medium carbonation .

from a brown 12 oz.bottle , cute dog , no date . poured a cloudy golden orange with a thick , dense , white head that almost topped the bottle before i began to pour , and left nice lacing .  m - moderate carbonation-almost too much , dry finish , medium bodied due to the carbonation .
appearance is good - clear chestnut color with a pretty good cream colored head that sticks around awhile .  mouf & gt ; sudsy .

comes out of the tap looking brown and alive . absolutely perfect lacing . one of the best looking beers i 've ever had the pleasure of admiring .  t : wood chips , obviously , tastes like a sauna smells , charcoal , molasses , savory like breakfast sausage , soy sauce , real sharp sweetness that 's broken down by hops lurking in the background and that 's absent at the finish m : medium body , very low carbonation , i 'm surprised this was n't the cask ( it was n't but they did have it ) , dry bitter charcoal finish . the mouthfeel was a big drawback for me , it was very flat , considering this was the draft veraion .

pretty nice ; once i got used to it i really started to like it .  very ashy , very charred , and it really lacks some body and sweetness to back up the astringency . feel is very light , a shame , because a thick , chewy , silky body is a necessity in the style .

bam noire pours a dark brown that approaches black . ruby red highlights can be seen along the edges of my chimay chalice . fully inch of creamy tan head that refuses to die down . tons of thick webbed lacing .  great big head , perfectly tempting aroma , somewhat thin mouthfeel .
i was excited at first , as it came to me looking dark and frothy , and the smell was nutty and malty .  mouthfeel/overall : the body is very light , and it has pretty high carbonation .
the appearance is a perfect amber .  it was pretty smooth for stout and for for the alcohol content . i tried it with a few other beers .

i know this is a beer and should smell like one but this smells really good to me , reminds me of candy apples when i was a tyke .  m - fairly zesty and zingy carbonation that left me feeling a touch bloated after a third of a glass . medium-light body that also has a bit of grain character .
the appearance was stellar . it was a murky amber color with a beautiful head .  m- a little thin , but not too bad . nicely carbonated , with a slight bitter hoppiness at the tail end .

summer : clear gold in color with a huge , meringue like white head that really hangs around for a while . winter : dark copper pour with a big , lasting , frothy , off-white head and good lacing .  nice aroma of hops but i would hope for a bit more being a hops lover . the celebration ale , from the same company , seems to hit the spot more than this beer but still worthy of a place in the fridge and still better than many micro beer ipa ii . sierra nevada seems to me to be the only mass beer company that brews excellent beer for `` mass beer '' prices .
smells sweet and malty with a really nice hop presence . i 'm excited to taste based on this smell .  mouthfeel - very enjoyable borderline complex character .

the smell is nice and wheaty . definitely smell the 12 percent .  500ml bottle served in a shaker glass.enjoyed on oct11.melon yellow in color.haze appearance.white close & dense crown.good retention leaving lasting lacing collars.citrics & hints of melon to the nose , some banana hues.sour upfront then a pleasant sweet malty flavor comes , subtle spicy hues too.slightly astringent notes.medium body.medium carbonation.rough but gentle finish.refreshing.well balanced flavors .

viscous notes , along with minimal head retention & lacing s : orchard fruit , grainyness , & pineapple t : peaches , pineapple , honey , boozey grain & a kiss of estery yeast & mushroom like funk .  the mouthfeel is sort of watery , but it 's alright . this drinks very well .

could n't decipher a date code on this one , so not sure how old/new it is ... pours an absolutely beautiful pitch black color with a deep tan foamy head .  mouthfeel : a bit thin in body but makes up with an even overall texture not much carbonation very wine like with each sip .
appearance : very much a rich dark brown color that lets no light through . great measure of head .  the mouthfeel seems a bit week and flat , but it 's not bad .

s- huge floral hop aroma escapes from the glass . t- extremely flavorful , very hoppy with a hoppy grapefruit finish . d- exceptionally drinkable .  mouthfeel : this is the one downside of this beer ; it 's just a bit thin .

the beer after its removal from the 12-ounce brown bottle resides in my glass a pitch-black color with a moderate sized creamy tan head and after its decomposition , the lace forms a thick and sticky sheet upon the glass .  m & d = carbonation stings a little more than i would like , has good medium body but mouthcoating , while medium , is a little less than i would have preferred .

appearance : pours a beautiful dark amber with a finger of light tan head that leaves some lacing and a ring around the edge of the glass .  taste was pretty balanced with a bit of malt sweetness . overall i liked this one . this is the first beer i have tried from boulder . based on this one , i 'll have to try some of the others that we can get in ct . the website says that a secret spice is added , but i can not really taste any spice . maybe i 'll figure it out by the time i finish the six . good brew .

s-this beer has a nice sweet flower aroma with hints of roses and apricots .  i was disappointed by this beer . it 's also obvious a lot of quality ingredients went into this brew . it was as if they intended to toast something , left it heating too long and then used it in the beer anyway . so my opinion may not apply to all bottles of this beer ever made . the finish was so bitter/burnt ( and someone else said aspirin-like , and i agree ) that drinking a whole one was difficult , and i found i did not want another when i was done . i do like brown ales , and i 've never tasted one that tasted like this . if the brewer is reading , this will be an abomination to him . the result is quite nice , with the bitterness now toned down to just one note in the chord and the revelation of some of that band-aid-like taste i associate with belgians . i 'm on the second mixed brew now , and i must say i 'm quite enjoying it this way .

a : the pour is a deep dark brown , essentially black , with a fluffy tan head .  flavour is better than expected- a little woody and slightly spicy , with a thick strong maltiness . i 'd like the hearty body on this one , were it not for the turbocharged carbonation .

poured a beautifully clear , clean amber golden color , with a huge 3 finger , frothy , white head . lacing was incredible on this one , totally covered from the top to the bottom of the glass when finished .  the carbonation is surprisingly strong for the style .

s : great smelling beer . c-hops and american malts . potent nose . d : great beer , absolutely delicious , with the delicate touch of a masterful brewer .  like the aroma , there was a maple hint somewhere in there but it was incredibly hard to get the taste and keep it , it was very slippery . the cloying sweetness kept me from even finishing the beer and my girlfriend refused the rare chance to finish one of my drinks after trying it herself .

very nice . nose is absolutely beautiful with belgian chocolate , rich cocoa , caramel , toffee . smells like this one is going to be a whopper ... ... and sadly it 's not . finish is very clean and crisp . the nose , however , is truly wonderful so one should at least experience that .  m : the feel is slightly creamy but on the lighter side of medium bodied . could be a bit thicker here ... d : if you like coffee beers i could see someone drinking good amount of these .
s- has a nice old ale smell with similarities to thomas hardy 's and the like . the smell is this beers strong suit .  thin to medium bodied with moderate carbonation .

a : pours opaque jet black with a formidable tan head -- nice retention .  dare i say it seems a bit on the thin side . the meatiness in the flavor is not backed up by the body . not bad , but just a little disappointing ... this is a fine stout .

clear reddish amber with a rich firm tan head .  a : pours a dark brown with a two finger head ; burnt orange around the edges of the glass when held to light ; lacing is excellent s : smells of caramel and coffee ; very earthy aroma t : tastes like a bitter coffee initially , but the sweetness of caramel and honey slowly creeps in m : i think its a bit too watery and the carbonation does not seem right d : two in a sitting is nice ; i 'm generally not a porter fan , but i enjoyed this beer
poured into a pint glass , this radiant beer had a crisp , clear orange body and a thick white head .  m : light but slightly creamy body .
dugana pours beautifully for a 2.5 finger thick off white head , with great retention .  the palate is somewhat thin for the style but it 's still smooth .

the smell has a great citrus/banana smell to it that captions your nose the second you pour into a glass . very satisfied with the smell . taste - the taste is very good . the smell and taste together make this an exceptional beer to drink .  the mouthfeel is just a little light and watery .

s-what comes through first is a perfect balance of sweet caramel malt and a blast of citrus hops . d- this brew is pretty awesome . brews that emphasize the citrus/spicy hop combo are hard to come by and this one does an excellent job with it .  m : okay , mostly wet and satisfyingly quaffable , but with a noticeable alcohol presence in the finish .
pours a massive , incredibly thick , dense and chunky white head that is long lasting .  m : the body is medium and so is the carbonation .

pours a jet black wth a huuge , really tight brown head that retains really well , beautiful !  it 's sort of smokey but in an artificial way . rubber and alcohol . the rubber turned into a slightly smokey malt flavor but still lingered in there . alcohol dominated any sort of flavors coming through . i just did n't enjoy this beer at all . if i ever cross paths again with this beer i 'll re-review it .

the beer poured a beautiful translucent red colour with a 1 inch tan coloured head .  the rye is evident , as is a tangy almost sour note along with the bread . a little over-carbonated ... i found it slightly distracting and that it may have affected my enjoyment of the beer 's complexity . light-bodied and very refreshing . while i have little to no experience with beers of this style , i enjoyed this one and i believe that its a great refresher during the summer months .

cranberry nose with traces of brett-like peppery suede funkiness ( either from the kombucha or actual brett ) , black cherry , dried peaches , honey , and cider . it 's one of the most distinct and delicious smelling beers i 've come across in a while . it 's clever enough to inspire analysis , while still being relatively drinkable , in spite of the co2 struggles .  m - average mouthfeel . carbonation on par , but a very thin feeling brew .
convict hill oatmeal stout pours a solid black with ample dark brown head .  the beer feels just a bit thin on the tongue .

poured into my pint glass the beer is dark chocolate brown bordering on black . the dark mocha head bursts to full three fingers and flirts with going over the top edge of my glass . after a brief rest the head fades leaving a small cap and no lace .  drinkability - taste is pretty good , stays consistent throughout , isnt too thin , and has a reasonable abv so overall this would be a good beer to have a few of if you options are limited .
appearance : orange/amber body with a nice two finger head .  the mouthfeel is much like an american macro lager , but a bit wimpy .

really nice nose on this . a big whiff of belgian yeast , revealing dark fruits and a faint hint of very bitter cocoa . after a few nose dives in this one i 've become a bit used to the yeast smell and richer chocolate notes are revealed as well as a faint alcohol aroma .  drank in a chalice from a bottle in brussels at delirium cafe.. this is very good lambic . it smells great very sweet with cherries . the beer has a beautiful red/brown color with a white head , not a lot lacing . it tastes sweet with cherries dominating but has a nice sour kick too .

sweet and sugary , but delicious and unique . alcohol is absolutely brutal on this bitch as the heat slaps you in the face with the force of 10,000 fighting japanese midget minnow farmers .  the beer seems to thin a bit in the mouthfeel . very clean beer for a triple , slightly thin in the mouthfeel , but that helps give this beer a nice clean dry finish .

a careful pour produces a robust , sandy colored , three-finger head with excellent retention and lacing .  a very special thanks to zeke at the speakeasy for sharing a bottle of this 1995 treat . it still had carbonation in it which was crazy . the beer was very dry at this point . the spiciness of this beer has been cut down from the aging .

appearance : a massive white head sits atop a slightly hazy golden body . classic looks and perfect presentation for a tripel .  this cask had not dropped bright or was a few days past where it should have been , my guess is that they put it out too early or the servers that placed the keg out rolled it out from the back and mixed all of the yeast back into the brew . full of yeast yeast in the aroma and flavour , just down right crappy cask what a disappointment .

a- clear auburn and orange , massive three finger fluffy/foamy white head , excellent retent s- hops , oily and leafy , citrus and caramel t- just as hoppy as it smells , hop flavored alcoholic heat at finish , grape skin , grapefruit , caramel , butterscotch , fruit like characters , hop oils m- medium body , lots of alcoholic heat , dry after , smooth , hops abuse palate much d- lots of interesting things happening here , but i think the alcohol presence was out of control , not to mention this might as just be hop juice .  drinkability : mouthfeel is a little thin , but this is a very solidly crafted stout , up there with the tops in style .

pours out a completely opaque dark brown colour with some ruby edges . big frothy one inch head has some serious staying power . of course that leaves lots of sticky lace .  body is light and a bit watery , not too syruppy at all .

this beer looks great , clean and clear , good carbonation and head .  very simply -- -if this were n't a trader joe 's beer , it would have higher marks -- i 'd bet anything . at least here on the west coast , there are no examples of this style , at any price point , that compare to this beer . heater-allen , the only contender in oregon , way more expensive and neither as good , nor as consistent as this beer . while not in class with the best german hefeweizens , it 's damn close and an absolute steal for the price .
a smooth golden color with a nice fluffy white 2 finger head .  m. actually a bit thin , would have liked a bit more substantial body , but it went down well enough .

the smell had a distinct piney hops character - lots of spruce needles . also present in abundance were the usual line-up of spices anchor employs ; clove , nutmeg , cinnamon , and molasses .  the mouthfeel was its weakest point , i thought .

s : i found the strong tart raspberry with a faint mandarin-orange nose to be both unique and satisfying . not overpowering , like some over-the-top fruit beers .  the beer feels light but not watery . there is a little prickle on the tongue at the swallow .
poured into a shaker pint glass at cellar temp results in a nice frothy tan head that slowly sinks to a thin cap , lots of lacing .  mouthfeel is soft and a little heavy .

coffee and lemon aromas , very rich and inviting . thick , thick , thick mouthfeel ... molasses , some coffee , and a dense and vaguely cherry flavor . bitter as all get out .  m - nothing special just went down really easy ... .it was n't bad tasting ... .i was surprised how quickly i finished it because it went down fast .
