s. smells like christmas . hints of cloves , allspice , and roasted nuts .  the mouthfeel has a little bit more carbonation than i would like a brew of this calibre to have , thus the 3.0 .

smells amazing ! smells like raspberry muffins , with the sweet and tangy fruity smell and the bread-y , yeast-y almost sour smell of muffins . raspberry taste is very muted , almost would n't even know it was there . if only it tasted as good as it smelled .  high carbonation detracts slightly .

had this out of a bottle poured into a snifter ... a : jet black with a very small head , decent lacing ... s/t : smells and tastes like creme brulee .  lowish carbonation and a slightly thin mouthfeel .

poured into a fluted pilsner glass , this czech pils showed an exceptional ability to form a stiff , meringue-like , rocky head of foam . retention was great , lasting for the duration of the glass , leaving irregular clumps of foam on the way down .  rich , almost like chicken soup broth , and very low carbonation . in the world of bocks , this could be a new favorite of mine .
a gritty caramelized-orange color , a little haze .  mouthfeel lightly carbonated and a tad bigger than light-bodied .

hoppy scent is medium to intense , with a nice mix of fresh citrus and toasted , darker hop bitters . malt figures its way in to create a staggeringly intense aroma for an irish red .  taste : a bit thin for a porter , almost to the point of being slightly watery .

fine bubbles rise vigorously to create a large , long-lived fluffy white head atop a bright goldenrod colored body .  feel seems to be about medium in body , but slightly watery , with a lingering semi-bitter dark unsweetened chocolate/coffee bean aftertaste .

the aroma was simply outstanding . i have tried a number of the best coffee beers but none even came close to the nose on this one . pure and simple . every time i smelled this , i imagined myself walking into a coffee shop . the flavor profile was not quite as coffee heavy as the nose , but it was indeed more complex . malty rich up front .  m- actually the mouthfeel is n't that bad but it was really hard to focus on that while i was drinking joan rivers perfume .
pours a very hazy orange-amber with a massive , pillowy , long-lasting head and great lacing .  mouth- thin ? it 's a little thin , it lacks depth , and too much raisin for my taste .
an extremely pretty looking beer . dark brown in color , close to black .  a bit watery at the start , but , it gradually gains weight as it rolls to the back of the palate .

poured into an imperial pint , formed a 1 1/2 '' dense beige head above the slightly cloudy orangey amber brew . head falls way slowly , leaving a tall monolith of froth in the center , and thick coating all down the glass walls .  the mouthfeel is light , but hey , its a light beer ! for drinkability , again , one of the beers that could probably never offend me .
heaps of coco in the nose . roasted malt on the tongue , but the taste is surprising fleeting .  it seems to light and over carbonated for a stout .

remains hazy as it warns , unlike the 2010 . among the best sour aromas i 've had the pleasure of experiencing . t : fruits , oak , and brett share the spotlight . great blend of the three flavors . m : body is thin and weak , yet nicely oily . d : sessionable , even at $ 40/bottle .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied .

a : pours a cascading nitro-foamy head in a black background . the beer itself appears black at first blush , but upon close inspection is actually a very deep ruby/mahogany . it is a gorgeous beer .  m- a bit over carbonated for me , but other than the crisp nature of most kiwi beers , nice malty and dry .
pours a truly awesome blood orange reddish tan color with a tan head .  surprisingly light mouthfeel makes it a fairly easy drinker for a 9 % er
pours black and thick . substantial tan head that forms of a billion tiny bubbles then morphs into a very slow fading creamy foam .  m : very carbonated .

s : sweet dark frut nose come out followed by a chocolate toasted malt . on second whiff i am reminded of chocolate covered cheries .  refreshing when ice cold , pleasantly balanced when it warms a bit .

it has the wonderful spicy aroma that the style should always have . slight phenols , cloves , a sweet bready malt and a beautiful underlying fruitiness are all there . it finishes very very clean and does n't linger at all .  but there are hints of dark fruits that seem to disintegrate on your tongue , slight astringent alcohol tate/smelll this is defiantly a very drinkable brew .

12oz bottle , best by 04/29/12 ... a : a perfectly clear super deep ruby red brew with a humongous 2+ inch tan head that fades very slowly . very good .  m : the body is not as thick as i was expecting . it on the thin side as far as stouts go , but drinks very smoothly . i would have liked a thicker body , but that 's just being picky .

pours with a vast amount of co2 . produces a beautiful light tan head that sticks around forever . the body is dark amner in color .  mouthfeel is a little thin and alcoholic with low carbonation . overall this beer has a nice balance of flavours but i feel the barrel presence is a little bit too subtle and the mouthfeel a bit too thin to prevent a higher score .

s : a great big whiff of piney , citrus , and florally goodness hits the olfactory receptors . i 'm expecting a decent malt backbone here . o : this was only my fourth offering from 3 floyds ( alpha king , apocalypse cow , arctic panzer wolf ) and i 've been impressed with most .  a- blackness with a espresso colored head s- coffee beans ground soaked in licorice coffee and dark chocolate really bold t- straight up coffee and espresso with bitter chocolate and a slight tang finish m- medium carbonation and a bit watery for the style d- i drink 3 cup of coffee a day who am i to judge ?
smells like apples , tastes like hops . very tasty . the fragrance certainly did not match the taste , which is a good thing .  mouthfeel is a bit light .

pours a thick black color with a medium beige head .  it may not be for everyone but i think this is a beautiful product . flavor is far less sweet than the smell and look might hint , in fact this is gobs of sour black cherry . it 's an instant classic and one of only a handful of lambics i 've liked so far .

had a pretty nice look to it . pours dark , dark brown with a dark colored frothy head that lingers .  long , super bitter piney bitterness , aftertaste almost of pine-sol but i love the hop attack . problem is that it 's too sweet and slightly syrupy , especially evident in the middle . a little harsh and unbalanced overall , big beer and it shows .
the best thing about magic hats roxy rolles is the appearance , a dark ruby brown color with a creamy burnt tan head .  m : still a bit watered down , but again , it 's better .

the appearance is amazing . it pours really really dark brown , safe to say black . it leaves a thick lacing around the glass that is very very intimidating .  quite watery for the big flavor this one tastes and smells different from the main stream craft ipas , which is a pretty new category i 'll give it that .
dipas aroma 's are awesomely hard to describe .  m : the only thing that let me down was the thin and carbonated mouthfeel .

2009 vintage poured into a pint glass a : aggressive pour yields 3/4 finger cream colored head with good retention . clear reddish copper liquid is beautiful s : herbal and earthy hop aroma .  last weekend fellow ba das freak showed up with the dundee craft pack sampler . after tasting the pa , ipa , porter and pale bock lager i thought we had stumbled onto something above average , then came the honey brown lager . at first i thought it had a funky after taste but it does n't wait until after . when my dog broke wind i thought i was at a beer pairing in hell . sorry for the negativity but if i can save one ba from this fate it will have been worth it .
smells interesting and fun . the taste is floral and spicey .  very low carbonation , strong , hoppy with lingering after taste , a very typical english bitter but not my cup of tea .

pours a dark brown with hints of red at the edges , crackling four finger light tan head settles to a finger tall , and remains all the way through , leaves temporary sheets of lacing that fade ( probably due to the abv ) .  some hop aroma and flavour , a little to light in the body for my liking .

despite the abrasive alcohol , the nose is still pretty damn good .  take this beer for what it is ... a nice `` treat . '' it 's not something you will want to drink all night long . but for a nightcap , or change of pace this beer fits the bill . the vanilla taste is not overpowering , it 's there , but not so bold and overpowering that it seems fake .
nice looking lager .  m-medium body and syrupy with a grainy tough texture . strong carbonation and a slightly messy carbonation in the finish .

the color is incredible . i 'm not sure how you give this appearance anything other than a 1 or 5 . excellent retention , settling to a thick film and rings of clumpy lacing .  the taste is very good , it could use a bit more body but the flavors are great . tons of chocolate and roastiness dominate the profile but there is also some caramel and hops . the bitterness is at a great level in comparison to the sweetness , especially for the style . the guy below me has it right : not quite edmund fitz or blake butte but this one is one of the supeb examples of the style .
s = this had me hoping . smell was very sweet and inviting . nice fruity ( plum , prune maybe ?  for the mouthfeel , i found this stout almost watery in consistency .

a lovely jet black stout color , with a decent froth , though the carbonation is rather light .  mouthfeel suffers a little bit as i feel a higher abv would 've left this coating the tongue a little better . it seemed a little too thin to match its flavor profile .

this beer pours a hazy honey golden orange with a huge fluffy white head , that leaves some seriously sticky lacing . i could only think to myself that this is an absolutely beautiful beer .  t - tastes like a combination of pine-sol and a basic light lager m - who cares ?
bright , slightly chill-hazed copper body in appearance , very tall spongy off-white head with excellent retention .  nothing special here .

aroma is incredibly full and delicious . very very nice aroma . the flavor is just as incredible as the aroma . cherries , both sweet and sour are here in abundance , as well as a bit of graininess , and almost a thin flaky pastry flavor .  had this today on tap @ hibernia in boston . diacetyl ? in an ipa ? and what 's with the low hop profile and mega-sweetness of this beer ? my pint was quite cloudy too . beer drinkers of the world ... this is not an ipa , and it 's a pretty crappy beer to boot .
smell is absolutely fantastic ! huge , un-mistakable aroma of honey .  mouthfeel is a bit thin .

very dark mahogany red . beautiful foam , creamy , beige in colour . it left a lot of laces on the glass . a taste that remains on the palate , and it is not a beautiful sensation .  mouthfeel : it 's a bit heavy for the style .
s. plenty going on here in this one . d. a very good porter from left hand . the combination of aromas is brilliant . the taste is lighter than its 5.8 % abv .  m - a little on the thin side .

it pours a decently frothy tan colored head .  not too much that i can to the other reviews here . this beer was nothing but dissapointing . the label does say ipa right ? where are the hops ? i know that it does n't have to be a hop bomb but the flavor just is n't very good at all . i 've got 5 bottles left from this 6-pack . now i have to decide if i struggle though them or i just pour them out .

pours a golden orange with lots of suspended floaties . it has a huge spongy white head that retains well and laces the glass .  pretty weak mouthfeel , it 's a bit watery . i 'm enjoying the flavour and aroma quite a bit but the mouthfeel is a bit weak . but lacking in mouthfeel .

the beer i poured into my goblet has a creamy merengue head , and itself is a rich , effervescent amber . almost like a river-worn globe of amber .  very dry with a bitter finish . a little sticky from all the sweetness .

appearance- beer pours a wonderful looking amber golden with a thin wispy head one finger high of whipped cream foam . this is about the most perfect appearance i 've seen for a marzen . very impressive from an impressive brewery .  smell was sweet , with a citrus hint and strong english ale smell . initial taste was interesting , and i was n't sure about whether i would like it . by the end of the bottle , it had become one of the best beers i 've tasted . i would n't recommend it for any parties , but in small groups of like minded people i would say good call . very drinkable beer . looking forward to trying more from the brewery ( if i can find it )
nice warm smells , clear and well-executed .  average body and carbonation .
a - this is a beautiful looking beer .  the body is surprisingly light with moderate carbonation , helping to make this very drinkable .

a : pours an extremely dark , clear , mahogany reddish-brown with a couple finger of thick light tan head that faded into a thick film . a great network of lacing was left down the glass .  appearance : pours a clear , healthy copper color , with moderate carbonation , yet quickly dissipating foam and nearly no lacing . smell : light scent of fresh hops is predominant , slightly dry with a piney undertone . taste : begins clean , progressing into a moderately dry hop taste ; as the scent indicates , there is a note of piney taste that is part of the dryness of the hops , finishes with a slight dryness that yields clean . drinkability : prime example of the style , well hopped , abv is adequate , and the fresh and clean taste only enhance its drinkability .

appearance : this one pours a very dark mohogany with an incredible red hue . great head rentention very frothy .  mf : a bit thin , light body , medium to high carbonation d : another winner from sierra nevada .

i was incredibly excited to get a can of this stuff in my recent trade with tripelhops from what ive heard , its basically a can of hops . s : damn juicy in the nose : big grapefruit hops and creamy , fruity malts . love it . t : good candy sweets and light , drinkable hop-bitters on the front of the tongue ; herbal and a bit funky , even . good , balanced flavor . o : very drinkable a great ipa for the can .  i got this beer in the beers of the world gift box for christmas . immediate taste is a lil sharp and bready with a hint of citrus in the smell . it was not an out of this world experience , but it is a very light and enjoyable beer for everyday or get togethers .
pours a beautiful head of dough bread mass cloudy caramel color .  perhaps a bit thin for the style , which i suppose makes it a good pale ale for summertime quaffing .

smell - the rich , complex sugars here steal the show . in particular the raw sugar aroma was indistinguishable from the real thing .  m. thin to medium body with a somewhat biting carbonation . ends fairly dry .

its been awhile since i went belgian even longer since i had a lambic beer for wich iam not a big fan but i decided on taking a chance on this pretty highly acclaimed on today and iam glad i did.first off what a pour into a tulip glass a a rosey color with a fluffy pink head that settles slowly into a creamy-like mass with globs of lace behind.a whole lot of stuff going on in the nose a little funk and iron to go along with the sour cherry and vanilla just alot to take in , the flavors are just so much rolled into one starts off big and nearly puckering sour but is stopped abruptly by a cedar wood dryness and iron/metallic note.a nice vanilla pod lends itself well as it melds nicely between the two extremes of this beer.this is a doozy and makes me think more about a style that i didnt care for much before but maybe i havent explored it enough , it might be my beer phase i go into exploring the fruit lambic style .  s- coffee , malty caramel t- more coffee , chocolate , caramel and a little alcohol in there too m- medium bodied , a little watery really , decent carbonation d- a great example of a porter , just the wateriness that draws back from it

pours with a beautiful amber body topped by a thick lasting head with a good amount of lace left on the glass .  it 's a black colored beer with ruby edges . fairly nice nose , with a variety of dark fruits , as well as a bit of chocolate and coffee . really nice nose . flavor is fully packed , loaded with dark fruits ( blackberry , plum , cherry and currant ) , as well as some notes of dark chocolate , coffee and a light hint of alcohol . i like it .
pours pale yellow with a huge foamy white head that leaves tons of sticky lacing .  m : light body , watery touch , smooth with low carbonated in the mouth .
appearance : gorgeous beer with strong lacing throughout the entire glass . it looked sooo good , but there is almost no aroma .  m : very carbonated .

almost one-finger of fluffy dark brown head over an almost perfectly clear orange-brown liquid .  mouthfeel lots of fizzy carbonation , lighter bodied , finishes dry . the high carbonation combined with a thinner than usual mouthfeel really did throw off the beer making the flavors less prominent than i feel they could have been had the aforementioned two things been toned down a bit .

jet black in color with a huge , coffee colored head on top . just a clasic looking stout if there ever was one .  ordered this one in a taproom and was vary pleased . this beer is solid , as one might expect from north coast . it 's is as good as any pilsner i 've had . it drinks easy , has a hint of subtle fruit flavor , and smells very good . it also pours very nicely from the tap with a fluffy head . i 'd pick this one again on draft and might pick it up as a favor for a host when a house guest .
saranac black lager is a dark and clear tawny brown beer with a thick , lumpy , light beige head that has oily bubbles ; outstanding retention and lacing .  the body is rather thin though .
complex and strong aroma of wild flowers , banana , orange and coriander .  m-medium carbonation . medium body , slick .

s : the aroma is inviting with tons of spice and fruit . fresh ground cinnamon , nutmeg , hints of ginger can be noted . t : despite the aroma , it is a bit off in taste . everything mentioned above is noted but it does not meld together in taste as good as it does in the nose . the beer just has too much going on . d : just too much going on . it is a love it hate it brew .  mouthfeel is full and seems overcarbonated for the style , but overall has the typical heavy/slightly syrupy mouthfeel characteristic of wheat beers .
nitro-can encouraged frothy tan head , superb retention , some lace , almost opaque hue .  the palate is thinner than expected but not bad .

when poured it produces a vast amount of off white head , which sticks around for a good while .  mouthfeel : i wish they would dial it up a notch , needs a better backbone . stopped after one because it needed more body .

heavy caramels , bourbon , dark fruits , a fruity sweetness and a touch of tobacco.. this is really a fantastic smelling barleywine . i 'd dare to say it is one of the best smelling barleywines that i 've had to date . kudos to a great bouquet . plenty of caramel malt to provide a creamy mouthfeel , king henry takes off with sweetness but not cloyingly so .  m : aftertaste is bitter and body as well as carbonation is medium .

the color is dark like black coffee . i hesitate to say pitch black because there is some light shining through when held up to the light . the head is huge , maybe from a poor pour ? the head also sticks around for a long time and is sticking all over the side of the glass .  not too complicated , but a pleasant experience overall . goes down quite easily ( in part because of the low carbonation ) .

the smell is also great , sweet and hoppy and quite complex with smells of oak and apricot as well . the oak is a nice note in the aroma , but becomes too much on the taste level with very heavy oak throughout and unddetones of dry vanilla . mouthfeel is nice as far as heft goes , and theree is a good bit of creaminess , but the tannic oak cuts against it somewhat . too unbalanced for me to really call this very drinkable .  if you closed your eyes and smelled this you would think your smelling a good octoberfest beer due to the scent of carmalized malt and faint hops . has a carmel toasted nut flavor on the tounge and finished dry . i like the fact that this irish red is a little more bitter than most red ales but still not overpowering . tongiht i will be reviewing 4 of hook and ladder beers as i bought a gift pack that came with 3 bottles of 4 different beers . the beers i got were backdraft brown golden ale pipe and drum irish red ember amber ( a type of black and tan made with their backdraft brown ale and golden ale ) . try these beers if u can find them they are good

one of the darkest black beers i have ever seen . the only one that compares off the top of my head is dark lord .  light copper color with a large head s. malty with a slight resiny hop smell t. more bitter than sweet but well balanced with roasted malt m. a little to acidic and carbonated for my tastes d. a good lighter amber ale that i can heartily recommend

smell is an excellently projected , and wonderfully layered and clean tangerine , apricot , pear and lemon .  ( i actually do not care for this sweetness , but the beer still has great flavor ) m : nice carbonation , but the body is a little weak .
s : very fruity , dark fruits ( raisins , plumbs ) and malts . t : very fruity , specifically raisins .  the mouthfeel was medium/light bodied with a fine , prickly carbonation .

anyway , it had a great head , probably because of the nitro , but it was large , white , creamy and fluffy . great lacing to boot . kind of milky , gauzy .  mouthfeel : i 've always thought this was a little off ... not quite enough spine to offset the sweetness .

s : smells phenomenal ! booze , oak , and sweet sugars upfront . breadiness on the backend . t : good . not great . has a nice boozy / oakiness to it , not a whole lot else .  this one is a bit light and watery but does have a decent taste .

an absolutely beautiful pour generates a very active three finger head of dark brown chocolate colored head that quickly faeds and leaves no lace .  ( m ) - this is where the beer starts to fail in my opinion .
this is a lovely slow-sipping beer .  it was watery with no carbonation , and had a bitter aftertaste . but it had good flavor and decent body , and was fairly clean and easy to drink .

my favorite part of the beer was the aroma . it had this very intense chocolaty smell that while sipping was very pleasing to the senses .  surprised didnt taste as much hops as anticipated since it is called `` hopfish '' lighter on palate than majority of ipas mouthfeel- slightly watery but pleasantly smooth .

nose brings toffee , yeast , cherries , dried apricots , chocolate , coffee ice cream , and spices . very complex and wonderous . palate gives us sour cherries , yeast , sweetened iced tea , hints of caramel and toast , and some overall tartness . the mouth has some good , sharp peaks midpalate and the finish is a slow , deliberate fade . a very smooth and clean finish overall .  i like a little heavier of a mouthfeel than this offers , but the lighter feel is not surprising considering the crystal appearance .
pours a hazy golden amber with a medium creamy white head that retains well and laces the glass .  maybe a touch too much carbonation .

poured into a tumbler it produces a 2 inch head that persists and clings to the glass in great clumps . the appearance is perfect pale and slightly cloudy .  pretty thin mouthfeel i guess , but overall its a great balance of flavor and drinkability , something i would definitely buy again .

reviewed 11/16/2008 ( tap @ the stables , st. louis , mo ) : very cool presentation in a kasteel glass with a castle on the stem of the goblet-like glass . pours a very dark blood red body , with a lasting frothy pink head .  the carbonation is interesting , but a little too fizzy for me , i feel like this beer has a watery quality to it which i do n't particularly like in a porter . it starts out watery , then the carbonation kicks in .
smell - coffee , roasted malt , dark chocolate , and a touch of bitter , maybe hops .  3.0 m : medium body . smooth , but not creamy .

look : bright golden color , white head of creamy foam with 2 fingers thick , very good lacing , has a sticker that say it was the best beer in the world in 2002 , let see if it 's true ; smell : biscuity malts and fruit essences ; taste : pine and spicy hops , molasses , some biscuity malts , alcohol and sugars at the finish ; mouthfeel : dry and very bitter , bittersweet and spicy finish , the body is creamy and thick ; drinkability : the first time i try the `` tripel '' style , very spicy .  s : slightly citrus , faint banana t : citrus & yeast & candy sugar m : bit thin , but not uncommon for a triple o : i am sure age did this one well reading the prior reviews ... think i paid $ 3.50 for it , well worth the price and a good brown bagger at a tasting .

poured very nicely with a substantial head ( which receded faster than i expected ) and left lovely lacing down my pint glass .  4/5 m : surprisingly thin side of medium , slightly tongue numbing , spritzy .

tasted in mid-may 2009. nearly opaque , black/brown , with reddish brown on the edges under the light . great lacing , forming curtains in the latter half of the glass .  the body was medium to medium light .

aquired through a trade with xpimptasticx , thanks wanted to try for a while a- well , it looks harmless , it looks like a regular dipa except it had hardly any head and no lacing but ... that 's where the similarities stopped s- incredible smell : blood orange , booze , hops on performance enhancing drugs and a faint mango in there t- sweet booze , like a orange hop liqueur or triple sec .  not too complex- makes for easy drinking , as does its texture . carbonation level seems low , though as an earlier commenter noted , it is actually just very fine .

pours clear copper , with a two finger off white head . the head sticks around a long time and laces good .  an e-mail from the brewery indicated that twins lager is not the same beer as hauenstein , just with a different label . schells tells me that the twins lager uses a different recipe and yeast than the hauenstein , but a side by side comparison leaves me wondering why they would go through the trouble . i have always liked `` cheap '' beers . the beer drinkers of olden days wanted it cold , crisp , and cheap . but for afternoon lazing back and swigging , there is certainly nothing wrong with a cold bottle of twins lager . twins lager might be `` twice as refreshing '' as the label purports , but , boy would it be a treat to drink an original recipe fitgers again !
looks fantastic ! sort of a hazy golden apricot colour with a finger of foamy head that sticks around .  the carbonation is ok ; small fresh bubbles at a decent strength .

poured into my aventinus glass . a very light orange color with a massive head , great retention with about a half inch of foam maintaining throughout the coarse of the beer , and some lacing .  m. a bit acidic d. overall a nice iipa .

very unique . i could tell from smelling it that it was going to be sour , but had no idea the extent of sourness .  smell : uh oh , something is going wrong ... taste : blecchhh . my stomach is starting to turn . what happened to this beer ? simply put , the taste is sour and offensive . beef notes : horrible . what was the thought process when putting this beer out for sale ?

s : smell on this beer is amazing . i gave this beer a 5 . the beer smells like a cream stuffed pumpkin . d : drinkable for the style but still 1 bomb is good for me .  i have had ipas that went down a bit smoother but this one is n't bad it still goes down good but with just a little more carbonation and bite .

appearance : poured a milky orangy and yellowish hazy color , typical of hefeweizens , especially authentic german ones . yielded a huge 3 finger creamy head that came right out of the glass but maintained its shape is it was thick and creamy .  taste some roasted chocolate flavors . flavor lingers on the tongue after each sip . not quite what i would consider a savoring beer , but tasty none the less . i could drink this beer around the fire in the winter or after raking leaves in the fall .

this weissen beer pours darker than the others i have had . the color of this beer is a dark/blood orange . the thick off white head quickly builds toward the top of the glass and slowly fades to a thin lace to the end of the glass .  the drawback on this beer is the carbonation - it 's too heavy . sparkly but with a nice dryness in the finish .
s- it almost smells like a hoppier bock with plum and some chocolaty malt aromas .  little fruityness . light to medium body , oily , light carbonation . could be a little more carbonated .

the grapes come through again from the aroma but the flavour depth is n't as good as the nose . a decent ipa with lots of great aroma but lacking a bit of flavour . a really nice showcase of the nelson sauvin hop and a great idea from mikkeller .  mouthfeel was unremarkable .

s : a really interesting mix , i get a strong strawberry aroma mixed with a heavy caramel smell . there is also a nice hop/citrus aroma in the middle , some tangerine maybe . overall a really nice beer , very drinkable .  do not know if this was an aberation , but this caused a lower score in mouthfeel .

a - pours a very deep dark red , with ruby highlights throughout . there is lots and lots of thick , fluffy tan-ish head . it has excellent retention leaving a thick ring on top after it settles for awhile .  mouthfeel : high carbonation gives the impression of a thinner mouthfeel , and the carbonic acid and alcohol bite knock this one down a little in the mouthfeel rating .

lots of bubbles along wall of glass . leaves a huge & healthy white cap with bigger lacing along the outside of the body .  very nice m : medium bodied-a bit thicker than i expect from an ipa or a dipa , but it works well with the oaky sweetness of this beer .
classic stout appearance -- black body with a thick creamy dark-tan head .  mouthfeel is pretty average , as is the smell ... i ca n't think of anything distinctive about these characteristics .

on tap tonight at fountainhead in chicago ... poured into a tulip ... pours dark brown with nice dark ruby red highlights , good clarity . capped with three fingers of cool whip-esque white head that leaves a bit of lacing ... sweet and sour cherries dominate the nose with bits of oak and vanilla .  mouthfeel however seems a little thin for this complex brew .

very aromatic . t - chewy malts with the same fruity ester present in the nose .  a : dark reddish copper ; flat head ; strong carb ; not much lacing s : strong raspberry aroma , very inviting ; occludes other smells t : expected sweet -- it is n't ; the raspberry dominates , but it 's quite sour , draped over a wheat-beer-like base ; i must confess , this tasted terrible to me ; it tasted like nothing else i 've had , so i do n't think this is something against the genre m : good carbonation redeems the experience a bit overall , a terrible beer , for me .

heading was awesome , big , white and fluffy , with many tiny air bubbles racing toward the head .  mouthfeel : light bodied . i might even go as far as to describe it as watery . the carbonation was where i like it to be .

pours a very dark brown with red around the edges and a large tan colored head . a small head remains throughout and leaves great lacing . looks good .  the mouth is a little lighter than years past .

appearance is nice , dark but that red cherry goodness shines . smell is the winner here with loads of cherries and chocolate . taste is good , and hits big with cherries , a little dark smoke and chocolate .  mouthfeel : a little slick , thinner on the palate than i expected drinkability : a fine porter , would definitely drink again .
deep amber 2 finger head .  mouthfeel : thin body and medium carbonation overall : a nice geuze , a bit too watery for my liking though .
s- very strong smell . could smell it without even putting nose up to it ! some fruitiness , sweet like a candy store .  a sticky medium body with good carbonation . a bit too sticky for me .
a light orange marmalade cropped with a white , creamy top , it looks damn delicious !  mouthfeel is okay , no carbonation to speak of .

smell : strong citrus aroma boasting orange , pineapple and sappy resin . they really knocked it out of the park in the smell , what an inviting and pleasing scent . has west coast written all over it . overall : a pretty impressive brew from cisco brewers .  the taste was very light and highly carbonated . overall i 'm really surprised at all the negative reviews of this beer . maybe it 's just the fact i had it on tap , or that it was fresh .

heat is starting to mellow with a year on it , and the fruity development of the nose compliments the flavor beautifully . freshness indicated that this beer needs some time , and boy was i right .  mouthfeel : the carbonation is light , as is the body .

smells absolutely wonderful ... pungent aroma of hops all the way ... piney , citrusy hops and i 'm loving it ... i want to smell this all night ... terrific blend of piney/grapefuit hops and sweet malts.. thought this was going to be a hop bomb all the way which would have been fine but i 'm surprised at the balance on this one .  the mouthfeel is just a touch too syrupy , though it does n't detract much at all from the enjoyment of the beer .

nose is great on this - grassy hops , estery yeast and sugary , bready rye . very nice , everything comes together extremely well . yeast seems more tripel than saison , but compared to the smell the yeast is quite tame unfortunately .  good carb , but feels a bit thin and watered down in general .

appearance - very dark red , but clear and looks quite impressive when held up to light . 2 fingers of head with very good retention and lacing .  i 'm rather late with this review but i had this on tap at nicholson 's downtown and it reminded me of sierra nevada celebration . in fact at the time the original name was celebration ale . i 've since had a few growlers from jungle jim 's and though it 's a quailty brew i 've experienced some diacetyl like off-flavors when served from the growler . still it 's quite enjoyable and recommended . i wish the best to mike and his future brews !

the pour is black with a billowing light brown head with some very nice lace .  m : it feels light- to medium-bodied , smooth and a bit watery on the palate with a moderate amount of carbonation . o : the beer goes down rather easily and is quite flavorful despite its thin body .
a : pours brown with a really tall tan compact head that sets slowly into rich lacins .  light to medium in body .

s- wow , loads of scents starting with a spiced apple and spiced pear followed by great light sweet malt scents and of course the belgian bready yeast ... this reminded me of my trips i used to take to julian with my parents and brothers as a child , we would always go up there for some fresh apple pie and hot cider ... t- not as much as the smell , but still great . you pick up on the apple/pear , spices , light sweet malt and loads of bready yeast with a nice crisp finish .  remarkably good . but pay attention : almost 10 % alcohol , but you hardly remark it . it does not have that much body , but it surely has a delicate taste . i 'm a bit more inclined for brown beers , but this one is really good , and not brown at all .
however , the smell is unbelievable . this is definitely a dessert beer .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and the carbonation is too light in my opinion .
a- this one pours out a beautiful dark ruby red colored body with a small tightly knit finger of foam .  the mouth is a tiny bit like flat soda which was the only off-putting part of this beer .
a - black ad pitch .  m : slick mouthfeel with a medium amount of carbonation that can be prickly at times . body is medium and has a bit of resiny stickiness to it .

s- great pumpkin smell up front with a nutmeg spice on the back end . smells like a fresh baked pumpkin pie at thanksgiving .  a completely black beer with a thin mocha head . boris is a thick , almost to the point of sludgy beer with a roasted malt taste with a noticeable but background hop presences . the oatmeal comes into play as a slight cookie taste . overall it 's a great beer that worthy of a try .

beautiful red orange color . a tan head sits on top for a while . a very pretty beer . we tried it with some honey ham and then some apple pie and it was terrific with both .  the mouthfeel could use some more body to combat the higher level of carbonation .

burnt , dark orange in color , and hazy clarity poured this one . plenty of carbonation led to a creamy light tan head .  has an awful , mouth-burning sweetness , a very artificial flavor , and a sticky-sweet mouthfeel .
smells great , best part of the beer for sure .  m - a little thin-bodied and watery and a little low on the carbonation .

one of the best aromas to come around in a while for me . very decadent chocolate here ... sweet , silky ... you can really smell the cocoa nibs here . a slight hint of hop bitterness as well but this is a very chocolatey aroma . the body is a bit light , and the taste is certainly full of chocolate , but is more of a mix between a sweeter chocolate and a bitter , roasted chocolate . this marriage keeps it from becoming cloying or just being too bitter . what was a pretty sweet and rich beer on the nose was n't quite so on the tongue .  m & # 8211 ; thin , refreshing , light , plentiful , smooth carbonation .

i love nitrous beers - they have this amazing waterfall effect as the head settles . the beer 's head was a nice creamy tan color and featured some light coffee/mocha scents . appearance - 5.0/5.0 - love the waterfall effect of the nitrous , tan creamy head - very full taste - 4.5/5.0 - silky smooth - coffee and light chocolate taste feel - 4.0/5.0 - no aftertaste , extremely smooth in mouth smell - 4.0/5.0 - very light with coffee/mocha accents drinkability - 4.5/5.0 - way better than a guiness - very tasty , smooth - i will be repeating this beer .  m- medium body with medium carbonation . a bit to high carbonation for this brew but still has a light creaminess to it . nice blend of flavors just mouthfeel is lacking a bit imo . also the head could of been a lot better especially due to how much carbonation .
it smells great . t : the taste didnt exactly match the smell but the taste was good too .  smooth , mellow finish , and a thin watery mouthfeel .

this is one great looking brew ... . both big and small bubbles and what appears to be a layer a grease on the head .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin and the carbonation is quite sharp ; a bit fizzier than i 'd like .
a pint of the black stuff , or the priest , looks as good as ever , enjoyable to watch it settle over a minute or so .  the mouthfeel was lowly carbonated .

the smell has that fruity scent that just says dfh in my mind , must be the local weather . lots of subtle scents here and i am sure i am not picking them all out .  mouthfeel is a little thin and aftertaste is a little too much ... like the brew has gone stale , although i know it has n't .

the aroma is a beautiful butterscotch malt and caramel experience , like candied hops . there is a hint of some apple but all in all i would say this smells more inviting than it tastes .  mouthfeel is a bit thinner than i would have expected .

s- this beer smells great , typical ipa smells ; pine mandarin , pineapple , grapefruit .  parching on the tongue . almost no flavor : slight sweetness up front , trace of bitterness on finish . really .
pours a clear dark brown with superior side lacing and a copious tan head with very good retention . appearance is exceptional .  m - thin with medium low carbonation d - not a bad amber .
a-bronze and brilliantly clear . huge eggshell head .  easy drinking but it has a different mouthfeel , it almost leaves a film in my mouth .
the scent is excellent and strong , with a bouquet of citrus .  the mouthfeel is larger light with a very , very slight fizz .

beer is a slightly hazed mid-orange . very generous , sudsy white head is slow to go and leaves thick lacing .  heavy in apricots and dates with some coriander and maybe some hidden hops late in the nose . the spice showed more as the beer warmed in the glass . the drink started with a heavy fruit taste , around the middle of the tongue the spice showed up . the finish was lingering hops with and oily attribute followed by a light alcohol heat . all and all a good beer to drink with friends and discuss the merits of beer drinking . but i do n't think it would go good with food and it 's not the most refreshing beer .
a wonderful sweet , almost fruity smell after opening the bottle .  m : relatively light though not particularly carbonated .

a big , thick , creamy , dark-tan head forms on top of an opaque black body .  this beer poured nicely with a creamy white head , giving off nice citrus aromas . the flavor was shocking , however , reminding me of kool-aid orange flavor , and with almost as much sweetness . i could n't distinguish any hop bitterness , though it could have used some to balance out the excessive sweetness . this beer tastes as though all the yeast were filtered out , and then orange kool-aid added post-fermentation

a - wow , the gentlest of pours brings forth a beautiful ( slightly clouded due to my misjudgment ) light orange brew with the most ridiculous pillowy head i have ever seen , four fingers to start , sticks around for what seems like forever , and leaves great lacing s - pear and apple , along with a little cut grass , lemon zest , lots of yeast , clove and pepper t - smooth maltiness , slightly tart , with a lot of green apple , a little fresh hay , some yeasty goodness .  surprisingly carbonated , almost like a lager .

smell : very well balanced . citrus notes with a very nice malt background .  perhaps a touch lacking in body , but dextrinous enough to help facilitate excellent drinkability . although stoudts fest falls a touch short in malt character and body , but is nonetheless a well crafted , tasty and highly quaffable brew .

aroma of tart dried apricots , fresh apricots , canned apricots ... uhh , pretty much just apricots . quite a great smell actually , as i like apricots ( this is why i ordered an apricot ale ) . decent apricot ale , maybe a shade better than the apricot wheats i have tasted off the shelves , but not the game changer i was hoping for .  mouthfeel : medium bodied .
beautiful rich yellow color , with a decent , small head .  body is fairly thin , but that is expected for the modest abv .
the nose was amazing . hints of fruit , plums , raisons , apples , yeast , with a few earthy woody notes .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with no carbonation .

pours nearly pitch black with a big frothy , creamy mocha colored head . looks similar to a ris . great lace , great retention .  the mouthfeel is slightly buttery but leans more towars a syrup-like feel . carbonation would be greatly appreciated and add a very unique feel for this beer .

pop goes the cork and a soft pour fills the glass with a clear golden color and a dense white head filling the upper half of the tulip .  mf : the carbonation is n't quite as spritzy as i would hope to go along with the huge sourness , the body is light d : this is a great lambic .

very nice . t : everything indicated by the nose was delivered in a very lush , balanced flavor .  does smell a little like `` beer , '' as my wife would say . so sweet on the tongue . slight raspberry tartness but it is like drinking raspberry sorbet after it melts . it is still trying to recover from the sweetness . a good once in a while beer . sorbet beer , i tell ya .

smells creamy/milky with rich , almost sweet coffee , chocolate , kaluha , cocoa , and a touch of green hops . absolutely divine . the flavor is roasty with burnt/charred malts , coffee , chocolate , and a medium bitterness .  this was my first encounter with pumpkin ale . i must confess that i could not finish the bottle . i had the distinct impression that the beer was trying to taste like something and not quite getting there . fearing the latter , i tossed the bottle after about five sips .

goose island 312 urban wheat poured clear , straw yellow in color topped by a fluffy white head . 312 is a great looking beer .  my only complaint is that i wish the mouthfeel was thicker . it was smooth , but a bit watery to me .
big bulky beige head 1 1/2 inches . a thin head remains throughout no matter how long it sits ( very nice ) .  a tad thin .
a : black it is ! with a thick brown head .  mouthfeel : bubbly and light body . the mouthfeel is a little peculiar and affects my experience .
it smells awesome , but i 'm concerned that it 's going to taste a bit too sweet . upfront is strong bourbon , which is quite pleasant .  mouthfeel seemed a bit to lean to me .

odor : rich citric aroma , tangerine , slightly lemony , floral backbone , some red fruit in there as well , pleasant and mellow . consistency : big carbonation , too much for my taste at least , it is straddling the line between gentle and tingly , no doubt that it gets in the way of the flavor a bit .  m : the feel is creamy and medium bodied . rather light for a ris and that really detracts from the beer in my opinion . the mouthfeel is lighter than what i come to think of when i thik of a ris .

smell is of bourbon , wood , malt , brown sugar , toffee , and dark fruits . overall , this is a fantastic beer with very complex aromas and flavors . i am really glad i was able to try this one .  t - great pilsner , very slight hops , clean finish m - light body d - very smooth and very drinkable .

very nice and clean aroma , even with the `` funk '' .  t- the taste is dry , and more of the wood flavors seem to be more present . it seemed a bit much for the style of the brew . d- it was n't bad , did n't go down as smooth as most ris do , but it was still easy to drink .

a toasted head has great retention and lace .  smell is cocoa , touch of coffee , licorice , slight vanilla , a whiff of smoke . taste is thick creamy , dark and bakers chocolate , touch of espresso , end is dry and slightly bitter , a woody aftertaste .

a : pours absolutely perfect ! cloudy , creamy orange body with a glorious mountain of head that fills just to the edge of the glass and hangs around until the glass is empty .  a bit thin , for i think i like them a bit more bodiful , but smooth and flavorful i do think this one , yes .

s - good smell , lots going on .  s- smoky wood and scotch , one of the more interesting noses on this beer t- malts , with some nice roasted flavors that come through and then a hit of alcohol m- lighter bodied than expected d- a very interesting and drinkable beer , but one i need to be in the mood for

just when you think you have seen it all when it comes to beer appearances , this one comes along . strangely fascinating looking beer .  m - the reason i dinged it on mouthfeel is because it actually left some of that nasty coffee-mouth feeling in my gullet .

pours a deep chestnut brown , with a layer of foamy white goodness on top . laces amazingly . the more beers i try from this brewery the more i realize they sure know how to make a beer look good .  mouthfeel- light-medium bodied , high ! carbonation , and leaves a bit of hop on the palate but nothing else ... pretty boring here . refreshing and highly carbonated , this one grabs your attention for the beginning of the drink but then finishes weak .
the beer looked good with a nice amber color and a thick creamy and frothy head that laced and retained well .  m : very carbonated - almost too much .

12 oz bottle poured into a snifter - best before oct. 19th 2007 appearance : harsh pouring reveals a generous 2 '' head that lasts quite a long time . the head is tan with tiny bubbles that leaves a bit of lace behind .  medium bodied and a bit sticky in the mouth .
one beautiful looking barleywine here . it almost glows a nice dark amber color .  perhaps a little watery , fuzzy . quite drinkable but somewhat sweet .

it really reminds me of the nose i get off a really good heffeweizen ( spelling might be wrong , but there ya go ) . it 's a bright and inviting smell and makes my mouth water .  in the mouth , it 's rather average , with light carbonation .

appearance was the best characteristic of this one . super fluffy head that lasted a short while , but then died to a thick laceing .  m : fine , nothing special d : probably too sweet for a lot of people , but i 'm a fan .

it looks good , always being ( in my experience ) in a nitro can or on nitro tap . it has an almost black body with an even , medium , creamy light tan head that lasts a long time .  m : upper light body with high carbonation .
pours dark black - thick brown foam , long retention and heavy lacing .  mouf & gt ; meh . okay . average .

came out of the tap a deep brown , almost black color .  a - black on the pour with no head whatsoever s - big burnt malt and bittersweet chocolate aroma along with some bourbon , some oak and vanilla in there as well , slight alcohol , as the beer warms up , smells almost like straight bourbon , maybe more like a bourbon and cola t - big bourbon flavor right up front , lots of oak as well , some bittersweet chocolate in the body , finish is more bourbon and oak along with some vanilla , alcohol notes , long finish m - a bit too flat for my taste , full-bodied but totally devoid of any carbonation action in the mouth d - i 'm glad port put this in a 375ml bottle , because this is a sipper , treated this almost like fine bourbon sipping for quite awhile , but i could sip on this all night very interesting beer .

some of shakespeare 's stuff is pretty dark , but shakespeare stout a nihilistic black , with a big head the color of creamy coffee . the little black bubbles peppering the head make it look alluringly like a chocolate chip cookie .  the only thing i felt was it could use a little more carbonation to balance the tart flavor and make it more perky .

a special cask tapped last night at the j. clyde . s : an absolute explosion of floral and citrus hop aromas -- it smelled dipa-esque . a rich crackery malt backbone is evident , as well . a solid offering , and if gpbc decided to make the aroma of this beer into a car air freshener , i 'd be all over that .  i found the body to be a bit thin carbonation medium to low .

11.2oz bottle poured into a chalice pours a murky , deep brown with a thick , one-finger head that has awesome staying power and leaves rings of lacing down my glass .  good , but the mouthfeel is distracting . 3.0 m : light body , mainly due to low carbonation . need to get some better carbonated beer .

smell is dates , toffee , chocolate , some light roast , touch of floral , quite nice . taste is very roasty , rich chocolate , cherries , bit of beef jerky smoke , powdered milk , weird fruitiness , kind of cloying flavour . i enjoy the aroma a lot , and the flavour as well but there are a couple that were off , but my mouth felt kind of dirty after drinking it , pretty strange , i 'll try this again but i 'm kind of on the fence at this point .  i wont go through the details but if you are looking for an ipa do not drink this beer . it may sound novel , but black ipa is a retarded name for this , its not an ipa whatsoever . no hop flavor in the taste , not even close . im pissed i paid 4.30 for this . ridiculous .

pours a hazy golden-orange with a rocky , fluffy 3 finger white head which recedes to a dense blob resembling an orange soda and vanilla ice cream float . solid ring of retention and loads of soapy lace .  m- a little too carbonated for my liking , that makes this beer have a little `` sting '' to it ( especially if it is served too cold ) .

a very nice appearance : a persistent creamy dense head remains in the glass til the end .  this is a very good pumpkin beer . picked a 6 pack up at the local market , came home on a chilly night here in rural mi , and my girlfriend and i finished the whole six pack . lots of pumpkin taste , beautiful color , and an overall great seasonal choice . i would n't drink it in warm weather , but on this cool fall night , it hit the spot . i could see picking this up in the future to bring to a bon fire , or to enjoy while i hand out candy on halloween . cheers !

the closest thing to bourbon county stout ive ever smelled . a wonderful nose of raisins , oak , vanilla , bourbon , chewy chocolate , cocoa , rum , and god knows what else . it seems there are citrus hops that are mixing without dropping a beer with the malt and creating this rather sweet fruity start . finishing with bourbon and a touch of alcohol bite . overall im pretty happy with this beer . huge thanks to crushedvol for this extra .  slight astringent twinge . d- very good `` sessionable '' strong ale .

color me surprised that this is a stout at all and then an ris ? big ipa nose . big old ale taste - tons of smoother , sweeter dark malts . more like a normal stout , i suppose .  m - kind of watery , but good carbonation .

a : my antonia pours a lovely straw/amber hue and is marked by a monstrous head of the consistency of whipped egg whites . definitely appealing ... .  the carbonation is around medium . there is a watery texture to the beer which is not pleasant .

the head very slowly fades to a 1 cm cap atop this impenetrably black brew , leaving beautiful , copious lacing everywhere . perfection in appearance .  the mouthfeel however is slightly taut . body is clear red copper with sustained carbonation .
smell was deep with plenty of sweet chocolate aromas and bitter grains .  medium bodied fairly low carbonation .

a : what a great looking stout . deep brown color with an extremly silkey 1/2 '' head that slowly disipates into lacing s : roasted malt t : grain sweet ness and roasted malts m & d : mouth feel was medium and dry .  cake/nutty malt up front with a huge , thick spiced tea hop flavor headbutt with the swallow . not just season 's best , but saranac 's best . i usually find them to be just an average brewery but this stuff is nice .
it is a gorgeous beer- excellent clarity , pale golden hue , and generously sized head .  body is on the thin side of medium and the finish is both mildly astringent and slightly bitter .

taste : something about the taste does n't quite live up to the smell . the taste is a weakened version of the caramel malts in the smell leading into a dark fruit plumlike aftertaste .  mouthfeel is way more thin than the head and lacing made me think it would be . very quaffable .
big aroma of alcohol and vinous fruit , almost christmas pudding-like .  it has a medium body and a fair amount of carbonation , but again feels a bit weak .

the nose here is at first reminiscent of a barleywine ( raisiny , sweet ) , then an imperial stout ( chocolatey , roasty ) , and ultimately an outstanding cabernet ( earthy and leathery notes on top of dark fruits and floral perfumes ) . i find this to be an ideal complexity - notable not for its blunt force but for the way it continues to surprise . cigar box certainly comes to mind . barleywine-type sweetness is much more prevalent in this dimension , although it interacts in interesting ways with a darker , roasted quality . the finish is warm in a pleasing way . outstanding beer for slow sipping and contemplation .  a-garnet with small ring of foam s-raisin , pancake syrup , faint vinager t-assertive sour front , sour cherry , some malt sweetness , dates m-medium , with average carbonation d-very tasty !

ah the smell of the hop flowers , dominates this magnificent nose that is also sweetly malt , fresh and clean , the quintessential dry hopped aromas all present , sweet malt start , the top moderate in feel . finish is delicately acidic , boom , the hops slap your palate and cling till the very dry and lovely finish , just plain yummy !  ran into the maui brewing company while killing time until our dinner reservations were ready . there was a very slight bitterness in the aftertaste but was well hidden in the passion fruit sweetness . found the beer to start like any average golden ale but the aftertaste was what i really liked about it sorta like an ice tea aftertaste .
nose is really great . a lot going on in there .  m : medium body with a sticky quality when it enters the mouth .

glorious aroma of silky dark chocolate and dark-roast coffee beans . very pleasant . the dry , slightly acidic roasty finish leads well into another sip .  m : light to medium bodied and highly carbonated .

aroma is a sweet malt-candy smell , bready , with a note of ginger and sourness . this beer tastes almost as good as it smells .  no sediment at all when bought fresh . this really brought out flavors you could not taste beforehand . a wedge of orange or lemon is a nice touch also . best served a little warmer than most beers . goes really well with food . a beer you could drink all night especially during a good bar-b-que .

paid $ 24.50 or so for the mixed case via lancaster county ... the beer pours a slightly hazy amber color with a large white head , exceptional retention and a dozen or so lacing effects , almost a perfect pour .  mouthfeel is moderate and relatively flat .

have had this a couple times at churchkey and paradiso in dc & gt ; a : a very sudsy pub cask like look to this one with sticky lacing , a beautiful finger of fluffy head and a darker orange body . great start .  body was medium with med/high carbonation and a dry finish .

the smell was magnificent , and like i said i wish it had been in a snifter to catch more of these floral and citrusy aromas . outstanding .  m : um . it was carbonated and did n't leave any odd off flavours on the palate .
smell - like other little creatures ales , the hops really hit you as soon as you sniff it . passionfruit with a fair bit of malty sweetness .  mouthfeel is sticky-sweet and dense .

a : amazing head on top of a dark yellow body launches up to the top of the glass and hangs out forever , ending its long life in a spiderweb of beauty . glass is soapy all the way down . this beer could not look any more inviting .  this is the least impressive quad from the trappist breweries ... do n't get me wrong , it has a similar taste profile , although not that perfect as a westy 12 or a rochefort 10 , dark fruit , plums , candy sugar , but i did n't like the mouthfeel on this one . too much sparkling going on ... pretty funny thing is i just absolutely endlessly adore the la trappe quadrupel oak aged batch 1 version ... so so so much better then the regular one , especially when the oak aged version , bottled this summer , is coming around fantastic ! i like their dubbel more too .
dark mahogany to black with a two finger beige head . great lace and retention for a porter .  tastes pretty amazing really . watery on the tongue but ends dryish .
appearance : a wonderful amber color .  m : medium-full bodied , zero carbonation , silky . d : lacks the warming feeling that is usually related to a winter warmer .

s- awesome char smell with chocolate and roasted coffee , and supported by a rich dark fruit sweetness . hoppy bitterness is a fantastic undertone . m- nice smooth mouthfeel .  the flavor is a bit harsh and a bit watery , but not too much .

s - i really like the nose on this one a lot . healty dose of peppercorn with some complimentary citrus , something i usually do n't go for . the winner is a great hot chili burn on the backend of the nose from the chili pepper . really excited to try this one .  carbonation is ample but the body lacks a little texture .

bottled in july 2011 poured into a tulip glass . still manages to create a creamy , thick-looking head , quite impressive . head fades gradually to a thin ring around the glass with some islands , leaving lots of lacing .  dark dark amber colot cant see thru at all thick white head remains on the glass and laces well the smell is of roasted and caremel malts , like a traditional english ale slightly different then my expectation of an alt but i like the smells tastes like a homebrew very fresh and smooth with crystal and roasted malts through out . to finish not a lot of body or carbonation leaves a dry roasted flavor

the looks are the best thing about this beer . beautiful presentation .  nice dark brown color with fantnaztic lacing ! smells choclotly with coffee . tastes even and thick with cocoa sweet caramel flavors continuing thru . good for its class this porter represents well , its much better than its younger brother . would drink again .

drank on-tap at miracle of science bar & grill , cambridge , ma poured a gorgeous , crystal clear , dark orangey-amber with a clingy , off white , one-finger head that lasted the duration of the beer .  mouthfeel is a little too carbonated & acidic , which in my experience is typical of the japanese beers .

aromas are full of the whiskey barrel , but really well balanced with a ton of tree fruit - especially apricots and apples . flavors are a rich mix of fruits , thick bread/yeast , honey - lots of honey , just a kiss of hops , vanilla icing , maybe some fruitcake ... just a lot going on here . and fairly sweet , but delicious . as it warms , it converts to creme brulee and banana pudding - but never loses the whiskey barrel .  light bodied .

cloudy pale copper color and of hazy reddish tone nearer to the top which is adorned by a rich creamy head of froth about an inch high and colored of dark ivory . head retains its thick body to settle a bit with a lumpy top and lots of lace in big blotches , looks scrumptious !  lighter feel and dry in the mouth with a little too much carbonation .

appearance : pours the color of a tripel ; that burnt golden orange appearance . head is gigantic and rocky which dissipates slowly into a thick rocky soapy lacing that clings to the glass tenaciously and refuses to let go . it even have yeast in the bottle which i found out on the last pour of my bomber . so really proper looking for an imperial ipa and the color of a tripel . i 'm giving this a 5 ! its a beautiful beer smell : this a very hoppy beer .  incredibly light with cereal grains , very grainy taste , hops are nowhere in site . there are way better summer beers out there .

gives a snootful of dark chocolate and sweet dark molasses from 6 inches away , truly intense aroma . flavor is gently dominated by the chocolate , leans a little toward chocolate flavor extract , but nothing definitive .  this brew is 5.2 % abv and my bottle looks exactly the same apart from the two silver australian international beer awards one from 2007 & the other from 2008 in the top left of the label anyways it pours a dark cola hue with a fast vanishing two finger head and sporadic lacing , the aroma is fresh chocolate icecream and vanilla expresso , it has an average mouthfeel with tastes of fresh chocolate icecream , vanilla expresso , macadamia and it finishes with a light bitter mouthfeel , overall a nice brew that is just lacking that full mouthfeel of a stout in my mind but in saying that its very sessionable and ill definately buy this again .
a good looking beer that smells perfect , but ca n't hold up in the taste realm .  heavy mouthfeel .

the smell is exactly like a cafe mocha -- dark chocolate , buttery , and quality roasted coffee . the taste is very intense on the chocolate but the roasted coffee malts come through nicely too .  mouthfeel works just fine , but is a little watery . highly drinkable .

s : the smell is very balanced and i am loving it . mild fruity esters mix with sweet bourbon , vanilla , and coconut to form what is probably the best smelling beer ( non-ipa ) i 've had before . d : fantastic barrel aged barleywine . great job mayflower .  mouthfeel - medium body with a very active carbonation .

very enjoyable smell , roasted coffee , chocolate , combined with a truffle like fruitiness . the alcoholic notes get more and more present , and totally unbalanced .  im augustus gloop : ) m - carb a little low , a little on the sweet side .

pours a clear amber color , a few bubbles rising to the top . creamy ivory head fills the pint glass , leaves a bunch of stick and keeps a very nice lace .  mouthfeel is very dry with almost no carbonation .

this reminds me a bit of pte with that ridiculously great aroma and bitterness but not quite having the citric hop flavor that i would normally want in a dipa . this beer is incredibly bitter on the back end and the hot alcohol make this beer difficult to session .  very light mouthfeel .
the lacing is astounding . pretty appealing .  mouthfeel is decent , this beer seems to foam up in your mouth .

two brothers heavy handed ipa : terrific aroma , very full and noticeable from several feet away . some heavy malt syrup aromas coupled with flowery hops make the aroma very appetizing . slick mouth feel .  but i felt the feel was a bit thin .
it pours a dark brown to almos black color with a huge fluffy tan to light brown head .  mouthfeel is light , and carbonation is set at medium .
great retention and great lacing .  mouthfeel is ok. a litte too dry for my liking though .
smells very delightful , just like fresh lemonade .  overall , quite easy to drink and enjoyable though the mouthfeel is a bit on the thin side and not up to par with the style .
appearance- very dark , almost black pour . fat 2 inch head just about overflowing out of the glass and excellent lacing .  mouf & gt ; easy , average .

appearance : pours a motor oil black with a 1 finger creamy milk chocolate brown head . excellent lacing . like all the other yetis , this one looks perfect .  m/d - body is a little thin for me , would like to see the consistency just a hair thicker .
source/serving : 650ml bottle dated 2/19/2010 ( 6 months old ) smell : delicate and complex , but not dynamic . very nice overall .  this beer has a fairly heavy body , a bit too much for my tastes .
this is probably the most impressive smelling amber style ale i have enjoyed .  mouthfeel : it feels like an astringent hop bitterness , but i sure as heck ca n't taste any hops .

a - beautiful amber body with intense white huge head and sheets of lacing remaining for an insane amount of time .  mouthfeel : this was my one issue with this beer . it loses carbonation quickly , and with not that much to start with , it is kind of a bummer . a little sticky as well but the taste makes up for a bit of this .
s - mmm , what a good smelling beer . delicious smell , and a lot of it .  m : lighter body , medium carbonation , somewhat watery thin feel to the body , with a crisp finish .

the aroma is a very nice rich creamy milk chocolate . the best part of this beer is that the aroma is so strong , it is a major component of the beer even while drinking the last swallow . nice feeling coming out of a bottle .  have you ever canned tomatoes ? if you have , you should be familiar with the smell and flavor tomatoes have when cooked . this beer had an overwhelmingly strong odor and taste of spicy stewed tomatoes . it was too strong to drink . i know this is not normal for this beer from the other reviews of it i have read ( and the style does n't allow for many strong flavors ) , but it was only days past the best by date and had been stored in a refrigerator . there was also some floating particles in the beer which i also assume is not normal , pilsners typically being filtered . i will come back and rerate , but i 've been told by some fellow raters that i should take this beer into account for my rating .

perfectly balanced , wonderful , and refreshingly innovative . i 'm starting to think rogue bombers might be worth their exhorbitant price out here .  m - exceedingly bitter . needs to be a little creamier for this style d - not a session beer .

pours a nice amber color with a white head and excellent lacing .  the colour is a light straw , probably the weakest colour i have seen in a pale lager , the head is very pleasent and has some serious glass cling ... the aroma is very skunky when first opened but quickly disappears and the taste is highly sweet malts on a thin body , very nice for dining , not a stadium brew ... i first reviewed this brew in march of 03 , approx 10 monthes ago .

smell : awesome . juicy citrus hop hit the nose hard . taste : does n't quite live up to the smell , but still very good . the hops are more herbal with some citrus in there as well . still very good and really glad to have tried this .  the mouthfeel is a little thin , very dry , but well carbonated .

this beer is excellent , from the moment you open it till the las drop i have tried this beer on tap as well and it is good , the 22 ounce bottle for some reason does not taste the same in my opinion as its 12 ounce brother .  the mouthfeel is a little on the thin and watery side though .
clear dark amber colour with a smooth , creamy light tan head . good head retention .  mouthfeel : medium body and a finish that is a bit dry . this beer almost flat .

s - the first thing that hits you is a bourbon alcohol smell , which is quite potent . the aromas are incredibly complex , i 've never smelt anything like it . it is incredibly sweet , it makes your teeth ache just at the thought of it ; maybe this will lessen with cellaring .  mouthfeel is just a tad watery .

a- pours a pitch black hue with brown and amber highlights , small tan/brown head that is mostly sustaining , fair amount of lacing throughout s- fruity scents dominated by raisins and dark fruit ( as advertised on the label ) , i am also getting tones of apple , peach , belgian candy , sweet caramel/toffee malts , and a modest alcohol presence t- initial taste is raisins , raisins , and more raisins ( almost cloyingly sweet ) , followed by a variety of fruits and spices , yeasty/bready/sweet malts , a little bit of chocolate and belgian candy , finishes with sweet malts , a touch of bittering hops and warming alcohol presence m- medium/full bodied with good carbonation , nice slick texture that coats the tongue in sweetness d- 9 % abv is well-masked , but this definitely a sipping beer to be enjoyed over time ( much like a port or desert wine ) .  mouthfeel is a little thin , but not offensively so .
great , great look .  body is light and the carbonation is lively , a bit too much for my preferences .
it has a very deep black color and tan head that make it beautiful to pour .  mouthfeel is a bit thin for my liking .

pretty good aroma wafting from this especially when warm , distinguishable espresso and coffee grounds with baker 's chocolate , coarse grains and a earthy woody note , not unlike campfire smoke with the addition of some licorice . great aroma and feel , solid overall .  body is perhaps the one less thanexcellent area , as its a little too light and i would have preferred something heavier and slicker ( more like the maui offering ) .
i enjoy just about everything this beer has to offer .  taste is dominating by anis with some candi sugar . body was above average and alcohol was well hidden .

smell is of fresh hop , so fresh.just layers of vegetal , cirtusy hops with a slight hint of pine and pale malt .  the mouthfeel starts off kind of watery since this seems to be a light to medium bodied brew and leaves a dry , but sticky feel to the lips .
cloudy blonde coloring with good head retention and excellent lace on the glass .  m : it 's a little thin , but i kind of like it . d : improved because of the thin mouthfeel .
dark brown with a light brown , foamy head that stays through the entire pint and leaves a nice lacing .  the mouthfeel is light carbonation , somewhat on the watery side , but very drinkable .

on the nose : ( hold on a sec , i got ta blow my nose , goddamn pollen ) sweet pine and hops sandwich , a touch of dry alcohol , almost has that earthy breadiness of belgian trappist offerings , slight prune detected as well , an excellent olefactory exercise on the mouth : tastes flatter than it looks , not to a huge detrement mind you . the 10.5 % is subdued on the take , nice warming in the gullet however , not as interesting as the nose , solid but nothing to go gaga over imo . drinkability : for the style it is standard if not a touch boring overall , a nice beer , one to start people out on the style perhaps , the abv is well hidden here so take some care .  light bodied d- in moderation , this beer is perfect for a 2 beer session .
a nice balance .  very creamy mouthfeel .

s : boozey up front , with some vanilla and whiskey barrel charateristics , followed immediately by caramel and white grape juice and an interesting hops profile , which is mostly citric , somewhat resiny , and with a deep earthiness to it . t : sweet and everything you 'd expect from the smell , except for a noticeable sticky molasses cigar linger . this is malt heavy , but well balanced with hops that are n't overly bitter . it 's nice , maybe a little too sweet with a dry malt extract coating on the mouth , but nice .  m : nice light body on it with mild carbonation , which was perfect for this style of ale .

the smell on this one is incredible , and leaves little to be desired . a lot of chocolate hits the nostrils as well as bitter espresso . this is by far the best porter i have ever smelled , thus far . the taste is not quite up to par here .  m - smooth and creamy ! d - surprisingly good for an american porter .

smell : lovely aroma of toasted fresh bread with earthy hints of nuts , vanilla , and molasses . drinkability : starts off with a great aroma , but the taste slips just a bit .  m - very creamy and milky and chewy , and not heavy in the least , this combined with the fantastic flavors gives one much to savor .

s : nose is pleasantly funky , mild barnyard with notes of hay and grass .  i keep tasting chocolate ice cream ... dry chocolate ice cream ... not cloy at all ... very fantastic finish and mouthfeel ... german beer ftw will buy again !
wonderful caramel , butterscotch aroma with a delicate spiceness .  mouthfeel was great , it was very rich and smooth with little carbonation but it fit the stout just right .

wow , the smell is the absolute best part of this brew - strong on the citrus . when first tasting dreadnaught , i picked up more piney hop taste than the smell indicates . the more i drank , however , the citrus hop flavor came through . i paid $ 8.99 for this bomber and it was worth it ( although pricey for an everyday beer ) .  i love the mouthfeel on this beer , probably my favorite part of it .
smell is one of the best ever , strong flowery , grassy smell . slight grainy smell also . you know what is about to happen .  a nice smoothness develops into a wonderful creaminess .
smell is hops - straight , beautiful hop smell . seriously , smells awesome . okay , taste is lagging behind a ways .  the mouthfeel is one of the best i 've ever had .
nose is heaven , sweet green apples , almost like a sour cider .  great mouthfeel and is smooth on the palate with a hoppy bitterness that lasts forever .

i gave it a good rating for smell just because it 's so damn unique . taste is sweet malts , some hops and a bitter finish .  this is a big , complex , full bodied beer . the huge amounts of malts in this thing are chewy and even feel like they stick to the teeth some .

the aroma continues to provoke the senses with a luscious , mouthwatering perfume . its flavor had a tough time catching up to its exceptional aroma , but still came through with a graceful sequence of sweet malts modestly checked with a light hop scheme .  taste- wonderfully intense malt , and a big bready character that thankfully outweighs any unpleasant sweetness that the malts could impart . fantastically effervescent , it rides into the mouth and over the tongue with confident grace ... all the while alive and outspoken .
the smell is great , roasted barley , choc , some hints of caramel , delicious . taste is fantastic .  super creamy mouthfeel , medium body and carbonation level .
the nose is impressive . easily the most enjoyable part of drinking this beer .  the mouthfeel is exceptional and that is all i am going to say about this .

s - heavy red wine , oak characteristics and obviously a brett brew t - follows the smell , close your eyes and you might be deceived that you are n't drinking a beer almost .  mouthfeel - heavy body with mild carbonation . it 's perfect to me .

a - surprisingly decent head retention and lacing for the style , that eventually settles to a partial white cap and thick collar .  m : the mouthfeel is delightful . fairly thick for an ipa , almost creamy with mild carbonation .

i 'm gon na call this one black with a three inch cocoa head .  appearance : cloudy burnt orange/brown - nice head retention smell : cinnamon , nutmeg , pumpkin spice taste : hops , cinnamon , coriander , nutmeg - similar to an american wild ale - very tannic mouthfeel : my favorite part very tannic , smooth - the rye dries the palate out so you 're ready for another sip or another bite of food .

hops are juicy smelling . very complex and citrus-fruity aroma . t : mmmm ! d : this is a tasty beer on the verge of being terrific . a solid offering , i would have a few of these .  m - the creamiest beer i 've ever had . wow . thick , smooth , perfect .

poured into a chimay goblet.. well , the name does n't lie ... this is a pitch black with a creamy but small head ... laces unbelievably though.. this almost has an ris look to it with its perceived thickness.. this has one of the best aromas i 've ever experienced ... it has all of the aspects of a great stout with an added extra of smokiness that reminds me of a nice thick cut bacon ... it 's just wonderful ... it 's loaded with roasted malts and i might even get a little touch of hops here as well.. just magnificent ... very rich roasted flavors here ... loads of dark roasted malts with that smoke that i was getting in the aromas mix wonderfully with a tinge of hops on the finish ( although not much ) ... there 's a thickness to this that belies the export stout style.. i would guess ris or double stout all the way here ... there 's a meatiness here as well that i would assume comes from the smoke.. it 's a nice brew , i know that.. i 'm really digging it ... i 'm very glad i got to enjoy this brew.. it 's loaded with rich dark flavors and the aromas here are ridiculously delicious.. the whole experience was terrific.. very nice export stout.. very drinkable although at 8.5 , it could hurt you quick ...  bear republic really , really nailed the mouthfeel on this one .
