a : pours a deep , hazy plum body that resides beneath a three-finger head of creamy pinkish-tan foam ; good retention and tons of lace . probably the best-looking barleywine i 've seen . beautiful .  m : nice and light , yet still has some body . very smooth , good carbonation , good residue . exceptional .
smells great . taste : pretty disappointing after the aroma .  however , it tastes great and feels great in the mouth .

aroma is sweet delicious malt bomb extravaganza . dark fruits , plenty of sweet caramel laced with burnt sugars , no heat at all , and a small amount of oaty malted milk ball aroma . a+ aroma for sure . this is one amazing beer , it woo'ed the hell out of me .  the mouthfeel is oh so smooth and creamy , just perfect !

upon opening the bottle you receive a pleasant aroma and on pouring the smell is obviously even more intense . the mouthfeel is actually kind of weak and bitter , surprisingly , given the pleasant look and smell of this beer .  mouthfeel- damn , this sh*t is creamy ! smooth , medium carbonation , but goes down super smooth . nice light bitterness in the aftertaste .

smell- the smell is another one of my favorite parts about it . i can smell mangos i think . taste- ok at first it is a little bitter but once it settles it has a great full flavor tast to it .  sweet malts are offset by crisp hops together producing a wonderful balance and mouthfeel . sooo smooth !

it feels odd to categorize such a beer as a stout . the aroma is very tame first tiem around , as it warms it become beautiful and fragrant with mocha , coffee , coconut , and lactose together .  the mouthfeel is light , with excellent particulates that roam the mouth . a most excellent brew that i would n't hesitate to try again .
most impressive is that lacing absolutely coats the entire glass top to bottom . color is bronze .  m : smooth as silk but liquid is very thick and creamy . low carbonation .
the smell is amazing . coffee dominates , and while i 'm not a coffee drinker , i like the smell of it .  smooth and creamy , very soft carbonation . booze is extremely well hidden .

if you are going to have a flavored beer , apricot is a good one . it 's all about the smell and the flavor . apricots and other fruits .  mouthfeel is truly wonderful , with a heavy , syrupy feel mixed in with a light tingle from some hidden carbonation and the alcohol itself .

spicy and compliments the smell . m - thin and smooth , carbonation does not come in to play which may be from the age . d - this beer is very drinkable .  super creamy mouthfeel w/o any overcarbed bite .

the aroma is fantastic , sweet , sour , chocolate malt all blending to a wonderful bouquet . taste is a bit too spicy , but otherwise very pleasantly complex . mouthfeel is dry and acrid , not as smooth as some others .  m-grand canyon deep and gordian knot complex . amazingly tantalizing on the palate . while it looks still in the glass it bursts with palate stimulating carbonation with each sip . like an amusement park in your mouth ! this is a highly enjoyable and palate stimulating sipper . a mighty fine drinking brew .

the nose is pretty interesting in this one , with a complex aroma profile of orange citrus , funk , light clove and some honey .  the mouthfeel on this beer is abosolutely amazing , almost like carbonated cream , it is wonderful and invites another sip immediately .

the nose on the beer is very good with a nice orange burst type hop presence . i just wish the taste followed suit . the beer is overly bitter , with a very pungent tangy hop bite , and not enough of the enjoyable orangey citrus hop and estery juices that i was expecting from the aroma .  t/m - well carbonated , providing a prickly yet very smooth feel as it rolls across the tongue .

smell : wow ... i was n't expecting this at all . incredibly hoppy , honey , almost strawberry jam sticky hop smell . taste : i found it a little too watery at first , which was a dissapointment . another intriguing brew with an awful label from ray mcneil .  again this is a beer with a very good character but i still feel it does n't perfectly balance m- incredible mouthfeel .
s : very nice and inviting smell of lemon and malt .  m- great body , great carbonation . feels good .
definite beer geek cologne going on .  m - rich and thick , very chewy .
just excellent .  excellent mouthfeel , low carbonation .

poured worthily into a duvel glass an orange amber with a thick white froth appearing and clinging nicely as a sip smelling of glorious flowery pine , dank indeed , bursts into bitter pine in the front of the mouth before cascading oily bubbles across just enough malt to save the day , without much abv burn , from what is otherwise a seriously bitter villain lacking a bit of nuance .  m : perfect . syrupy feel at first , but it does not over pollute your pallate like some brews .
smell is strong , and fruity for the most part .  finishes dry with nice mocha notes & a touch of charred grain mf : very oily & smooth as all hell with low carbonation & nice stickyness .

the aroma on this beer is a little bit of a lot of different tones , with nothing over-powering , really nice . taste is decent .  bitter black chocolate moves into the woodiness and finishes boozy m- creamy , full-bodied , coats the mouth and boozy heat d- really impressed with this one .

s : earthy tart wheat , lots of honey , sweet toffee , and a nice floral hop/heat combination . bit-o-honey candy comes to mind .  round velvety texture , excellent carbonation , and ( as you would expect ) some warming . exceptionally satisfying brew - if not my absolute favorite from unibroue , it is the one i return to most often .

the initial nose is wonderful . first comes the hops . i actually can smell parts of all 3 bastards in here , awesome . the taste is slightly disappointing relative to the nose .  the malt is well back but the beer still has a nice light body . the palate is a great balance of all that and a nice honey quality in the background .
reviewed 12/27/2008 ( bottle ) : pours a pretty clear darkish orange colored body , with a huge foamy off-white head , very lasting .  it 's just smooth and thick enough to feel perfect going down .
pitch black with a moccho coloured big head , really , really black .  mouthfeel is sublime . kind of like a benign dreamy tingling that coats the palate evenly .
not sure if i need a spoon for this one . pours thick as anything i have ever seen .  a full bodied beer that is creamy smooth and goes down really easy .

s -- amazing smell of dark chocolate and roasted coffee , no sweetness to it , but very pleasant . t -- the coffee in the smell comes through the strongest , with a hint of the chocolate .  m : wonderfully smooth . nice creamy texture that does n't stick too long in the mouth .

appearance : big pillowy off-white head . minimal lacing . burnt orange color .  a faint bit of tannins in the middle of the tongue starts the finish , which is incredibly long with trailing , vineous notes of chocolate and spiced orange peel . ya it 's a bit like those warheads candies , but it 's tucked in such an incredible silky richness .
the hop aroma was very good , while the malts were only so-so .  m/d : a full , silky smooth brew with low ( perfect ) carbonation .
smells wonderful . taste - tastes buttery and lemony .  subtly carbonated , with a medium-full body and a delightful smoothness .

a - translucent , super vibrant golden straw color that could illuminate a room . finger eggshell ( always wanted to work that color into a review ! ) head with a nice bubbly ring and a thin white film of bubbles remains on the surface .  mouthfeel is where this beer really shines , and makes one understand why some folks are such lager fans . the balance in this beer is amazing , with everything seemingly in the right preportion .

very alluring aromatically , strong bakery smell , quite yeasty , some wheat a little bit of sweet and citrus thrown in .  the mouthfeel on this is exceptional , so smooth will alcohol masterfully controlled .

i must admit i havnt tried this beer before and have seen it around heaps and have just avoided it for some reason so finally decided to finally see what its like after hearing mixed reviews and set the record straight , it pours a jet black as night colour with very nice carbonation that leaves a two finger cappicino laced head with heaps of visible lacing , it has aromas of strong alcohol and mocha malts and almost smells similar to a bourbon and coke not a very nice smell , the mouthfeel is above average with a mediumish mouthfeel at the start with hints of raisins , chocolate , coffee and some hops right at the creamy finish and im so glad the taste is so different to the aroma very nice , i cant believe a beer can look this good , smell bad and still taste beautiful anyways would drink again .  m= perfect dryness and crispness .

i absolutely love the aroma of this beer , and with more restrained alcohol its drinkability would improve .  not the stunner i was hoping for m- beautiful mouth feel . i sure hope this is not the `` great sculpin '' i 've been waiting for for that past few years .

well , not quite , but it is a very nice , very complex blend of sweet malts and almost floral scents . it 's a very subdued sweetness , heavy for a lager but no where near as complex as its smell would lead to expect .  m : the feel is exactly how i like my imperial stouts . there is a decent amount of carbonation in there as well .

beer also appeared to be quite carbonated smell : hot-day-amn . the smell of this one is trump tight . the eastern spices are like aroma therapy . those clove-ish spices blend with the hops and a sweet fruit scent to create an enticing aroma . taste : from the second this one hits your lips you just know that this is an `` americanized '' tripel .  mouthfeel was phenomenal - silky smooth and with a slight hops bite on the tongue , giving 'way on the finish to a great caramel sweetness .
smells of loads of caramel , vanilla , sugar , lactose . basically like dessert . far too sweet .  the mouthfeel on this beer is almost perfect . a nice smooth drinkable beer .

it smells like a a big pile of hops . there are also some alcohol esters and actually a decent aroma of biscuit-like malt . t : hops dominate .  the mouthfeel was phenomenal . to have a cask conditioned beer is such a treat , and i 'm glad my neighborhood bar always has one beer on cask .

smell is incredible : pure piney , grapefruity hops with a veneer of rich malt . and that in itself is amazing ! finishes like an unsweetened soda .  visual appeal : a bubbly , misty bar of shining gold , appealing streaks , almost continuous effervescence smell : very reminiscent of hard apple cider , mild hop aroma , strong yeast , really grew on me as beer warmed flavor : pilsner malts and bohemian hops and very strong cloudy yeast flavor lingers a long time , feel warmth of alcohol on back of palette , hints of citrus but not strong enough , i 'd prefer this a little sweeter , however mouthfeel : lovely effervescence plays with whole of tongue drinkability : heavy abv -- sipping beer , definitely would not drink more than one at a time my first ever belgian ale , right before the yank memorial day weekend , and i 'm definitely feeling it ( the ale , that is . ) i have `` gained a level .

a big , beautiful whack of tropical fruits on the nose - pineapple , passionfruit . superb . the tropical fruits are still there on the palate but perhaps a little more resinous than i was expecting .  the body is very full & rich with just the perfect amount of carbonation .

brewery states they did pick up some brett recently , popped the cork off ... corked talked about brett to me , more fruit than funk . hops stay modest . mild tartness , infancy of the brett ? it does have a ghost-like funk within . sweet roasted finish , pretty much burnt sugar . not a hair short of being great , the brewery admits to some funk ... wish i had another bottle to see where it goes .  the carbonation is very low ( natch ) , the body silky smooth , and dead creamy .
pours a beautiful slightly hazy amber color with a large two inch off white head . excellent retention and some great lacing .  first sip reveals a soft creamy texture with mild rolling carbonation .
s - nutty , chocolaty , malty aroma .  mouthfeel : exceptionally smooth and silky as can be .

nose is very complex , sweet stone fruits ( nectarines , peaches , and plums ) , a bit of the the pit of the stone fruit , woody , and sour funk . however , the taste was very disappointing , with a distinct stone fruit puree like taste dominating any sourness perceived in the nose . decent medium bodied beer with light carbonation , but the taste really disappointed .  really coats the mouth for an excellent mouthfeel .
bright grapefruit and citrus with a very sweet candy malt aroma . candy coated hops ... yum !  mouthfeel : about as perfect as could be asked for .

the smell is aggressive , and with high standard , quite classic . a vanilla character from the oak treatment adds nicely to the vibrant sweet malty caramel butterscotch toffee brown sugar molasses notes . really nice ! ! the flavor is quite nice as it reflects the nose yet has a surprisingly black licorice thing going on , especially in the really enjoyable aftertaste .  perfect . d- a remarkably smooth beer , although a bit mild .
aroma has nice sweet notes , but it 's dominated by hop perfume . nice pine and floral notes abound .  f : wonderfully thick .
pours a hazy full copper color and is topped by a two finger thick , frothy , tan colored head .  m : very creamy feeling , small bubbles , not too sticky .
smells quite good . pours dark apple juice color , clear , mild head .  full rich mouthfeel , particularly fun after back-to-backing the hansenns cassis .

sweetish and beautiful . t : unfortunately , the alcohol flavor jumps to the front , and while it 's not quite overwhelming , it 's a large part of the flavor , which i do n't find pleasant .  body is velvety , full , round , and waiting to be enjoyed like a dangerous fruit i have in mind heh heh . finish is a fascinating contrast between exquisite and coarse , not too long and proly not a session unless ur into gettin hauled off .

pours a murky borwn with some red hue with absolutely no head to speak of here but was expected , great aromas of cocoa some sugar cookie dough and orange with some noticable nuttieness.a real sipping brew here and fruity to the hilt big orange flavors along with some sour cherry and i have to say it does have this vodka and cranberry flavor to it the first i have ever experienced that in a beer , as the beer warms a real nutty presence come out as well.a nice before bed beer very enjoyable and exremely complex .  the alcohol burns just a bit in the back of my throat , but overall the mouthfeel on this is amazing . d- wow !
a : huge , creamy , tan head with insane lacing . very dark red-brown , but not utterly opaque . it certainly looks impressive . s : surprisingly neutral .  exceptional body .

when i first opened the bottle i could smell the cherrys right away . it was a very sweet smell which suprised me that the beer was not as sweet as the smell . very nice appearance .  '' love the mouthfeel .
i can also catch a slight nose of peaty scotch if i catch it the right way . fantastic aroma here .  mouthfeel : full bodied , chewy , carbonation is spot on .

smell is incredible . a big sugar smell is predominant accompanied by nice dark malts . there is a nice thickness to it as well , that makes it incredibly smooth . drinkable beer for a strong abv .  this was the first belgian i ever had . it has a very creamy smoothness that i really love . finishes long and dry with more fruityness .

poured into a tulip a nice dark brown color , nice carbonation , awesome fuckn ' head , never seen a head like this from a bw , two-finger creamy tannish head , tons of sticky lacing and islands through out the drink .  the taste is a rich velvety malt with an amazing mouthfeel and a fully satisfying richness .

this is obviously a schwarzbier or brazilian black beer -- not a euro dark lager . anway : nice black color with thick , foamy tan head , fades slow , very nice sticky lace .  very big and chewy mouthfeel

flavour is bit more restrained , still very nice with all the traditional hefe characteristics , wheaty and yeasty with cloves but also some caramel and brown bread . aftertaste is , like with most wheat beers , very moderate but nice . can you expect a hefeweizen to be much better than this ?  body is medium-full for style , and this is just about perfect on the way down .
bronze coloured with a big head and marvellous slightly citrus , very herbal nose . hops dominated with a very distinctive lemon rind flavour to the fore .  great mouthfeel .

body is significantly darker than i 'd expect out of a typical hefe , but not to the point that this should be called a dunkel ; kind of a thickly hazed tarnished bronze , with weird , grainy chunks of yeast . massively fruity , spicy , and complex . it 's nice to see japanese brewers stepping outside the box a little . sadly most of the other flavors from the nose are very subdued here , though the cidery sweetness remains . drinkability : this is one of those beers that 's more fun to smell than it is to drink , but it 's still pretty good . worth whatever exorbitant price i paid for it in nagasaki , but not as enjoyable as the pils .  solid mouthfeel , smooth and dense with animated carbonation .
pours nicely for a two finger thick tan head , and has a copper colored well filtered body .  interesting effervescent mouthfeel makes it a pleasure to savor .

a- nice pour into a standard pint glass , about 3 fingers of nice creamy/airy/cloudy head , great release . deep rasberryish/velvety red rusty color . nice consistent lacing throughout .  really big round full mouthfeel .
upfront the smell has alot of oak and toffee . no alchohol .  high level of carbonation with tons of tingle on the tongue . another excellent beer from ommegang .

bomber appearance - well , hello tall , dark and handsome . what a beautiful pour - thick , mahagony brown with a cocoa head that seems to sort of fade into the beer ( no clear division at first ) .  it is exceptionally smooth and drinks perfectly for the style .

smells awesome . if this tastes anywhere near as good as it smells , i will be happy . the smells are simply fantastic - if i have another bottle , i may just let it sit and inhale the fumes rather than actually drinking it .  m - full thick body , chewy and creamy at times .

it smells awesome and makes my mouth water just anticipating the first taste !  the mouthfeel of this bastard makes the beer for me -- incredibly soft and smooth for strong ale , probably the result of the oaking .
pours with a hefty amount of two finger thick light tan head , and has a clear copper colored body .  mouthfeel was full , thick , and creamy with a rich sweetness on the tongue .

s : striking tropical fruit , pineapple , lots of oranges , kiwi fruit , very nice . my kind of nose in an ipa . d : the nose tricked me into thinking i was going to get something great , but this beer still impressed me just going on the previous scores .  first sip reveals a smooth silky textured beer with a fairly thick body and gentle rolling carbonation . there is a sticky sweet residue on my lips after each sip and the boozy warmth lingers as well . the booze factor makes this a sipper and it is a little sweet and boozy to drink a full bomber .

great amber apperance with thick ass head that will not stop clinging to the glass .  mouthfeel is oily with a full body and fine carbonation for a smooth chewy feel . surly always hits this aspect right on the nail and this beer is no exception .
it is very nice however .  a great take on belgium ale ; apples , pears , lemons , apricot and orange flavors nustle their way thru a carbonated full bodied swig .
nutty aroma with lots of caramel , hay and oats seem to scream out at me .  it is very creamy and very smooth . it 's like chocolate silk . very delicious .

nose : chocolate and caramel , some fruit notes like plums , brown sugar . quite sweet smelling , marshmallow and milk chocolate . nice roasted malt character as well , a bit of burnt toast , a bit coffee .  m : the mouthfeel is what really sold me on this beer .

this beer smells amazing but its taste is over the top .  mouthfeel - great smoothness , i was inclined to take a deep draw at the outset , very quenching . restrained carbonation adds to the smoothness .

holy hops . i like me some hops . huge hops and not much else to smell ... maybe a touch of some orange peel or citrus something . i was blasted immediately with the hops from the first taste and on . overall i liked it ... i would n't complain if i drank it again .  the aroma is bold of chocolate and roasted malts ... the taste is very mild for a stout , blended extremely well between the sweetness and the roastness ... the mouthfeel wins top honors , this is even smoother than samuel smith 's imperial stout , absolutely incredible mouthfeel !

quite nice . p : rather boxy and angular at first , with no discerning flavors other than a malty bitterness .  mouthfeel is just perfect - thick , rich , and creamy , with a slightly oily sheen that coats the mouth and throat .

it could stand to have a little less heat , but it was otherwise pretty delicious . again , it 's slightly hot , and seems a little less rich than the smell , but it 's still quite good . m - pretty much flat , syrupy aftertaste , thinner than i 'd expect for a 10 % brew .  exceptional silky mouthfeel .
big chocolate smell , hint of coffee .  m : incredibly creamy leaving a nice coating around the mouth that tingles slightly .

aromas were the strong point for this drink . deep blackberry aromas mixed with bready , wheaty textures . although nice and light for a summery day , its strong blackberry taste ( albeit weaker in comparison to the blackberry smell ) did not really make this too refreshing or crisp .  super thick dark chocolate flavor , light coffee flavors , good coffee bitterness near the finish super creamy , heavier in body , extremely smooth and hopefully i 've mentioned the creaminess overall , i love this stout , give me more

very sharp and fruity hops , with a good amount of grapefruit and pineapple . the hops seem to disappear from the flavor , very surprising considering the aroma . the hops are more tea-like , sitting on top of a sweet bread-like malt base .  mouthfeel is astonishingly smooth and creamy for such a rich , complex ale .

the nose is extremely complex -- clay soil , caramel , butter , farmland , and fresh aromatic hops are all in there , along with some more elusive intangibles that are conjuring up all sorts of images of rural europe for me . on the tongue , the caramel sings out with a spritzy edge , the hops keep it interesting , and the butter moves to the forefront , but what really does it for me is a slight sour twist towards the end -- reminiscent of those flemish ales that ive recently fallen in love with ( such as duchesse de bourgogne ) . this says to me , `` drink with food !  great bubbly mouthfeel , no aftertaste at all .
the sweet malts balance this very nicely . m & d : medium body beer , nice level of carbonation , makes for a semi-creamy mouthfeel . just an outstanding ipa .  wonderful full mouthfeel .

smell is dominant dark fruit ( plum and fig ) with just hints of chocolate cake , cherries , and that leather smell . very complex . there is a dark smooth malt character and some caramel as well . i could smell this all day . taste is the nose , followed by a whiff of smoke and finishing like a rich deep red wine . my brother commented that he picked up on dr. pepper like qualities . caramel malt . mouthfeel was oily and clingy . drinkability : i know it 's a great beer but for me drinkability was just ok .  the mouthfeel of this beer is great . they do an excellent job with the carbonation and creating the perfect body for a beer .

this is where this beer truly shines . sweet brown sugar and candied fruits - i thought of cherries and apricot - are met head-on by the alcohol . the result is a rich , warm , somewhat medicinal elixir that was just wonderful to inhale . do n't get me wrong - it 's very nice . it just did n't quite live up to the advance billing . very nice .  mouthfeel : true german feeling on this beer . medium viscosity , rolls across the palate smoothly and is perfectly carbonated . great overall feel and authenticity .
smells delicious and this scent would be a great air freshener .  mouthfeel : truly phenomenal creamy medium body with the slightest touch of syrup likeness .
this was hard to decide on , the smell was really intriguing , but taste more mediocre .  perfectly carbonated with an amazing mouthfeel .
big aroma full of treacle , vanilla , oak , and hints of raisins and bourbon . an acquired taste , but very good .  m : absolutely wonderful ... smooth & creamy .

it was quite amazing . nice bitter coffee notes , with more chocolate notes and sweet malts than with the aroma . this was smelling great , drinking good and going down easy .  m- medium body and creamy soft carbonation lends to this one being a great sipper . d- pretty smooth but balanced , could have more now and will definitely have again .

s - great mix of malt sweetness , roasted coffee , raisins and alcohol .  mouthfeel is full and rich , easy to sip and enjoy . sweetness hinders the drinkability a bit , one bottle at a time is enough for me .
the aroma was fairly balanced between biscuit , roasted malt , woodiness , vanilla/nut , and mild citrus .  mouthfeel : has a great mouthfeel . it has exceptional smoothness .
the hazelnut scent was so strong and so nice , it easily could have been mistaken for frangelico .  mouthfeel is medium-thick but amazingly silky . carbonation is moderate .

nose is big sweet plums , ripe pears and sweet cooked peaches with light spice - big , full , rich and assertive with big candi sugar tones . flavors are very complex and layered . front palate is sweet spiced cola and compote cooked fruit that goes to a dull bitter mid palate and finish .  m - perfect . exactly how a dipa should be .

super sweet aroma with lots of yeast an plenty of sweet , dark fruit . some toffee aroma as well . sweet flavor , though there 's a little sharpness there as well that reminds me , again , a little of port .  amazingly full body and mouthfeel for an american wheat , yet is crisp and refreshing at the same time .

amazing , both the most unique and best smell i have in a beer in a good long time . taste- a strong and front malt body .  taste- for a double ipa , this beer is not on a mission to wreck the palate ... with so much flavor i 'm surprised that the malts weigh in so heavily . solid . it 's sudsy ( the name of my beloved late parakeet ) and sublime . drinkability- one real attribute about this bruiser of a beer is that the abv ( 10 % ) is completely hidden ... it 's nowhere in any of the above categories . this is more like a nectar , thick and juicy , garnering respect for each sip .

wonderful tropical fruit and floral aroma that from my experiences is ever present . the centennial hops are very distinctive as they come out in the aroma and flavor .  mouthfeel is very soft and full bodied with light carbonation .

not much there in the way of lace ... s - i could smell the hops when i was pouring this ... beautiful floral aroma with a little citrus ... like putting your nose in a bag of fresh hops t - good balance for how much hop aroma there is ... more on the sweet malty side rather than bitter ... definitely a sweet aftertaste .  m/d : full bodied , very smooth , velvet like .

a - pours an orange copper color with a layer of fine bubbles on the surface s - lots of piney and citurs hops , lemon , orange , just a totally amazing aroma t - grapefruit & orange upfront , sweet malt & a slightly bitter hop finish , a really flavorful hopbomb m/d - medium body with good carbonation , just a really drinkable beer , somehow its 10 % which you really have no way of knowing  the texture on this is great . with the silky texture and sweetness , this is a good sipper , but nothing you 'd have more than 2 of in a single sitting .
the aroma was quite exceptional . never before have i whiffed this nose of smoke in a beer .  taste & mouthfeel : thick , full-bodied texture goes well with the rich and yet smooth malt flavors .

a-dark brown/black s-nice blend of cocoa and leafy hops..really impresses on the nose . t-hops are a little more forward on the taste ... .interesting hop dimensions ... some bright citrus ... .and some grungy pine and weed like notes ... roasted malts ... .also some darker cocoa ... m-rich ... fuller bodied ... .feels bigger than a regular black ipa ... body fits ... o-top notch effort .  while there was no head , the carbonation is just right ; the body is no thinner or heavier than it should be .

the aroma is pretty complex like any respectable barleywine , but definitely more on the malt side . brown sugar is obvious and is of pleasant company to figs , peaches , alcohol and an all-around complex fruitiness .  however , the mouthfeel of this beer is phenomenal , on the tim of your tongue it tingles , in the middle it is smooth as silk , on on the edges it is a touch syrupy ( amazing ) a good beer , but not worth the price they charge for it .

s-this beer has one of the most pleasant aromas that i have smelt in a long time .  unbelievably smooth in mouthfeel - bittersweet chocolate and bitter roasted notes played effortlessly on your tongue .

12 oz bottle cloudy , dull golden amber color with a massive , creamy light brown/off white head . very dense and foamy , the head hangs around forever and leaves a lot of lacing .  feel is pretty rich for the style , although it 's medium body it 's almost full really , with such a rich , smooth feel . excellent . honestly , it 's not very typical of the style at all , but i 'm not letting that change my rating .
d - this is pretty good ipa .  amazing mouthfeel . creamy and finely carbonated .
aroma is clean and bright . sassafras along with quiet vanilla sit beneath a strong phenolic note .  velvety mouthfeel and smoother than sinatra .

a : two fingers of sea-foam-esque froth , barely off white in color , tops this brew but rushes to depart and leaves only traces of its existence . astonishingly clear .  the mouthfeel is dead-on creamy .

grapefruit ! my favorite aroma in beer and life for some strange reason , but enough about me ... .once i break from my grapefruit coma , i do notice pine and a little lemon rind in the background t - there is that damn grapefruit again , i just ca n't get away from it . immense hop flavor with a surprising amount of malt that finds its way through the hops .  mouthfeel is a heavy but perfect . heavy with lots of lactose , light but fizzi carbonation .

the smell was slightly chocolate . 2007 bottle 02/23/2008 beautiful smell like gourmet chocolates , an amazing improvement over the last year . this beer is a really good example of a cellar-worthy beer . 2006 vintage 01/10/09 smells malty grains , some chocolate , tastes good and probably ca n't get much better .  m- very , very thick and chewy . also quite heavy .

smell : sweet and pungent . horseblanket nose . spicy belgian funk is reminiscent of a gueuze .  everything blends nicely in ot 's thick , chewy , oily body . minimal carbonation here , and it works nicely .
s : very hoppy . has a floral , citrusy sweetness that is very deep and pleasant . faint candy smell also present .  m/d : full creamy body with light carbonation , pretty drinkable for 9 % .

poured a brilliant gold hue with a completely hazed clarity .  m - absolutely creamy and delectable ! the amazing , tiny bubbled froth envelopes and contains any alcohol sharpness that would otherwise make this 8.0 % beer a bit fiery in the swallow . superb . d - the mouthfeel makes this otherwise straight-up scotch ale an incredibly drinkable beverage . but be careful ! at 8 % , this beer is like getting a two-for-one special in each pint !
the aroma is the best part , but it goes down smooth and tastes nice .  mouthfeel is where this one shines , smooth as can be and perfectly carbonated , a light yet creamy quality .

there are several layers to the nose that create a great amount of depth . and finishes of with a chocolate covered apple character very nice . taste : the taste starts out very similar to the nose with very light touches of bourbon and oak but for me the beer has more chocolate than anything else very rich dark chocolate character and finishes off nicely with just a touch of apple mouthfeel : medium body with low carbonation overall : very good beer .  m- full body in the mouth and sticky on the lips .

there is something hypnotic about watching the beer cascade into a jet black liquid with a wonderful tan thick creamy head . to me , the head on this is the best of almost any beer , and has a unique look .  m - perfect . excellent balance of thick and creamy yet smooth and light enough to drink without too much concentration .
very good smell . taste- there is a good amount of alcohol and hop bitterness on the palate for this one .  m- creamy smooth with just the right amount of carbonation and a nice , dry finish .

smells amazing , like the normal version with some oak and bourbon . the smell was amazing to me . i thought the taste was a bit hotter than the normal irs , but that 's to be expected .  wow . the thick and creamy mouthfeel is perfect for the winter months and so warm .

apples , pears , plums , cherries , and a little bit of orange . interesting . some bubblegum/banana in here also . t- the taste isnt nearly as inviting as the smell , and is kind of a let down . d- after the smell this one sort of fell apart on me . i dont think id seek it out again .  the mouthfeel is a true hallmark of this beer .

aroma - this is where the beer shines i feel . a great funk , barnyard , grassy , astringent blast right to your nostrils . taste - definitely follows the nose . barnyard and belgian yeast right up front , almost a brett taste , the astringency is in the back with grassy notes . great smell and decent tasting beer , i am enjoying it !  mouth : velvety good . nice water . sweet , full , but not thick . medium to full bodied .

smell is beautifully complex & bright , like i just walked into an herb garden : really picking up on the rosemary , floral notes that are big but gentle , something kind of savory like oregano , maybe some basil or mint notes in there . seriously , this is fantastic , i do n't think i 've ever smelled a beer like it .  a bit astringent . fantastic , full body with a very creamy feel -- pretty impressive .
the smell is filled with some nice hops with a good bit of sweetness .  the mouthfeel is chewy , thick and amazing and the light carbonation is just right .

strong medicinal smell almost a eucalyptus quality also some fresh cut wheat or alfalfa , and some small notes of tropical fruit . smell is subtle at first and as the beer warms it really opens up . best quality of the brew is the smell . taste and mouthfeel is not as exciting as the smell . not bad at all a tingly carbonation and a little on the thin side .  wonderful carbonation .

look : it poured a transparent orange-brown colour with a thin tannish head that did not disappear smell : exceptional . it smells delicious . a little sour with some sweetness in there .  full creamy mouthfeel with a low carbonation . thick , thick mouthfeel .

s - roasted coffee , dark berries ( raspberry ) ripe fruit , dark chocolate , little bit of booze ( bourbon ? i 'm all for interesting beers , which this very much is , but i have had straight bourbon that goes down more easily .  mouthfeel : fully body , lower carbonation , love it .

big crazy head thats nearly out of control .  taste again where do i start ... sweet , spicy dark fruits soaked in alcohol ( raisins , currents , dates ) , toasted caramel notes , bready , some brandy / rum traces , biscuity , warming alcohol , spicy hop bitterness forces itself through the sweet maltiness , light madeira wine hints ... feel - so silky smooth ... rich and creamy ... light viscousness.. low drinkablilty for this one - a beer for savouring and sipping slowly ... overall - a phenomenal beer ... highly recommended .

cabernet scent is definitely apparent and quite unique . beyond the fruit and wine qualities , the aroma is a bit subtle .  m- extremely smooth with the right amount of carbonation d- this one goes down too easily .
i really like it .  smooth grit with comfort .

flavor did not quite live up to the aroma . it is a bit more piney than the aroma suggests , but still is dominated by citrus . there 's a strange quality right at the beginning of the swallow that i ca n't really describe except that it 's not positive .  the mouthfeel of this beer might be its most remarkable consistency ; velvety , silken slickness .
very nice sherry character to it with a hint of a woody edge .  in my mind , this is the perfect feel for an imperial stout .

it smells distinctly like pineapple cake . i mean you get the sweet pineapple and a really bready smell underneath . probably my favorite smell in a beer ever , different than the norm for an apa . definitely does n't live up to the smell but i enjoy it . the carbonation level is good and there is n't really a harsh aftertaste . there certainly is n't anything off-putting , and i would recommend it to anyone , at least for the sake of smelling it .  the mouth feel is awesome . i let a full gulp roll around from cheek to cheek just to let my tongue play in the surf .

smell was amazing , coffee , toffee , bitter chocolate , sugar , fruit .  very thick with just enough carbonation that completely fills the mouth and leaves a bittersweet flavor lingering on the palate , and a bit of a syrupy feel on the back of the throat with just a bit of alcohol heat that is perfect for the style .

smell is heavenly , with the almost overpowering aroma of peaches . there is a slight coating of sweet , sticky phlegm in the back of my throat , but it is sort of pleasing . over all this was a great journey and the buzz is just what i needed .  m : wow ! just so damn smooth .

a beautiful deep amber with ruby and copper hues . frothy white head with superb retention and lacing down the glass .  very palatable and no alcohol taste at all m - silky smooth , great carbonation .

glassware - imperial pint appearance - dark amber/red in color , which makes sense . nice two finger white head that leaves a lot of really great lacing on the glass .  unbelievably smooth . feel is so outstanding for a heavy dark lager .

hard pour gets a beautiful head to rise up , just a little more than two fingers worth of off-white frothiness . smells phenomenal . a bouquet of citrus hops , with a little bit of floral and maybe piney for good measure . so nicely balanced , just a little bit of bitter and the rest is flavor . the alcohol would probably catch me a buzz after just a couple , but it certainly weighs in a little lower than some comparable ipas , which is nice .  the mouthfeel was very very thick and creamy and not as thin as say a sierra nevada .

i 've always like tryign various fruit beers ... .and this one was certainly one of the better ones that i have tried . the raspberries are extremely prevalent to both smell and taste , but not to the point of being overwhelming .  m - huge , thick , syrupy , creamy , perfect carbonation .
great smell . on the buds , the mint is first and foremost .  m : the best feature of this beer . rich , creamy , and silky as it goes down .
appearance : black in color sporting a two finger creamy head that lasted a long time .  m- incredibly smooth with a nice carbonation .

an agressive pour was neither necessary nor desired to result in a glass 1/3 full of beer and 2/3 dense , off-white foam . robust carbonation , with many small bubbles .  the taste is initially of a very light porter and with a clean aftertaste that becomes a fruit sensation on the palate . the hop/malt balance is the real achievement here and it really contributes to the supreme drinkability . the smell upon opening the bottle is not an effective contrival of the taste that this beer is hiding as it only gives you an idea of the rooted flavor that is to be unleashed , the supreme balance and sublime flavor . great bier .

s- great nose ! pine , citrus , grapefruit , orange , malt , lots of hops yum . start is week middle is weak end is great . m- medium body , nice carbonation , o- this beer has a killer nose , one of the best but its color and flavor are a bit off for me , i would enjoy this fresh as opposed to part of their gabf temporary distribution in denver . good beer , but not world class by any means .  the mouthfeel is dry with a long and deep finish which is full of blackened malt and char . very very nice .

luckily , the aroma of this beer is quite good . a butterscotch maltiness was immediately noticeable and complemented perfectly with floral and spicy hop notes .  a - bright golden orange color with some chill haze present , two fingers of white frothy head that leaves thick froth-lace s - not too much rye here , just hints ... hops and bready malt t - hop bitterness up front , sweet bready malts in the back , only a hint of rye in the middle ... the malt backing is about as significant as it gets ... taste 's more like a straight up ipa than most rye beers i 've had m - hops tingle the tongue and give way to very thick , chewy malts that slide down nicely ... full-bodied and very enjoyable d - this is a reeeally well-balanced beer , i just wanted more rye flavor .

s : raisins and dark fruits with a mild white wine aroma .  m : one of the most enjoyable mouthfeels i 've ever had in a beer ; medium-bodied and moderately carbonated , immensely smooth and surprisingly creamy . d : i thought that the taste here was good , not great ... but the amazing mouthfeel and complex flavor keep drawing me back in , and at much faster rate than that of many beers whose tastes i prefer .

aroma definitely carries a strong banana smell to it with some clove in there as well . it smells like a hefeweizen for sure , but it 's categorized as a wit here . it starts out with a good banana presence , as was seen on the nose . no surprise there .  s - sweet malt , molasses , licorice and red grapes t - sweet dark malt and licorice with a pleasant spice finish m - strong carbonation with a chalky finish that subdues the strong alcohol taste nicely d - very strong licorice and spice flavors combined with a great mouthfeel that balances the alcohol

wow , this started off so well , looking great and smelling great , but simply fell apart at the taste .  m/d - the mouthfeel and drinkability are exceptional . this is a simple brown ale that i could knock back one after the other .
it smells great , but the flavor just ca n't back it up .  m : thick and creamy , the mouthfeel holds up to the indulgent theme set by the flavor .

this beer poured pitch black with a thick light brown head out of a 12 oz . this is how a stout beer is supposed to look !  m : very viscous and full . smooth carbonation and a nice stickyness make the mouthfeel very complimenting to the taste .

smell is boatloads of grapefruit , orange rind , and lemon ; really fantastic in the aroma department . taste is brisk , with a light but flavorful hop attack , refreshing wheat tartness , and perfect carbonation .  t- pretty solid all around . very smooth , robust , and thick .

strong aroma consisting of citrus bananas , cloves , vanilla and an overall strong alcohol presence . there 's a lot there . the mouthfeel is pretty full although something seems a bit off with a tangy , somewhat sour , very yeasty , citrus ( oranges and bananas ) flavor . i 've had other tripels recently that are better , karmeliet and chimay cinq cents come to mind , but this is a better beer than i original though .  the mouthfeel is what really sets this apart . having had very few english cask ales , i do n't know if this is gold standard , but it is the best mouthfeel i 've had on this style beer .

a : opaque , poured with small bubble head , thin veil of head , gives way over time to bubbles on side of glass but when glass is rotated there is still a ton of carbonation trapped in the beer s : full bourbon nose , malty , bourbon dominates , treacle , vanilla , intense t : full-flavored , extreme malt and bourbon flavor , not a great degree of heat , i love bourbon but it seems just a bit too much , toned down once beer warmed up m : warming , rounded , creamy , good body and mouthfeel without tons of etoh , strong bourbon aftertaste  creamy but thin body .

what struck me first was the phenomenally fresh smell . the roasted malt and slightly bitter hops hits your nose and just stays there , begging you to take a sip . while the beer is great , the taste did n't quite live up to the smell . a bit thinner than expected and a bit less complex than i had hoped .  mouthfeel is full but not too heavy .

malt and hop scents are virtually non-existent . very aromatic . t : starts off with a quick dose of pumpkin flesh .  great relaxed flavor , it has a nice sweetness to it , a good malt body ; it would be a great beer to drink while out on the river all day , as it has a wonderful flavor without having too much ( it was made with this in mind , according to one of the brewers ) . goes down extremely smooth with a great crisp , sweet aftertaste . ( had on-tap at the star city vfd brew fest fund raiser .

strong dance of raspberries , prunes , blackberries , oranges , ribes . you feel it 's still young on the nose too . t : sour taste of raspberries .  t : the taste was about average for a stout , almost identical in flavor to guinness m : amazing mouthfeel , so creamy and so smooth .

looks less viscous then i had expected smell is bourbon all the way . probably the most bourbon i have ever smelled in a ba beer . the smell prepares you for a very chewy brew but the mouthfeel isnt so .  mouth is extremely crisp , clean with tremendous carbonation and a nice light body .

what an aroma ! ! ! funky , fruity , sweetyeast , vinegar , spicemagic marker , sugar , oak , vanilla , cherries , sour-candies.you cant count all the smells . the taste is equally thrilling.sour and mouth puckering one minute , sweet and succulent the next . this brew is a little sweeter than expected , and very earthy . at times it seems to have a musty , woods-like quality about it . lingering , funky finish .  the mouthfeel on this ale was great , and i think the mouthfeel of just about any beer is enhanced by cask conditioning . it had a nice thick feel on the tongue .

it reeks of pumpkin pie without being too aggressive with it . the pumpkin pie aroma does n't dominate the taste and it actually tastes like a beer instead of some kind of pumpkin pie flavored wine cooler .  smooth as hell , perfect weight and carbonation .

the nose was the winning feature for me . it was a stunning coffee and chocolate explosion . it almost reminded me of a warm bowl of oatmeal with mocha covering it . it was a little too bitter and i really tasted the alcohol .  mouthfeel is very full and round .

overall the aroma is very nice . first sip , small tingly carbonation and average body . flavor is much less complex and rich than the nose advertised. , some toffee and fruit followed by a very clean yet somewhat empty finish .  the evil spirits pass by , leaving behind a faint citrus peel flavor as a reminder that they now own your mouth . it 's insanely smooth and creamy ... absolutely perfect in that aspect .

the smell is strong with brandy ( and seemingly bourbon ) and dark fruity sweet malts , caramel , and vanilla . very pleasant . holy shit , what this beer would be if it were carbonated ! dark fruit sweetness complimented by a smooth and invigorating alcohol presence ( 12.5 % ) , much like an imperial stout ... its damn decent right now , but so much greater in my carbonated imagination .  mouthfeel is very delicious with some creamy notes but some nice crisps and sharp grassy hop notes .

smells good too , obvious floral hops and substantial bready slightly sweet malt , both of which hit at the same time . this review is probably going to come out higher than it should due to the deceptively good appearance and smell .  the mouth feel is perfect , medium-thin , medium-low carbonation .

a : there is not too much better than a nitro'ed beer to look at . thick , rich creamy white head with tons of lacing .  mouthfeel is really impressive . very gradual on the tongue and extraordinarily balanced .

s : intense volatile pine , fresh grass , lightly toasted bread -- a very attractive , yet clean , smell . d : this ipa is a lightweight when it comes to taste , featuring a flavor profile that just ca n't live up to the remarkable smell . clean flavor qualities are taken too far at times , with only the finish really representing the style faithfully . it is genuinely appealing to sniff and to gaze upon , though .  the mouthfeel is outstanding , substantial and even sticky .

sticky , webbed lacing s - booze ! bourbon , vanilla , malt hiding under there somewhere . t - booze ! d - booze ! this one is just a little too 1 dimensional for me .  mouthfeel : delightfully creamy and full-bodied . very pleasant .

the aroma is amazing . smell it a mile away ; rough citrus , honey , upfront biting bitter that is unrelenting throughout . i really like the aroma .  silky silky smooth on the mouth , it makes it feel as light bodied but if you take the time to get a feel it 's almost medium . just fantastic . o- this is deffinitely a good saison , the mouthfeel is the highlight .

the first thing you notice is that this beer smells very floral and sweet , perhaps the most beautiful smelling beer i have ever had .  mouthfeel is incredibly smooth and creamy - almost reminded me of a nearly flat ginger ale , with more depth/body .
very sessionable , but only an adequate porter with the exception of the nose which is amazing .  just a hint of carbonation on the palate - utterly smooth .

pour yields a really beautifully colored beer , has a rosewood color , with a pillowy white head .  a very heavy body that is infinitely swishable in your mouth and extremely creamy . this beer is truly fascinating .

smell : nice . yeast , red apple , caramel malt , cake spice , with a slight hint of wood and butterscotch .  all the great flavor of the bottled lhms here , but perfectly creamy and full in texture . this only further reinforces my belief that nearly every big beer should be served nitro .

poured ~4c into a perfect pint glass . nice white head that is laying there forever and leaves nice lacing .  you can feel how well-crafted this beer is : perfect body ... thin , but not too thin ; carbonated , but not overdone ; hoppy aftertaste , but not a tastebud destroyer .

excellent aroma . lots of fruits both sweet and citrus , doughy yeast , something unknown but floral and distant anise perhaps .  mouthfeel is thick as hell and creamy , perfect for a big ris this is smooth as hell , much smoother than beers with this much ash flavor usually are .

750ml bottle poured into a tulip glass . appearance-brilliant ruby color with good clarity-absolutely gorgeous . moderate pale-pinkish head with decent retention .  thin in the mouth but heavy on the tongue . perfect for the style and the season .

i absolutely love the smell on this beer , but i also love peaty islay scotches . the smell reminds me of a campfire on a beach , with the peaty campfire smoke , wet wood , and leather aromas . the complex aromas are a little subdued on the palate . tons of different flavors in this beer , but none really stand out in front .  the lush velvety texture takes control of your mouth .

the scent on this beer is very sweet . tons of grapefruit and orange come through very strongly . also get a lot of alcohol in the nose . upon first sip , i get so much thrown at me at once . the hops are a bit overwhelming , as well as the booziness .  m - very smooth for such an alcoholic beer . disguises the bite very well .
smells great though . tart aromas and there is some great fruity and malty notes there too .  m - smooth , silky , full body with the perfect amount of carbonation o - great brew !

aroma is of caramelized sugar and taffy ; it really does smell just like creme brulee .  the mouthfeel is the standout . it 's thinner but soo creamy and velvety . the oatmeal gave it the feel i had hoped .
aroma : smells really good . nice malty aroma of coffee and a hint of chocolate .  mouthfeel - big , bold and smooth with lots of carbonation .

that 's what i get in the nose . fresh hot bowl of oatmeal delivered fresh to your nose with dallop of caramelized brown sugar and a heaping of fresh raspberries . a deep burgundy/purple color , it almost looks like a shiraz . i love the complexity and uniquness of this beer , but it tastes too much like a wine cooler for me to love . i just ca n't handle all of the fruit .  the mouth feel is amazing on this beer .

smell : the smell is excellent . the bourbon comes through in the form of vanilla and a touch of oakiness . it is exceptionally tasty and smells fantastic , but i am having a very hard time getting over the mouthfeel .  mouthfeel : great thickness ; fully coating the mouth with great flavors . the mouth is great and just thick enough .

lots of intense sweet and spicy hops in the nose , insanely floral . i prefer a more balanced beer , but for the style , this way pretty damn good .  the mouthfeel was awesome with silky smooth liquid and superb carbonation .

smells very sweet , of caramel and spice and a definite alcohol presence on the nose . i love it . one of the best smelling beers i 've put my nose to .  the mouthfeel , though , was the best part . it fills your mouth with mousse like consistency with very round edges .

smell : a deep and delightful warm caress to the nostrils . chocolate , molasses , brandy , and oak joint together for an exquisite amalgamation . wonderfully sugary , earthy , and effervescent .  m : medium in body with a really smooth and creamy feel on the tongue .

a very pricey brew in my area , with a four-pack going for nearly $ 13 ... was shrewd enough to pick up a single 12oz bottle which still ran me a hefty $ 3.50 ... pours a beautiful , dark , mahogany-brown tan color that resulted in a fluffy white head that had some staying power ... smell is malty , with a prunish aroma ... taste is very complex with an almost root-beer , licorice flavor that tingled on my tongue for awhile after the first-sip ... i really enjoyed this brew , put for the price , not sure i 'd pay again unless i could find a single ... definitely interested in the pale version from this brewery ... the taste is sweet , but an alcohol presence is certainly noticeable.. a good brew , definitely recommended ... .  the carbonation is perfect . i love this .

pours an effervescent honey color with3+ fingers of cream colored head . insane lacing & head retention s : grapefruit & lemon , fades a bit as this warms t : follows the nose , plus pineyness , slight breadyness & a touch of leafy hops & dryness hiding behind a ton of grapefruit up front .  mouthfeel . amazing , thick rich and seems sweet but comes together .

a big frothy white head that sticks around forever , and then leaves some pretty sticky lace on the glass . a very pretty beer , love head .  m : the feel is excellent with fine carbonation lending a creaminess that is top-tier and a clean scrubbing finish with the right balance of crispness and aftertaste . d : an fine tripel with classic light fruit flavors mixed artfully with pepper and spice and a top-notch mouthfeel compose a very good brew .

s : holy hops ! strong citrus and pine hop aroma , sweet and fruity , not very bitter smelling . t : follows the nose , tropical fruit and citrus hops dominate , followed by piney flavors . o : this beer gives me a rock-solid .  mouthfeel : low carbonation leads to thirsty gulps .

a : pours a dark brown , almost black , with a tan 1 finger head and decent lacing s : lots of coffee , chocolate and roasted malt , cant wait to drink this one t : not as much coffee as i thought would be there , a lot of chocolate and roasted malt coming through with a nice coffee bitterness .  the first thing i noticed actually was the incredible mouthfeel .

the head is fluffy and impressive with a slightly off white color and nice staying power . it leaves pretty average lace .  m : the best part of the beer . very creamy while still having a touch of that hop thickness you want .
appearance- dark brown almost black with tan head with decent lacing .  incredible mouthfeel .
it smells delicious . appearance : deep amber in color with a thick light cream colored head .  mouthfeel is probably the best part of this beer .
big roasty coffee with cocoa aroma is readily evident upon , without lifting the glass .  still i thought the aroma was alittle weak , but once it hits your mouth it is amazing .

aroma is crisp blend of citrus and hops slightly sweet , wonderful . best part of the beer do do n't drink this on out of the bottle pour it or you will miss out .  super easy going down with a perfect dry finish .

there is also a nice toffee and molasses sweetness to keep the aroma balanced . there are also hints of dark berries : to me it smelled like blueberry and raspberry . it is a very enticing aroma . taste : more roasted glory , and the first sip was a shock of burnt bitterness ; the overpowering intensity , though , passed after a couple sips .  medium bodied beer combined with very active and tight carbonation combines to create an exceptionally creamy beer .
i like the flavor and am very impressed by the aroma it offers .  hard to imagine this almost perfect mouthfeel sticking around too long .
amazing nose of peach with a high , frothy , long lasting head with an almost soapy mouthfeel .  perfect silky creamy carbonation .

a : fantastic clarity , golden , and a relentless head , a 3 millimeter head is still visible after 20 minutes , leaving rings of lace in its wake .  the finish lingers for a while , almost spicy with a slight alcohol burn m - pretty ideal for this style i thought .

it 's really smooth and i appreciate the level of authentic bourbon present in the nose . the flavors consist of chocolate , roasted malts , light coffee with cream , vanilla , barrel and alcohol . the 9 % is n't hidden at all and after the nose , is pretty surprising . and it is n't the bourbon that is overpowering , it 's the abv of the beer itself .  a thick , milky mouthfeel , with tiny , spritzy carbonation carrying the rich flavor through your mouth .

a - pours an opaque golden hue with limited head and noticeable lacing s - apples , bleu-cheese , cherry pie dominate the aroma , surprisingly . citrus and grapefruit as it warms . t - very sweet , especially for an ipa .  outstanding mouthfeel ! very drinkable .

the smell is very nice . lots of tropical fruit flavor on this one and sweet candy .  nice touch of bitterness lingers as i contemplate the rich , full mouth feel . nice beer , much more approachable than the expedition .

poured a solid black , even when i held my led flashlight up behind it , with about an inch of thick , sturdy light brown head that had great retention and moderate lacing .  the best part of the rwanda gatsinga coffee stout is in my opinion the mouthfeel which is extremely smooth and leaves a pleasant malty coffee-dominated aftertaste and a smile on your face .
looks inviting .  smooth and rich on the tongue .

taste s not as rich as the aroma , but still excellent . slightly warming alcohol if felt but not tasted .  entering the mouth , i immediately take notice of the huge mouthfeel on this . this is fluffy , powdery , quaffable , and has this charming soft carbonation that is typical of great beers . palate displays a superb spicy bitterness executed in incredible balance and harmony ( this and the mouthfeel are the 2 attractions imo ) , gentle woodiness .

pours a deep copper color with a big creamy tan head that lasts forever and leaves a great looking lace all the way down the sides of the glass .  m - exceptionally impressive mouthfeel , it 's extremely smooth and rich tasting .
s- lots and lots of chocolate here . roasted malts as well .  perfect carbonation to it .

aroma : sweet candy like roasted chocolate , burnt marshmellow , citrus and spicey hop arma . smells so good ! appearance : clear , dark brown with ruby highlights . this beer kind of dissapointed me becasue the hop aroma is supposed to be a lot more intense . i was expecting a burst of hop aroma which was n't really there . this is a well brewed beer and very tasty .  great mouthfeel - full yet fluffy , almost leaving my tongue numb .
a- served in a tall pilsner glass . excellent clarity . looks beautiful .  m- full , smooth mouthfeel .
taste- delicious representation of the smell . strong hops up front , especially for a pale ale , then dry malt .  ideal texture for an ipa .

the aroma of this beer is amazing ! hops hops and more hops ! very deep and complex . citrus , spice , pine ... but not much of the barley makes it through . wow this is hoppy !  mouth-feel was velvety smooth and creamy .

very full and nice aroma , probably the beers best quality . the aroma of this beer is what really shines , everything else is just above average .  the mouthfeel is excellent . it has a medium body and good carbonation .

pours a deep murky brown with a nice frothy light-tan head that lasts and leaves great lacing .  mouthfeel- medium bodied ale for sure and had small amount of carbonation . very creamy , and left a easy feel on the tongue .
incredible retention and ok lacing s- sweet and hoppy .  this has an excellent mouthfeel .
back to the smell - oak , but the lovely old sort . . .  m : very smooth and full bodied with a low carbonation .

incredible and intense . t : bitter roasted malt throughout . overall , a fantastic beer .  mouthfeel is absurdly rich and creamy , silky smooth and slurpalicious . ) it 's the best feature of this brew . i mean , i like the taste , love the mouthfeel , and would enjoy having two or three of these , but that abv is on the high end .

the aroma is awesome . right away it reminds me of kuhnhenn raspberry eisbock with huge notes of sweet raspberries and chocolate .  mouthfeel : perfection . the bead is neither too large nor too small .

poured from bomber into my stone irs snifter ( 2010 ) a - pitch black with a big persistent dark tan head . the head is beautiful on this beer . what an appearance !  some of the best damn mouthfeel you will ever get in a beer too .

sugary , carmelized , sweet smell . fruity pebble cereal is the overall smell result , very nice ! it 's smell is amazing . picking up a faint vanilla extract smell as well . delicious . it was hard to move my nose away from the smell . but , yeah ... lets get onto the taste . not as amazing as the smell , but still good . mouthfeel is creamy , and dry . while this beer may not be spot on for the style , it 's quite unique . it 's positives by far outweigh the negatives .  m - perfect for a porter .
the strong , sweet caramel nose immediately kicks the salivary glands into gear .  added points for excellent mouthfeel and drinkability .
poured a illowing ornage with a big white head and excellent carbonation . thick pour and cloudy .  ( m ) mouthfeel is perfect for this beer .

up top , a cardboard-colored head recedes quickly to a wisp of foam , but is revived nicely with a quick swirl of the pint glass . the aroma brings everything the style should have : floral , bubble-gum like hops with tropical fruit , pine sap , and spiciness from the rye . still , it 's quite tasty . mouthfeel is dry and juicy at the same time , with an uppity carbonation level that fuels the aggression from the hops .  excellent mouthfeel and not too heavy .

a-pitch black with a nice tan head that thins s-chocolate , red wine , licorice , and black pepper . strong and complex ! possibly some ginger in there too .  i really this the mouthfeel is perfect on this beer .
it pours as close to a pitch black without actually being pitch black . great head retention so this really has it all going on in appearance .  m- feel is exceptionally clean and smooth .
poured - beautiful dark color .  regular boris has the most incredible smooth palate and this follows suit . so silky smooth from the oatmeal . definitely an interest beer for this alone .
the smell is wonderful , but what happened in the translation to taste ?  m : awesomely smooth .

a true imperial ipa , copious amount of pine and grapefruit . truly a beer geek 's beer ... my wife hated this beer . this is a well-made beer , and i certainly enjoy haivng one every now and then , but more a treat than a beer staple .  it has a wonderfully creamy mouthfeel that makes each sip a pleasure .

a : dark brown with yeast particles s : could be the strongest smelling dark fruit belgian style beer ever .  mouthfeel is lucious : creamy and oily , rich in the mouth , but smooth enough to want more and more .

the aromas were delectable , with a balance between the banana and the spices ( clove & coriander ) with the banana just edging them out . they are all there , just much too subtlety .  excellent body d - pretty solid imperial amber / ipa ( ? ) .

aroma is great . rich dark chocolate . wow , what a disappointment after the aroma . mouthfeel is nice . a shame that a beer that smelled so good did n't live up to it .  the mouthfeel was buttery smooth as silk with full body and low carbonation .
poured from a 750ml into a tulip . the look is spot on . moderate gold , huge head , great lacing , very visible carbonation .  the carbonation is spot on and that 's what makes the mouthfeel .

head retention was excellent , melting down to a slightly less huge frothy , rocky head . lacing was thick and plentiful ... .a beautiful looking beer .  mouthfeel is perfect . not too thick and good carbonation .

the aroma is sweet and rich , on the softer side as barleywines go , well balanced between caramel malts and woody hops .  where this brew really stands out is the creamy mouthfeel . that smoothness works to perfection with sweetness , but does n't work quite as well with bitterness .

it is a beautiful beer . a nice white head sitting on a clear amber body . some lacing left behind as it is consumed . the rest of the beer is rather mediocre .  very excellent mouthfeel and drinkability .

this beer smell awesome ! ! ! as i drink it , the problem is , what flavors match up with these aromas ? the beer has a great london/english fruity estery taste with christmas ale type flavors of nutmeg and cinimmon . i wish i had more than one of these to review beacuse its a really complex ale that i would like to clone . a very drinkable ale with a great nutty spicey fruity finish .  it 's definitely thick , but it does n't feel anywhere near as syrupy as it looks . o : this beer has a great appearance and mouthfeel .
the pour was impressive as a dark chocolate filled my beer mug , the smell was pretty good with those hints of chocolate coming to bear .  it is a full bodied beer with perfect carbonation .

s : a rich citrus , piney hop aroma is released when you open the bottle and once in the glass that 's all you can smell . sweet grapefruit - fantastic smell . t : unfortunately the smell seems more powerful than the taste which seems a bit on the light side .  full bodied and silky .

smell is a tart , floral aroma with crisp , clean edge ; simply put , it 's delightful . this ale 's taste is a crafty hop blen dover a clean , crisp start .  the mouthfeel was amazing . nearly full-bodied .

big piney and resiny hops fill the aroma , backed by a pretty sizeable maltiness . tobacco and bread come to mind . the malts may dominate the hops in this aipa , which almost always results in an iffy beer , that has you questioning the style .  feel is really nice as well , lightly creamy and buttery with super calming smoothness and a bit of chewyness with a slightly bread dough drying in the finish .

aroma of a quad / stout mix with the figs , plums and spices plus a hint of grape hi-c infused vanilla . full bodied , viscous without being cloying , chewy . the alcohol is amazingly restrained , not even the inherent warmth you 'd expect at this abv level .  m - creamy and rich . the carbonation is very laidback ... almost feels as if it floats on the tongue . very soft ... puffy , in a way .
poured dark brown with a light tan head .  m - creamy and full in the mouth , so good , this is just what i want in a marzen .

smell is exactly what you 'd expect , with a strong earthy espressor aroma and some chocolate notes , with a bit of sweet maltiness in there .  mouthfeel is incredibly thick and heavy , like drinking warm honey .
a : aptly yclept schwarzbier ( blackbeer ) -- dark opaque black with a frothy head and a ruddy hue around the edges . i like the way this looks . s : not much at all .  fantastic mouthfeel .

big foamy head , a mix of burnt malt and thick coconut in the aroma & # 8230 ; very aromatic . nice clash of burnt malt that strays to slightly to the acidic side and the mild sweetness of the toasted coconut . very interesting and yet another beer i wish i had with dessert though this would have been better with the sweet potato pie .  m : medium body with a fantastic carbonation balance ! amazing here !

smell : cocoa powder and chocolate . sweet but not cloying so . really digging the aroma . taste : where 's the sweetness ?  the taste starts with a slight carbonation . the carbonation builds to reveal a sweet velvet feel . a milk chocolate flavor with a roasted finisht showcases a great mouth on this beer .
i absolutely loved the smell of this , chocolatey , with some sweet fruits from the yeast and subtle hop profile .  m : perfect . it 's thick without being cloying .

a gorgeous midnight pitch-black , with luscious creamy , light-tan head , almost a finger thick . impressive sticky lacing .  taste & mouthfeel : smoothness is impeccable within the moderate body , big doughy biscuity malt flavour is the showcase of this brew .

s - super sour , nice , complex nose . slight vinegar notes . my grandma 's perfume . not nearly as complex as the nose , and manages to fall short of the mark it 's intending to hit .  full bodied , super creamy and smooth . very nice .

espresso and chocolate aromas , with hints of vanilla , roast and brownies , quite the vibrant little blend of malt aromatics . slightly bitter and astringent malt , but still decadent and enjoyable , with chocolate and cream flavors .  the silky smooth mouthfeel was fantastic and carbonation was spot on .

this beer gives you a great looking glass ... smell- ... and a great smell ! incredible smell , might be the best smelling ipa i 've had so far . really nice batch . smells like a field of flowers and with its distinct flowery smell that might remind some of opening a pot of honey .  ( m ) - this is ridiculously smooth despite its hop dryness and woody bite . great carbonation level and balance .

50cl bottle poured into my paulaner weissbier glass a - hazy pale golden body , with the thickest ice-creamiest 4 finger head i have ever seen . super brussels lacing on the glass throughout .  the mouth feel was excellent and one could tell the cask was being maintained properly .
a - pours as a perfectly clear golden color with a finger of off white head that has decent retention .  mouthfeel : excellent light and crisp mouthfeel which is perfect for this style .
just about perfect for a true winter beer .  mouthfeel is quite exceptional .

smell : absolutely delicious . the hops really fused well with the cedar in this case . love it . taste : it is a very sharp flavor .  m - medium body and low carbonation , so incredibly smooth . perfect mouthfeel .

a - extremely dark brown body topped by a frothy bark tan head standing a couple inches tall . the head has some great stamina ! the lacing this beauty leaves is also worth noting .  m : great carbonation feel with a nice medium body . amazing here . perfect !

overall a fantastic beer .  good and special beer , cloudy , double fermentation , yeast , hops , malt and wheat are present in smell ; taste fruity , and floral like grassy and herbs ; good for mexican haute cuisine , try with pasta and salads ; mouthfeel exceptional , well balanced and litlle strong for the palate ; 96 % recommended .

the beer poured out the classic golden yellow color . the bubbles clung to the side of the glass and continued to rise to the surface like a glass of champagne .  mouthfeel is very crisp and smooth with some thickness from the yeast and bite from the hops .

smell is on the sweet side but hoppy as well , sweet bubblegum scent , weed , juicy citrus and a malt punch , great scent . taste is enjoyable , alot of different things balancing sweet and hoppy in that order with the above mentioned scents going into the taste without the weed .  mouthfeel is full bodied and super smooth . very enjoyable .
smells wonderful , though a little bit of a mess , taste wise , still worth enjoying while available .  mouthfeel is exceptional ! this beer is smooth , silky , creamy .

aroma is good . vanilla and raw oak . the aroma is really nice but the taste is just like being hit over the head with sticky sweet caramel and fruit - too much for my taste .  m. just perfect for what it is . very smooth and thick .

majestic sniffs . taste is equally multifacited . one of the maltier versions i 've encountered , laid out in a doughy , bready fashion . this is a very fine hefeweizen  each sip of this full bodied beer is smooth and creamy with light carbonation . this beer is so smooth it goes right down .
a - golden brew with extremely intense carbonation large head fueled by the bubbling .  mf - perfect ! soft carb .

aroma smells a lot like centennial and amarillo hops - a touch of tangerine and bubble gum mixed in with the grapefruit and pine . i love it . flavor is fairly sweet up front , with good piney notes , and a strong grapefruit bitterness in the finish . as it is , it 's still really good .  the mouthfeel is silky smooth and really rounds the beer out nicely .

'01-'02 : starts by pouring a jet black , your unable to see through it , with a nice dark tan head that settles with deep fluffy pockets .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel is outstanding . it sparkles just enough to give the palate a good tickle , but not so much that it scrapes away all of its flavor .

great hoppy citrus punch to the nose . very distinct grapefruit aroma .  very light carbonation and a perfect body for a porter , combined with what i have already mentioned , makes this a very drinkable proposition .

appearance : black like the back ground on this page smell : chocolate , coffee , malts and cookies taste : not as heavy as u think it would be taste like it smells butit is not a strong taste mouth : thin and creamy no carbanation drink : dont really like it that much i usualy only have one or two of these when i go out to eat .  mouthfeel : perfect , just like champagne .

a deep mocha head emerges from the bottom of the glass to form a nice half inch layer . exactly the appearance a big stout should uphold ; textbook .  m : glorious . so creamy and good . reminds me of a cask pour .
it looks similar to a darker version of a rose champagne . the nose has cherries and some pear .  perfect in this sense .

smell : this is an outstanding smelling beer . floral , hoppy and piney with a hint of grapefruit and orange . overall : if this beer tasted as good as it smelled and felt as good as it looked it would be one of the best in the world . it is still pretty good , but not what it could have been .  the mouthfeel is full and warming , in fact , this beer is a huge belly warmer .

rarely , have i encountered an iipa with a nose as complex as this . it 's earthy , fruity , funky , dank . wow . dripping with pine and citrus oils . behind the woodsiness and sweetness a delicate floral aroma gently emerges ... seriously could smell this and be happy . thick , oily dark orange pour with a sustained white , frothy head . shit this is good . thick and mouth coating body never becomes oily or cloying . dripping and oozing with oily and resinous hops throughout but still manages to show a wonderful balance . thanks a ton brian !  m - this is one of my favorite parts so far about this brew . moderate amounts of carbonation that whirls around your tounge and warms it in the process .
really complex nose . smoke , bourbon , dark cherry sour notes . the taste was excellent . really nice with the bourbon not over powering .  mouthfeel is fantastic .

the aroma is honeysuckle and dark fruit , complex , tropic , and soothing . mouthfeel is brighter than i would have expected , but leaves a slightly gritty film on the teeth . the taste is not nearly as complex or abundant as the smell and alcohol does not feature much part in it .  a nice chewy , creamy malt backbone makes each sip a pleasure .
looks very lively . this looks amazing and out of control .  m- creamy and full-bodied . what else would you expect from the style ?

smell is superior . a robust but citrusy smell that you get a hint of straight out of the bottle .  excellent medium mouthfeel , that is slick yet dry - i could drink many of these but i am confident that time will lend complexity -- - please !
smell is of citrusy hops , a bit of malt , and some bitterness .  mouth : full mouth on this one , just right for this style of beer .

wonderful aroma . warm and oaky , molasses . almost get a bbq sauce scent , very spicey like a worcester sauce . very interesting tastes in this one , unusual .  the texture is amazing . thick and silky , but because of the low abv , drinking this is just too easy .

bottle ( 2011 ) port bottle shop carlsbad , ca transparent golden with a thick and persistent nearly white head , with lots of lacing left down the glass . gorgeous pale ale .  sweetness with great balance . great example of what a tripel is supposed to be . drinkability : extremely smooth and creamy , incredibly so , on par with a westy blonde . extraordinary tripel !

smell - pumpkin , nutmeg , cinnamon , malts , brown sugar , spices . smells like liquid pumpkin pie . rather smooth and easy drinking .  great full and luxurious mouthfeel , witha soft , albeit intense carbonation that really lifts the brew .
s - coffee . geez .  what i really loved was the mouthfeel . very good for a lager style beer .

n : this is a beautiful , mouthwatering nose . smells very close to liquid pumpkin pie .  first sip reveals a smooth and slightly creamy texture , carbonation is almost non-existent as cask ale should be .

there are references to ginger , spice , pumpkin and fresh wet hops . packaging says best before march 2012 . the beer is very cloudy and the color is along the lines of pumpkin pie .  m- wonderfully creamy . the carbonation is spot on . one of the creamiest belgian beers i can think of .
