very nice but honestly could have less of the nutty/bitter flavor and more of the sweet adn sour flavors m/d - very drinkable , a bit more carbonated than i like .  mouthfeel : perfect mouthfeel . very smooth , lightly carbonated .
the aroma was wonderful with a sweet hoppy smell .  the texture is likewise decadent , being somehow both silky and creamy .
smell is strongly sweet & sugary , with citric , woody hop presence . interesting & complex but sweeter than i prefer .  mouthfeel - smooth , evenly carbonated , and a perfectly solid body .

light tan head for a second , poor retention and lacing ... the aroma is sweet with lots of nice sweet bourbon on the front . its a really nice smooth bourbon , makes you really want to drink it ... the taste really lets me down sadly .  very nice full bodied mouthfeel . easily drinkable .

pours a four fingered faint pink head that slowly fades to a thin layer , leaving a good lace . color is nice crystal clear amber .  the mouthfeel is luxurious , thick , and chewy . amazing . i am impressed with this brew . flavors are great and the mouthfeel is unearthly .

smell is phenomenal ; coffee , mocha , vanilla , kahlua , coffee cake ... the aroma is outstanding . perhaps the best porter i 've ever sniffed . this beer is simply delicious . slight let down from that a+ aroma but minimal . tastes like the smell but with some malt and roasty notes . very drinkable .  mouthfeel : wonderful balance all over the pallets and each taste-bud . the slightly raised abv can give cause to the minor warmth in mouthfeel .

oh , man ... the aroma on this is , perhaps as the name implies , heavenly . almost a perfect balance in the nose -- fruity , pine needles , grapefruit . and this one goes through three `` hoppings , '' kettle , hop back , and dry hopping ... awesome . the flavor is just about perfect . a fine balance of hop flavors , including a nice grapefruit bitterness and a light bready undertone . but , as a whole , this is a very drinkable beer ... and quite delicious .  exactly how i like my stouts to feel -- heavy and chewy .

the first thing i noticed about this beer was the strong and wonderful flower aroma . quite spicy and with a very strong odor of coriander . quite a nice smelling saison in the same class as hennepin .  smooth , airy , luscious , divine mouthfeel . tremendous ! a wonderful bsda .

s - the nose is quite nice , suggesting vanilla , oak , smoky whiskey , chocolate and marshmallows . basically the nose is colored like a s'more . o - it is a nice beer , but way underachieving , and almost frustrating to drink as a result .  this beer 's greatest attrubite is , in fact , its spectacualrly creamy mouthfeel .

smell is great - lots of mild coffee and dark malts , burnt bread and sweet caramel .  mouthfeel is wonderful for the style ... crisp , wet and fresh with a punchy finish . this does n't look or smell like a euro-pils ( much closer to a craft brewed american pils ) , but the mouthfeel is nailed and compares to the fresh pils i had on tap in europe .

very nice . mouthfeel : a little thin and watery . taste : i was a little disappointed after the wonderful aroma . the flavor was very muted and somewhat watery , not unlike the mouthfeel .  mouthfeel is thick with smooth and creamy carbonation .

it 's black as the devil , not a hint of light going through this , and a thick brown head which lingers for awhile .  the mouthfeel is , in a word , glorious . smooth on the tip of the tongue , then seeming to evaporate off your tongue leaving a crisp , somewhat spicy finish .
very enjoying ! t - malt is smooth , caramel sweetness is restrained and some dark fruits show up .  mouthfeel is just about right , not too thin .
amazing . t : sweet malt that has plenty of peat flavors that i love so much in scottish ales .  mouthfeel : fantastic . rich without being syrupy . carbonation is just right .

this smells amazing . like perfumed hop elephants . but damn ... this smells amazing . i could inhale this all day . which sounds odd .  initially the softness of the carbonation and the sweetness of the fruity flavors makes it like a sweet soda ( can anyone remember tahitian treat ? again with the yeast character and the near rancid presence ( the brett i presume ) , yet the overall soft flavors and soft feel are greatly appealing and enjoyable . the light , fine and bubbly carbonation brings an element of childhood fun to the drink ( how about fizzies , anyone remember that ) as it brings a tickle to the nose and tongue . light overall feel and great softness . soft and light and tasty ( again in a soda pop manner ) .
amazing smell -- coffee and chocolate dominate the aromas with some caramel in the background .  perfect mouthfeel .

laced well . smelled freaking fantastic . toasty , dark fruits .  extremely smooth tasting beer . bodied is so full its nearly chewable . mouthfeel is full and round . finish is clean and very smooth .
aroma - dark fruits with a caramel and sweet malts .  m : one of the fullest and creamiest dipas i 've ever had .

very nice and original beer - more body would have been better but still a great treat from a great brewery .  m- full bodied and creamy . very smooth and silky in the mouth . full bodied but not heavy .

great nose - big , malty , sweet . smells like barley malt fresh out of the bag . a rather abrasive malt profile - i hate to use that word , but it best describes it for me . nice flavors all the way through , but fails to deliver a big full mouthfeel as promised by the nose and malty attack on the tip . the finish cleans out fairly well .  mouthfeel is creamy smooth , thick body , low carbonation .
pours a clear deep red-brown with a big white head .  the feel is big and thick .

rodenbach grand cru , abv : 6.0 % . s : big aromas of red wine , cloves , ginger , oranges , berries , juniper and liquorice . like a mix of glgg ( mulled wine ) and julmust ( a swedish type of soda , drunk at christmas ) . t : rich , sour flavours of red wine , cranberries , apples , oranges , cloves , juniper , liquorice , brown sugar and black pepper . it 's unusual to me ( but i like it ) . i do n't know what to say - it 's the sourness that does the job for my tongue . while i 'm all alone in the dark , the aromas and flavours bring a lot of memories and other stuff to my mind - i think i 'm going to enjoy more of beers like this in the future .  the mouthfeel is great , for the bittersweetness from the roasted malts provide the ideal amount of oomph to an otherwise creamy body .

very pleasant complexity that is worth lingering over .  thick with just a little bit of slickness and just enough carbonation . sly fox oatmeal stout is a solid beer with a fantastic mouthfeel ; probably something i would order again .

smell : the best part of this beer in my opinion . extremely complex ! i smell the chocolate and coffee but i am also overwhelmed by the super sweet heavenly smell of vanilla . taste : i was so happy that the taste was so refined , understated , elegant and smooth . drinkability : love it love it .  mouthfeel is damn near perfect for an o'fest , i think . impeccable balance .

an alcoholic praline . profound amber hues and sticky fingers of lace .  smooth and thick ( of medium thickness ) , with small abrasive bubbles ( in the best possible way ) . wish i had let it chill a little longer to see a greater range of flavors as it warmed , but still a nice experience .

s- the dry hopping really comes through nicely . it 's quite floral with just a touch of an orange juice aroma .  body is n't the first thing you notice , but once the distraction of the sour wears off , you realize this brew is very smooth , neither tacky nor sticky , nor drying . carbonation can be swirled up , and compliments the feel of the sour in your cheeks quite well . all in all , a crazy departure from the normal dfh offerings and dang fine weissen .

amazing smell ; right in line with what i expect from stone .  m : one of the most silky smooth beers i have had in quite a while . i would love it on cask , although the low carbonation is nearly perfect .

lovely aroma of figs , coffee , licorice , lavender , pinesap , chocolate & mint . the dark roasted malts smell so very fresh , almost as if they were right there damp in the palm of your hands .  the feel of the beer was smooth as silk .

smell is amazing ! you can pick out both beers , which is the goal of black and tans . prism hits the nail on the head , because in the beer , you can pick out the lemony hops of the pale ale and it goes very well with the licorice aroma of the porter . carbonation is right on , not too much , and at a very natural level . it brings something else to the table , and yet it works for the style .  the mouthfeel was silky smooth , and i think it was the best feeling oatmeal stout i have ever had . the low carbonation perfectly complemented the medium body , and the smoothness from the oatmeal made it a joy to drink .

a-black , a lot of tan head s-dark roasted malts and a lot of sweet creamy chocolate , there 's hint of caramel as well t-hits with a very light hint of roasted malts and chocolate but they come in quite strong within the after-taste .  m : the mouthfeel is perfect . full and creamy with a little grittiness in the texture .

s : cranberries , some grapes and apples . good hop character . very complex and well done aroma . t : finish is slightly bitter but nothing overpowering , with a warm alcohol character that becomes a little cloying .  the mouth feel on this one is perfect . the head retention is outstanding and just adds to that smooth , creamy , malty , citrus finish .

s : sour cherries are noticeable before the glass reaches my nose . t : the aroma carries well into the taste as the sour dark cherry hits the palate first and then gives way to the sweetness which tastes more like a jolly rancher than sweet tart .  mouthfeel is as silky as they come , the sensation over the tongue is as pleasurable as quaffing god 's nipple lactations . taste is , however , the killer here because it 's just not as explosive as the complex nose and full body could easily have supported .
appearance : beautiful translucent orangish copper with a thin white head . the head dissipates quickly leaving behind a white glass ring . good lacing .  t/m : mouthfeel is perfect on this beer .

`` hello , my name is coriander and pepper '' says the aroma in a pleasing fashion . a bit heavier and sweeter than i would like hurts its drinkability , but the great aroma and pleasant flavor make this a very nice beer .  exceptionally velvety mouthfeel on this one -- noticed that right away .

very complex the joys of the smell were almost problems with the taste .  mouthfeel is very smooth , perhaps my favourite part of this beer . full bodied with subtle carbonation , it feels just right .

right when i opened it the first wiff was a great strong smell of piney hops . outstanding smell . the freshness was still there .  m : as expected it has a wonderful feel to it that only a belgian can give . thick and creamy with a medium weight that gives way to an extremely crisp finish .

aroma : heavenly . roasted malt , chocolate , a hint of coffee , and i detected a hint of whiskey aroma that was very pleasant . taste and mouthfeel : slightly chewy but not quite creamy .  mouthfeel : fantastic . great carbonation , no real aftertaste and washes easily over the palate .
had awesome retention and never showed signs of totally leaving .  m - thick , very smooth and very viscous with little carbonation .
s : some malty caramel and butter . tons of ripe fruit . t : malty and buttery again with some honey .  mouthfeel - exceptionally smooth , with an awesome eveness that carries the taste for a while .

aroma : coffee and chocolate malt meld accented by a whiff of hops and a touch of smoke . nice complexity and balance leads to a very appealing invitation . overall impression : thick and creamy with a wonderful nose . unfortunately the taste just didnt live up to the billing .  the palate is delightfully smooth and creamy . overall , this is an outstanding dipa that is sure to fill anyones hop fix for the evening .

s- strong cherry and rasberry charachter . a pretty strong tartness is every step of the way as well t- very strong tart charachter , not as sour as i was thinking , nicely fruity at the start but it stays too sweet at the finish which is a little off-putting , however some of my friends realy liked it .  mouthfeel is so big thick and creamy .
smell : smells like a banana laffy taffy . also get some pumpkin spice aroma in there too .  this beer has an amazing mouthfeel , very full and luscious , super smooth .
smell was strong with bananas , sweet , bready malts . an interesting beer , and one that 's good as a crossover beer .  the mouthfeel is absolutely perfect for a porter , so smooth and silky .

2010 batch @ harvest fest 10/1/11 a : golden body with fluffy white head and a good cling s : smells like it will be very good : lots of sour-adding oak , some noxious funk and tartness . t : definitely a let down .  great , creamy mouthfeel .

pours a mouthwatering dark , rusty , brown color . head is substantial in size and settles to about 1cm thick . light tan in color with a dense foam consistency .  really great mouthfeel of this one has won me over .
one of the best smelling beers i 've tried .  slick mouthfeel with perfect level of carbonation .

smell has a strong piney grapefruit aroma , the grapefruit really shines through as the star , the aroma kind of reminds me of the 1260 triple ipa .  m- great mouth feel . very smooth and not over-carbonated .

bottled april 22 , 2009 poured into a pint glass amber with a very thick white head . very good retention and lacing .  caramel , mocha , strong booze , brown sugar , raisins , figs , chocalate t-malt , mocha , booze , brown sugar , caramel , raisins figs , chocalate m-spicy , creamy , thick , barely carbonated d- pretty thick & filling .

unusual , overwhelming and lovely aroma of port wine , raisins and dried figs , hints of barnyard . i understand that some people find it cloying , but with a beer this rich in aroma and flavour , i accept the sweetness .  huge bodied and full ( again , suggesting iipa classification ) . this is a beauty on cask .

one of the best smelling dipa 's i 've tried . nice dry finish . o a great dipa . enjoyed this beer very much . this is a hop monster with a nice sweet malt complimenting everything .  m : full-bodied , a very firm and brilliantly sructured beer .

the aroma - mango , pineapple , & exotic flowers - is delightful . smells like hawaii in a bottle ! not as grapefruity as i usually like , but i did n't mind the lack at all ; a very pleasant surprise .  the mouthfeel is great ... medium on the palate , but slick and well carbonated ... compliments the black pepper flavor perfectly .

pours a opaque black no light showing thru this bad boy with a thinner mocha colored head , wow the aromas damn where to begin heavy on the dark roast coffee , bitter chocolate a hint of almond extract as well just awesome.flavors are heavy in the coffee department for some it maybe to much dark roast coffee and chocolate malt flavors with a malted milk type flavor , nice creamy , silky mouthfeel glides down pretty easily.if you like strong coffee and bitter chocolate you 'll love this beer .  mouthfeel - per style it is dead on ... fairly dry and actually not sticky compared to other barleywines .
aroma is a decadent mocha and milk chocolate , but the taste does n't quite live up to it .  the mouthfeel is very smooth , with minimal aftertaste .

buttery , pure milk chocolate sweetness hits the nose at first , then is ceded by notes of carob and suggestions of chocolate covered candied orange peel along with coffeeish , borderline burnt roasted barley . real chocolate never wavers in aroma , remaining constant and assertive .  creamy , silky mouthfeel .

it is an aromatic potpourri of lighter hop notes . i like getting mint flavors and smells from a beer , it 's a sense that is under appreciated in craft brewing .  a great feel that has a body that replenishes itself .

it has a wonderful smell of yeast and citrus .  m : full-bodied , silky smooth , velvety rich and downright luxurious in the mouth . these guys have this whole mouthfeel down to a t. notes : malty rich , fruity sweet , and explosively spicy , this bspa is quite enjoyable !
t : bit of a let dowm after this promising smell . orange , citrus , grains and a little hops .  mouthfeel is very thick and chewy , silky and long lasting on the palate , near perfect .

this has got to be one the best smelling ipa 's out there . the fruity and hoppy flavours balance out perfectly to leave a tasty , dry , almost graperuit-esque finish which is just fantastic . this beer packs a mighty punch .  the mouthfeel is outstanding , like an expensive champagne and it finishes very dry .

330ml bottle served into an snifter glass.enjoyed on sep11.pours intense orangish copper in color , chill haze appearance.crowned by a creamy light yellowish off-white thick layer froth.brief retention leaving some spotty lacing.yeast & intense caramel malt aromas . buttery bread , toffee hints & slightly fruity -apricot & peach- notes to the nose.spicy , orange zest & subtle coriander flavors.gentle warming alcohol.sweet bitterness in the middle.medium but intense body.soft carbonation.dry bitter finish.smooth fruity aftertaste.a beer for a long & paused drink.a nice warming beer .  amazingly full mouthfeel .
this nose is so unique and amazing . as i take first sip i wasnt ready for the electric sour rush that attacks the tongue .  m : lovely . sort of creamy , without being too heavy .

dunkel malts smell really nice , along with promising upfront bitters .  appearance : amber , clear carbonated , medium head smell : alcohol , grapefruit , and citrus taste : alcohol , grapefruit , malts , hops , and slight caramel mouthfeel : smooth , slightly hard finish , can feel the carbonation ... it is amazing how smooth and unbitter this beer is for a beer with its abv drinkability : i will have this again , but may be one of the few that prefer the 60 minute ipa .
massive head over clear copper liquid .  m : full body , and shockingly creamy . this brew is extremely smooth of the mouth .

s : caramel malt with a nice sweet spiced aroma . smells like brown sugar . t : tastes like a cola at first , then the hops hit you squarely .  starts with roasted coffee flavor , mouthfeel is incredible smooth .

i smell orange , tangerine , kind buds , papaya , pine , and hints of rock candy . the aroma is lovely ! it smells like someone is peeling an orange next to me . good , but not as amazing as the nose .  m - perfect ? perfect .
also , a wonderful , frothy , mocha head retains throughout .  beautiful .

it 's sitting across the table but throwing great scents my way hazy amber orange with some sudsy head juicyfruit aromas : immense , zesty citrus , mint . not much pine , which is a nice change from the norm . good , robust , woody bitterness ( it really hangs on the tongue ) with excellent hop depth . mint .  perfect ris mouthfeel .

s- as only a good british beer can smell , luscious . very complex . t/m- ok , the taste lets down a bit after the luscious aroma . a good beer but disappointed that it is n't a great beer .  mouthfeel is a great aspect of this beer . a big , creamy , velvety beer . soft and velvet from the oatmeal , low carbonation .

a : reddish amber color , clear , no head retention or lacing s : although you get the belgian yeast banana and spicy notes , in the background you can notice the subtle blueberry aroma of real blueberries , not some extract .  mouthfeel is silky smooth , really nice . body fairly full and the beer leaves an impression all the way over the tongue .
very impressive appearance .  finishes fruitty & spicy mf : huge & well balanced this was bit ponderous , but tasty .

pours a brilliant colour , reddish , orange , very clear , just amazing , thick white head , lots of lace , great retention , head never leaves , i have to give this a 5 for appearance , simply one of the best looking beers i 've ever seen .  mouthfeel is velvety and smooth . great length on the taste .

a - pours a clear gold with a small head that lingers throughout s - pineapple is the main nose with some biscuit and some other tropical fruits t - spicier and less tropical fruit than the nose portends . hops dominate with a little bit of malt .  m- the first thing i notice with this is how smooth and creamy it is . d- a very enjoyable english barleywine . tasty .

i can smell this beer from the other side of the room ! this is one of the best smelling sours out there ! flavor is good ... but not as crazy as i expected . a good sour , but does n't stand out like i wanted it to . the obvious sour/tart funk is right on key ... and very clean and crisp . overall , a very solid sour from captain lawrence ... a must try !  this is so creamy and not too carbonated , its just enough to get both senses of substantial and refreshing . quite thick , not so much as syrup but a few steps under . one please , fills the stomach nicely , not too harsh on the throat or stomach . it has a nice balance between warmth and coolness in the stomach .

50cl bottle , best by 9/2010 a- the best head on a weissbeer i 've ever seen . huge retention , great lacing . cloudy orange/tan color . looks fabulous , smells great , but the odd mineral/metallic component on the taste really ruins it .  m - smooth as silk .

sweet tropical notes , mainly mango accompany a major amount of hops in the scent . there was a lot i liked but overall very good .  m : full-bodied and lightly carbonated with a soft and creamy texture . alcohol noticable in a nice warming effect .
pours a beautiful dark brown with a slight ruby hue on the outer edges , nice thick microfoam head that leaves nice lacing .  the mouthfeel is great and smooth as can be .

pours a translucent medium copper with some awesome bubbling and a thick doughy head .  my favorite thing about this obviously the sweet rich malt character which adds to a very nice body for a beer of this alcohol content .

smells heavenly - a brilliant blend of maple syrup , caramel , toffee , figs , burnt sugar and bourbon . just a hint of booziness at the end . tastes a lot like it smells - however the bourbon is much more prevalent than the other flavors - you get hints of the caramel , figgy , malty deliciousness present in the nose , but they 're largely overpowered by the bourbon .  mouthfeel is just perfect . the way this thing finishes it has a slight peppery aspect but it is dry and clean .

on tap at kuhnhenn winter , solstice night two . a big nose of spices .  the mouthfeel is amazing . the belgian in this beer seems to come from the relatively light body but firm and billowy head that rollicks around my mouth .
aroma is nice : lightly caramel with a tangerine citrus hop character . does smell nice though !  mouthfeel is superb . almost perfect , well rounded , full , with a snappy finish .

s - very pronounced chocolate aromas , backed by roasted malts , some earthy , pine hops and a touch of coffee as it warms t - follows the nose , with the hop character very subtle , and the coffee barely making a presence as it warms .  m : a great , great medium body , that grazes you at the tail with sharp carbonation .

the nose is one of my best ipa aromas ever , with a powerful yet less aggressive hop blast , full of fruit and floral notes , and only flavored with pine , not dominated by it . extremely impressive stuff from these salt lake city brewers .  mouthfeel/overall : this beer is every bit of full bodied ; thick , chewy and creamy . everything an imperial stout should be . overall , a very good imperial stout that i 'd love to have full time access to .
smells great . huge floral and citrus hop aromas with a bready malt that asserts itself more as the beer warms .  mouthfeel - very smooth with a rich body and muted carbonation .

new holland mad hatter ipa 12 oz bottle recent bottling , tumbled down the rabbit hole 10/06 medium pour in a tulip glass . poured a hazy copper orange with a frothy mostly lasting white head with excellent lacing .  mouthfeel is thick and chewy , as it should be fir a beer of this strength .
not dominating like some ipa 's , there are also crisp malt notes . the blend is just about perfect . this is one inviting beer !  mouthfeel is thick and creamy , very nice .

smell is very floral and fragrant , wow , fantastic . as it warms , you get more classic nw hops , pine and citrus .  mouthfeel is perfect ! not thick like a stout , but with enough meat to be very smooth and coating .

s - chocolate and lots of it . earthy dark chocolate aroma reminds me of opening a box of cherry cordials . the aroma lingers quite a bit and stays until the end of the glass .  full bodied with creamy carbonation and a lingering sweet licorice finish .
smelled great ! t : was a bit disappointed by the taste .  it 's as smooth as silk - perfectly suited as a dinner and desert sipper and easily the best porter i 've had the pleasure of tasting .

smell is a strong dose of mixed raw grains , silage , molasses , a bit of smoky roasted malt , some earthy nut aspects especially as it warms . the mouthfeel is quite light and drinkable , bordering on watery , despite the huge malt nose . taste is also very thin , not nearly as intense as the smell . mild caramel sweetness , some mixed malt body , a hint of vanilla .  full , thick , rich mouth feel .

this beer has a decent amount of hops for an apa and the nose is quite nice , but the flavor and mouthfeel do n't offer enough to really set this beer apart .  mouthfeel is great . just the right level of thickness here .

i prefered the tap version as the apricots were so intense in the aroma as the bottle had more funk and barnyard . apricot , lemon and peach flavors . moderate acidity for a cantillon . the palate could be drier and the carbonation more lively but this a stellar offering by cantillon once again .  the way this tastes is absolutely nothing like the way it smells ... m - full , pleasing mouthfeel . the best part of this beer .

big aroma for such a little head ; bright fruits , dried fruits , plum , cherry , red grapes , slight caramel and a smooth yeasty character . fruity malt character also displays some earthy , hearty grain notes and much of the same fruits as in the nose . nice medium yeasty twang marries well with the fruit notes .  very full body that stretches the cheeks . just such chewy hops .

wonderful aromas of fresh pumpkin pie ! i could really smell the spices of nutmeg and cinnamon , plus the fresh smell of carved pumpkin to round out the spice . t- pretty much tasted like it smelled but not as pronounced . it 's easy drinking , great autumn flavors and smells ... .a real pleasure to drink !  the texture is rich and creamy and coasts your mouth in deliciousness .

exceptional aroma , not alot of ipas can match this , very floral and unique , with grapefruit and mango front , notes of apricot , lemons and lychee streaking through at times . brilliant nose , could smell it all day . turned out to be a rather balanced ipa , the nose was so great it would be hard to match on the flavor as well . if you can get this one fresh it 's absolutely worth it and the nose is unique even amongst the ever growing masses of ipas .  excellent in the mouth .
intriguing . the nose is awesome , but the flavor is a letdown .  mouthfeel is full and round .

tasted nov. 21rst 2011 ( from notes ) tulip a - very nice translucent blood red , 1/4 finger off white fizzy head and minimum lacing s - peat , smoke , nuts , alcohol , slight wine , lots of yeast and oak t - so much peat , wow ! sap , wood , lemon , citrus , alcohol , sauvignon blanc , more peat , some nice hops and the peat kind of peats ( haha ) out all the other flavors m - medium body , medium acidity , low complexity , not balanced and very long finish d - while at first few sips the peat is overwhelming and almost nasty , after a bit the peat is more in the background of a smokey , citrus , alcoholic ale .  m= smooth and crisp . feels resinous as well which is great for an ipa . d= super drinkable .

poured into a chimay goblet . the aroma is potent and pleasant : there is a strong , sour yeast smell plus a significant evergreen , pineapple sharpness complimented by some bready tones and honey-like malts .  the alcohol is kept well in check allowing the finish to cascade over the palate with a ton of character and wonderful texture . strong , long finish .

beautiful fresh dry-hop aroma . the malt is not hidden , though , with a pale malt aroma blending in with the floral hop resins .  sour , some cherries , but most of all very tart and bone dry ; element of french cheese in it ( brie ) , some cream ; m : lovely alcohol , nice tartness , very drinkable ; o : not too complex but but very good kriek , which i will buy whenever i see it .
a- this one pours out an opaque black as night colored body with a small coffee colored head on top .  easy to drink due to it 's creamy mouthfeel and pleasant flavor .

s : smell is great . bourbon , vanilla , and coffee . t : tastes of bourbon , vanilla , and coffee with hints of toffee and roasted malts . d : this is very drinkable , especially for the abv .  m - perfect body .

overall very nice . taste : a little sour up front , but quickly fades to a lingering `` bitterness '' - not of the hop variety .  the mouthfeel is absolutely perfect . it goes down full-bodied yet absurdly delicately and dries the mouth a perfect amount for the hop zing this one has .
just great . t : similar to the smell but with bit of smokiness .  it 's thick , creamy , rich , and robust .

s - big aroma of cherry juice , some apple juice , molasses , malts , just a great smell . t - a nice balance of molasses , licorice , malts , some cherry .  m : the mouthfeel is dense and creamy and frothy ... and almost stout-like . excellent .
pours a dark redish brown with a nice tan head .  overall a really complex , fantastic stout , one i 'd be happy coming back to over and over .

thought i would try this beer being i 've never had a apricot one before and i liked the other st-ambroise that i 've had . when looking at the beer it 's a dark golden color that has a white head , in which quickly depreciates/leaves a ring the smell is the most obvious/easy to describe as you get a strong initial smell of apricot 's when opening the bottle .  visibly effervescent , the mouth feel is perfect ... classic rich micro bubbles lend a smooth creamy texture .

| 11.0 % abv | 2010 brewer : southern tier brewing company style : american double / imperial stout glass : pint appearance : coal black with a small mocha head aroma : roasty and malty taste : ahh ... eck ... ewh .  in the mouth , the tiny bubbles announce and incredibly smooth and balanced beer , with a roasted , slightly sweet flavor .

smells of deep , dark chocolate and sweet milky aromas taste is rich and complex of dark rich chocolate . still an enjoyable brew although i was a little bit let down i was expecting a little more from this brew .  smells like a smoke beer ... .i get a little chocolate in the nose ... but the roasted smell is overpowering ... taste is sweet on the front end ... and an overall smooth taste ... .with a little bitterness on the back end ... very nice feel ... .creamy and smooth perfect for the style ... .velvet like smoothness ... drinkability is not bad ... although it is a stout and it weighs you down ...
a big floral hop aroma -- smells great . taste is bitter hopiness , floral and citrus .  m- great mouthfeel .
overall : well , the smell is great , one of the best .  mouthfeel is rich and creamy .

the aroma was simply fantastic . sweet candy sugar , cherries , white pepper , and leather were present in the smell is quite abundant quantities . citric sourness tang remained however , making it hard to really dislike .  pours a rich copper with a creamy one finger head that that settles nicely leaving some light lace , deep intese fruity aromas with some underlying but very noticeable pine.wow a big flavorful barleywine very pacific coast piney and resiny upfront with a big fruity alcolholic finish the alcohol really hits.just a sublime creamy mouthfeel and pretty slick going down the hatch and it warms the insides.wow truley and awesome big brew a night cap that cant be beat .

strikingly effervescent . s : even before i hold glass to my nose , i can smell whiffs of lactic sourness . yes , lactic acid is sharp . some vinegar , red wine vinaigrette , flowers , and a suggestion of brettanomyces . additional aromas includes oak/barrel and citric acid . i keep picking up a very light buttery note .  this brew is a tremendously creamy medium-body with a tantalizing , light bite about the tongue what can i say !
a : nearly black brown , long lasting tan head .  medium body and a wonderfully sprtizy carbonation keeps it light and makes the tartness manageable .
big rich sweet aroma , distinct raw honey scent .  altogether pleasing to the tongue and brain , it also had a beautifully full mouthfeel from the oustandingly appropriate delicate carbonation .

fantastic . i 'm a big fan of floral ipas , and not so into the bitterness . delicious . reminds me a lot of abrasive in this respect ( the floral/citrus vs. bitter balance ) , though not quite on that level .  mouthfeel was full and rich . this is a very good beer , and quite a unique one .

hazy and dark copper-amber in color with a thick cream colored head of super tightly laced foam that left great lacing at it receded at a slow but steady rate ; the head reminds me of an improperly baked cake very slowly losing its leavening .  m/d - medium to full bodied with an excelent feel .

smells like delicious ginger snaps , cinnamon and some clove . delicious . it has a medium body with a good amount of carbonation . definitely a sipper , but a very good sipper .  feels wonderful on the tongue , perfect for a summer or spring day .
smell is sweet and a really fruity in aroma . quite spicy in aroma vanilla , cinnamon and black pepper .  thick creamy mouthfeel and mild carbonation . smooth silky mouthfeel is lucious .

a : pours a pale yellowish amber color with frothy white head and lots of lacing on the glass s : smells like major hops , citrus , grapefruit , some pine ... the usual great dipa scents t : tastes just like the smell , but the hops are less prevalent that i expected .  carbonation was nice and light , body was perfect .
a quick swirl brings nice crimson flashes to the glass , quite amazing ... the aroma flows to my nostrils from feet away .  perfect carbonation .

aroma smacks you . good and hard . hops and oak would be an obvious statement . my notes indicate an amazing floral and woody perfume aroma . initial flavor is upfront pine and sweetness .  this beer feels absolutely perfect in the mouth .

quite nice overall . taste : bit of a letdown here ; there are mild caramel and nutty flavors , but not much depth ... there 's a bit of biscuit on the finish and it 's kind of acidic , almost tart actually , and some mildly fruity flavor that i ca n't quite place and is mildly annoying .  superb mouthfeel . excellent amount of carbonation .

poured into a snifter , revealing rich black body and one of the thickest and darkest heads i 've ever seen on an ris , one which bubbles down nicely into a turgid foamy mess of a surface .  m- the mouth feel is excellent for this beer .

s - love the smell . citrus ( grapefruit , orange ) with enough hop smell to it . t - pretty good tasting but not remarkable . smooth , fruity . however , an easy and nice tasting ipa to knock back a few of on the weekend .  m- smooth and velvety , perfect carbonation o- great beer , bottle is on par with the draft .
this beer looks really , really nice .  the mouthfeel is excellent .
almost black ( ruby red highlights ) with a nice brown head that leaves sheets of lace .  m - extremely smooth .
intense sweet banana scent . very full bodied aroma .  mouthfeel is smooth and rich , medium-full body , with wonderful carbonation .

charcoal black with an inch thick teddy bear brown head that quickly sinks to an eighth of an inch . excellent lacing persists for some time thereafter .  the balance here is seriously excellent though , and the mouthfeel is probably the best i have encountered in an ipa , period . truly a creamy elixir , perfect carbonation .

the aroma , however , is a-one , outstanding , and really well captured in the wineglass : nice , fresh pumpkin accompanied by strong notes of cinnamon , nutmeg , clove , maybe some ginger ... wow , this is the smell i look for in my pumpkin ales - imo they nailed it . that said , i feel the flavor takes a step back ; maybe the nose raised expectations too high ... still very nice , with the pumpkin and spices pulling through , but perhaps not as robustly as the nose had led me to believe ; there 's also a not entirely pleasant though subtle bitterness to it , as well as a bit a boozy bite to the finish .  a big rubber sensation , great deal of that , with a fair amount of barnyard funk and a carrot flavour as well . beautifully textured feel - full-bodied but smooth with a great earthy feel .
nose : a nice profile of strong citrus notes , not overly complex , but nice . tongue : what strikes my first is just how malty this is .  its very smooth and velvety , very nice .
i really enjoyed this one . perfect copper looking beer .  extreme balance and smoothness in this beer , its quite good . big full body with a champaign like fizzyness . im impressed .
very pleasant . t : this is too light for the style .  m- mouthfeel on this is incredible . medium to full bodied , chewy and creamy , moist , and not a hint of alcoholic bite .
the aroma is wonderfully smokey and peaty , with some dark malts in there too . great aroma and interesting flavor .  m - perfect feel to this medium bodied brew .

good lacing & head retention s : intense almost burnt caramel & malt & some alcohol t : smokey caramel & a little aclohol up front , then a hint of cherry & oak . finishes with dryness , a slight smokeyness & a praline sweetness mf : sticky rich body with excellent carbonation & balance drinks good , but 2 would be about my limit .  in addition , there are hop oils , caramel , some sweetness and perhaps molasses along with a medium body that is oh so smooth and coats the mouth well . delicious and well balanced .

really loved the nose .  m : soft , smooth carbonation , big and viscous body , excellent finish . there 's very little more that i want from a big ris d : i drank my bottle in an hour and was craving more notes : i did n't really expect much from this beer because nh have n't really impressed me with much of what they 've done but hot damn , this was impressive !

wonderful nose on this beast . but it is n't very rich . its kind of one dimensional . has big hop character , big malt character , roasty , chocolate , caramel , but that 's about it .  one of the best mouthfuls ever !
smell is of butterscotch and very pleasing . like you are about to have a delicious dessert .  perhaps my favorite aspect is the full and very creamy mouthfeel .

very inviting . t - a little bitterness as if it had dark chocolate and you can taste the alcohol . a rather large let down after the amazing scent . m - good coating , but the only tingle is in the throat from the alcohol .  feel is thick and full , nice and creamy .

smell is full of strong c type hops . strong pine and grapefruit with some cinnamon in there . cedar wood and a little hay scent . faint pineapple smell .  feel : low carbonation , medium body that is extremely smooth for so low abv , very nice drying finish .

great looking pour for a white ale .  the feel is super dry , tannic and superb on the palate , rough , sticky , and full ... easy to drink as this crushed by the girlfriend and i in about 15 minutes .
big grapefruit aroma . good head . high 75 ibu .  full bodied , heavy on the palate and full of flavor . i love it .

the aroma is like a fresh hop cone very nice . from what you expect with the aroma is a slight let down but that said it is nice . the taste malty to start the taste turns to a earthy hop flavor .  really wonderful . the mouthfeel is the most impressive and outstanding attribute of this beer .

overall , very nice smell . taste is fruity , quite a bit of the banana in the smell comes through in the flavor .  aroma is finely balanced between sweet buttery/caramel-like malt and big herbal hops . while the taste treads the high wire between hops attack and malt sweetness the same way the aroma does , the hops edge out the malt on the tongue . without feeling heavy , this has both a creaminess and stickiness that works well to match the aggressive hop profile and carry the candy-like malt sweetness that rides along . bitter and resiny in a way that inseparably welds flavor to texture , and really helps define the beer . feel-wise , it 's magnificent . while my description of the taste sounds like the description of a big-ass double ipa , it manages to pack in a lot of flavor without going imperial . the sensible abv helps with that , and this is basically an all-around excellent , clearly california-fied version of the style . another fine brew from the typically hop-heavy moylans .

citrus hops dominates the smell . citrus and pine are the taste that stick out . a good beer but there are so many better ipa 's out there .  the mouthfeel is great on this one too , effervescent and full at the same time .
s : molasses ! brown sugar ... dark fruit ... some tanginess noted . t : chocolate ... sweetness from the malt .  m- awesome thick mouthfeel on this seasonal .

it reminds me a bit of some barley whines . quite complex . taste : sweet apple , honey , strong grain , plenty of oak in there , dark fruits and alcohol .  m : really a standout porter . carbonation is perfectly dialed in and gives a very subtle tingle on the tongue .

smell is very strong , very tasty , and actually has a mouthwatering , rich coffee character to it . start is somewhat sweet but very oaky and heady .  mouthfeel/drinkability- sublime mouthfeel , super-easy in the mouth .

very interesting beer . you can smell the hints of black & blue berries which is quite nice . it 's got a sharp taste of fruit , it reminds me almost of a fruity wine .  and even so , it is still incredibly smooth , and the alcohol flavor can not be detected . the body is huge . one of the thickest beers i 've had the pleasure of eating . very good stuff .

smell - i thought the nose on this beer was the best part . malt with grassiness . fresh smelling , almost floral . taste - wow ! that 's one bold and bitter finish !  mouthfeel is perfection . perfectly carbonated and very refreshing .

this thing pours up a crystal clear copper with big rocky white head that leaves behind some of the prettiest lace i have seen in a while . great head retention and beautiful rising bubbles in this incredibly clear beer just make this look positively stunning .  easy to drink , amazing body ; feels perfect to me . d - overall this is a very good doppelbock with an amazing mouthfeel ; felt like i could have had a few of these .
it has a very sweet aroma to it and that makes it all the more appealing . smell is more prevalent the more it warms up .  it seemed to just coat my whole mouth on its way down .

pours a two finger white head that fades slowly , leaving a good lace . nice crystal clear amber color .  the rich , smooth , roasted chocolate flavor works well with the silky body . this is definitely highly recommended , as the beers tend to be from great lakes brewing company .

the nose really is redolent of pepe du chat , gooseberry , bright herbal citrus with a nice minerality with a touch of dry malt - very sauvignon blancesque .  m-medium carbonation with a great creamy finish d-hmm i actually like this a lot ... .i 'm very confused by the other peoples ' reviews ... the taste is n't too complex but its otherwise a great drink .

poured the 22 oz bottle smells amazing , looks great , with good carbination the flavor let me down , the initial impression was stellar but followed by a light bodied lingering hop flavor that doesnt seem to justify the body style of the beer .  m : medium to thick bodied . the carbonation works well for the brew , and there is a lovely creamy finish that really melts in your mouth .

s : quite good . vinous , and i 'll assume chardonnay-like , notes are at the forefront , with brett and lemongrass also inserting themselves into the mix .  mouthfeel is superb . great level of spice , perfect carbonation , medium body .
not a terribly complex smell , but its really appealing nonetheless .  it is full bodied and creamy in the mouth .

well after all the hype i had to give this one a try , pours motor oil black with two finger tan head , smells of alcohol and burnt espresso , tastes the exact same , if i were to roast some espresso beans until they were charred all the way through , then threw them into a blender with ice and vodka , thats exactly how this tasted to me .  m - this is by far the smoothest ipa i 've ever had . the pour from a hand pump straight from the cask creates the perfect texture for this beer .

very nice aroma here -- spot on for the style -- as notes of fresh orange peel combine with soft coriander spice and a hint of lemon .  mouthfeel is extremely smooth & this is a perfect beer to sip on on a lazy pm with no kids in sight !
this is more like it ... pitch black . pours a thick brown head that quickly swells to 2 inches and then recedes to 1/4 inch .  silky smooth on the tongue and exceptionally creamy .

an amazingly rich and creamy nose with strong aromas of toffee , cream , and roasted marshmallows . body is very good . drinkability : whatever hesitancy i had after seeing how it looked following the pour were overcome by the amazing aroma . a solid , flavorful drink that i would kill to try on cask .  the mouthfeel is exceptionally smooth and creamy , terrific . thanks bif for the sample .

it is deep , dark and mysterious -- perhaps much like the ellusive rasputin himself . it mixes roasted coffee aromas , with the sweeter remnants of chocolate , caramel and toffee . there is also a nice , bold noticeable tinge of hops to the overall inhalation . in the mouth , this beer is amazingly bold and full . there is also a nice biting aftertaste , allowing its overall substance to be reckoned with .  wonderful body .

aroma is big sweet , multitudes of dark fruit , caramel and quiet peat moss . quadish exceptional highly complex flavor , something for everyone . sweetness not equal to the expectation from the nose . the evolution of the taste is significant .  mouthfeel : thick and smooth in every sense of the words -- a very pleasant experience indeed !
this beer pours a golden color , with a thick and fluffy white head . the head fades slowly , leaving a nice lacing .  this beer has a smooth , creamy mouthfeel .

it is also carbonated like a fresca soda , which seemed a bit odd , but it also helped to create a great aroma . i could really smell the cascades in this one when i poured it , but as the carbonation dies the hop aroma turned to a sweet malt nose .  typical stone excellent mouthfeel .

the nose ? wow ! intense citrus and definite grape fruit aroma is almost overwhelming , but in a very , very good way . never had anything like it taste : as i go for the 1st sip , i 'm almost squinting my eyes , expecting to drink a form of carbonated grapefruit juice .  nice full bodied and well carbonated mouthfeel .

smell - smells absolutely delicious ! ! lots of fruit/wheat and some toasty nuts ... yumm , 5 for sure .  the creamy , delicious texture pairs well with the flavorful personality of the smoked porter . the dancing carbonation paired with the brews creamy-smooth feel and intense flavor essentially block dopamine receptors in your brain .

another beer from the sam adams mix six pack , black lager pours a deep ruby red black with a light brown head .  mouthfeel is outstanding . super thick and syrupy , that flavor coats the palate forever .

the beer has the unique feature for this style by including a spiced-raisin aroma although it is mild . no hops contribution to the scent .  silky smooth thick bodied with a perfect amount of light carbonation and a ridiculously long lasting , balanced tart and sweet aftertaste .

smell- by far the sweetest smelling beer i 've ever had .  actively carbonated , yet still seems mellow and full . strikes a perfect balance between crispness and creaminess , just heavanly . strikingly balanced for the how big and malty this beer is .

huge fruity aroma , kind of a grapefruit/lemon hybrid . extremely bitter , even for a west coast ipa . this makes for a tasty , although not particularly well balanced , ipa .  mouthfeel : crisp , clean , and exceedingly refreshing .
smells like sour cherries and sour grapes with a white wine smell .  mouthfeel : spot on in my opinion . medium to medium-lite body with perfect amount of carbonation .

s - huge pine aroma that is quickly and easily enjoyable . massively beautiful from the get-go , with underlying citrus notes . a perfect , varied aroma that promises wonderful delights within t - slight pine taste , bit of grapefruit , pure hops abound . d - very nice , but perhaps lacking a bit of malt balance making this a bit more difficult to enjoy .  body is medium full with a great velvety smoothness .

really fantastic nose , the raspberries shine through . good interesting beer that is cool to try to reach both the girls and the boys beer drinkers or not .  mouthfeel is phenomenal , rich and creamy it 's quite thick and chewy without going over the top .

s - very lovely . a nice mix of sweet citrus fruits and hops . nice .  very smooth and rich taste though and perfectly balanced . wonderfull to drink though think it should be drank as i do n't think that more age makes this one any better .

smells great ! t-hmmm this is a fairly complex beer , which is surprising coming from abita .  rich roasty chocalaty with a fabulous creamy mouthfeel . mouth again is just amazing . another great brew by troegs .
smell : wonderful aromas on this beer .  the mouthfeel is thick and rich with a nice amount of bubbly to round it out . the taste is full , many-layered . . . wonderful . a little vineous though .

dark brown head over a black body . there were tons of good stouts opened at the tasting , but this rose to the top of the heap . lovely stuff  like other fine belgian beers the carbonation produces a surreal creamy consistency that serves to deliver maximum taste .

great nose and look that screams hops but the taste is not really that hoppy and has a soft finish that is in contrast to the huge nose . very drinkable but not really a balanced beer and not really fitting the style .  great palate , though . even when it gets warm , great warmth and sliky smooth syrups .
s- excellent . wheat , yeast , and citrus immediately hit the nostrils as you pour this one . t- initial taste of sweet malt and citrus .  extremely satisfying in this regard .

s : nice big belgian yeast nose . one of the best smelling beers i have ever encountered . t : starts off sweet with some raisins . the worst part of this beer and it was still way above average . d : very drinkable .  mouthfeel is utterly smooth with just a hint of carbonation ... placidly perfect .
smell is wonderfully floral and hoppy . not floral or hoppy , but more like perfumy .  mouthfeel is the star here . it 's plush , velvety ... is nice .

still , the beer does n't follow through on a great aroma .  bordering on chewy as you work toward swallowing . carbonation was excellent on tap , just enough to contribute to a dry and clean finish despite the initial sweetness of the beer .

a harmonious aroma of raisins and rosemary , dominating . dates and caramel , intoxicating sugars . wow , taste is right there too . it 's just alluring .  m - full body , viscous and chewy with low , delicate carbonation , very smooth across the palate with some heat from the alcohol/bourbon content .

pours a nice dark toasty color but not so dark when heald to the light . red comes through if you hold it up to dome light .  the carbonation is fantastic -- beer feels creamy and smooth- almost velvety .

5.0 s : lots of oatmeal is apparent . this may be the most oatmeal laden beer i 've had . awesome balance between sweet and roasted flavors . 4.0 t : the taste is just about as good as the nose , but the mouthfeel is too distracting for me to enjoy it .  extremely smooth mouthfeel and very easy to drink .
very nice ! the taste is more pronouced citrus fruit and pine that slowly reveals the malty backbone of fresh baked bread .  but the mouthfeel is absolutely incredible .

one of the best smelling beers i 've ever tried . good amount of pumpkin . clean and delicious . lighter side of medium in body . not sure if this is a drastic improvement from regular pumking , but this is surely tasty .  great creamy thick mouthfeel , light carbonation .

a- starts as a massive foamy cup of liquid , then turns into a very impressive carmel colored beer with excellent one inch head that hangs around for the whole pint . creamy look that is very appealing . heavy lacing on the glass ... great retention .  the feel is creamy , rich and smooth . just the right amount of carbonation keeps it full , but not overly thick .

a : pours a muddy muddy thick black with a little ring of head that sticks around but i was not expecting a head anyways , its just dark and inviting black as night s : smells incredibly sweet , like a sweet port , huge huge nose on this , plums and rum raisins with hints of sweet and dark chocolate . i mean there is not real reason to get more specific it smells pretty much like exactly what is listed here , very luxurious . t/mf : the carbonation is a nice touch here and allows an extremely heavy and creamy body to impart the flavor all across the tongue .  mouthfeel : amazing . creamy and smooth , thick .

earthy , weedy , hoppy , piney ! a real west coast ipa . love it ! not for the faint of heart hop haters , but awesome for hop lovers ! definitely interesting with tropical fruit hints in this one . mouthfeel : deliciously crisp and oily .  thick rich and creamy mouthfeel . for such a rich and big beer it is remarkably smooth .
smell is great . coffee beans and some roasted aromas , a touch of chocolate .  thick lushious body and moderate carbonation .

if you like hops , you 'll like this . it is overloaded with hops , but very very tasty .  silky smooth , it has just the right touch of carbonation to keep it full but not too thick or syrupy . awesome ! overhyped ?

smell- nice nose of hard alcohol , vanilla , deep caramel and barrel flavors .  m - very rich and thick , has a nice little burn and pop at the end from a combo of carbonation , abv and hop bitterness .
seems very complex , i love it . t : disappointed from the smell .  m : exactly what i look for in a beer : full-bodied and creamy with abundant soft carbonation .

the initial smell is awesome -- somewhat of a bubble gum and lemon mix . a strong taste of fruity malt/yeast and a very dry aftertaste , the strong feel of hops comes on towards the finish of this one .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , very smooth and creamy . overall this is pretty damn good .
pours almost black , with tan 2 finger head .  the aroma speaks strongly of roasted grains , as you would expect from a stout , while on the tongue the beer has tremendous body .

smells robust with citrusy hops , orange peel and pine . medium bodied and a bit watery at first which is subsequently overcome by a good balance of hops .  mouthfeel is about perfect , and the body is about perfect for a bock style .
overall , this beer looked and smelled great , but has too much bite to really enjoy .  the mouthfeel is full and velvety .

aroma is on point with many ipa 's out there and really doesnt smell like an apa . very attractive nose . taste falls short of what i expected but still nice and balanced . has some sweet pineapple like sugary aftertaste that is appealing but throws me off from the lack of hop bitterness .  moderate body , excellent smoothness .

appearance : the body is a deep black color . the head is a velvety light tan color , small bubbles , two or three inches tall , excellent retention as well and lacing .  a very smooth , luxurious malt backbone enhances the mouthfeel , but a bitter smack of hops reminds me that i 'm drinking an ipa . quite enjoyable .

pours dark orangey brown , slightly hazy at first , then extremely cloudy as i pour in some of the yeast dregs . the aroma is huge - sweet brown sugar and honey with floral notes , alcohol and some breadiness . flavors are very aggressive in this fresh form - a huge honey presence meets with the aggressive bittering hops and some dark fruit sherry notes . excellent barley wine , both in its fresh and aged form - a testament to the value of bottle conditioning and cellarable beers .  first gulp of this was outstanding.. nice creamy , mouthfeel to it that just bombards your mouth with sweet , delicious beer flavor .

s : great smell , fruity although i can not place exactly what fruit .  this beer is on the lighter side of medium-bodied beers and boasts an exceptionally pleasant mouthfeel . carbonation is perfectly balanced , i could n't imagine any improvement here .

s : love the nose on this one ! was expecting a typical citrus hoppy aroma , but instead it was a more roasted/toasted & earthy .  the mouth feel is the richest and thickest i have ever tasted in a beer !
amazingly attractive .  m : creamy and delicious . everything is dead on here .

nose : very fragrant - smoke , chocolate , charcoal , caramel , grapes , more chocolate , alcohol as if it were a liqueur , marshmallows . mouth : first impression = boring ; after taste = unbelievable delicious ; as it warms up = undrinkable .  mouthfeel : perfect mouthfeel .

right after i removed the cap i got this instant burst of fruitiness on the nose . then when i began to pour it , the aroma segued into a toasted bready , creamy , yeasty , and neutral hopped balance . i was sold before i even tasted it . fortunately the taste was just as endearing with a bold body and a sharp bitterness nut-like quality concluding with a pleasant dry hop finale . this beer really hit all the pressure points in a good way and is highly recommended .  maybe i could not taste the `` rare '' but this really sucked compared to the 2008 classic gueuze which is a fantastic gueuze .

: ) s. an incredible aroma on this one . absolutely fantastic . t. awesome , just like the nose . incredible smell and taste , unfortunately difficult to obtain in my area ( even for those in mi ) .  body is right- light , lively carbonation , not cloying or excessively dry .

s : fragrant molasses , baked dark bread , brown sugar , sweet , loving the nose . t : baked brown bread again , baker 's chocolate with a fair amount of roast . d : great nose , solid taste , in the end a nice effort , it needs more sweetness to be really good , it definitely has potential .  feels right in body , but the taste is just off .

there 's something indescribably beautiful about a stout in a pint glass s - a wallop of chocolate and dark roasted coffee , some malt and alcohol notes , but the smell of fermented hot chocolate rules the day t - same as the smell .  yeast , stale hops , a little grass , so boring with a duvel quality ... the taste is equally as bad , bitter toffee , light stale hops , way too much yeast , sour finish . pass .
it 's a solid gold with a sprightly white head .  the carbonation and mouthfeel were appropriate for this style .

pours a deep , dark muddy ruby topped by a large bubbled head . the head retention is fantastic on this .  there is a little tart cherry , but straight blonde base beer is like 75 % of the beer equation . i 'm not sure if there is wild yeast in the bottle , but it does n't seem like this beer has developed much over time . the sourness is only noticeable , and in the end there is a good deal of artificial sweetness in the finish of the beer that is very off-putting . truthfully , it 's better than a lot of back-sweetener fruit beers but if you think this is a lambic like cantillon , you are mistaken .

the beer is wonderful to look at and has a very nice robust and scotch like in complexity nose . the taste is what killed this one for me and the fact that it has almost no carbonation.did i get a bad beer ?  mouthfeel - some good body , oily smoothness per the style . carbonation is moderate .

and lists it as a strong pale ale aroma : grapefruit flowers on a sugary base . mouthfeel : medium body , a bit oily overall impression : nice and easy , a bit boring maybe , but thats more about me than the beer .  mouthfeel : light-bodied and crisp .

surprisingly hoppy aroma for the style with a prominent earthy pine presence as well as hints of citrus and tropical . it smells great just not like a wheat beer . clean , crisp and easy drinking with a slightly dry finish .  i 'm thinking of a breakfast bed . the beer was thick and the foam was velvety . the drinkitbility was okay for its thickness . however , the taste was terrible . a quick slam of semi-sweet citrus that is too heavy on the lemon . the beer ends with an unbalanced bitterness for more than half of the drink .

a - very good , very light golden orange - pretty decent head retention s - the most unique citrus nose of any dipa i 've ever encountered . upfront dried fruit basket and grapefruit blast to the senses . i can pick out the citra hops , that for sure . bitter dry , crisp finish . very , very good beer .  was pretty decent mouthfeel : smooth and crisp , went down easy drinkability : good enough on a hot day and goes great w/ bbq .

terrific . tons of pepper and biting bitterness on the tongue . big letdown from the outstanding aroma . lots of citric flavor , especially grapefruit and orange , but the sweetness of the malt just does not do any justice to the balance and drinkability .  the mouthfeel is smooth and oily and the carbonation is alright .
what a gorgeous beer ! incredibly dark brown head , near pitch black color , and smells just right .  medium bodied ; good amount of carbonation .

full black color with a thick , creamy head .  saccharine all the way . how can you add fake sweetener to bier ? the beer is best described as diet raspberry 7 up . i already go to the gym 4 times a week so that i can drink all the fabulous beer i desire . flavors were overwhelmingly sweet , and tart . complexion was shirley temple , and body was crisp .

very nice 3 finger head that was creamy with a great deal of structure . deep orange/amber in color and quite translucent . great lacing and a touch of visible carbonation . this short description is not an indication that it was n't great .  i believe the bottle i got was 8.75 percent.. looked pretty good for a esl , smell and taste reminded me very much of great western extra gold.. very malty with a nice solventy sweet-like alcohol burn ... carbonated perfectly , making it halfway drinkable , still hangover juice as far as imports go.. cheers !

one of the most appealing scents i 've ever came across : rich malt with heavy caramel sweetness and pronounced chocolate qualities , strong esters of fully ripen figs and dried cherries ; aromas are perfectly mellowed and reminiscent of good port-wine . rather airy initially butt seems to be quickly loosing carbonation trapped within medium body and gets rather flat . overall , a good bsda with remarkable ripen fig & dried cherries aroma . ( 330 ml , into tulip )  mouthfeel - explodes in the mouth with carbonation , yet maintaining a noteworthy smoothness afterwards . the body is sturdy but not overly big .
smell : sweetened chocolate , floral notes .  m : probably the best thing this beer has to offer . very smooth , with just a little bit of unwanted bitterness and carbonation .
s : pumpkin pie baby ! very nice . t : pumpkin spice , clove , nutmeg and caramel from the malts .  mouthfeel - good feel , not too thick , kind of creamy , decent carbonation .
the aroma is just amazing . it is easily the best smelling ipa i 've had in my young beer tasting career .  this beer does have a nice smooth , dry mouthfeel .
euro dark lager fits the bill better . looks good , as expected . dense tan head , lots of lacing .  m - solid and full , with good carbonation .

huge waves of vinegar and tartness on the front followed by a very sweet cocoa character on the finish . very interesting . t : like the nose , the sour character of this beer makes a huge appearance .  the milk sugar cuts through and makes it a bit artificial and like one of those creme savers candies . creamy on the palate with sugary milkiness with some of the same strawberry flavor and other general fruitiness , a touch of tartness in the finish . weirdness in the finish ... not medicinal but has a certain harshness and fake tasting combining with the artificial fruity sweetness like many of the shorts beers , nice to try , but i did n't have any desire to finish the 12oz .
poured a very deep brown with a massive brown head and tons of carbonation .  feels very creamy but that does n't make the beer more drinkable to me .

the beer has a golden color with a hint of orange and features a wonderful malty aroma that is crisp and rich . the flavor is also crisp with some malt highlights and a pretty bitter aftertaste , and overall is heavier than i expected ( i was expecting something like a brewpub blond from this since they also offer a pale ale ) . my last swigs still get that great malt aroma wonderful ! !  however , the mouthfeel was very nice , which lent a overall smoothness and softness to it .

smelled really fresh . plenty of floral aroma and sweet citrus aroma present .  recommended by bert from bert 's better beers . smells like dark chocolate , burn caramel , and vanilla -- sort of like an chocolate chip oatmeal cookie . smooth roast malt , dare i say a tad burnt . there 's a mild pharmaceutical character in back that i 'm not a fan of . i drank half this bottle one night and the second half the following afternoon .
perfect head retention and plenty of lacing left behind in the glass .  mouthfeel is pretty good , goes well with the style of light and highly carbonated .
insanely sticky , a spectacular pour .  there 's actually a nice amount of body to this one .

the aromas amazing . its like smelling a glass full of fresh fruit . theres a little belgian malt in the aroma as well , but the fruity character of the beer is the most amazing quality of the beer . the yeast flavor is intense , and a little distracting , though .  mouthfeel was smooth and taste was of sweet malts at first but finished quite bitter with a sharp hit of hops , alot of hops .
somewhere there is a aroma i ca n't describe , but it is very familiar . marvelous aroma , but it ca n't keep that promise .  the mouthfeel is very full and hearty almost meaty- sort of flat .
this is one of the nicest smelling beers i 've had .  m - good carbonation and a nice balance .

slightly billowy , about 1/2 '' and slowly drops . looks sticky . very natural . not bright orange . i think this is as good looking as an ipa gets .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with smooth carbonation .

sour cherries , fresh-pressed apple cider , mild marble rye , yeasty esters and a faint touch of alcohol . complex and rewarding . effervecent and envigorating without overwhelming the tongue . much lighter than the appearance would lead you to believe and it resembles many other belgian-style ales in this regard . maybe not everyone 's cup of tea but i find it to be immensely drinkable and the alcohol is hardly noticable . quite good .  mouthfeel is nice and thick and well carbonated . the best part of the beer .

this is a fairly average offering in liquor stores round the calgary area , but it is one i can never pass up : this is a very flavourful beer by any means , though it is the most mass-produced of the scotch ales . i love the hue of amber/red glow to this beer . the colour itself is almost appetising . the aroma is my favourite part of the beer . sweet candy , or blueberry gum , rich sweet malt that evokes red licorice , candy cane , sweet bread , sourdough , and other sweet confectionaries . the taste is not as full as the aroma . this is a sweet offering from the time it hits your tongue to the time it leaves your breath : up front there are cherries and irish-red tastes . the hops are there , adding a touch of balance and grass to the finish . the mouthfeel is well carbonated , full , and heavy .  good mouthfeel and texture for a tap beer .

another malt bomb for me . lots of rich malts with dark fruity characteristics . plumbs come to mind with a cranberry aroma layered with cinnamon and a maple kind of sweetness . the taste is not quite as rich as the aroma . slight hints of pine and not quite as much fruit presence as i 'd expected . decent , but the aroma certainly outshines the actual flavors .  as hard as i tried , i couldnt find any `` beer '' flavor in it ... it was almost like it was one of those syrups you would see vendors putting on shaved ice and making a snow cone out of , it was that sweet . the mouthfeel was good , thick , syrup-y , heavy , and coating like an imperial/double stout should be .

a-pours a cloudy orange ... i 'm docking points because pilsner 's should have good clarity ... also excessive head ... s-outstanding aroma ... spicy , floral and somewhat fruity ... very inviting and the type of beer you could sit and smell all day long . but i found it an exciting , and tasting brew ... .one of the best smelling beers i have ever experienced .  mouthfeel is good bordering on to thick .

the aroma is very appealing . sweet hoppy fruit notes , strawberry licorice , apricot nectar . very nice .  glass : new belgium globe aging notes : one year at ~60f in the dark bang for the buck ( oz* % / $ ) : 22*6.2/10 = 13.64 a : orange , white lacey head , slightly cloudy from yeast s : horse-y farmhouse brett with hints of orange t : brett dominates ( horse-stable hay , a little dung almost ) , notes of orange m : silky , coating , lingering , pleasant o : worth drinking , a little one-dimensional with the brett .
a : pours to a frothey tan head with a deep and beautiful copper body . excellent lacing .  mouthfeel - nice body , pretty crisp .

exquisite nose has brandy , oak , vanilla , dark pitted fruits , candy malts , port wine and whiskey . taste does not hold the same complexity . some tart cherries , plums , caramel , toffee , wood , vanilla , wine grapes and cognac . past prime for sure , but still an interesting beer .  a - opaque black color with a small head that disappears quickly s - rich chocolate-like aroma , mild yeast esters , some smokiness , no hop perceived t - roasted malt flavor dominates , some yeasty esters and mild hop flavors take a secondary role , very gentle mild hop finish with some lingering smokiness m - smooth creamy medium body with moderately low carbonation d - this is a decent enough oatmeal stout . the head and retention is disappointing , but the smell , taste and mouthfeel are acceptable .

a : this thing has a huge head . a perfect billowy light-tan colored head with so much fluff , it might as well be whipped cream . the beer is a darker shade of brown when poured , and nearly black in the glass .  well , the bottle states this brew has a `` rich dark malt complexity '' among other things . unfortunately , i do n't care for that rich dark malt complexity at all in this red ale . i like my red ales `` red '' , but without an overpowering harsh chocolate/roasted character . i did like the hop character which is mingled in with the other flavors . i also liked the color and clarity of this brew . overall , this brew just did n't work for me . oh well , that 's why they make lots of different brews , right ?

the beer pours beautifully with a nice deep dark brown color that passes no light through it , has a nice brown foamy two finger head with great lacing on the glass .  oily mouthfeel with next to no carbonation . quite thick and heavy , coating every area of the mouth .

i look at these two next to each other and woder if i have not walked into a paint shop and someone mixed my color swatch perfectly ... the aroma is fantastic . it has all the elments of a wonderful malt bomb , and just enough hop remnants to keep it interesting .  mouthfeel was smooth , light , though i do n't know i 'd go as far as crisp .

a - two fingers of off-white head slowly fade on top of a gorgeous translucent amber beer with bubbles rising steadily through it s - smell is a juicy blend of citrus and apricot , grapefruit is most prominent but plenty of orange zest comes through , apricot is muted and there 's a little bit of mint and pine in there too , do n't get too much aroma from the malts , a touch of toffee maybe t - flavor is far too muted considering that the beer is so appealing to the eyes and the nose , a touch of sweetness , a lot of hop bitterness , some grapefruit and orange , some apricot , but so subdued m - nice tongue coating from the hops but the carbonation is a little prickly , not as smooth as it could be o - not a bad ipa , not a great ipa .  mouthfeel was really good for a light beer . liked the carbonation , and felt richer than it tasted .

the beer poured into the glass crystal clear medium maber with an off-white frothy head which lasted to lace the glass .  mouthfeel was good and very drinkable ; however , it was slightly bitter ... something i was n't expecting this to have considering the malts .

aroma was ridiculously appealing - sweet malt , caramel , maple , vanilla , oak , some dark fruit , and alcohol . wow . d - this was a sipper , but drinkability benefited from the fact that it tasted so damn good .  watery quality to the flavor . has a creamy quality and a smooth carbonation , but i ca n't recommend this beer other than for that .

the two versions are enough alike that any impression of 15th anniversary will translate to 16th ; therefore , my review of 15th anniversary follows : [ `` great divide 15th anniversary wood aged double ipa poured a beautiful copper with red hints when held to light . there was a massive creamy head and huge amounts of lace clung to the glass .  the mouthfeel is very smooth , with fine/sharp bubbles .

the smell was great , had some cocoa , coffee , caramel , vanilla .  mouthfeel : well-carbonated , as expected from the heady pour drinkability : low- i could n't get over the tire flavor , which is a shame because every other aspect of the beer was delightful
a tawny amber gem in the glass , champagne bubbles like fireworks , and an incredible mountainous head .  m : fairly light , highly carbonated , and very soft . i like it .

smell of dark rich chocolate , coffee and molassas , having some dark fruity earthiness to it . taste is again rich as in the above aromas with some roastiness and having alchohol present , but not overwhelming .  m - good . a little sticky .

sour flemish aroma , sour apple , somewhat like a wild ale . numbing sour mouthfeel , with significant carbonation , refreshing . not for a newbie .  dark brown/amber body . it is a very smooth and a sweet sipper . some hops , caramel , candy sugar and oak . not much bourbon . i was way excited to try this and actually find it to be rather average .

s-awesome aroma of top quality chocolate starts things off ... then a little bailey 's irish cream notes ... .caramel ... the more i smell this the more of the irish creme coffee notes but light on the java ... also some plums , and raisins ... .really a great smelling beer . t-dark unsweetened chocolate ... .charred raisins ... licorice ... good amount of pure hop bitterness ... .a lit bit like rogue is in the hopping ... .some alcohol is flexing its muscles and is quite evident ... .exudes what you 'd expect from an impy.. m-rich , and full bodied..velvety.. d-damn nice impy that ranks on the top tier ... i like a couple others better than this but that is no knock on this beer because there are really some kick ass impy 's being made these days ... a must try if you like this style..  has a medium body which is needed to carry all the hops and alcohol . low carbonation lends a nice texture without letting the flavors being cloying .

`` 2021 '' julian date code on the bottom , june-july 2011 apparently . dark tawny copper , sticky cap of fluffy , creamy foam that leaves copious lacing inside the glass . head retention is strong , as it 's long lasting , maintaining a stiff meringue froth for the duration of the glass .  m : good mouthfeel , its crisp , refreshing , light bodied with moderately high carbonation .
the beer smells pretty good , very hoppy like one would expect from this type of beer .  the body is somewhere between medium and full , with a creamy mouthfeel .
a - reddish mahogany hue , off-white head , huge blanketing lacing .  mouthfeel is quite nice and full .
absolutely wonderful ! t : unfortunately , does n't quite live up to the aroma .  highly carbonated .

great aroma , sweet malt , banana , spice , wheat note . medium feel , too cloyingly sweet for me  everything about this beer was pretty light - light , crisp malt scent ; light fruity taste ; light body . feel - 4.0/5.0 - refreshing , which was really nice .

aroma is great - nicely hopped and strong chocolate . flavor is a big disappointment after the promising aroma . too grainy and acidic with a harsh nut-skin flavor .  m - very dry with hop resin in the finish . medium bodied , with a high carbonation .
first off , this is easily the coolest looking beer can ever . awesome retention and lacing .  m. medium-high carbonation , zesty on the tongue .

poured a cloudy yellow gold under a big ( really big ) white head with lots of contour . excellent rings of lace went down the side of the glass as the head retention was outstanding .  m - medium body and low carbonation .

the flavor is a letdown after the excellent aroma . it starts off strong , with bourbon , milk chocolate , and an upper level of roasted malt that continues on to a honey sweet midpalate segment , things seem to go downhill from here with the advent of a combined onslaught of stinging alcohol heat , burnt malt , astringency , and harsh solvent .  there 's also just a hint of citrus from the orange peel ( or orange oil extract ) the smooth mouthfeel and moderate body is not unlike that of a german hefeweizen .

aroma : geuze like . very exciting . battery acid , funky rotten hay , sour lemons , feet with warts on em , horse manure , etc yum ! this is fricking awesome . taste : sour cherries , rancid malts , waterlogged hay on a hot summer day , some putrid strawberries that have been stomped by angry goats . delicious . mouthfeel : very light body .  body is on the full side of medium . moderate carbonation .
pours amberish black . nice pillowy head . retention and lacing are nice apples , chocolate in the nose .  adequate carbonation .
a - huge head , really fluffy . beautiful amber color with appealing haziness .  very smooth without being too full bodied .
