it poured a beautiful copper color with lots of bubbles coming up from the bottom of my beer-clean glass . the beer had abundant head that agressively stuck to the side of my glass and slowly and inconsistently faded , starting from the middle of my glass . this beer really was quite attractive .  goes down smooth , no bite , and finishes with an appropriate amount of stickiness . carbonation is on the lower end of the spectrum . nice feel .
t- very very nice . lots of chocolate & lots of coffee .  this is a medium bodied , well carbonated beer .
the smell is stunning . if i could bottle this and wear it , i would . just incredible . the taste is great , but does not live up tot he smell .  m : it has a nice smooth body .
this beer poured a deep mahogany brown color . very clear and was topped with a creamy lacy head .  good carbonation .

i am smelling a creme brulee desert right now ... i do n't think i could tell the difference from the real thing . exceptional . there is a touch of courseness in the back of the throat from the abv and bitterness .  m - nice . thick .
s- smell is absolutely perfect . sweet , floral tones with a huge aromatic pineyness . t- taste is milder than expected from the ipaesque nose but good none the less .  carbonation is right on par .

really , this is an outstanding looking beer .  taste is a very light malt sweetness upfront with a moderately bitter finish of good length and crispness . a pretty uncomplicated beer , good for the style , a good lawnmower beer .

pours a very clear budweiser gold , with a fluffy white head . in a big glass mug it actually looks refreshing . the can looks pretty cool .  the body of this beer suits the style with the usual level of north coast drinkability and feel to it . definitely the best feature .

pours a slightly hazy amber body with a good inch or so of off-white head that persists and leaves great lacing .  being of fan of bocks , i was fully prepared to love this ubiquitous doppelbock . it was kind of sweet and malty , smelled great , felt nice going down -- quite satisfying . there was a slightly funky smell to it , and an even funkier taste . i thought that was more common in highly hopped beers . at $ 10 for the four pack , i hate to try it again for fear of wasting my hard-earned beer money .
absolutely beautiful orange red body with a thin white head .  this beer has noticeable viscosity and a big thick feel . minimal carbonation .

pours from the bottle to a reddish orange with medium off-white head that lingers , and excellent lacing .  hints of chocolate up front , but quickly overrun by the massive spices . reminds me of chewing on a mixture of green baking herbs , and about as pleasing on my palate . an interesting brew to say the least , but not one i 'd purchase again .

the aroma is both unique and memorable , with a cornucopia of fruitiness : pineapple , mango , strawberry , and starfruit . the hops taste grassy and resinous , but the highlight is the tropical fruits derived from the yeast ... excellent stuff , even though it 's not the most cohesive-tasting flavor profile . a crafty anniversary beer..complex , tasty , and original . kudos , real ale .  after smelling , i picked up on a semi-complex mix of belgium candy , malts , cherries and alcohol . it sat heavy on me and did not taste refreshing to me . i enjoyed this beer and can tell there was definitely quality & craftsmanship involved in it 's making ; but it 's not the best tripel i have ever had .

the aroma has a unique sweet-fruitiness too it that i was not expecting . sweet dates and raisins all-over , a touch of hershey 's chocolate syrup , mildly sweet red fruits and a bunch of heat , which is also a surprise . the aroma is nice and draws you in . the malt is very smokey and fruity ... which seems like a strange combo , but it works .  mouthfeel is crisp and drying , as it should be .

the aroma is spicy with loads of malt and touch of hops . the nose is spot on with what i think a marzen should smell like . overall a decent marzen .  the feel is between medium and full for the style and enjoyably so . moderate carbonation nails the feel .

nose is fantastic ! uniquely fruity , like a cranberry-mango chutney . hops are detectable and make this a complex sniffer , probably the best smelling tripel i have ever laid nostrils upon . fruit levels take on the best from belgium , impressive . very nice brew , might be my favorite that i have had so far from the bruery .  the mouthfeel is notably well contoured . dark and hearty though at times cloying .
this really is a lovely looking beer .  m -- thick , slick d -- very one dimesional brew .

smell- unbelievable aroma ! overall- has a great aroma but falls short with the taste .  lovely thick aromas of blackstrap molasses , dark bitter chocolate , strong coffee and deep roasted malts ... awesome aromas to this one ... lazy and flat tasting ... strange bitter almost sour taste present ... . not much in common with the aromas ... thick oily mouthfeel is great but i ca n't get by the taste of this one ... drain poured this one ... maybe a bad bottle but as is , a big disappointment ...
pours a deep deep dark brown with a monumental rocky khaki head ... . beautiful .  pretty refreshing , not overwhelmed with carbonation .

aroma is right there with what i look for in a bsda : nice bouquet of caramel malts , dark fruits , belgian yeast , and maybe some candied sugar . i 'm suddenly pretty jazzed about this beer . if the sweetness was dialed back a bit this could be a great beer ... still very good , but imo just a bit too sweet .  it is medium bodied and smooth in the mouth .

aroma is powerful , though not overbearing . piney/resiny hops are dominant , yet there is also a good helping of pineapple , tropical fruit and caramel .  you do n't get much of the sweet malts you get from the aroma so it really confuses the senses and does n't make for an enjoyable experience mouthfeel is heavy and it sticks to your mouth for minutes .
from a bottle , poured into a pint glass a - deep black color with a mocha head .  mouthfeel is light bodied with good carbonation .

decent lacing left behind . s - wow , great aroma here . immediately there is a lot of pineapple and coconut aroma making it clear that this has been barrel aged . lots of stuff going on here .  m : medium in both body and carbonation .

smells fantastic ! fruity , citrus , & some serious hops . one of the better smelling beers i 've had .  the carbonation on this beer is very light with a medium body , the beer itself has a sliky relaxing feel with every swallow . its has a mellow feel to it nonetheless . overall this an average beer that im sure has its audience who will think less of it and people like myself who may not dislike it but not exactly like this beer .

a deep mahogany appearance with thick lacing on the sides gave this a beautiful appearance . i emailed the location and i guess what makes it unique is its cross between a red ale and a stout .  thick and smooth mouthfeel .

advertised as a belgian-style golden ale , from looks and smell alone it starts out as good as any of the actual belgian pale ales have tried . this is still a wonderful brew for the smell and balance alone , but as a belgian pale ale is pretty much my favorite style in the summer months i 'm probably more critical than most with this style .  body was medium , and the liquid was fairly smooth overall . 3.03 rdev -19.5 % look : 3.5 | smell : 3 | taste : 3 | feel : 4 | overall : 2.5 1366

down to my last g'knight so i felt the need to review this beauty and hopefully it wo n't be long before i can get more . i 'll never forget the first time i popped one of these open , the smell was amazing , i could drink it straight from the can . pure sweetness in the nose , a bit of resiny hops , caramel , cake , so sweet you can taste it .  mouthfeel is very light and well carbonated .

smell : the highlight of this beer ... beautiful clean aroma of light fruits with a backbone of belgian yeast and a moderate citrus hint .  i like the thick , syrupy mouthfeel as it 's quite comforting but the taste gets old fast and just is n't complex .
s- banana aromas dominate with subuded peppery yeast notes .  good , solid creamy feel with enough dryness to get you through .

smell- big , rich chocolate . bourbon and vanilla . it 's very nice . taste- it has some nice chocolate , and some booze . overall- i was so excited about this one after the smell . this is just disappointing .  m - light to medium carbonation with medium carbonation .

i enjoyed this stout as it warmed up to room temperature . this is as black as you can get which is expected for a stout .  '' m - actually a nice and robust mouthfeel , i just do n't really want to feel this beer in my mouth because it tastes kind of terrible .

) aug. 15 2008 @ hop cat ba / brewery grand opening event , served in tulip glass . opaque black , creamy tan head , beautiful bubble suspension after pour , wow ! looks thick smells of roasty heavy malts , dark fruit , smooth and creamy , mmm taste is of thick heavy bitter chocolate , hot alcohol , rich and smooth , compared to keg this is way mellowed , not as harsh and easier to drink , amazing ! , raisins , chocolate , slight coffee , earthy peat , mm mouthfeel is oily slick , smooth , creamy , viscous , a sipper for sure - delicious !  the flavor that by far took the lead was chocolate ! there 's an overpowering ( and for me , disappointing ) chocolate aftertaste in this beer . mouthfeel- smooth , no complaints here . drinkability- well , the bottle looks cool as you drink from it !

i noticed a nice hop bouquet on the nose which suggests it was dry-hopped . maybe it was n't , perhaps just really fresh as the beer had a born on date suggesting the beer was less than two weeks old .  it was somewhat thick with some carbonation , and had a hot aftertaste .

smells rich and sweet with a nice peaty smokiness to it . overall it 's nice .  notes : brewed with 100 % scottish maris otter malt ( used in distilling ) and fuggle hops , this is quite the unique beer , albeit it is also excessively raw and aggressive in its flavours . the hops are a way too perceived in the flavour and aroma for the `` scottish-style '' , hence the experimental beer placement .

hopefully since it appears to be bottle conditioned that the beer is still holding up a - poured into goblet an opaque black color . fluffy inch tall light brown head that disapates into a tinner covering that lasts until the end .  m : nice carbonation and pretty effervescent .

very rich and interesting smells . tastes almost apple-y with more spices from the nose continuing .  let me first say that the brugse tripel used to be one of my favorite beers . nowdays its called brugge tripel and the taste changed slowly ... but a lot of small steps make a big one and today this beer is nothing what it used to be . smell of spices and a little hops , not fresh at all and a dull taste make it just a drinkable beer but nothing great like it had in the past .

good retention and lacing ... the aroma is pretty nice , sweet candy wheat , honey , floral finish ... the taste really is disappointing , borderline bad . pretty disappointing for me after such a great aroma . i ca n't recommend this .  m : medium bodied , good amount of carbonation .
looks pretty damn nice .  mouthfeel is medium , carbonation average-high with some pleasant warming feel .

head is enormous and very thick and creamy .  m & d - this beer is great on its own , too light and carbonated and malty for me , but suits a nice dinner perfectly , goes well with food and that was its intention so i must review it within its intentions and the style , for which it is very good
i love the smell of this stuff , there is n't a better smelling stout in the world , even if its from a can .  m - good mouth feel . somewhat unique in feel .

color was a little hard to see as it was fairly dark in the bar but appeared to be a very deep red , that while really dark was no opaque . slightly off-white head that left excellent lacing on the glass . not sure if it was the branded oversized wine glass or what but this was probably the second best looking beer i 've ever seen .  the body is light-medium with good carbonation .
pours out to a sparkingly clear medium amber , forming a tall , creamy very light yellow head with excellent retention and large sheets of lace . nice looking brew .  m : good mouthfeel .
medium intensity and a very smooth and mellow character .  big body , low carbonation .

wow , this smells hoppy . i have never smelled this amount of hops in an ris , i get a lot of really citrusy hops , maybe some toasty chocolate under it , but the hops dominate , wish i could know when this was bottled . it is really interesting though .  mouthfeel is round and full , thick and sticky .
aroma is powerfully sour and very champagney . this is a very good beer , and quite a unique one .  there 's moderate carbonation to it as well .

s : smells really good . lots of bourbon , vanilla , oak right away , giving a huge barrel presence . the barleywine aromas of caramel , toffee , brown sugar , and dark fruits are evident and impressive as well . o : a really nice nose but the flavor was disappointing .  amazing . while the style is not my first choice for a beer , i 'd been told that i really needed to try something from unibroue and this one was it . i taste coriander and a lot of other , complex flavors that i am too n00b to identify . as for aromas , just a very pleasant yeast smell .

s - raisins and dates with stewed apples and a slight smoky character . strong presence like a nice port wine . currants and a touch of yeasty alcohol are in the mix . not the greatest beer ever and the carbonation is nuts , but it tastes , smells and looks nice .  mouthfeel : really thick and chewy . this part would be enjoyable in a good-tasting brew .

nose is roasty coffee , caramel , roast chocolate , herbal hop , and fruity , spicy and nutty yeast products . crazy . the first thing that hits me is fruit bouquet , then herbal hop ushers in phenols . good if you do n't think of it as stout .  mouthfeel is quite decent .

this thing looks good ! beautiful two inches of white plume on top of a hazy orange , slightly red color that provides a light orange glow when held up to the light . the smell is n't nearly as impressive as the looks , though .  very tame malt , very little hops , and weak alcohol that 's more like aftershave . definitely not over-carbonated , the texture fits the style . actually the best element of this beer .
left tremendous lacing all throughout . simply the best looking stout period .  m - pretty thin and definitely refreshing .

aroma is full of floral notes and hoppy sweetness . gummy ... lavender ... spicy ... oh so nice ... smooth on the palate ... a smallish touch of burn on the way down the throat . more balanced than i was expecting ... a nice sweetness up front and a good bitter back-end .  it is very finely carbonated , giving a tickle on the tongue .
pours a clear gold with a 1/4 '' head with great retention .  feels nice in the mouth .

pours honeyed orange with a big beige foamy head with tons of sticky foam caking the side .  taste - 3.0/5.0 - light `` summer '' type beer , prob good if really hot , some malt crispness feel - 4.0/5.0 - smooth , light , refreshing drinkability - 2.5/5.0 - would have again , if it was hot , but not enough flavor make this a go-to beer

it smells awesome , everything works together and you get something else every whiff no issues here t much more booze then the nose , more toffee , smoke , and fruit with some burnt brown sugar , still very nice but without as much balance m enters silky then the bubbles make it feel creamy , quite thick and the flavors linger , the heat lingers too and that 's my only complaint in this area o for a big fresh barley wine i thought it was pretty good , the barrel agings there but not overpowering and its oh so mellow i was hoping this one would suck so i would n't need to buy a couple of them to age , pretty expensive but this would be amazing after some time , pretty mellow considering the 13.8 % fresh i can only imagine this 5 years down the road  m- medium viscosity with a well integrated carbonation .
a : nearly black in color , a very dark cola color with a thick , foamy cocoa head . great retention and lacing .  m : it has a nice mouthfeel .

s : chocolate covered cherries , vanilla , mocha , amazing ! t : huge vanilla ( a little much for me ) , oak , bakers chocolate , mocha .  the best part of this one is the mouthfeel ; to my surprise , it is rather thick , at least for a beer of this style .
pours with a deep amber/red body topped by a thick off white head with lots of lacing .  the mouth is pretty nice , feels rich but easy to drink .

wow . thick bourbon and aforementioned flavors , mostly caramel . lovely beer , quite exceptional .  mouthfeel : light/medium with a tart , crisp finish drinkability : i really do n't crave another of these ; this certainly would n't be a lawnmower beer for me conclusion : just kind of unsorted ( also kind of an odd bitterness on the finish ) ... i tried this a year or two ago and was n't a huge fan ... now that i 'm reviewing it ... i 'm still not .

this brew is quite hazy with a golden orange body . the head produced is massive and bright white .  this beer tastes like sheep shit . this may appeal to some people , but it 's definitely a very unusual belgian ale . i enjoyed drinking half of this beer for the experience . it 's so pungent i laughed out loud . it 's always fun to be exposed to a radically different flavor profile than you 're used to .

light brown pour with red highlight and a voluminous foamy light tan head . good retention and some nice lacing , though the size of the head on pouring does make me concerned that this has carbonation issues ( thankfully it does n't ) .  mouthfeel is about the only thing going for this one . medium body and appropriate carbonation .

smell is kind of `` down on the farm '' and very deep and enjoyable : aromas of good bread , malt , wool , leather and coffee , subdued but complex and rich .  m - nice and creamy in the mouth , goes down smooth .
pretty tasty with a great aroma .  the mouthfeel is medium to full with decent carbonation .

the smell- incredible . at first , very sweet smelling- hints of pineapple . for such a strong beer , it finishes very abruptly , leaving you with just a tad of malt . overall , incredible .  full body , syrupy like samichlaus . very similar tastes and mouthfeel .

448th review on ba bottle to snifter 750 ml c/c batch 2 2011-2 best by : 1/2013 bottle # 9711 app- a gorgeous garnet red with a huge two finger head . puddles sit on top of this brew .  the mouthfeel is moderately thick and full for a pilsner and has a creamy texture . the citrusy hops create a crisp bite towards the end .

s : the glass was a foot and a half away from my face and i could immediately smell a warm pumpkin pie coming out of the oven with a nice floral hops on the back . t : the spicy pumpkin flavor swirls with a strong caramel malt flavor .  body is medium and carbonation is mild .
this beer pours with a thick and foamy head . wonderful active bubbles slowly float to the top to form a thick white head .  light body and nice and creamy . moderate carbonation .
the aroma of it is amazing , almost a pumpkin cider type smell .  '' the mouthfeel is good . its quite smooth and slightly creamy .

floral pine caramel . t : at 99 ibu and 6 % i was expecting a hop bomb that was crazy unbalanced but the scottish golden grain holds up against the hops . real bitter and dry mouth with a little astringent flavor d : besides my mouth being super dry and bitter its a great session beer . one of the best ipas ive had considering the flavor of the beer .  decently carbonated mouthfeel , and medium-bodied .
amber colored ale that pours with a rocky head .  m : about the same consistency as the boston lager .

pours a good head that has a beautiful big lacing , and it has an orange copper color to it that 's appetizing . there 's only a slight amount of sediment at the bottom of the glass .  for a big mouthfeel , this simply does n't have a flavor to match . very nice mouthfeel , good bite up front , a bit of carbonation in middle that emphasises the rye flavors , and a crisp finish that is actual slightly ruined by the lingers smoked flavor .

smell : so wonderful ... the smoky peaty aroma fills the nostrils . cloying . i really did n't care for the sweetness of this beer .  char davies , the artist in 1998 , made a fully interactive immersive visual/aural virtual artwork called ephemere , which furthers the work begun in osmose started in 1995 and displayed in the national gallery of canada in ottawa on june 26 , 1998. who cares ? this beer is almost close to a champaign ( and i would think that the yeast probably is champaign ) . also there is bitterness , which is nice to know that at least there are some hops to the so called beer . it is not advisable to use apples with fermenting , as the yeast creates funky flavors from apples , but this is much better than expected . although i would not want to drink this beer on a regular bases , thus low score on drinkability , i think it has a great taste like a grandsmith apples i use to eat as a kid .
it has a massive creamy bone colored head , very large and good retention for a cask ale . decent lace trails stick to the glass .  the mouthfeel was the best thing about this beer .

aroma is mostly complex stages of hops , it 's easy to believe there are 10 varieties , there 's the big american c hops character combined with the refined english ones . very relaxing to sniff on and ultra-complex , like a touch of vanilla on fresh citrus ( grapefruit ) . in mouth this dances on the tongue , nice effervescence , creamy , full-bodied , complex malt sweetness and an obvious balancing yeastiness . this is a delicious big generous beer . tasting this with my buddy martint , we came to the conclusion that given the choice to pick only 2 beers from a same brewery to have an infinite supply of , hotd with fred and adam would probably win over quite anyone .  a nice mouthfeel with some decent nuttiness and a tasty touch of roast .

tons of banana in both the aroma and the taste . this is a very fruity beer , and i think the sweetness would not be as pleasant over a whole pint . a very decent brew though .  mouthfeel is fine . medium bodied with the right amount of carbonation .

hazy blond in color with a steady stream of bubbles rising from the bottom of the glass to form a huge , thick , rocky white head that lasts for the entire glass .  mouthfeel is solid - fairly light , appropriate carbonation .

s : it smelled very malty with hints of doughy white yeast and whiffs of ripe white ( apricots and pear ) s fruit and sweet citrus ( mandarin oranges ) .  and of the 6ix , cranberry lambic will likely catch your eye first and disappoint you the most . if you are like me the word `` lambic '' leaves you with a dumb look on your face . you can relax because this is not a real lambic . just as champagne is not champagne unless it is bottled in champagne , france : : a lambic is not a lambic unless it is brewed in pajottenland , belgium . aside from that minor detail a lambic is brewed using spontaneous fermentation and possess a clear vinous finish , cranberry lambic does not-and that maybe a good thing . do n't drink this cold-i 'll be honest , this beer is n't great , but it does deserve more credit , the balance between cranberry and yeast is impeccable ; the finish is crisp and light like a wine , less the vinous/lambic feel . it does great before , during and after dinner , this unique `` boston lambic '' is worth an unbiased try .

the aroma is a lovely `` double '' chocolate with lots of heavy roasted malts muted amongst the rich chocolate aroma .  the mouthfeel is very nice.. feels heavy , thick , smooth , and not over-carbonated .

smells like oak , vanilla , rum , chocolate , caramel and other malt notes . a lot of wood up front , very sweet malt beneath and a strong rum and vanilla character in the finish . this one is a unique beer and rather tasty , if a bit sweet and one-dimensional .  m : creamy and spot-on carbonation .

looks great , smells great ( campfire char , bacon fat , and woodsap ) , but fails to deliver any real smoke flavor in the palate or the finish . quite disappointing for the style , although it would make a fine amber ale .  very nice feel .

served in a wheat beer glass . beer is yellow and hazy , forms a big white head of small and medium bubbles that leaves some lacing on the glass . looks good .  it has a canned fruit essence to it , but i ca n't pick up what kind of fruit . first couple of sips and i get a strong cherry pie filling flavor . i eat a lot of fresh cherries in the summer so i do n't automatically associate cherries with pie filling . not overly sweet but it does have a tart tang finish . a unique beer that i appreciate as well done , just not to my tastes .
pours a pitch black color with a huge brown head into my glass .  m : crisp and clean , moderate levels of carbonation and warmth . medium body .

extremely fruit-fillled aromatics - pungent apple sauce notes lead the way into a more diverse array of stone-fruit esters . lush oaky notes with a touch of bergamot in the finish - complexity grows as the beer warms . i 'm still impressed that the base beer can be improved upon by soaking up the best characteristics of the barrels it is aged in , but these special editions of harvest ale have certainly `` matured '' more than simply `` aged .  m : the body is medium to full with a fairly high carbonation . this is actually one of the best things about this beer .
a nice wine scent . taste is like it smells , which is good .  m : medium bodied with moderate carbonation .

smells of coffee and also some sweet chocolate .  served in a pint glass mug a : pours a clear bronze color with about an inch of thick head s : a smell provides a nice rye scent with a very sweet undertone contributed by the honey addition t : very nice smooth tasting beer , has a slight hint of honey and perhaps a slight rye note but other than that there isnt much to comment on , smooth and slightly sweet but thats about it m : very smooth in the mouth with a slight bite on the tongue as it is drank d : high level of drinkability , very subdued taste that is great for a hot summer day but leaves the drinking looking for more otherwise .
quite a nice choice of fragrance hops . looks and smells phenomenal . taste , i just ca n't wrap my tongue around it .  pretty solid .

smells strongly of pine and.. well.. marijuana . a nice earthy hop with most of the aroma hitting deep in the back of the nose . flavor is a nice mix of biscuity malt and rich fruity and piney hops .  mouthfeel is decent medium bodied and goes down smooth .

the nose was spectacular . sweet tar , coffee , chocolate , sappy wood all leap from the glass . molasses and brown sugar are buried within the beautiful , rich nose . overwhelming loads of flavors battling for attention .  the mouthfeel is crisp overall .

a= a hazy orangish amber color with an enourmous off white creamy head with amazing lacing and retention . really nice looking s= fruity for sure .  the mouthfeel is thick and oily with a mild burn going down . have a bottle of this is all i can handle , which is good because the full bottle would have me a little too buzzed .

a : pours a yellowish orange color , like apple juice with a little fizz ; head is huge and rocky , foamy and thick , like something out of a bubble machine ; yeast sediments sink to the glass bottom upon pour and settling s : everything you 'd expect from a belgian strong ale ( dark or light ) , with complex , sweet dark candied and dark fruit aromas ; however , there is a hint of dry , hoppy citrus and bitterness just underneath the heavy sweetness ; definite booze smell as the beer warms t : the first flavor is alcohol , but not in a sharp , unpleasant way ; it 's there , but tempered with the great and significant sweetness only found in belgian strongs ; great maltiness ; sweetness ranges from tropical fruit flavors to bits of caramel , vanilla , cloves and banana ; m : smooth and heavy up front ; warm , tingly on the tongue ; finishes with a surprising and welcomed touch of dryness that finishes in a refreshing and crisp way ; amazing ! maybe i 'm just an american , but this one 's damn good .  medium full bodied , somewhat creamy .

a nice cloud of white head that really sticks around and leaves nice lacing . beautiful in the glass and that nice tart , musty funky taste .  m : the mouthfeel , on the other hand , was quite good . d : it 's certainly very sessionable , with a low abv and a really nice mouthfeel , but the flavor is just so weak that it 's difficult for me to really recommend it .

s - smells very inviting ! full of citrusy hop aromas ( pineapple , grapefruit , and orange ) and some pine scents as well . t - taste is different than expected . d - moderately drinkable - it would be nice if the malt flavors competed a little more with the hops to help balance it a little .  m : easy drinking with medium-body and low-moderate carbonation .
really nice . t - red wine grapes , cherries and leather stand out to me , as does the vanilla and wood from the barrels .  very creamy and full . very dry .

immense multi-layered head with frothy , large bubbles at the base and fine meringue top . lasted for ever , leaving beautiful lacing behind .  this is my first review and hope it looks well , even if not my favorite beer . leaves a malt taste on the roof and tongue . this is the first scottish ale i 've tried . for comparison , i love dark ales , like ommegang abbey belgium ale and founders breakfast stout . bottle serving .

what a shame ... pours a pretty golden-amber color topped by a huge , thick , creamy white head .  taste : a wink of hops , than the shows over , a surprisingly dry finish mouthfeel : decent - nice restrained carbonation , ever so slightly creamy notes : this is the driest , and least bitter ipa that i have ever experienced .
roasted coffee and smoked/roasted malts .  most everything else about this beer was great , looked good , good mouthfeel , but the taste .

pours an impossibly crystal-clear straw color . the bubbles are as fine as you will find in a beer , crazy lacing on the sides of the glass .  m : the carbonation is pretty much just right , and it 's smooth .
it 's an awesome smelling stout !  mouthfeel : thick and what you would expect from a ris .

lightly spicy with some typical weizen-like notes of clove and yeast . this is quite a fruity smelling brew with alcohol esters being fairly pronounced . for a beer that smells quite deep and intense with character , the flavor falls a bit short and is not nearly as complex . as the brew warms up , some chocolate grain notes become evident .  nice creamy mouthfeel .

s - great smelling ! lots of nice fruit and hoppy deliciousness . overall , a fantastic beer . it 's odd that it 's an amber , as it tastes a lot like an ipa .  flavor is malty and sweet , and on the finish , bubble gum ! mouthfeel is firm , and drinkability is high .

s : citra hops up front . smells of pineapple and other tropical fruits . i 'm in love with the aroma . t : slightly sweet malts .  mouth feel is smooth and clean , with an average carbonation level . overall , good aroma , blend , body , and feel .
pours a fluffy , thick , white , three-fingered head , fades very slowly and leaves gobs of lace .  moderate hops with lots of body , almost chewy .

the first thing that struck me about this stout was the aroma , very complex , almost sweet , with what i thought could have been vanilla among other things . the # 1 surprise was the texture and consistency of this beer , i was expecting something much thicker , more like guiness , and boy was i surprised , a much smoother , lighter consistency with a great taste and just enough flavor to let you know you are drinking something quality without being over whelming . it took me more time to get a good overall sense of this stout then i would have expected , a compliment to the complexity of the flavor .  this is my first , of hopefully many reviews , so bare with me . once they were chilled i poured them into a pint glass and sat back with my favorite tv shows a- pours a dark red almost brownish color s- smells like your average porter , did n't really pick up on too much vanilla t- taste more of chocolate or toffee but with hints of vanilla m- pretty smooth , goes down easy without any bite o- not sure if i would buy a case of it , but its good when thrown in a variety pack

the nose is great , with notes of roasted barley , chocolate malt , and a little bit of coffee . has some creaminess as well which is very nice . the beer is medium bodied , but is a bit light on carbonation .  boiled pasta water finish . good carbonation . twinge of acid is perfect .

appearance : dark red-burnt orange body , medium head . the head is creamy and tan , leaves full lace .  the feel was light , clean and crisp . damn , and after smelling this hefe , it had so much promise .

great hop bouquet -- sweet and juicy , with citrus highlights laid over a smooth backbone of stonefruit ( mostly red ; think cherries , plums , grapes ) , and a little oak . i really like the aroma this beer puts out . the body of the beer is a lovely dark amber color that tinges toward straw around the edges of the glass .  mf : soft and medium-bodied . coriander and crispness does n't stand out enough .
the smell was light , floral and fruity ; i almost imagined it apricot if i had n't known it was raspberry .  mouthfeel was good , carbonation was adequate .
pours a beautiful color , have to admit . deep gold/cherry in color -- like a cognac .  m - full bodied and chewy with a moderately dry finish with some alcohol noticeable .

smells great ( but nothing like a gumball imo ) . incredible . very bitter for a pale ale , or pale wheat ale , whatever . it certainly smelled good , but nothing more than the typical tropical fruit-heavy pale/ipa .  mouthfeel is pretty good .

s : amazing aroma . very syrupy and sweet smell . lots of brown suger/toffee/caramel notes , some faint char and even some coffee . o : the smell on this beer is phenomenal , but the taste just does n't deliver .  buttery thick mouthfeel .
aroma is a staggering , fresh , really rich chocolate .  flavor was very strong ginger , and this made the mouthfeel quite crisp and pretty good .
smell is unbelievable . tons of chocolate , dark fruit , and malted milk balls .  taste is mild but the mouthfeel is full pleasantly full and quite nice .

a : pours a dark black with a massively thick mocha head that seems to last forever ... excellent lacing throughout .  the mouth-feel is thick almost porter-like with the cooling of the alcohol evaporation .
this beer looks like the platonic ideal of beers . light amber/orange color and a fluffy white head that dissipates slowly .  the mouthfeel was decent , medium with adequate carbonation .

a : this is simply a great looking beer , pours a deep rich carmel with quckly dissapating head s : slight maltiness , and , unexpectedly , some barnyard funkiness , but very faint t : starts off malty but quickly gives way to mild hop bitterness , finsishes pretty dry ( like the dry maltiness of a helles ) m : pretty dry and clean on the palate , although , disapointingly , had almost a watery mouthfeel d : pretty solid sessions lager that would be a good find on tap .  finish is very grainy and `` off '' lol mouthfeel : full-medium , creamy body with moderate carbonation .

on the nose , fresh fruits , cherries , peaches , green apples , pears , simply amazing . a bit twangy and just on the border of being chewy , but not quite . dry and a bit laid back ; decent yeasty body with some reserved sugar , candy cane offerings . sticky as it warms , sort of a bubble gum palate and a bit rustic .  mouthfeel was smooth , slightly thick for a pils , and with a nice carbonation bite .
a : beautiful . three fingers worth of foamy mocha colored head . lots of lacing here .  very refreshing in the mouth , its best quality .

smell : wow . butter cream , pecan , caramel , custard . butter rum lifesaver , anyone ? awesome . taste : bready and nutty . not as complex as the aroma but still very nice . lingering alcohol finish .  the mouthfeel was full and sweet .
the aromas are magnificent ! espresso coffee as if fresh brewed .  m : medium body , low to medium carbonation . smooth and creamy . d : something does n't quite work for me .

appearance : deep brown to black with a creamy one inch white head .  nice creaminess from the malt . probably the driest amber ale i 've ever had . usually not a bad thing , i like dry beers , but this was too much , there needs to be a little sweetness there to bring it to life . should n't be called an octoberfest and would n't try again .

s : the best component of this beer , gratifying spices on top of a light roasted malt . d : good smell and its light make for easy drinking , but i would prefer more commanding flavors and spices .  mouthfeel is good and thick , finish is dry with a moderate dose of alcohol present .
very fresh and clean smell , hardly any yeast aroma .  this one is crisp and carbonation is at a good level . body is n't as light as i had expected ; this one 's medium-bodied .

yeast totally non-flocculating , so even a careful pour would have left 1/2 the bottle behind if i didnt take some yeast . aroma was typical ommegang , sour and spicy with vapors of peach and cherry . palate was less sour than aroma and about 1/2 way between duvel and ommegang ommegang . the `` fine dose of yeast '' did cause massive rumbling in my plumbing later that night though .  mouthfeel is nice and balanced , although approaching thin at times .
it pours clear ruddy amber with a very thick and creamy tan head .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with a velvety texture , and appropriately low carbonation .

it has a lovely roasted , woody aroma and the initial body is a full toasty , roasty malty assault that jumps quickly to a firm , dry bite and lingering hoppy finish . a beer like this is actually a good reason for my pessimism at another certain large brewer 's foreign extra reviewed in february , because this is what that could have been : firm , full and nuanced .  hoping it 's one of those better in a bottle beers i 'm returning to give it another try . so far so good . maybe , and i 'm stretching , some neutral hop spice . this beer makes me try too hard . these hops should be hops should be ashamed of themselves . good malt base to support hops , were they present . bottle is equally bland as on tap .
smelled pleasant . fruity with nice hop smell .  it 's fairly pleasant in the mouth . combine the crisp and refreshing mouthfeel with a decent flavour and this beer would be worth getting .

the beer looks great ! s : i get some notes of honey , grass , caramel , and light seasonal summer fruit .  mouthfeel : light body , medium carbonation , but the bubbles do n't really `` prickle '' the tongue like i thought it would . a very nice and smooth carbonation .

a : absolutely beautiful looking brew .  very rich flavor of dark malts and smoke , with hints of coffee and chocolate as well . the finish is almost all smoke , much too intense for my liking . ive used this many times in making caribou pot roasts in the crockpot . they even have a recipe on their website , which is delicious . i was informed that this beer has won more medals at the great american beer festival than any other beer , quite an accomplishment .

s - beautiful wet hopped aroma with a citrusy and piney profile that is extremely fresh . there 's also a bit of bread and caramel malt present .  the mouthfeel of this beer ( outside of taste ) was great . great carbonation , bitter hop aftertaste , medium bodied .
very clean aroma of bourbon and some licorice .  the body and carbonation levels are appropriate .

the head recedes smells great , rummy , oak-y , sugar cane , caramel , coconut , spicy , very layered and complex nose . there 's a little hop bitterness in the taste but all else is overpowered by the rum and oak taste .  mouthfeel : crisp and refreshing .

the color is pretty cool to look at .  orange , darkish color , looks a lot like the two previous hop project beers i had . the flavor also left a lot to be desired . the last hop project beers i had were both quite intriguing and sadly this was just boring as far as the hops were concerned . oh , well , hopefully i get to try more of this crazy series .

huge smell of prunes , chocolate , a hint of molasses and some licorice . has that belgian `` funk '' as i call it . i do n't care , smells great ! deep rich chocolate and molasses covered prunes . this is a brew that has been blessed by the gods . there are hints of mint and licorice along side with a hint of anise and some bitter chocolate . a+ taste ! omg this beer makes me want to guzzle , but i think twice and enjoy each and every sip .  the mouthfeel at the start was mildly crisp and finished dry and smooth . the unbalanced flavors knock down the drinkability for me .

the aroma is of peat , caramel , nuts , and chocolate . i really like the uniqueness of this aroma . the taste has more caramel than the aroma . overall , this is a really , really good scotch ale .  the mouthfeel was quite good , though . well carbonated and it felt good going down .
the smell is certainly its best quality .  medium bodied and smooth .

it 's bronze , perfectly bright . it 's foamy , with a good head and strong laces . this beer shows that a beer made to please the most people can still be made with great quality .  ) mouthfeel : in one word , thick .
the foam is perfect as is the amber clear color ; perfectly bright .  this beer has a high level of carbonation with a very crisp and clean mouthfeel .

this beer sure looks good , but it sure aint of me . stone ris pours an oily thick pitch black witha huge brown head . as the head disapates , it leave so great lacing .  m : chewy and viscous . if anything , the aging has tempered some of the trademark trainwreck mouthfeel and flavors of base dark lord , so i 'm impressed .

pours copper in color , red hues and gets lighter the more you drink ... how surprising . a massive off-white head , tight bubbles of carbonation and superb staying power .  quickly hops dominate and overwhelm with a slightly unpleasant linger . smooth with a light bite . it 's not too bad until the hop bitterness overwhelms and turns this into just another hoppy ipa . all the other flavors disappear without anything to redeem it beside bitterness and a nice feel .

aroma : the aroma was very nice . chocolate , burnt sugar , vanilla , roasted grains . the aroma made me really want to try a sip .  we 're okay though , as next time we get a samuel adams winter sampler pack , i 'll give her my cranberry , and i 'll have her boston lager . it 's not a bad beer , it 's just not to my liking . i ca n't even really say why . a bit sweeter than i 'd like , and just nothing that stands out and says `` i 'm great '' .

the smell is unique , all the normal bready , earthy notes are right up front but the herbs in the background really add a nice complexity to the beer . mmmm sage . the taste is just as unique as the smell . the herbs give it a bit of a medicinal quality that is n't as enjoyable in the taste as the smell . citrus right up front but the herbs are all i really taste after that . $ 3.69 i think .  mouthfeel : medium body , medium carbonation overall : this beer has almost no taste , pity

it smelled of the mediterranean sea and beautiful , long-legged , not to be fucked with , italian women with sensuous lips . a very sweet , lemony ipa that is excellent for what it is , and enjoyable , for a time .  the mouthfeel is decently crisp while not out-of-control with carbonation .

starts off creamy white and then cascades from the bottom of the glass to the top changing to black as it goes . there is a thick off white head that lasts forever and covers the sides of the glass in foam and thick rings that mark each swallow .  m : crisp , clean , would call it refreshing if it tasted better .

smells fantastic . spicy , fruity and different . really intriguing . tastes similar to the aroma -- some malty , almost candy-like , sweetness underneath , but with a strong bitterness taking centre stage .  the aroma contained notes of malt , hops and a discernable alcohol content of medium strength . it had a stong alcohol flavor that was very over powering the other flavors . it was smooth yet burned as it went down . truely a devilish brew !

this might come as a shock , but this beer actually smells like real chocolate !  the flavor is a bit better as the taste of both a good belgian tripple and a solid ipa can both be percieved ; however , the flavors compete for dominance instead of blending harmoniously . i think the problem here is that tripple is a big , expressinve beer . with exit 4 the subtle flavors are masked behind a second layer of bold expressiveness . i love the brewery for pushing the envelope and i look forward to buying the next release in the series . with innovation like this , flying fish is sure to hit a huge winner sooner than later .

this one sure looks like an ipa , pouring a nice copper color with a huge head that leaves nice sheets of sticky lacing on the side of the glass .  the mouthfeel is slightly creamy and very enjoyable . this drinks nicely . there is a lot going for this though , the mouthfeel in particular .

serving type - 22oz bottle appearance - very dark tan , black , great 3 inch thick creamy head smell - coffee , cocoa , mocha , hops , chocolate , malts , barley , smells amazing taste - as the smell prepaired me , very strong mocha coffee taste .  it was smooth and had a decent mouthfeel to it , with some nice malt flavor .
smell is excellent and unique . predominate smell i get is apricot .  mouth feel is completely crisp , refreshing , and clean .

heady ginger smell , nice . t : heavy ginger and sweet malt , quite medicinal .  the same color , mouthfeel , and drinkability were there , just the hopiness , aroma , and flavor , as well as most of the bitterness seemed to have blown away .
fruity and floral , very nice . t - slight malt at first taste , but the bitterness of the hops kicks in and lingers .  mouthfeel : lightly carbonated and creamy .

s : very complex and aromatic , dark fruits , like figs and raisins , some dark sugar is there as well , with a bit of port wine and grapes . t : taste is of a medicinal , dark fruity brew . very complex , though the flavour did n't really come through until the beer was at about 60 degrees , so serve this one a little warmer than usual .  hard to rate , as i appreciate that it is flavorful , but do n't like said flavors ... medium-light bodied , creamy , and well carbonated .

bottle acquired through recent secret santa swap w/ alohac pours absolutely beautiful brown tinged amber . fluffy , long lived , tan head with loads of lacing throughout .  mouthfeel : nicely carbonated and good level of thickness - probably the best part of this beer .

short 's nailed this one . spicy tomatoes , peppercorns , alcohol , tabasco , peppers .  mouthfeel was nice - weizenbock like . bananas , black beans , chile peppers and/or pepper jack cheese with some creamyness amidst the carbonation . interesting , no doubt , and worth seeking out if you want something really different .
burnished cherry color , fairly translucent , with a good 2 cm of vanilla colored head resting atop .  medium mouthfeel .

copious carbonation visible throughout . head is a dense , small-celled foam that swarms out of the pour vigorously , and stays for ages , fading to a mottled cap .  mouthfeel : medium bodied beer . very short aftertaste with his beer .

black raspberry desert chocolate . slightly smokey and tart in the back . vanilla , fudge , and chocolate . d : described as an `` experimental '' beer , this one is definitely unique . worth a try as i 've never experienced a prominent chocolate raspberry taste in my imperial stouts before and i think i like it !  the mouthfeel was good , but the drinkability hass to be chopped down due to the smell and the taste of this beer .

medium amount of carbonation s : i really enjoyed the burnt caramel smell that comes from the roasted malts . there is some maltiness , smokiness , and some slight sweetness in the aroma .  mouthfeel is nice and full and slippery without any carbonation .

the haze really detracted from the appearance for me ... ... but it made up for the look with the smell . i honestly smelled this for a few minutes before tasting . the smell was very citrus like , with lots of malt and hop spice .  m : super-smooth , eminently drinkable . lighter body , but crisp/clean finishing .

deep mahogany in colour , crystal clear when held up to the light . the head poured thick & white then retreated to a light surface covering , still maintaining the lace on the glass .  m/d : light and smooth feel on the mouth , drinkable but not something i will ever get again .

very attractive layered orange and brown color with creamy head remnants and a spicy , fruity , malty nose .  palate : very enjoyable . great , smooth , and light on the throat . it would be stellar with cheese .

there is the overpowering scent of nutmeg , cinnamon and some other christmas seasonings . the taste is about what you would expect from the smell . the cinnamon and the nutmeg dominate so much that it almost fails to taste like a beer .  the mouthfeel is medium and creamy .

the aroma is jam packed full of rich bourbon right up front . hints of chocolate and licorice in the background with dark fruits . the pallet has a nice chocolate flavor to it with some vanilla notes . overall a nice treat here .  mouthfeel is actually pretty nice , medium body and carbonation with a creamy quality .

the smell was excellent . i happen to love maple ( though i confess it is n't something i usually have in my beer ) , and the rich malty aroma of nutty maple notes was divine . ah , well this is a toughie for me because i 'm sure that this is the perfect beer for my girlfriends who are n't so crazy about things that resemble hops , barley , malt ... or hmmm.. beer .  mouthfeel is fine for the style .

a : thick and black , dark almond head ( more like a thin disk of residual bubbles ) s : strong note of alcohol , bitter dark chocolate , coffee m : very alcoholic feel ; initial taste of a dark stout followed by the heat of a liquor akin to scotch .  aside from the taste , mouthfeel is actually pleasant on the palate . good medium body and carbonation is about right on the tongue .

anywho , nice nose . love the nose . really nice citrusy hops with just a touch of wheaty sourness in there , but barely any . just a nice fresh smell . the beer has quite a bit of flavor for only 4.8 % abv .  mouthfeel is good .

aroma is highlight of the beer , a rich , unique blend of dark fruit , bourbon , chocolate syrup and light roast . one of the better heavy seas treatments and they 've somehow managed to salvage a base beer i typically deplore with a passion .  the mouthfeel is fine . it is a low/medium bodied beer with good carbonation .

a gorgeous beer , this pours a rich , hazed , honey amber with a killer head of eggshell puff that forms stiff rocky peaks and deposits thick clumps of lace .  the mouthfeel is surprisingly creamy and not too heavy . the drinkablity is pretty low , not from the booze , but extreme bitterness , which overwhelms the decent , but not exceptional malt .

a very attractive beer . powerful aroma . moist , sweet raisins at the forefront , with bitter chocolate , roasted malt , soy sauce and sweet sherry behind .  feels slick , not very carbonated , and heavy . alcohol warming is powerfully strong . lacks balance and drinkability .

aromatic and hoppy from the different types of hops used - there is some fruit and alot of pine . this is pure heaven in a glass from the aroma to the taste and finish everything is enjoyable . the abv is not to high but you can still a get decent buzz but drinking a few .  wine like alcohol warmth , and a vinous texture , i rather like this feel and good carbonation .
a - a lovely copper with startling clarity , it truly poured beautifully .  mouthfeel is medium , well carbed , nice on all fronts but where it needs to be . big failure , in my opinion .
fruity nose ( orange and berry ) hides wisps of wheat and hops . different is good here .  m- nice carbonation while retaining a good smoothness .

pours a deep , deep garnet , with a big , three finger tan head .  the mouth is thick and malty . as far as drinkability , i have to say that i would be really happy to have one of these if i was alive 4000 years ago but for now i 'm going to have to go for something else .

hard to imagine the being sweeter , loaded with caramel , chocolate , toffee , brown sugar , molasses , prune , fig , plum , cherry and apricot fruit , orange marmalade , bubblegum , candied nuts , on the hops side has pine and flowers , nothing too biting . in spite of this theres more room for more focused clove , ginger and pepper spice , quinine and earth . this forestalls the eventual onslaught of caramel , toffee , molasses , maple syrup , chocolate and so on , the orange to lemon citrus retains that syrupy and candied character . more yeastiness here with that bubblegum to banana touch . plum , fig , date , cherry , apricot , peach flavors , nice mix of darker and lighter fruits . booziness elevates as it warms , more rum notes and feels like it goes to your head faster . one glass is really all you need .  the carbonation feels pretty crisp .

overwhelmingly the finest ipa i 've ever sniffed . perfect . m - very good . nice carbonation and appropriate chewiness without being syrupy .  the mouthfeel is good , but obviously does not improve the flavor !
aroma is fantastic , reminiscent of triple sec and cognac . an intriguing failure of a beer .  mouthfeel is crisp and a little sizzly . refreshingly light bodied and clean .
poured from short bottle into chimay chalice huge , long lasting head with large bubbles over a golden brown color . perfect dubbel look .  a little sticky and a very bitter aftertaste .

stalagtites of drippy lace . fantastic barrel aroma , soaked in bourbon and sun-dried , retaining it 's oaky complexity . mouthfeel is smooth and rich , alcohol really only detracts from the taste slightly .  light and creamy mouth feel with obviously knocked down carbonation .
impressive looking beer .  ) and is a deep rich molasses s : once again , may have been too cold for phenols to waft up t : slightly sweet really tasty m : nice and cold d : pour me another
delightful smell . the taste , not so much .  the mouthfeel is the pinnacle of this brew . full-bodied with a dry crisp feel .

aroma : an amazing , complex aroma which far exceeds any other pils aroma i have smelled . lemony , peppery , summery , yeasty and malty all zipping around my nose . taste : does n't live up to the aroma but is n't bad .  m : thick , chewy..medium carb .

brown bottle , there 's a spot for a bottling number on the back label but it 's blank , poured into a pilsner glass . appearance : pours a crystal clear golden yellow , lots of carbonation bubbles rising inside . probably a good one to bring to a party , as it looks similar to the macros , but tastes much better .  mouthfeel is fine and not heavy .
two fingers of thick , creamy baige head with great retention and tons of lacing .  mouthfeel : good .

s- deep and floral , huge plum notes , banana , indistinct sweetness . the smell was great but the taste just didnt deliver .  pours a cloudy , almost 'chunky ' looking way -- looks a bit similar to an apple cider ( non alcoholic kind ) . caramelly sweet too . vanilla . taste is what kind of throws me - again , both the oak ( taste of whisky barrel ) and smokiness are there . i like both of those favors in my beers , but combined , my jury is still out : like they are competing for my affection . alcohol is quite present too , which seems to go well with the aforementioned whisky oak . a lot going on in this brew .
looks the part . `` glugged '' into my tulip glass and created a nice tight brown head that leaves lots of lace as i drink .  m - crisp and refreshing o - overall pretty meh .
big , meaty chunks of yeast floating around in the ebony liquid . has a giant , thick head the color of chocolate milk .  m - pretty good .

a : the beer is a deep dark brown color , with a large brown head that fades slowly and leaves a thick lace on the glass .  mouth is medium bodied , but with some good tingly action on the back of the tongue , so also good .

the aroma is decidedly tart and funky , with some citrusy hops . complex and enticing . the flavor is dry and yeasty , with some interesting phenolics bordering on burnt rubber .  m : lovely long bitter aftertaste .

a fragrent nose brings about thoughts of raspberry chewy candy and a bit of candied malt . enters the mouth with a long creamy tart feel . notes of crisp apples , fresh raspberries , and even end a nice mellow malty sweetness is faint on the end of the palate . i speak a lot of the sour and tartness of this beer but it is not to harsh but well balanced with a touch of woodsy malt sweetness . enjoyable for the style but drinkability says i still need to share the bottle with a friend .  m- pretty good body , minimal carbonation but works for the beer .

pours a huge head with crazy retention that wo n't leave the glass .  mouth feel is more medium bodied than the wheats i 'm used to , a nice change and the full blast carbonation leaves one a happy advocate overall it is lacking smell , good in flavor , great in feel .
pours deep brown with a nice creamy head of foam .  medium mouthfeel .

aroma packs in big notes of freshly-brewed dark coffee . nutty caramel notes and an earthy hop presence are in the mix as well . surprisingly , this beer did not overwhelm me with coffee , but despite the excellent balance the nose is still dominated by the bean . overall , i was expecting a bit more from this highly-touted coffee stout .  m : medium bodied with a medium carbonation .
pours a nice amber with 2 fingers of head . gorgeous lacing also like nothing i 've ever seen . a solid 5 for appearance .  carbonation done very well .
body is somewhat lighter expected while pouring , but looks black in the glass s : oak and coffee , come sweet roasted malt . t : slight sweetness .  carbonation was crisp for a medium body .

appearance : clean , clear golden body . very nice looking .  i have the mom version the head was initially strong , though sudsy and it fell quickly . carbonation is plentiful from the surface of the brew come hop aromas -- minty and herbal -- and coriander . it does n't smell as though an authentic yeast was used , which fits my preconceived notions for rogue 's methods the flavor confirms my american yeast suspicions . light fruity flavors , strong hop contributions , though little spice .
just unbelievable . on the palate the beer is very good , but does n't blow my socks off . very nice beer from stone brewing .  mouthfeel is light body , medium carbonation . fairly nice .
aroma is lots of banana and lemon , very nice and assertive .  there 's big citrus/grapefruit hops , but then a nasty onion/vegetable taste . mouthfeel is fine .
i hate it when that happens- it looks good , smells good , and then does n't taste nearly as good .  mouth is no complaints , it 's low-medium body with relatively high carbonation .

pours black with virtually no light around the edges . towering cap of light brown foam that grew on the pour like one of those ash-growing snake things from a fireworks stand . retention is great , as is the lacing .  the mouthfeel is good - smooth with a right amount of carbonation .

a giant , rocky , off-white head explodes out of the bottle , leaving strata-like rings on the glass as it settles , which is a good amount of time .  mouthfeel : medium-plus body . medium carbonation . some oily viscosity to the mouthfeel .

this one pours a dark muddy brown that shows some ruby highlights when held to light . the beer is topped by a nice frothy khaki head that lasts and leaves beautiful lacing .  m- mouthfeel is nice . medium body with a good amount of carbonation .

aroma is very hoppy . mainly floral hops . taste was not as bitter and flavorful as i was expecting , based on the smell . the floral hops and honey are present as well as some citrus fruits . overall , i was a lot more impressed by the smell of this beer as compared to the taste .  the mouth is smooth and light .
nose : a pleasant light piny hop aroma . a very inoffensive ipa .  m - nice light feel with a crisp finish , accentuated with a alcohol warmth .

just plainly delicious as hell . goddamn , what a insanely alluring nose . on the palate , the dark grains come to the fore , with a rich roasted character , leavening to a light burnt cacao husk note .  m - tongue ripping bitterness . medium to full body and tingly carbonation to go with it . good .
pours a chill hazed golen amber with a very impressive white head that melts to a very thick lacing .  mouthfeel -pretty good . foamy , not spritzy . nice and full , for a lager .
looks like a great beer . a golden/amber colour with a foamy , thick off-white head that sticks to the side of the glass .  m : creamy to a crisp finish with a good carbonation throughout .
this smelled like the kitchen while my mom bakes banana bread .  m : dark beers always feel good in the mouth . this one isnt super smooth , but the feel is good .
s : lots of bacterial funk , acid , and dark fruit , very fragrant and pungent .  m : a nice , medium body .

it smells great t-comes in with grassy belgian malts and then belgian sugars that are fairly boozy and have a bitterness to them . i 'm not getting too many good hops in this .  m : lots of carbonation , but a pretty smooth medium body nonetheless .

an immense hop punch to the nose . extremely fresh , bitter hops practically leap out of the glass . further in i get notes of orange and citrus , wrapped into a pleasing sweet malty undercurrent . superb nose . t. alas , after such a superlative smell , how could the taste hold up ? it 's a fantastic smelling , `` lite '' double ipa that is easy to put down .  2.5 t & m : mouthfeel is fairly viscous and silky .

appearance this one poured a beautiful , hazy orange in color with a monster head that i had to control at the pour . it came down pitting , leaving a whitish film all along the inside of my glass .  the mouthfeel was sticky and thick . there was tight and crisp carbonation that was nice .

poured from a 750ml ( purchased at uncork it ! on grand ) into a pint -- the wheat beer glasses were all dirty , and it 's been a long week ... pours a gorgeous cloudy golden color with a nice foamy head ; it looks the way witte ought to look .  m : silky smooth feel . i like the finish . smoothed out my palate .

poured into a rapscallion glass , formed a 3/4 '' dark brown head over the opaque dark brown/black brew . head is n't going anywhere fast , with lots of heavy lacing , nice for the abv .  - well carbonated , dries the mouth a bit . nice smooth body , probably this beers highlight is the mouthfeel .

i had this beer poured from a bottle into a pint glass ... a : the beer pours a darker color than golden , with a small white head and okay lacing ... s : the smell is very strongly grapefruited ... t : wow , a very potent hop flavor . the bitterness is actually quite light ... m : crisp , pretty light , and slightly dryish ... d : a really nice beer .  good medium body with great carbonation .

nose was wood the wonderful blending of currant . an herbal note of something meaty in the nose . funk like that of brie cheese skin and a bloody fruit . there was some mineral wood interaction with the fruit that gives it a food palatable quality , but it was quite subtle . overall i would only have this if you 're eating some sort of exquisitely cooked fish .  m : a bit chewy for me albeit nicely carbonated .

a nearly perfect appearance for a pilsener , with a completely transparent orange-yellow body with a thick white head .  m : fizzy carbonation that smooths out a little into the sip and works well with the body of the beer .
a beauty of a glass to behold ! ok , the smell absolutely is void and null with a fairly non-existent roasty malt and thats it !  pretty slick mouthfeel .

it had a very pleasing scent , nice and clean with a great malt/hop balance , and kind of reminded me of a fruit and nut chocolate bar .  m : fuller side of medium-bodied with moderate carbonation that tickles the tongue and throat . this aspect of the beer is really nice .
aroma is big citrus , sweet fruit , tropical and juicy .  thick body is very good . it 's just passable for now .
bottle courtesy of plucier : poured extremely cloudy whitish/yellow color ale with a nice small pure white foamy head with good retention .  m- good carbonation and substantial body , not bad here .
s : the bouquet is quite vibrant , with grapefruit and pineapple jumping out of the glass .  it has a very soft mouthfeel , a little like soda to be honest and you can barely notice the alcohol .
smell is amazing ! nice and sweet and very hoppy . very appealing and aromatic . a very good blonde .  mouthfeel : nicely carbonated , and nice and creamy . feels good on the tongue .
see-thru burnt orange body with a huge frothy head . excellent retention and plentiful lacing .  m - medium bodied with some soft carbonation .
d- a decent ipa but i prefer dc 's stout and american pale ale to this offering .  good carbonation .
smells of roasted malts , cherries , nuts . tastes of cherry , nuts , roasted grains , sugary syrup .  mouthfeel : light-bodied but not watery . it had a nice feel to it .
the smell was everything you would expect from a beer as hoppy as this . the smell of hop oil was big .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with moderate carbonation .

pours a murky , dark dark brown colour , only a sliver of colour really visible . head is stunning : beige , dense , small bubbles that wobbles on top but retains , with a beautiful , vibrant cascade when poured . lace is clingy and thick , like coffee foam . that 's a stunning beer .  feel is pretty smooth , nothing weird here .
the nose was definitely black currant . fully authentic , interesting and inviting . a lindemans trademark smell .  m : dry and crisp but smooth as butter .

a - no pop when i pull the cork , pours a lifeless , soul sucking , pitch black , with a big oily slick on top , no head s - big nose of chocolate , coffee , vanilla , carmel sweetness , booze , smells pretty damn good t - taste is nowhere near as robust as the aroma , huge coffee flavour , basic sweetness , booze , gigantic roasted coffee finish m - no carbonation , heavy mouthfeel , dry finish , big boozy warmth d - another half assed effort from mikkeller no carbonation , ridiculous , over the top coffee flavour , and massive booziness ( even after cellaring for close to 2 years , best before is aug 2011 ) .  m- decent carbonation , light and airy .

the most beautiful foamy head i 've ever seen , and it lasts forever in the duvel glass , sitting atop a gold so intense it almost glows .  but it does n't make me puke ( and it tastes better than bmc by a sconch ) mouthfeel is nice . kinda creamy mixed with crisp .
the smell is very pleasant , a combination of biscuit , pear , and pepper .  m : very fizzy , light on body , about right for the style .

its smell is its best characteristic -- floral hops , malty , a hint of wheat -- really beautiful . the taste is sweety & malty , as well as bitter .  fine mouthfeel , nothing objectionable , but it 's not a stand-out lager either .

scent was very pleasant with loads of dark roasted earthy malts and chocolate . very rich nose - with a touch of malted milk also . the head , lacework and scent of this beer were outstanding !  mouthfeel - good smoothness , a medium body on par with the style , crisply carbonated .
very powerful sweet aroma . overall : fantastic beer , will definitely get again .  m : creamy mouthfeel with prickly carbonation .

pours a dark golden ruby color with bright red edges and a two finger frothy light beige head . very good retention , only slowly fading into a lasting cap that coats the glass with streaks of soapy lacing .  m : tingly carbonation , medium body and refreshing enough .
s - oh my , one of the most delicious aromas i 've ever experienced . d - fantastic stout .  feel medium body , pleasant texture , some drying and bitterness in the finish .
huge head , very lasting w/big bubbles & good lacing .  smooth in the mouth with nice , crisp carbonation . nice feel , but flavor is not there .
a nice , interesting nose .  m : creamy and sticks to the mouth for awhile .

the pour is a nice blackout black color with a good looking two finger head on it that holds it 's retention and has excellent lacing . the heads color is a nice dark tan color .  smooth and refreshing , light to medium bodied with a slight tingling on the tongue .

it had a very beautiful aroma of dried fruit and alcohol . almost wine like to the nose , and was enjoyed by everyone i offered it to .  mouthfeel- medium mouthfeel ( for the style ) . carbonation level was perfect for bringing out the bittering hops .

quite close to black with a fine textured tan head . i love the way the beer horizon ( the separation between the beer and the head ) looks . it stayed that way throughout the beer .  m/d : a medium body with good carbonation .

it is overpoweringly fruity and has an amazing aroma . it pours a cloudy light rose pink with a huge head.you are overwhelmed by the raspberry nose .  mouthfeel is medium-light bodied , a nice creaminess to the carbonation .

smell is very sugary with a fruit and spice scent of apple butter . apple , cinnamon , clove , raisin , grape , figs , black pepper and sweet prunes are all in here . taste is drier than expected sweet but not very . good spice flavor that builds as you sip . the flavor just is n't anywhere as complex as the smell . mouthfeel is good nice drinkable belgian here that is worth a try , only problem is that there are lots better around .  but , also an odd smell kind of like salami . this must be some nasty phenol created by the yeast . a bad yeast flavor here and a lot of it . i usually love unibroue brews for that complex yeasty quality but for some reason this one tastes a little off . that lunchmeat aroma and now this bad oily yeasty taste make this beer almost undrinkable . i doubt it considering it 's called edition 2004 , we 're in 2005 , and it 's 10.5 abv .

4.5 s : smells delicious ! smells like a smoked pig wrapped in bacon . the smoke covers it up like it covers up everything else . very nice . 4.0 m : heavier medium body .  m & d : the texture is soothingly carbonated , quite good for a fruit beer , while the body is consistently light against the richly sweet flavour . the downside of using lichee for brewing is that an aftertaste can turn quite `` simplistically acidic '' , but this beer shows a decent balance in the end . compared with the other lichee beer produced by another taiwanese micro-brewery ( takau ) , this one comes a bit too rich in sweet lichee-juice at the expense of more complexity , yet the overall mouthfeel and a clean aftertaste makes up for it .

made a great appearance , poured a classic beer golden with a very large creamy foamy white head with a lot of sticking .  very syrupy and flavors linger on the palate . very unique . strongest beer had to date .

bottle enjoy before month notched-sep served in a pint glass the beer poured a crystal clear , deep , orangey-amber color . a two-plus finger tall crop of light beige froth topped the liquid . the head had excellent lasting power and it deposited a thick , drippy blanket of lacing along the top half of the glass .  velvety . good amount of carbonation .
excellent ! overall : amazing aroma , very complex and inviting , but i think it set me up for a super complex flavor profile that was n't there .  mouthfeel is good , soft and tingly .

small amount of lace around the edges s : roasted coffee and dark chocolate hit the nose first . very sweet smelling , as well as the presence of alcohol t : initially it was more bitter then i expected from the aroma .  m - good carbonation and it finishes clean . good light to medium mouthfeel .

smells great ! you go the same whitepepper honey spice wheatishness of duvel only with a wonderfully crisp , weedy background . tastes very nearly as good as it smells . big nodes of weeds , pollen , and wild flowers backing up a spicy , crisp , lightly lemony belgian pale .  mouthfeel is light with a good spike of carbonation .

appearance : poured with a huge fluffy white head that lasted forever . the beer is a clear golden color with a few bubbles rising , but the head sticks around anyway . there is a whole bunch of lacing left on the glass after the head falls .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied . fair carbonation .

a : pours a deep dark brown that is almost black in appearance .  first off , i can tell that this one is slightly skunked , but i ca n't really blame the brewer for this one as i am also able to pull out some nice mellow caramel malts and a touch of biscuity-bready goodness as well . nice mellow malts , not too sweet , but the hops come through for a bit too much bite from what i look for and love about english pales . the hops come on a little too strong and linger too long , not really allowing me the chance to savour the mellow malts as much as i would like . there is a slight sweetness about it that reminds me of fresh apples although not the biting green apple off taste . this is different , and nice , but not my first choice for an english pale .

the smell starts off with honey sweetness and pine resin which follows into vanilla aromas from the oak and the citrus aspect of the hops . some alcohol is present but it is n't overbearing . its like smelling a liquified custard of vanilla and orange zest .  mouthfeel is this beers strongest point as it is so watery it does n't feel harsh or overly alcoholic .

lots of sediment floating around on this one smell - this smells sweet and rich , brown sugar , plums , raisins , red wine , grapes taste - feels like i 'm drinking red wine instead of a belgian brown .  m - pretty thick , smooth and a bit refreshing .

insanely tart notes of lemon zest , white grape rinds , and dry oak barrels . so incredibly tart ; for me , the only comparable wild ale is batch 2 beatification ( in terms of sheer sourness ) . fantastic beer .  m- really good carbonation , low abv and the nearly great sweet/tart balance make it actually react quite nicely with the mouth .
pours with a giant , foamy , frothy , fluffy , white head and lots of lace . color is a clear yellow and some tiny bubble trails .  medium mouthfeel .
mouthfeel- nice carbonation , refreshing drinkability- overall , the taste did n't really live up to the smell and appearance .  meidum bodied and relatively smooth .
the beer pours out a very dark brown that is almost opaque expect for the edges .  m : light-bodied , crisp , very clean , refreshing .
this beer pours a cloudy , browning apricot with a massive 4 inch , creamy head that leaves soap like lacing down the entirety of the glass .  m : very viscous , pretty smooth .
s : strong enticing smell of toffee , vanilla and butterscotch . t : much the same as the smell .  mouthfeel good . creamy and subtle carbonation . cant complain about this .

smell is extremely fruity , primarily peaches with some apples , oranges , and lemons coming through as well . this is a pretty interesting and unique beer for the style . a pleasant surprise .  medium bodied and decent carbonation .

dark fruits and double fudge with a wisp of grass ... .nice ; profile is a bit of a letdown from the aroma . a very good approximation of a london stout although a tad thin for an oatmeal stout , it is very decent .  strong carbonation . m. very bitter and the carbonation is clean and tart .
the smell is wonderful . tannin , grapes , apples , apple peels , raisins , caramel , touch of cocoa , and a hint of alcohol .  feel is good - light , crisp , medium bodied .

poured into my big family guy mug and was greeted with one of the best looking heads i 've ever seen in that mug . perfect ruddy brown with a hint of mbver red , just like a bock should . nice and opaque too , hard to see any bubbles in there .  m : creamy and nice . decent carbonation keeps it from sticking to you .
deep brown pour with a gigantic , rocky , tan head .  good mouthfeel , crisp , medium body , good carbonation which is refreshing for a warm weather beer .

aroma is tremendous . dark , rich , malty sugars . drinkability is horrid , just alcohol and thickness . cloying . i hope to get to review a better bottle at some point , as i can tell the flavors are there , but this bottle was not something i enjoyed .  low carbonation and good mouthfeel .

impressive looking ale..bright clear golden yellow , with a rich , thick , creamy head and literally walls of lacing .  aroma : hops . the crystal hops dominate the aroma . the malt is there , but overpowered by hops . but i do n't taste the balance that an esb should have . the hops weigh far more than the malt in this beer . notes : this tasted like a very good ipa , but did not have the balance i was expecting , for an esb . a great beer , but did n't fit the style as well as i would have liked .

this beer has probably the best head i 've ever seen on a saison . saison de lente pours a massive 3 finger white head that has almost a pancake batter like consistency . the head retention is fantastic . the lacing is just magical . a thick french lacing accompanies the glass even when then the glass is empty .  starts off clean and finishes with metallic hops m : silky smooth , good carbonation d : why ?

a : golden , almost apricot in appearance with about a 2 inch head and tons of carbonation . s : i detected victory 's hop profile a mile away ! yeasty , with citrus notes .  m - good mouthfeel . a little heavier thanks to the lack of filtration .
a : a clear and deep golden-coloured liquid , with a nice-looking white head that leaves a nice ring of retention . beautiful .  light to medium bodied , with a very smooth mouthfeel .

pour is a burnt gold or darkish amber with a foamy white head , but the aroma takes over immediately . smell reminds of an american barley wine . very rich and malty with tons of hops , it could pass for sn 's bigfoot .  mouthfeel is medium bodied and crisp . good carbonation , but the overall trainwreck of flavor in the brew makes this one hard to take down .
it poured the dark copper of an old penny with a massive creamy tan head .  m - light-medium body with plenty of carbonation .

a : very good looking brew - copper/red clear body with white head .  mouthfeel is as good as you would expect with an aerator . all in all , you can drink it for the mouthfeel but do n't drink it for the taste .
