very enjoyable . taste is a little harsh , the sweetness takes a vegetable turn .  mouthfeel is good - medium-bodied , good carbonation , smooth .
thanks to mistakebythelake for this growl pour apperance- golden orange with a good amount of white head . a gorgeous beer !  m- very little carbonation . very full syrupy body .
two fingers of thick creamy head with good retention and plenty of lacing .  long , earthy , dry finish . interesting , somewhat unusual brew .

this is hands down the most beautiful looking beer i have ever seen . the head retention is pretty amazing and the lacing extensive .  mouthfeel is nice , good carbonation , but seriously , ca n't get over that ham finish .
s - a lot going on but still well balanced . smells of citrus ( maybe orange ) and pine , along with some winter `` spices .  m : mouth feel is pretty good .

s : a pretty complex smell , though coffee beans tend to be the dominant auroma . it 's nicely accented by a faint hint of sweet chocolate . t : there 's a real bright fruitiness that i do n't really pick up on in the scent that compliments ( but not well ) the coffee flavor that is n't so much roasted anymore as it is just kind of bitter . both are underwhelming to say the least , but this taste is n't as bad as it is disappointing .  mouthfeel is smooth , for sure , with mellowed out carbonation and a surprising absence of slickness , considering the alcohol .

dark roasted malts , espresso , bitter chocolate , vanilla bean , and some black currant . very one dimensional with little complexity . you mainly get a big slap in the face of dark roasted malt , with some bitter chocolate , and coffee in the finish .  nice carbonation and creamy mouthful .

smells slightly woody followed by ripe fruit , but relatively lean . this beer has a great aroma , and a few promising notes , but overall disappoints .  mouthfeel is about right for style , perhaps a touch undercarbed , but all else is acceptable , though it showcases a flavor profile best left behind the curtain .

pours with a fat thumb head , with decent stout lacing ... smell is amazing , lots of sweet bourbon and chocolate plum ... lots of bourbon upfront but it really is remarkable how enjoyable it is , despite the fact that its like sipping straight bourbon ... this beer would age soooo beautifully ! a wonderful beer that i was honored to have tried at a really fun event , but that open bar kicked my butt in the end ! !  m - a fairly heavy mouthfeel with all the sweetness .

a : beautiful , clear , dark ruby body under a majestic two-finger head of creamy , sticky tan foam . tons of lace . truly spectacular . s : a little underpowered - light acetic sting , some sweet fruit , and a bit of husky malt .  creamy mouthfeel with the addition of oatmeal in the mix .
aroma is excellent ; spicy and piny .  it 's very creamy and goes down easy . i 'm really disappointed with this .
golden yellow with a full white head that melts to a quarter inch covering of sticky lacing .  m : medium-high carbonation fits the style nicely .

s : chocolaty , coffee , roasted malt , maybe some caramel tones . the appearance and smell had me so excited for the taste , only to be let down by a watery drink .  syrupu sweetness , not cloying , with hop dryness in the blend . this is what imperial pilsner is supposed to be ? what happened to the pilsner part ?

s-really smells quite like a full bore ipa .  the tastes match the smell for sure , but this thing is way too sweet , it tastes like a thick maple soda . extremely malty , alcohol definitely makes itself known .

honestly one of the most impressive looking ipa 's i 've encountered .  light-medium caramel malt sweetness up front , continued in the middle with a hint of earthy hop bitterness , finishing with a more of the same . medium mouthfeel .

poured a hazy golden yellow with a three finger white head that remained throughout the glass and even continued to grow if left to sit for long . insane ! maintained phenomenal lacing throughout the glass . first off , the appearance on this one was ridiculous for the style .  as i drink more my palate adjusts but it does n't ever really get over the off flavors m - pretty thick , not too carbonated , nice mouth coating qualities d - burnt coffee does not go down very well , plust the thickness of the beer limits my ability to quaff this completely i like coffee , i like stouts , and i like a lot of coffee stouts ( new glarus and founders breakfast stout for instance ) .
a - dark maroon with lots of capuccino colored head .  mouthfeel is medium , clean with a bitter hop aftertaste .
pours a beautiful light honey color . have n't seen a pale lager with such nice color .  good carbonation .

smell : the smell really is impressive . heavy heavy coffee . good malt to support , but great coffee aromas . taste : feels like i 'm enjoying a nice cup of coffee fresh out of the percolator after waking up in a tent .  it has good texture .

quite surprising ... not because it 's a great beer from dogfish head ( that 's certainly not surprising ) , but because i have never actually enjoyed a pumpkin ale . seriously ever . appearance & gt ; what a beauty . colour reads from dark honey to a pumpkin orange glow . extremely lively .  the aftertaste lingers nicely , and the mouthfeel is firm . full bodied and smooth , but lacking an extra punch .
a - dark as night with amber hue creeping in with the light . thick head that lasts the entire time drinking it slowly and leaving very nice lacing .  m - medium bodied with good carbonation .
very interesting . smells sweet but different .  the feel of this beer is it 's crutch very creamy and boisterous keeps me tasting over and over .

smell : the aroma is full of brandy . nice red grape , molasses , caramel , smooth malt notes .  ) the body is a hefty medium , bordering on the truly heavy , with a light moderate carbonation and a fairly chewy feel . harsh .
mesmerizing , really .  really nice body all around ... overall - i would really enjoy this beer if it were n't for the bubblegum flavor , it 's really off putting and not very pleasant .

well , the label says brewed with peaches and pecans and you get tons of peach on the nose . and it 's a real peach smell too , not the kind in gummy candy .  m : solid mouthfeel , carbonation is pretty much spot on .
great `` belgian '' lacing & very good head retention smell : sourness & then woody , lactic notes .  light body with good carbonation .

pumpkin pie spice is felt throughout and makes it absolutely wonderful . absolutely amazing . going into this , i knew that southern tier made some great beers . i had no idea this would be one of their best !  still for such a big beer it had a great body , just not sure if i would want more , until it got about 5 years on it .

12 oz bottle , unreadable stamping on cap , poured into a flute . a : poured a nice tan one fingered head . blackness with dark red shading on its edges , great lacing appears .  mouthfeel - it does have a pleasant rich/buttery mouthfeel .
very good . taste : like the smell , there 's lots of clove and sweet malt .  mouthfeel is thick and smooth , no watery sensation at all .

2010 bottle had a ton of suspended sediment in a burnt orange body . wow , aroma is the big winner here . pumpkin pie with crust as it warms ; some clove came thru as well , and even somewhat herbal . pretty authentic pumpkin flavor - vegetable/squash quality , and good amount of spices , incl cinnamon , nutmeg , and clove - but not overpowering . decent volume of malty sweetness / richness ... touch of campfire as it warms . outstanding drinkability - this is the most aromatic and flavorful pumpkin ale you can buy at this level of abv .  the body is nice and thick , with a flavorful malt profile : sweet medium caramel malts with a bit of roast character . hops , by the way , are almost nonexistent , which would n't be bad if not for the oxidation , which makes the faint floral flavor seem dull . overall not bad , but has the same type of oxidized or maybe just oversparged flavor common to other corporate breweries like gordon-biersch .

smell- nice pungent scent of pine hops amidst lots of powdered sugar .  the mouthfeel is it 's only saving grace . it 's a light bodied beer and is very drinkable , although i know this will be my last one .

when you smell this beer , you know this is a big one . lots of power and lots of liquor , much like rum with some fruity notes to me . it felt like port or a fortified wine in my mouth and the taste was rather like a really , really nice rum .  nice lively mouthfeel .
pours a fascinating brownish black with little foam . very appealing to the eyes .  medium body , good crispness .

this may be the best smelling pilsener i 've ever experienced . lovely complex , floral hop aroma . pleasant light grained malt in the background . overall , a superior beer .  mouthfeel : light in body . very crisp throughout . clean aftertaste .
the smell of it was great . the taste was not as impressive , but i did enjoy the chewyness .  mouthfeel : light bodied beer . moderate carbonation .

a : almost totally opaque , thin tan head that generates late and dissipates quickly , not much lacing s : smells like a campfire is the best way to put it , some light hops and malt , but mostly that charcoal mesquite , wow t : again , the campfire , but a little more subdued , some chocolate notes in the middle , with a hop bitterness in the back that mixes with the rough , almost metallic charcoal character m : pretty thick , coats the entire mouth and stays with you for a while d : a true sipper , amazing for the style , but it 's so intense , i had a little trouble finishing the bottle , one would be enough for me for quite a while  m : full body with mild carbonation ; slightly clinging .

a brown/mohagany body held a creamy three fingers of head made of tiny nitrogen driven bubbles . strings of lace remained on the sides .  golden in color , slight haze ( nothing wrong with that ) , definite aromas of honey sweetness . lingering sweetness in the palate with a slight funk . interesting beer and something that one might only need to consume once .

s- it has a nice nutty character absent form most stouts i 've had . hazelnut and almonds combine with a bit of roasted malt and some coffee to make a nice aroma .  m : good thickness and carbonation .

a - this beer has an incredible appearance , murky dark brown with an awesome lasting tan head that leaves some foam and great lacing .  low carbination , medium body . smooth on the palate , the beer says nothing , if it does not say sour cherries .
smell- very fresh malts give a whiff of roast , toast , and even some plums .  good body and mouthfeel .

it 's a very appealing smell . taste : part belgian wit and part apple cider blended together . the smell is really good , but the taste is a bit disappointing in comparison . the good aromas in the smell do n't show up in the taste .  body is pleasantly creamy , almost akin to that of an esb or pub ale .
very good smell . t : roasted sweet caramel & malts .  m : perfectly fine . quite smooth , medium/full-bodied with a hint of ethanol .
a : the pour is deep deep burgundy with a really large thick creamy off-white head . the slow dissipation leaves lacings galore .  nice crisp carbonation to keep it refreshing .
aroma : lovely , substantial fruit aroma without overpowering the malt of the beer .  m = moderately carbonated . good .

a brilliant tan head rose quickly to three-fingers and lowered very slowly leaving brilliantly thick patchy lace on the glass .  pretty much just a tingly water . very smooth and somewhat refreshing beer .
it is good , but one at a time .  the mouthfeel is full and nicely carbonated yet still somewhat creamy .
richer . the sweetness comes through much more . i highly recommend storing one of these away to turn a very good experience into a great one .  appropriately light in body without being too thin .
i was much more impressed by the pour and visual of this beer than by taste or drinkability . nice puffy styrofoam cloud of a head .  m - nice average mouthfeel .
this beer is a very dark brown with a dense , light tan head that provides excellent lacing .  mouthfeel is spot on for the style , light and crisp and a bit dry .
smell is quite strong , a pine and citrus scent with a noticeable sweet honey or caramel malt aroma .  i liked the mouthfeel , smooth and gentle .

it had a great smoky aroma of smoked wood , smoked malts , olives , dark chocolate , roasted coffee beans , and just the slightest touch of caramel at the finish .  smooth with a creamy but dry finish . i walked away thinking that the `` smoked vanilla , coffee , and birch '' was meant to be flavor descriptors rather than actual ingrediants . all of these elemtns were way too weak to be appreciated for what other beers can do with them . call it a single , nix the mention of the adjuncts , and this beer would be alright .
the smell is outstanding , very malty and reminiscent of autumn .  m- medium body , pretty solid mouthfeel , nothing special but solid .

a : the body has a nice bright off orange/rich golden hue with a robust white colored head that sticks to the glass well .  m - good mouthfeel , and strong carbonation d - an okay beer , but a bit disapointing .

smell is the leader of the pack , amazing scent of coffee , cream , smoke . drinkability suffers from the mouthfeel since this is the only non style rating , but i really like this porter .  the palates leads with a thick , malty mouthfeel up front and a sticky , resiny bitterness in the back .
a - pours a dark , murky brown with ruby highlights .  m- the body is full . the carbonation is at a nice subdued level .

the smell was fantastic ! a hop bomb . nice hop finish lingered on my tongue . i 'm anxious to try the imperial version of this brew .  m & d : very good , sits well and fairly easy to drink once you get the first one down

it 's a good inviting smell .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied , with a soft prickly creaminess , along with some easy slickness in the body that helps that raw feeling finish go down . just a smidge of alcohol is felt but it is n't overly noticeable .

sn consistantly produces beers w/ amazing hop boutique aromas . t - flavor profile pretty much mimics the nose w/ the malts and biscuit holding the fort down so the trademark sn cascades can do what they do best . mf - creamy , medium body and goes down w/ a slick and oily feel d - balance , balance , balance . highly sessionable .  - 3.0/5.0 feel - coats the mouth well , with a bit of pepperly aftertaste .

overall the beer looks and smells fantastic . it falls way short on flavor and drinkibilty .  soft prickly carbonation does cleans the pallet , of this light to medium body beer with moderate astringency and warming alcohol .

the smell is really where this beer shined - a rich aroma of nicely roasted barley - coffee and chocolate predominated as well as a milky lactose aroma . this beer fell flat on the taste ( or maybe that 's just in comparison to the nose ) - it started off sweet , but never really delivered on all the flavors i had smelled . still , kudos for the nose . i probably wo n't be purchasing this again .  nice mouthfeel for a pale ale .

the second surly can i got from my man joe aka ineedabeerhere . the aroma is quite hoppy , even with all this time in the can . pineapple , grape , carrots ? you can also smell a bit of alcohol in the furious , but only after sniffing the juice . the taste continues with the depth of the aroma , and i 'm loving it . it could use a bit more sweetness to accentuate the fruity hops .  pleasantly carbonated on the palate , with a dry finish .

appearance - really dark with a very nice looking mocha/tan head . looks incredible .  crisp , clean mouthfeel with flavors of dry , pale malt . at first , i found myself wanting more flavor , a la boston lager , but the mouthfeel and resulting drinkability really brought things back up for me in the end .
smell is perfect - best smelling sour i 've ever had .  taste : muddled and uninspired mouthfeel : absolutely thin and lacking in every way imaginable .
pours a clear golden color with a thick , fluffy , off-white head .  mouthfeel is disappointing ; thin and watery , with too much carbonation for my taste .

smells nearly exactly like pumpkin pie . this was my first pumpkin beer , and it 's not a style i 'm particularly enamored with .  the body was disappointingly thin for such a big beer , allowing the unwelcome alcohol notes to really come through .
'' the appearance was awesome . huge head all the way down the glass .  it seemed to have very high carbonation .
pours clear deep amber body topped by mid-sized creamy beige head with excellent retention that sticks to the walls and never fades away .  mouthfeel - watery .
'' pours almost black with a generous amber head and fruity , hop-spicy nose .  md - thin and not much of a body to it .
a : black on top , fades to reddish/brown at the bottom when held up to the light . nice lacing . a real gem .  mouthfeel is entirely too thin and watery .

delicious smelling ! t- tart , slightly sweet with more ale grains in the taste . decent , but i was expecting more fruits in my mouth .  not much to say about natural ice other than that it is cheap . little taste that i could discern , but nothing abhorrent at that . maybe some sweetness , a bit more complex than some of its stablemates . of course , it is highly drinkable , which is the point . pressed for cash and desirous of a little buzz ? you could definitely do worse .
poured into an imperial pint glass , formed a 3/4 '' light brown head over the clear garnet brew . head lasts nicely , with ample foamy lacing .  thin to medium bodied with very little carbonation .
a sexy , blurred mahagony colour with patches of head . would leave small remnants of lacing .  2/5 m : thin and watery with medium carbonation .

poured to the expected golden orange with thick off-white head that stuck around for the whole glass , and left excellent lacing .  m. thin with no carbonation at all . d. i thought the flavors were interesting , but this beer was much too thin and flat for my taste .

aroma is predominately belgian funk and gambrinus honey malt . flavor is pilsen , honey , and belgian aromatic malt with just enough hop to balance . yeast flavor is a very nice blend of straight belgian and brett .  very pale straw yellow color , hazy but filtered look no aroma noted water like very light bodied taste and looks like water ... . however better than most would give credit to seeing how its bud .
aroma : pine and floral hops . big hop profile . overall , a decent brew , but nothing extraordinary .  m : medium bodied beer but it is a bit light on carbonation . feels dull and flat .
into a pint glass , it poured a transparent straw/gold ; heavily carbonated , two fingers of bright white , and great head retention and lacing .  feel is thin , dribbly and loose .
this has one of the best aromas of an ipa that i 've ever had . sticky , piney , resiny aroma . i find this to be a very drinkable ipa .  the mouthfeel is very thin .
slight visible carbonation , a very nice looking brew .  mouthfeel is watery and boring , with a decent carbonation level but not much else to write home about .

s : peaty , peaty , peaty . slight hint of oak back , but peat dominates the nose , entirely . t : first taste , blast of peat overwhelms the palate , nose , pores , everything .  the mouthfeel is one of worst i 've ever had with a saison .
the body is as dark as night ; it is absolutely impervious to any light .  tragically the mouthfeel is watery and the carbonation ( which others had noted ) , distracts from the overall experience .

smell : great aromas of licorice and chocolate . overall , the beer is a bit rough around the edges , perhaps from importation , but that is certainly part of its charm .  it was flat on the tongue and mouthfeel was very weak .

a nice blend is dominated by spices and finishes with a pumpkin quality . overall a great blend of scents . mostly spice flavor with only a minor pumpkin quality .  i am dissapionted in the carbination as it is nearly flat with a medium/light feel .

so dark you could hide a black sheep in it . cute labeling , special bottle , and usda organic slapped on it make it stick out yet it yields something akin to canadian made guinness .  appearance : dark amber color with a nice 1/2 '' off white head ... unfortunately this reminded me of a pop on the pour smell : pine , hops , citrus taste : kinda watery , slight citrus ( maybe cascade hops ) mouthfeel : thin drinkability : could do two in a night , but i 'd rather drink something that tastes better

overly sweet at times , but still nice . if it was n't for the mild astringent smell i 'd give it a 5 .  far too thin and light for a bock . carbonation was assertive , but the body just felt thin and watery .
black as night , half finger of light brown head with great retention . very good lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel - one of the most water beers i 've had .
pours a clear golden blonde with three fingers of fizzy rocky head , that drops slowly to a nice cap .  thin and tingly mouthfeel .

called the skellig irish red on the chalkboard , but confirmed with watch city that it is their shillelagh irish red . magnificent , bulbous cream of head that frankly amazes with its ocean of white and a knifes edge cut ; huge stick and lace . dark red hue with a dead quiet calm and plenty of crystal clarity .  although the mouthfeel is thin for a stout , the flavor is pretty good .

330 ml bottle poured into a tulip glass . appearance - the beer pours a hazy golden orange with three fingers of pillowy off-white head .  biggest disappointment was the mouthfeel which lacked any crispness/carbonation at all ; practically flat and way too light .
a : dark black , thick brown head that dissipates slowly .  it seemed really thin & watery , not offering up much complexity as i swished it about .

sweet banana like smell with a bit of spice . i really like this beer , but it 's pretty heavy and very robust and powerful .  mouthfeel : this beer is almost watery yet with a hint to tannins that leave my mouth dry and scratchy . the beer had a watery texture in my mouth and the flavors were not in balance with the nose . while it did have a light mouthfeel and i am used to drinking hoppy dry beers , this beer would have had an easy drinkabilty yet with its unbalanced flavors i had very little desire to do so .
when i pulled the cork out , a delightful smell hit me right away , but went away quickly .  the mouthfeel was flat and very dissapointing .
very attractive beer . massive sticky foamy eggshell colored head rises to 2 fingers and holds there forever .  the mouthfeel lacks more . and flat .

341ml bottle poured into pint glass feb4 2010 a reddish brown with loads of sediment being pushed around by a large amount of tiny bubbles . the head is massive and has great retention and leaves a fair bit of lace as it slowly falls .  above average taste for an adunct lager , but not great by any measure . this is definately better than budweiser , coors or miller , but not exactly to die for . foster 's price point is right about miller/bud level , but always slightly higher . it 's worth the extra coins if you 're on a budget . much more enjoyable than the run-of-the-mill macros .

really smells nice . the taste mimicks the nose ... .nice balance between the cloves and banana notes ... also some subtle but enjoyable caramel maltiness .  flavor : then , i drank some & everything went downhill . it was watery & disappointing .

pours a dark brown/black color with some dark ruby hues when held up to the light , excellent amount of head that fades at a good rate to leave some lacing .  palate is watery with that adjuncty grain flavor , but not too offensive . easy drinking .

poured into a standard snifter at about 55 degrees f , 1-inch head , light lacing , deep beautiful cloudy magenta .  m : this feels fairly thin ; the flavors fall quickly off the tongue , resulting in a watery finish .
poured into a goblet carefully to leave behind the yeast sediment . nice thin creamy head , that leaves great lacing all down the glass .  the body was very thin and the beer lacked substance .
a nice balanced nose with caramel malts , floral hops and a nice dose of sweetness coming from tropical fruits . the fruitiness keeps reminding me of pink bubblegum .  m : very thin and watery .

kudos to these guys for making such a fine looking beer . great head , elegant lace , interesting to look at .  coppery colored amber with a sudsy froth top that subsides to a foam slick , no lacing , body is very thin and under-carbonated . perhaps as an effect of my bottle not being quite as fresh as it ought to be , i am detecting absolutely none of the fruity notes commonly perceived by other ba members ... .and this really hurts my overall impression quite a bit .

poured out of a bottle to a beautiful dark color . really a beautiful beer .  has a malty aroma , enticing , maybe some wheat too ? fizzy palate , mallty taste , fruity , not very lingering . thirst-quenching .
the goosinator pours a nice red amber color with a big head that bubbles down to a 1/4 inch creamy smoothe head .  mouthfeel is thin .

a- pours an absolutely crystal clear light orange with a one finger white head .  very light bodied , an ok mouthfeel.. just way too watery and thin , not much for taste , just some lemon zest on the after taste .

above this is a lovely 2-finger head of dense light-brown foam that shows mediocre retention and nice lacing . great looking brown , and only the sub-par retention kept it from getting a perfect score .  i was again surprised to find a very thin mouth feel dominated by carbonation which seemed to accent the minimal hops to make them more pronounced .
great retention and globby lacing .  m - watery , light carbonation .
a : an impressive amount of slowly fading , creamy head sits atop a clear golden-straw colored beer . scattered lacing all around the glass .  not thick at all , but lacking carbonation .

pours a dark chestnut brown color that is completely opaque with a two finger frothy , pillowy yellowish beige head that has very good retention , only slowly fading into a lasting cap . sporadic spots of lacing left behind .  slightly watery body and bland carbonation .

reduces to a thin covering quickly with a handful of bubble trails enhancing the look of a beautiful fall season color .  a - medium to dark amber ; almost no head , but what little bubbling there was at the edge of the glass managed to leave a slight bit of lacing s - there was nearly no aroma , and what was there was nothing distinctive t - good malt/hop balance with pleasantly surprising bitter finish m - far too thin and too little carbonation in this sample ; a bit of a sticky finish d - though it will not be mistaken for a world-class brew , this one is easy to suck down since it is thin and flavorful ; without the sticky finish , it would score a half-tick higher

a : pours pretty much a pitch black in the glass , with a hint of mahogany translucence around the edges . the head is thick and cream-colored ; retention is outstanding , and it leaves nice lacing down the glass . truly a pleasure to see .  mouthfeel is thin i wish it had some body to it would make it much more palatable for me .

12oz brown bottle . frothy and creamy off white 1 '' head that holds for a while , eventually leading to some nice layers of lacing . very deep mahogany color with a shade of brown .  the palate is not unpleasant , with plenty of that molasses , clove , and dried fruit and some decent maltiness , but this beer is very light in body ( hence my unusually low `` mouthfeel '' score - i rarely dock or add points here unless there is significant deviation from stylistic expectations ) .

appearance : light yellow in color with a large soapy head that stays around the whole time . the head on this beer is remarkable and deserves recognition . at first the beer was fairly clear but later i swirled some yeast in and the beer became cloudy .  body is a nip thin . a bit too still , but more carbonation would have blasted through the empty body of the beer , making it even less desirable .

the nose of this beer is simply amazing . pure fresh cherries , almost like a top notch but soft lambic . some light caramel and hops could be smelled as well , but mostly fresh fresh soft cherries . light caramel tone , but just very clean and malty . the bottle is a little disapointing to be honest , but on tap this beer is simply amazing . fresh cherries and soft clean crisp malt .  the mouthfeel is unbalanced as if the carbonation and the liquid will not merge . for as much noise the carbonation made on opening the bottle , it seems quite on the palate .

appearance : large , crackling layer of fizz off pour , which descends to a firm , tan crown . deep brown body shines crimson in light and shows excellent clarity . nice head retention and lace .  the mouthfeel is way to under carbonated and watery for the style .
cascading clouds settle into a perfect looking glass of beer , dark with beautiful thick creamy head .  mouth feel was very thin .
the beer looks very nice . shows great retention and lacing .  very thin , and barely any head .

a : dark caramel ale with a finger of whipped toasted cream foam . this sticks around for quite some time before barely retreating to a quilt of the same . sheet lace . excellent clarity .  the mouthfeel is syrupy and shows none of the carbonation that the pour hinted at .

plenty of other fruit aromas to go around . t : like all hop bombs for me , a great aroma but as i take a sip a mouth puckering bitterness takes over . though this is still a very bitter beer . slick and oily . it looks amazing with a great nose . just to bitter for me .  thin mouthfeel with average macro carbonation . touch of caustic mouthfeel in the middle with the bitterness and petrol notes .
4 finger frothy white head with great retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is thin for a ris , almost watery .

smells pretty decent as well . quite delicious , really .  crisp to the point of being overdone , loads and loads of soda like carbonation . notes : ho hum , average , run of the mill , mediocre ... etc .

the pour was very good and this is easily one of the best looking beers i have ever seen with its excelent head , color and champagne like bubbles .  i recently bought a bottle and had it at home and was supprised to find that it really was not much better than the average super brewery light beer . the taste is almost nonexistant and unlike some mega beers has almost no aftertaste at all which for this beer is actually a benefit . i would compare is most to a pbr .

330ml bottle poured into tulip dec9 2010 a super hazy golden orange with tiny suspended particles being move around by a shitload of bubbles . a gentle pour leaves a massive 3 finger head that forms a dome over the top of the glass and just sits there for a while ever so slowly falling to a thick film with a island in the middle that looks like a little brain s a little yeast and pineapple with some other fruits i ca n't quite place and some booze t what i smell but with a little more booze , some cereals and a nice little blast of hops .  its rather thin in the mouth , and doesnt ready leave me wanting more drinkabilty - with its high alcohol , and bitter mocha overload , this beer doesnt do it for me .
pours pitch black into a snifter . the visual is as appetizing as it 's ever going to get for a stout .  skimpy in body , vapidly dextrinous and approaching watery in mouthfeel .
it is a very pretty looking beer when poured into a pils glass . straw blonde colour with a thick white head that lingers for a while .  mouthfeel is flat but this is the only disappointment .

the appearance of the beer was beautiful - the color was a rich black , there was nice head retention and some lacing . overall , this was a terrific and memorable beer .  mouthfeel was thin and tingly , and the initial flavor was sour fruit , which was fine , but then it too was quickly overtaken by the taste of grains .
pour : 750ml bottle to tulip glass . tons of webbing shows how big the head had been , like the water line of a flood . beautiful .  the palate is thin .
the color was a nice brown color , very little head and the aroma was no where to be found .  m - this bottle was flat . this gave the beer a thick and somewhat unenjoyable mouthfeel .

absolutely gorgeous beer.a ruby-brown color with a very slight head that is quickly gone.very little carbonation.aroma of malt.some fruity , wine like aromas.malt dominates flavor.fairly obvious alchohol.not as sweet as other barleywines.tends to almost be a tad `` harsh '' between the alchohol and hop bitterness.full bodied mouthfeel that obviously speaks for the `` big '' beer that it is.overall a good beer but the harshness detracts slightly.definately a monster in itself.worth a try by all means.i havnt had this in 2 years but remember past samples along the same lines.will be laying a few bottles down this year .  mouthfeel 2/5 mouthfeel got too watery as the beer warmed .

the smoked porter poured a dark black with a semi-creamy tan head that dissipated rather quickly .  for some reason i do n't taste the citrus like everyone else does ... m - thin and flat . propagates through the mouth pretty easily though .

it pours a rust-colored brown with a roasted 2-3 finger head . this looks as good as any of the big ipas made by stone , smuttynose and company .  the body is very thin and watery and the carbonation level is medium low which does not compliment this beer at all .
wonderful aroma of coffee , milk and bitter chocolate , and a touch of smoke .  the palate is thin .
nice tight eggshell head . nearly brilliantly clear .  mouthfeel is equally watery .

the appearance was great ( and yes i know to pour 2/3 of the bottle , let it setle , then pour the rest ) but the flavor was just not up to par .  smells basically like apple juice . watery . also , the carbonation that was so present during the pour now seems dulled . for all its faults , in the end rogue makes a malt liquor that achieves what you usually want out of the style .

a - dark brown with a chocolaty brown head s - there is a bit of chocolate malts and coffee , as well as some burnt malts t - hit the style well ... some coffee tones with a burnt malt finish .  not the worst tasting beer ever , but very thin and watery .

a-pours a deep amber ... .little head.. s-nice sticky sweet aroma of caramel is most evident ... also some mild chocolate notes ... .the more i smell this the more impressed i become ... .some dark fruitiness is there in the way of plums ... .also some very mild spicy black pepper ... t-the dark fruits lead the way here ... black cherries , plums , perhaps a little bit of raisins ... the spicy peppery impression blends nicely ... the caramel is strongly evident too and borders on cloying ... not tasting the chocolate but it is definitely there in the aroma . i was jacked up hearing this was the style chosen for this year as i have been mildly disappointed with the selections in the past five years ... this is a decent dubbel ... i immediately bought two six-packs of this when i saw it and i anticipate purchasing more .  m : super thin with no carbonation .
pours a darker , hazy amber-bronze with very thick , chunky white head resembling melted ice cream .  m : thin body with almost no carbonation at all .

a - poured a completely black with a gigantic 3 finger head .  nose : it 's aroma is a little bit malty , a little bit citrusy flavor : the taste has some lemon/citrus notes w/ some hints of maltiness , but the big thing that you notice is how fizzy this beer is . it 's far too fizzy for me .

a - dark caramel brown in color with some golden hues around the edges of the glass . hue , foamy off-white head with excellent retention .  finish really kills me as bad oaks comes off ... mouthfeel is the true downfall of this beer , watery light with no depth ... easy to drink but not good enough that i would .

a - pours a dark , cloudy copper with an amazing two finger light brown head . the head on this beer was huge and crated with never ending retention and thick , gooey lacing .  alcohol is very well masked for a 6.5 % way too much carbonation for my liking .
11.2 oz brown bottle with best by date beer is a beautiful medium brown . nice 2 inch head made-up of very small bubbles , no foaming agents here !  mouthfeel is very watery w/ average crabonation .
pours dark clear copper with a very thick , pillowy white head .  m : watery , high carbonation .

deliciously hoppy nose - massive sweet fruit backed with gritty , resinous hops . extremely fragrant , and powerful . palate is less robust , with a subtle , but pleasant hop character riding over the top of a smooth , buttery sweetness . this leaves it extremely drinkable - very smooth and refreshing . an excellent and tasty little ipa .  m - super thin , kind of dry .
this stout pours a deep tawny red that appears black unless held to light , decent head .  3.0 m too thin for my taste and my experience with better scottish ales ( like oskar blues ) .

this brew poured to a nice to an amber color with a very impressive head ! it is a very nice looking brew .  a nice chocolatey finish that lingers for a while on the palate is the best part about this beer . m : poor .

the carbonation gives rise to an absolutely stunning off white , creamy head with excellent retention .  the mouthfeel is quite disappointing due to carbonation that is much too high for a stout and a body which is not thick or creamy .
appearance - cloudy dark red , 2 fingers of creamy head with good retention and lacing .  taste is very light and mouthfeel is weak .
a - black as night with a thick frothy brown head . fades slowly leaving a thin solid layer of foam on the beer with excellent lacing .  the mouthfeel is astringent .

this is the only barley wine i have every tried , and chances are it will be the last . some people love this stuff , not me , not my taste buds .  however , the mouthfeel hindered any solid punch this drink could have had with its extremely watery and light feel .
a : attractive drink on the pour , looks like a lighter , creamier guinness pint from a good tap . huge head and flowing bubbles .  the body of this is way too light for a porter .

in the flavor : oodles of grapefruit and lime , fresh grass , a bit of dank weed , some sweet honey and black pepper . good hop profile ; great for a pale ale . i would n't say this winter offering from ska has flavors that really gel with the season , but it is a nice little pale .  the problem is that the beverage is thin and flat on the palate and leaves a really unpleasant metallic aftertaste .

thanks to paxton1978 for this one popped the cork that did not `` pop '' and poured pitch black with little head turning to film rather quickly . aromas of dark malty goodness , toasted coconut , roast nuts , fruit cake , anise , sweet spices and alcohol sweet tallahassee ! ! ! carbonation was lighter than expected which was not a bad thing but the body could have been much fuller and richer especially for what i expected from such a sweet decadent beer . i have really loved the ab series and am a brewdog fan .  mouthfeel : body is thin and water and a little flat ; finsih is wet and is like drinking malt flavored water . the flavors are mild and meek , the body is super watery and does n't offer much , so i do n't feel i will be drinking this again .
head is 2 fingers with very good retention eventually settling to a crown producing excellent lacing s- aroma does n't five much away .  thin mouthfeel .
a - caramel-butterscotch gold with a thick off-white head , very nice looking .  this beer is incredibly watery and light on the palate .
pours a very inky black with a dark brown creamy head . very oily and sudsy , looks great .  the mouthfeel is pretty sad on this one . very watery and thin .

a truly spectacular appereance , deep chestnut with reddish purple highlights . a massive head that left thorough lacing . really attractive . quite pleasing minus the fact that no taste seems to linger .  ok. m : kind of thin here .

pours an almost transparent golden/light copper with an amazingly fluffy 3 finger head from an extremely gentle pour .  on first taste the mouthfeel seems a little thin . all in all tasty , but quite thin and seriously lacking in body .

poures a deep tranparent amber in color . leaving a half finger of retention.thick gloppy rings of lace . : ( i was pretty excited to taste this after its wonderful appearance and terrific aroma .  mothfeel is very light and watery .

s - if you like coffee , this is actually really nice . great roasted coffee and espresso aromas , along with a little unsweetened cocoa and vanilla .  tastes like someone put artificial flavoring in carbonated water .

very still with incredible lacing s - dry roasted malts , sugar and bread , a touch of spice t - earthy roasted malts , dry corn , very malty with a mild hop finish m - nitro tap gives a creamy smoothness that makes it super sessionable o - really great !  m - thin , watery , overly carbonated .
beautiful nitro thick creamy tan head over a black body . has a lovely way of settling to a creamy solid chunk that wo n't spill out of the glass if you tilt it .  fizzy carbonation and no body .

pours black with a frothy , one-finger white head that lasted throughout the whole beer and left some lacing .  caramel , coffee and cocoa are there , but overall balance is towards the dry and bitter mouthfeel - 2.0 lightly carbonated , bordering on flat and a little watery .

appearance : this brew pours with a wonderfully thick head . lacings are plentiful and surface spiderwebbing is consistant and lasting . color is indeed a reddish amber . excellent first impression .  mouthfeel is also watery with not much body and no carbonation but essentially pretty drinkable due to the fact that is just resembles colored water .
the beer pours a nice clean clear amber color with a finger of head that falls to coat the beer .  too thin .
multilayered rings everywhere - one of the best lace patterns i 've seen from a beer in a long while .  mouthfeel is boring and watery .

while it pours beautifully with a deep copper color and wonderful head , this brew is all looks and no personality .  a - light , clear , yellow color with a thick head that dissipated quickly s - beer , cheap beer t - beer from a can , cheap beer from a can m - thin , flat , not much d - went down smooth , probably because i 'd wisely iced it down with some ice and rock salt so it would get really cold .

its pale golden body is saturated with torrents of lacing , and topped off with a meringue-like head of admirable retention . o : i do n't understand how people pay an extra $ 3/6pk for this garbage over bud ; it 's essentially the same stuff .  the body is light and really deters the taste .

the aroma of this beer was the highlight for me : banana , apple , belgian yeastiness , other fruits ... really great . golden yellow in color with a small ring of head at the top after it settles . alcohol comes through very nicely . sweet aftertaste is enjoyable .  the flavor was spicy and malty and the mouthfeel was tingly along with a burning sensation as it is swallowed .
bottle into an english pint glass appearance - dark brown/red hue reminds me of high grade saddle leather . a very handsome brew , sir .  m : this beer is almost flat .
very dark brown with garnet highlights and a giant , fluffy , dark tan cap .  flavor is of arange , and body is highly carbonated . prickly mouthfeel , and a bit boring overall

poured into a chalice a- huge huge huge frothy merangue like , sand colored head rises way above the rim of the glass . it has incredible stay with incredible lacing . the beer is a murky and clouded dark brown/umber .  nearly flat carbonation and medium body allow a solid diacetyl mouthfeel , which is done well if you like it that way .

gorgeous looking beer s- getting a bunch of citrus , but the aroma is really weak .  that being said i want to keep track of beers i have tried and will start to try reviewing beers i drink ) from a sampler pack found at specs liquor . tastes flat to me . no alcohol taste that i can tell of and not a whole lot of flavor . goes down easy and not much of an aftertaste .
dark chocolate brown with a nice , thick , creamy , khaki head atop .  m - watery and sticky . its almost a thin beer .

clear golden amber body with a steady level of carbonation and head that leaves a quarter inch of film like white head ; crystal clear .  mouthfeel : seltzer drinkability : would be good but the mouthfeel sucks .
wish this tasted half as good as it smelled .  overall , feels unbalanced , too much carbonation and a little too dull .

i think what happened was that the strain of bacteria or yeast that the brewer exposed the beer to ate more of the dextrins and made the beer less full-bodied . 3/22/2009 beautiful burgundy color .  very watery . the mouthfeel was thin and watery as well .
motor oil black with a head like you would see on a rootbeer float .  i thought that the mouthfeel was kind of watered down ... it needed more `` oommff '' .

there is a lot to this scent , but it is surprisingly balanced , pungent sweetness and hops with subtle funk . good stuff , but it 's a shame it does n't match the glorious scent . mouthfeel is medium bodied and smooth , but a bit watery .  the body is thin and watery ; one hardly notices the beer until it is gone .
aroma is piney and citrusy hops .  not oxidized , just old and flattish . flattish and heavy , but slick as well , drinkability suffers from the lack of carbonation , hard to finish this bottle .

a - only a sliver of red around the edge . tall very tight light brown head leaving considerable lacing .  the mouthfeel was then utterly unimpressive . overall , the drink looks good but the taste and feel are way too thin and watery .

this one gushed out an extremely creamy , frothy off-white head with a suprisingly long and stable retention . the bottom was also very appealing , golden orange-yellow hue that was opaque and reflective .  this is a drinkable brew that definatly packs a punch , but it 's kind of one dimensional and thin .
pours a dark brown with an excellent light tan head that billows and floats for minutes .  feel of almost flat carbonated water .

looks like a perfect ris : pitch black with barely no brown around the edges , even when held up to a bright light . an incredibly creamy , frothy and sticky dark khaki head forms and sticks around for quite a bit . impeccable .  mouthfeel : way too big-bodied , way too carbonated , and way too uneven .

pours a nice creamy sunshine-yellow-wheat color . head is thick and creamy which is typical of the widget-type cans .  it does n't taste bad or good , kind of like water . it tastes like bubble water with a hint of sweetness . it 's for getting your swill on , and nothing else . too bad this is what most americans think of , when they think of australian beer .
the appearance is beautiful . a bit darker than i 'd expect a golden ale to be , but it looked great .  it has a below average mouthfeel - boring , too watery and macro-brewish .
honestly , a fantastic looking beer .  the mouthfeel was thin and not terribly hoppy on the palate .

s - the nose on this one is as good as it gets . t - just wonderful - almost as perfect as the nose . this outstanding beer 's only downfall . d - great . tons of booze and heat on this one , but the outstanding vanilla and coconut flavors allow me to drink as much of this as is available !  m - light and fizzy , thin bodied .
plenty of head that lingers all the way down the glass .  overall flavor is nice , but the body is way too carbonated .

pours a bright , clear gold , with a three finger high column of dimpled white head . good head retention too . really it is absolutely gorgeous . i do n't think a saison could look any better ... the aroma has a bit of citrus ( lemon ) , slight grass , and mild pepper .  thin watery feel .

light-sucking black with a monumental 2.5 finger head of a nice deep tan . great retention and lacing . ca n't ask for a better appearance than this .  m : very thin and watery -- it has a consistency not far from kool-aid .
pours a clear amber color with a creamy off white tannacios head that leaves great lacing .  mouthfeel : not much carbonation and the body is kind of watery .

a very intriguing nose , wow , minty , citrusy , lemon-grass , soft licorice notes , very pleasant even with its slight funk of oxidation . this is actually quite nice even with its funk , i could deal with a little less carbonation .  pours a clear golden copper hue which leaves a creamy fast vanishing two finger head and creamy lacing , the smell is herbal grassy hops and some honey malts thats it , the mouthfeel is light and watery and has tastes of honey malts , herbal grassy hops , fresh cut grass , pale malts and finished with a mix of herbal grassiness and toffee and overall i definately would not buy again and the bitterness is only very light avoid cheers .

smells fucking amazing . this is the best-smelling beer i 've ever had . it smells like exotic , spiced , fresh-roasted coffee , like you 're standing in [ trendy east side coffee shop ] . really good , but not quite on the same transcendent level as the nose .  a little thin overall . mouthfeel : light-bodied and lacking . way too light and delicate of a beer to have an abv of 7.5 % .

a - deep gold color s- amazing , citrus , grapefruit , & bubblegum aromas t- bitter hops ( grapefruit-like ) with fruity undertones . m - dry to the finish o- i was impressed that brewers were able to capture strong complexity for such a bitter , hoppy brew . overall i felt that the bitterness was way overpowering , leaving my mouth dried out .  i picked up a carton of this pretty cheap the only downfall its in cans anyways it pours a golden amber see thru colour with nice carbonation that leaves a bubbly two finger head and sporadic lacing , the aroma is pretty macro with grains and a feint bubblegum aroma , it has a thin mouthfeel with a rather grainy taste and isnt nothing to write home about , its definately better than the macroswill that sells for much more and easier to down but its not a beer that i would drink if i wanted a nice beer with character .

aroma was intensely hoppy yet smooth and balanced . piney and floral hops , citrus and fruity esters came through strong along with a touch of candy-like sweetness . cascade hops and hop oils soon became bitter and biting and left a noticeable film on my tongue . unquestionably , this was the most bitter and unbalanced ipa i have had to date .  mouthful was watery and a bit disappointing considering the color and head .

the smell is amazing , strong coffee aroma , more so than any other coffee stout i 've had , easily the best aspect of this stout . the taste is a bit more reserved with the coffee as it 's hard to beat the strong aroma , but there is a good deal of coffee and roasted malt , hint of chocolate , and a decent bitterness in the end .  the body was light and very watery .
pours a beautiful golden color with thick , frothy guinness-like white head .  m : bitter , almost no carbonation , light to medium body .
a : nice bright golden color with a nice creamy head that you dont usually see on these american witbiers .  m- thin highly carbonated .
beautiful in it 's appearance , and a welcoming texture on the tongue .  the mouthfeel is surprisingly flat .
poured from 22oz bottle into `` balloon '' glass the darkest ebony color in the body with a rocky massive foamy/sticky dark tan colored head .  the mouthfeel was very thin for a stout .
had great lacing and retention .  mouthfeel on both is not much , just clear water with a bit of beer bubbles .
jet black ... amazing tan head .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and watery with almost no carbonation .

vintage : 2009 tasted after hibernus appearance : pours a medium looking white head with good retention . a great looking brew for sure .  body is very thin , drinkability is ok , but there 's not very much to this beer .

a- body is a nearly transparent dark copper hue that is served with the perfect 1/2 finger foamy white head . the head has perfect retention the whole way down the glass .  mouthfeel is very thin and dry on the mouth .

very very unique beer , the nose right off the bat informs you of it . rich aroma of the carmel malts used , very heavy scent , but goes along nicely with the character of the porter . really good on a cold day in warm house kind of beer .  strong roasted malt character with a twang of hop bitterness , but really light and pale in the mouth with a watery body . no creamy mouthfeel , which was somewhat disappointing , but it was overall enjoyable . clean , pure and watery finish was n't quite what i had hoped for , as i was expecting something a little more milky/creamy/smooth .

bourbon colored with an excellent 3 finger head that rises a good 1/4 inch above the glass . very foamy head that last a long , long time .  hard to slam the beer that got my through college but ... . the twelfth tasted like the first . not really whatt i consider beer anymore but my in-law says it is more of a beer than budweiser ? could there be a reason you can by `` cooler-packs '' in multiples of 6 !

perfect fruit scent . clean , pleasant , and wonderful . almost erotic , even - i want this beer to have my abortion .  not much depth at all m- lacking for a stout -- - no creaminess and it 's pretty thin overall d- wo n't seek this out again and i hope the rest of the breweries selections are better -- - really loses you in the mouthfeel

head leaves a serious amount of lace on the glass . really a great looking pint of beer .  palate scraping astringency . the lack of carbonation particularly makes me wonder if i should have given this more time in the cellar to condition .

pours an absolutely gorgeous dark cola body that illuminates to a caramel-amber when held to the light . creamy , light tan bubbles form a sizable froth on top and slowly settle to a thick veil of foam , thanks in part to a vigorous carbonation level .  it tastes ok. kind of watered down . cant taste any malt or hops . it was too bubbly , seemed over-carbonated .
a large beige head forms with great retention and lace .  the mouthfeel is light to medium bodied and just way too thin and watery for an oatmeal stout .
a freind brought this brew over ... a : perfect look for a belgian ale . deep dark ruby color like an iced tea .  m : medium body with lower medium carbonation . the mouthfeel is thin and watery .

the head is very impressive in that it 's a creamy tan , intricate lacing and last throughout the whole beer with a nice semi-thick layer of foam on top of the beer . it really is a nice looking beer .  watery mouthfeel in terms of a stout .
a - dark , almost black with a beautiful one and a half finger head that is very creamy , love the cascade effect .  mouthfeel : medium body , watery texture , very low carbonation .
really intense and really pleasant . 4.5 t : taste is much like the nose .  thin to medium mouthfeel with zero carbonation -- lifeless .
pours an opaque darkness with a huge stiff dark brown head that decomposes like an ice cream sundae , massive 3d lacing present .  very thin mouthfeel , almost tasted flat , nothing special .

ultra-creamy , chocolate-milk colored head , 2 fingers depth . huge , creamy beige lacing coats the side of the glass with each sip .  good lacing down the glass s : coffee , sweet bready malts t : coffee , slight harsh maltiness also slight hint of chocolate m : light very thin bodied beer .

it pours a cloudy golden orange color and smells delicious . the nose had hints of orange peel , coriander , hops and light caramel . drinkability was a little low though due to the over carbonation and the sweetness of the beer overall , but very good . will buy again  the malt is lightly roasted , but mild with candisugar and syrupy cane sugar . add to that the thin body caused by a lot of sugar and it will add up to a c for me .
i fricking love the way this beer looks . huge foamy white head , brilliant dark golden color with a cascade of carbonation bubbling up the side .  it is entirely too thin for a stout .

appearance : dark brown to black , almost opaque . pouring leaves a thick tan head that takes a while to go away and an island of foam that remains the entire time .  thin watery and light in body o - did not even reach moderate expectations of being a porter and tasting barrel aged , just not very good in my opinion .

boddingtons shows up a light amber , pale gold in color , with a beautiful inch of thick cream , the bubbles being almost indiscernible . the cascading action that takes place as the beer settles and the head rises is fascinating to watch . some of this head stays with the beer , and a thin layer of lace coats the glass all the way down .  where this beer falls off is the mouthfeel ; it was like coca-cola without the carbonation . drinkability would be pretty good i guess , if you can get pas the average flavors and thin mouthfeel .
nose was rich with fudgy chocolate , smoke and charcoal .  mouthfeel is thin .
this beer is a handsome black with a pillowy light tan head that has great retention and lacing .  carbonation a bit high . fails on this point . d- easy going macro lager .
dark brown with hints of red , and a solid beige head .  m - no staying power .

like the looks of this . full thick head .  feels thin and watery on the tongue with a low level of carbonation . bitterness is harsh and detracts from drinkability , mouthfeel is unsatisfying , and the flavors are n't interesting and complex enough to yield repeated enjoyment .

pours out a slightly chill-hazed brassy tangerine with a wealth of tiny bubbles making their way to the head . head is massive , foamy , and almost spills over the top . leaves some near solid lacing on the glass .  smell is not overwealming , but seems sweet with hints of yeast and hop . watery , yeasty , sweet ... more corn than i thought there would be ... taste relatively one-dimensional , unfortunately . fairly drinkable though ... inoffensive and cheap ...

pale golden-amber , brilliantly clear and bright , this is a beautiful beer . two fingers of head settles down to a thin disc that retains very well .  body a bit lightweight , no real follow-through or length .
a : poured perfectly dark brown with an abundant creamy light brown head . great retention and fantastic lacing .  immediately upon entering the mouth it felt very watery and light for an 80/- .

a beautiful site setting in the glass , this blackberry to almost brown elixir of life , the head gargantuan in size , creamy in texture , the color a light chocolate brown , the residual lace a thick clinging sheet .  the mouthfeel is medium-light bodied with a watery texture , and a little too much carbonation .

a : hazy yellow with a frothy head that has great retention ; what a hefeweiss should look like s : grainy with the typical banana and cloves poking through the hay/earthy/straw graininess t : a nice balance of earthy grainy yeastiness and banana and cloves ; subtle spice nodes ; a tiny bit thin on the way down f : pretty good mouth feel but a tad thin at back end d : wonderful drinkability ; the quintessential hefeweiss beer ; great especially for a hot humid day .  taste is rich and sweet , slightly nutty , but this beer really sufferes from it 's thin and watery mouthfeel .

label is shrink wrapped on the can , not printed . bright and glowing copper orange color . plenty of foam , visible trails of rising carbonation . a substantial head that laces well , with a skim that never breaks on the surface .  mouthfeel/ drinkability : the carbonation isnt stinging and seems appropriate . the body of the beer seems far too thin .
really cool head color : it is mocha with a red tinge .  mouthfeel was pretty watery and went down quickly .
it was truly beautiful , and left something more than lacing , almost a vanilla milkshake looking coating on the glass .  a : it 's still carbonated , that 's something at least . too fizzy .

huge 3 to 4-finger tan/beige head , slowly recedes to thin but relatively constant layer . great webby lace .  the sweetness died out in the taste , however , which was flat and slightly watered-down . a weird bitterness gave an unpleasant mouthfeel but still not difficult to drink .

a- pours a bright orange-copper color with great clarity and an exceptionally persistent head .  mouthfeel is watery . this style needs more body - the maltiness is there , but there is very little roasted character & not enough creaminess .

i am still basically against fruit in my beer . the smell is the expected apple smell . i have granny smith apples in my house year round so this was evocative of that .  m - thin , watery body , moderate carbonation , slight bitterness in the finish .

appearance : butte creek 's ipa sits in the glass a beautiful , brilliantly clear pale amber . butte creek has mastered the art of making a nice looking beer .  but i felt i owed it to myself to see if smaller carbonation meant bigger taste .

it lasts forever and settles to a nice pillow . usually old ales have no head at all . i 'm amazed this looks so good .  fairly watery on the tongue . i was exited for this one after smelling , but the lack complexity on the palate coupled with the watery mouthfeel made this one a disappointment .

) pitch black colour , moderate brown head . the appearance is top notch , a very fine and lasting brown head .  pretty nice . the body is as thin as water . that leads to a very drinkable beer , actually , since it goes down ... well , like water .

lots of sour funk upon popping the cork . great sour funkiness with sour apples and pears . also get some very floral notes as well .  medium body , almost non existent carbonation , sweet sticky syrupy mouthfeel . i think the lack of carbonation ruins the mouthfeel and makes this taste and smell overly sweet .

aroma held very much of the brandy barrel aging . cherries vanilla , and some very tart notes as well . tart cherries oak and vanilla mix nicely in the flavor good caramel malt sweet backbone . amazingly complex and flavorful . really great beer is grounded due to complete lack of carbonation .  mouthfeel is indeed excessively thin , leaving a slight tingle of carbonation , but otherwise going down like iced water .

into a pint glass , pours a kind of honey amber copper , with a heaping huge off-white head , settling down to a thick foam , lots and lots of lacing in rings and spiderwebs and bubbles down the glass . and upon second pour , the head swells again to two inches of foamy delight , a great big mustache is my reward .  s. nonexistent . m. also nonexistent . just plain and unoffensive . light beer on amber side ? nothing to brag about but goes down like water . above average in it 's class .
poured from my home tap , this one looks great in the glass , with a deep mahogany-amber color and a thick , creamy , foamy , sand-colored head .  it 's highly carbonated , and extremely astringent .

the aroma is that of a rich red wine , high in fresh fruit and tart cherry . complex undertones reveal the earthiness of damp autumn woodland , as it warms . the alcohol is greater than anticipated , and interesting , given that it is labeled as 4 % . a ton of character , oud beersel is my opinion of a stunning example of what this style can achieve . unpretentious and impeccably crafted , this is a gastronomical work of art .  m : taste was below average for me , but the mouthfeel is even worse . super thin . light carbonation and no body make this almost watery .

it poured caramel brown in color with a big , fluffy and frothy off-white head to it . a thin , frothy layer remained covering the beer well into drinking it and left some great lacing as well . exceptional looking barleywine overall .  but the overall mouthfeel is unbalanced , with simply too much fizz against a generally thin texture .
perfect lacing . very good retention .  m - kind of flat on the palate with very little carbonation . hop profile caught me off guard and the mouthfeel is pretty weak .

syrupy but not in an over the top fashion . s. phenomenal , tons of coffee , vanilla caramel and sweet chocolate , with a sense of dryness . there is a lot of complexity in the nose , i like it . t. sweet bourbon , oak dryness , all smells mentioned above , bitter coffee all the way through al little rough on the mix of flavors but still great . creamy and crunchy . i would categorize this along with bell 's expedition stout as being a bad boy of the style . its not a smooth and user friendly drink .  the mouthfeel is very thin and highly carbonated , very reminiscent of your typical macro lager .

this is a delicious looking beer ! dark with a creamy , full head .  i 'm going to have to go against the gimmick and with the style here , the mouthfeel just is n't there . i 'm not impressed at all , it 's like a half flat beer that you 've left on your desk whilst reviewing a beer and forgotten about it only to come back to it 30 mins later . the shining point of this beer is it 's drinkability .

this was poured from the bottle into a consendonk tulip glass . a - clear light golden straw color with a thick foamy , ice cream-like head that is very well retained s - sweet malt and fruity yeast aroma with a slight hop spiciness t - like aroma , sweet malt up front with fruit-like notes and a very slight amount of hops on the finish m - medium body with high carbonation d - this is a decent , well-made beer .  very light in body with a slick mouthfeel at first that becomes almost slimy .
this beer looks great ! very hard to pick up the toasted and almost roasted malt aromas .  mouthfeel was quite thin and highly over carbonated .
a : very dark brown with appealing 2-3 finger , rocky , off-white head with very good retention and abundant lacing in rings .  very thin , and watery . lower carbonation .
on-tap at the toronado . dark orangey brown with a nice 1/2 '' head of thick white foam that leaves killer lacing on the glass .  the body is a bit thin and feels too bubbly .

pours a hazy reddish-brown color with a very thick and creamy off-white head . really nice lacing and a good cap throughout .  carbonation is minimal , almost flat . again understanding its aged but this beer is pretty sweet and without some degree of carbonation to clear out the palette at the end it becomes cloying .

smell - citrus and strong pine notes with a little bit of earthy smell . very nice on the nose . taste - hop taste comes across pretty strong with an orange/grapefruit taste .  m : thin body and light carbonation .

tall , nearly white head with good retention and great lacing .  water with a little spice and alcohol . the smell is the best part with mainly cinnamon . the taste is one dimensional cinnamon with a super light water taste on the back . no malt or pumpkin to be found . not a good beer nor a good pumpkin ale but if someone handed me one i would have no problem finishing it . also you could down 3 or 4 no problem and being $ 6 a 6 pack you ca n't beat that .

this beer looks perfect . theres not as much smell to this one as others like it .  head falls into the liquid way too quickly and seems to look more like bubble bath suds that the typical beautiful belgian head . certainly is the high point of the beer . alcohol comes a little too strong on the palate and seems to take over the other flavors . flat on the tonque . outrageously overpriced and overrated .

s : sweet and dark ... rich .  for a russian imperial this is even for 9.7 incredibly weak and watery it 's the first thing i notice . the mouthfeel on this is not good , it 's even weaker than most american stouts i 've had .

a very aggressive head forms and is as thick as 3+ fingers . a deep ruby/amber color with excellent clarity and no visible carbonation . clumpy lacing everywhere .  a bit too sticky on the mouthfeel .
the nose was very rich and interesting , but the taste fell short .  mouthfeel : absolutely no carbonation .
great look to this beer .  thin , watery , overcarbonated .

looks like a ton of carbonation . golden , cloudy . great looking beer and i 'm excited to taste my first jolly pumpkin .  mouthfeel is very light and watery and it has a similar taste as many other bmc beers , however it does have some light maltiness to it that most macro lagers lack .

pours a luscious peach/dark gold color with a substantial , fluffy , two-finger head that exhibits excellent retention and lacing .  not much at all going on except for some sweetness and a very slight bitterness that gives way to a watery finish . not the worst macro lager by any means .

appearance : deep mahogany brown tone with a nice full more than two finger sized tan head leaves perfect even lacing scatter evenly around my glass .  mouthfeel : very carbonated with a thin , almost watery feeling .

bottle comes a fantastic cascading pour producing a thick , frothy tan head atop a translucent , deep brown body .  the carbonation seems artificial , which really brings down the quality of this lager to something like a henry weinhards ( goes for a good taste , but it all seems somewhat fake ) . without the strong carbonation this would have been a common sight in my fridge , but as it is sieraa nevada summerfest will only make occassional appearences .

a : pitch black . aggressive thick tan head that quickly dissipates and leaves lacing around the edges .  mouthfeel : medium-heavy body . makes my mouth feel like sandpaper after a taste . after reading other reviews , and letting the beer warm a bit , i & # 8217 ; m starting to appreciate it more , but i & # 8217 ; m thinking i & # 8217 ; m robbing the cradle a bit with this sample .
very resilient aromatics , wonderful . taste - a brief sweet malt start goes nowhere before some serious hops kick in .  sweet crackery finish , m - thin with very low carbonation .
appearance : pours an incredibly rich , thick molasses/mahogany . you 'll be hard pressed to find a better looking beer than this .  mouthfeel is thin .

it pours an orange yellow glow through the haze . the head is massive , billowy and ice cream like in its consistency .  the presence of tannin explains how , while quite watery , satan red is also quite drying .
an inspiring view and almost magical looking . big , sticky off-white head .  m : i was disappointed in the mouth feel . the light mouth feel really hurt for me .

pours a sparkling orange tinged gold , topped with a huge four finger pillowy white head , constant streams of carbonation bubbles , leaves thick puffy webs of lacing .  the mouthfeel is light to medium bodied and watery .
very pretty beer . deep dark brown , with a huge , tan head that stays for a while and leaves lovely lacing around the glass . just gorgeous .  it is a bit bland , the mouthfeel is way too watery .

excellent lacing and a fully lasting head .  color very pale green or lemon odor , which suggests more concentrated lemon juice only freshly cut lemon slices , but preserving a small mouth , perhaps a bit too much . the lager that is the basis must be extremely low in taste because the body is still very watery , just a few hints of lemon , no sugar but not bitter unfortunately .
a : a dark brown pour with a ridiculously huge fluffy light brown head .  light body , short finish , little texture , too much carbonation at the front .
pours a deep , hazy amber hue , giving rise to a humongous light tan head that fills half the vessel .  mouthfeel : a bit on the fizzy side - really scrubs the tongue .
this beer poured an opaque black with an exceedingly abundant head .  limp bodied and watery , with no real aftertaste .

750 ml bottle poured into a tulip glass . pours a cloudy corn silk hue with a pillowy cloudy white two finger head . super sticky on the sides with a head that sticks around forever .  `` simple '' is the best word i can use to describe the taste , but it does deliver with scorched malts with a touch of lactose . my biggest complaint with this beer is the mouthfeel- it 's way too watery .

the appearance is an exceptional golden hue with a slight red tone . a very minimal white head is apparent with smile delicate lacing along the side of the glass .  mouthfeel : medium to light treading dangerously close to watery .
one finger large off white that shows great retention .  it drinks as a light beer ; it is very thin and weak , much unlike guinness .
bottle : poured a deep pitch-black stout with a motor oil consistency and a small foamy head with good retention and some lacing .  m : bubbly and very thin .
a - black brew with two fingers of frothy light brown head . lacing is pretty thick in decent rings .  body is way too thick , sweet , and syrupy .

classic pride look - inviting transparent brown body with a reasonably large head , albeit casked up suds . leaves superb lace on the glass . awesome .  the mouthfeel was flat leaving a watery feel in the mouth .
very heavy hefe pour . thick , deep yellow gold that glubglubs out of the bottle and leaves a giant head .  i do n't taste any pecan ... m : thin . not to impressive in this dept o : do i love it ?
the beer poured crystal clear pale golden straw with a huge moussy white head which slowly fell to coat the glass .  mouthfeel was thin like water , very little body .

a nice amber color with a thick tan head . lace was thick and copious .  it tasted mostly like water with a very light toffee/sweet taste in the back of the tongue . that 's it . it was very drinkable in the same way water is drinkable . when a brewer wants you to chill his beer , there must be a issue with the flavor at cellar temps . i ca n't believe some people consider this to be the flagship for the style .

aroma- has a super strong pumpkin aroma with tons of sweetness , spice , and ingredient within ! rivals schlafly 's pumpkin aroma already ! appearance- pours a 1.5 finger head that has terrific retention . mouthfeel- medium-full bodied , medium-high carbonation , smooth , and leaves awesome amount of pumpkin/spice on the palate . overall impression- now this one breaks into my top 5 list !  the body is light and really lacking .

poured into an oversized wine glass producing a good two fingers worth of tan head with lots of lacing and looked mahogany in color .  mf : it 's medium-bodied at best despite the label 's claims of `` full bodied . '' speaking of which , it has a soda watery type carbonation , not at all the `` luxuriously smooth '' of the label . i have to say that they could get the mouthfeel under control ( i 'd imagine this is less of an issue on tap ) , it would be hands-down my favorite irish stout .
as far as a comparison with guinness , i thought this had a more bitter taste and a thinner body .  the mouhfeel is weak , watery , thin .

a- really nice big belgian-style head on top of a fizzy , slightly hazy , light straw colored body . looks lovely in a belgian tulip glass .  the mouthfeel is confusing as it feels too thin for the amount of sweetness on the taste buds .
dark-brown/mahogany color with a full creamy tan head and good carbonation which leaves sheets of lace .  mouthfeel is overyly fizzy and thin .

captain lawrence st. vincent 's dubbel is a great looking dubbel that tastes pretty good . a : red orange colour and a great 2 cm head that lasts very well . highly carbonated .  it does bring vanilla to mind . the sweetness almost removes it from the style of beer . far to thin for a brown ale .
a : this beer pours a beautiful hazy red color with a fluffy off white head . the color of this beer is amazing .  m=fairly thin , a little medium . watery .

bottle poured into a tulip glass . brilliant clarity . thick white crop of foam with good retention and moderate lacing .  good for a lager , but way too much carbonation really throwing this beer off .

4.5 s : bourbon and maple come through most prominently . oak and vanilla next . as i sort of expected , most of the wheat gets lost in the previously mentioned powers . i say the bourbon level is just right . 3.0 t : again , maple and bourbon dominate only this time it may be too forceful .  the worst part for me was definitely the mouthfeel , which was waaaay too thin .

the beer is an oil black , with no foreseeable brown hue when held to the light . the head is impressive , huge , sea-foam that stays around for a long , long time .  mouthfeel : lacking . too light for the style .
looks pretty nice , as did the bottle presentation , but is the beer nice ?  mouthfeel is weak and watery .

the body of hop head poured an absolutly beautiful copper-orange color , with a sizable custard head . retention and lacing were both excellent , thanks to a constant supply of carbonation from below .  m/d : a very harsh crispness in the mouth and to much carbonation for my tastes .
wonderful looking ale .  thin on the mouthfeel and the carbonation is way too high on this one making the thinnes hard to handle .
a : nothing to complain about here - dark black , with a mocha colored head that hung around for a while .  mf : too thin and slippery !
a : clear ruddy chestnut body under an inch of soft tan foam . good retention and some spotty lace . i love the color .  m = thin . thats it .

pours a dark copper with a large , foamy white head that hung around forever . large amounts of thick lacing left on the glass surface . this is one beautiful beer .  very complex and interesting m : disappointing ! very thin for a barley wine .
overall , the aroma is wonderful , the flavor is almost there , but the harsh bitter finish leaves you afraid to take another sip .  mouthfeel is thin and weak .
the foamy white heads even offers a nice lacing as it recedes ever so slowly .  mouthfeel feels thin and weak ; this is my only real complaint with this beer .
the beer 's aroma was fantastic , but the flavor just could not back up the aroma .  mouthfeel was just plain flat , no pep to it at all .
appearance : a big , rocky , dirty white head of both large and small bubbles . loads of lacing .  m : water thin , light side of champagne-like carbonation .

bottled on : ( should be on the bottom right hand side of the bottle but its just dots ) purchased through lakeview liquors , chicago , illinois price - $ 9.99/bomber appearance : pours pitch black with a creamy mocha colored head . with each swirl of the snifter another layer of froth reveals itself . looks tastey .  no attempt whatsoever to hide the alcohol and the addition of the heavy acidic espresso taste and a watery mouthfeel make this hard to down .
looks fantastic and inviting .  overall feel was very thin , not impressive and not terribly satisfying .

a 1/2 '' medium brown head takes a very long time to fade to a thick film . lacing is impressive , lots of thick , clingy curtains stick around for a while and eventually fade to thin strings that were still there when i went to wash the glass off .  the mouthfeel is light and watery , not much substance . a very watered down dunkel , i would skip this in the future .
