bottle says bottled on 4/16/09 a - pours cloudy orange with huge 3 fingers of pillowy foam that takes forever to die down - lacing is all over the glass . this is one fine looking beer s - very hoppy with a strong grassy aroma - there are so many other aromas also - reminds me of a wine t - bitterness is subdued , bready yeast flavor is present , solid malt backbone m - great creamy mouthfeel - but i wish there was a little more lingering bitterness to this brew d - this is a very sneaky 9 % abv - deceptively drinkable .  mouthfeel is thin and watery .

a : pours an extremely dark ruby red that appears almost black .  the finish is lightly sweet rather than crisp , and the mouthfeel , which started out thin , ends on a watery , undercarbonated note . zywiec is an average epl , making it a below average beer in general .
pitch black opaque pour with mahogany glints and a nuclear glow of a khaki cap .  2.0 m : light body . way too light for the style . also , too much carbonation .

this beers saving grace is a fantastic odor .  it is far too light and leaves the tongue and mouth with a stinging feeling and terrible astringency ... d- one redeeming quality of this is that it seems like a session beer but boasts a 9 % alcohol level .

bottle , a : a dark , black , almost pernicious looking brew , with a beautiful thick tan head .  the beer was entirely too light bodied for a stout , this really was one of the most disappointing elements of the beer .

glass : snifter temp : cellared @ approx 45 degrees this is perfect appearance for a stout . it 's as black as black can be . the head takes a long while to recede to a nice thick surface covering , over an 1/8th of an inch thick . visually , this is quite an impressive beer .  m- this is precisely the opposite mouthfeel that i want . it feels like it wants to be sweet and sticky , but it really just falls watery on the tongue .

into a pint glass , pours about as black as a beer can get , a big huge light tan head with a bubbly middle , good staying power , about as long as the drinkin goes , and lovely lacing .  very thin feel , little oily .

s : intoxicating mixture of sour fruit ( both peach , of course , and , oddly , raspberries ) and green aromatic wood - like sawdust from a live tree in springtime . unique and incredible . t : starts out with peach , then gets truly sour and funky ( with some great sappy sawdust coming through ) and finishes with some sweeter fruit and vanilla . great . m : fairly light-bodied with abundant soft carbonation . perfect for the style .  the first thing i thought when i tasted it was , `` wow that is watery . i think they basically made it too `` light . comparing this to their original , it unfortunately seems to fall into the `` watered-down flavor '' category . if that is what you are looking for , then here 's your beer , otherwise i would stick to the usual recommendation to avoid the light beers . then again it really was n't that bad considering it was so cheap at the time .

burnt amber with a fluffy , light tan head of good size and staying power . lots of foamy lace left in the tulip as the head never really dies but eventually falls to a cm or so in height . there 's still some retention before the glass is finished . very nice .  mouthfeel was poor .

app- a nice dark brown which looked alot like maple syrup .  this beer reminds me greatly of sol , corona , and modelo . i would n't be surprised if all mexican beer came from the same place ... dirty t-shirts squeezed out into a horse trough and then 'pasteurized ' by the horse before making its way into the bottle , but hey what do i know about cervezas .

appearance : beautiful bright amber with a slight haze and thick , foamy off-tan head that leaves lots of lacing . looks like rootbeer float head .  this is very much like corona . not as good as miller light .
a - dark ruby with tan head . gorgeous lacing .  very carbonated ... .too much .
poured at the rock bottom brewery prior to seeing the blue man group . beautiful honey gold color ... poured with no head .  3.0 m thin .

quintessential witbier appearance , with a color that is indeed as close to white as a beer can be , and without looking sickly like some of those fizzy yellow corporate beers . head is stupendous , a foamy thing that almost looks like shaving cream -- thick , bone white , rocky , wow . plenty of haziness and very slow-moving bubbles . this could very well taste like crap , but it looks marvelous .  a thin mouthfeel . extremely drinkable . but that 's all i can really say good about it , the taste is n't great , and the mouthfeel is too thin .

s - smell is terrific and pops way more than a lot of nitro beers i 've had .  mouthfeel is where the beer suffers . it just feels wrong . a very tasty and aromatic beer , and if you can get past or prefer the super-low carbonation level .
a really nice looking pour .  m : really unappealing .

great black appearance with cascade of bubbles when poured that lasted a minute , leaving 1/2 inch tan head that stayed until the glass was empty .  d-a little rough on the palate with the huge carbonation and extremely grainy feel .

s - best feature . aroma of bananas , clove and bubble gum t - caramelized sugar , sour mash , banana m - a bit sour as you drink through the bottle , like an underripe banana , cloying sweetness d - becomes monotonous the more you drink of it .  mouthfeel is thin , macro thin .

pours a clear amber , nice thick white head forms , as it drops leaves some pretty epic lacing , settles to a nice layer , great retention . looks great , smells good , but the alcohol takes too much of it .  mouthfeel is very thin .

below average head retention , but the aroma more than makes up for a lackluster appearance as it brims with bold espresso and sweet chocolate notes . one of the best-smelling coffee beers i 've had recently , and the malt backbone is nothing to scoff at , either . overall , brewhouse coffee stout is amazingly aromatic , but could use a few tweaks here and there with regards to the appearance and mouthfeel .  here we go : a - opaque reddish-brown , small head with minimal lacing s - malts , hint of hops , not much else t - much like the aroma , mildly sweet malts , faint hop bitterness with weak coffee m - thin , a bit too thin for a brown ale d - no problem putting down a few if i chose to , but i do n't think i would unless it was my only alternative to bmc lagers .

the picture looks like the marlboro man . it pours a reddish orange that is very clear . nice white-ish head that has some nice retention and lacing .  the second sip shows that this beer is just really thin and more watered down .

smell : they put some hops in this , a lot of them . pine , key lime , hop leaf , loads of bitter hop oil , hope there 's a base to catch me ... taste : surprisingly earthy , the hop leaf / european hop profile , was expecting a little more west coast . overall : a very flavorful texas beer , just a little more english than american in taste , like a english double ipa .  mouth : enters the mouth with very light carbonation that flattens as it goes back . overall , it 's not a bad brew , it 's got a great hop flavor but not enough depth or balance , and the weak mouthfeel ruins the experience .

appearance : very , very deep clear gold , head on this one is one for the ages , really spectacular . huge , dense , pure white and a bit slick ; looks a bit like whipped egg whites .  way too carbonated here , which hurts the mouthfeel quite a bit .

incredible looking esb . pours with the cascading effect and settles to a bright amber color .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied . it took much diligence to see my way to the end of this beer , and , were it not for the runaway carbonation , it could 've been far better . one to revisit , provided they clear up the carbonation issue .

s - grassy yeast , bread with some honey notes , earthy grains , green apples , with some spiciness as well . t - malty followed by a spicy citrus .  taste is malty to start , but very thin . the body leaves one wanting more . dry finish with an almost soda-like feel . despite the lack of body , this beer is rather drinkable .
smells very sweet , what you 'd expect . perfect for dessert or a nightcap .  mouthfeel : way too carbonated .
very promising . and then : the taste is a bit disappointing after that great smell . good , but not exceptional .  m - too light , watery , bleh .
pours smooth and deep , with a nice creamy off-white head . great appearance , large dark oily brown head .  the mouthfeel is way thin , but drinkability is ok .

wonderful aroma . really brilliantly done . moderate in strength , but fascinating . t : wonderful apricot fruit esters perfectly complement the wheat foundation .  the mouthfeel is disappointing with absolutely no carbonation and mild flavors lingering around . overall , i could have possibly gotten a flat beer but this beer had potential ( when carbonated ) but it didnt come through in my bottle .

750ml corked bottle poured into a tulip glass . ( a ) - pours a hazy golden yellow color that produced a huge 2+finger fluffy white head with fantastic retention . it is sticking to the glass in webs as it dissipated .  the first thing i notice with this beer is the watery mouthfeel . the mouthfeel is terrible .

a : pours a cloudy orange color with good frothy white head , good lacing down the glass s : smell is awesome , smells fruity ( apple/pear ) , good spiciness in there as well . m : light to medium bodied , dry finish d : very refreshing , complex smelling and tasting beer .  maybe a little dusty , but i probably dislike the low carbonation & tackiness more . my tongue feels like i just drank a pot of black tea .

light beige head is 1/4 inch on the pour but recedes to a thin cap . big gobs of sticky lace are solid down the sides of the glass .  very little mouthfeel , this beer is meant to be drank ice cold as implied with the cold indicator on the can unlike most beers that i drink .

i do not really know who hiroyuki fujiwara is , except that he is an illustrator , makes these limited editions out of hitachino , and everyone seems to think he is the coolest guy . yellow opaque pure white head .  smells and tastes bland and grain like . almost stale . it is a good beer to party with if all your doin is playin beer pong or circle .

appearance : pale caramel color with an amber tint . smaller off-white head never fully dissipates and leaves behind thick foamy lace as you drink it .  very sweet flavour , largely the same elements as in the aroma , but far too sugary and overwhelmingly sweet for me .
appearance : deep , dark , and black . decent lacing left on my snifter .  the body is kind of thin , and there 's too much carbonation , which brings the drinkability down a fair bit .
pours a vibrant and dark golden orange . totally clear with a slightly off white head that is sticky and thick .  mouthfeel is very , very light -- it goes down like nothing at all .

smooth melted creamy chocolate with tart raspberry , kissed with dark fruits ; plums , prunes and blackberries .  mouthfeel : this is where the beer went south for me . the carbonation was almost non-existent , which was in stark contrast to the initial appearance .

sadly , this is another short 's beer that is a huge let down ... a medium copper pour with tons of head . great retention , nice lava stack on the top ... aroma is super disappointing , light with only a whisp of sweetness coming through .  the mouthfeel is poor . it seems to lack enough carbonation .

big whiffs of tangerines , honeydew melons , bubble gum , concentrated pineapple juice , honeyed graham crackers , and lesser notions of iron-rich blood , spicy tomato juice , and grapes- via a lightly woody and vaguely oxided sense of madeira . for as varied and intriguing as the nose is , the taste is fairly straitforward and unnuanced .  m - light bodied , very thin feeling , and very little carbonation o - not too impressed with this beer .

a - tons of carbonation streams up from the nucleation point to a puffy off-white head of almost three-fingers . good retention and clumpy lace above a totally clear golden yellow beer .  t- vanilla/cream soda , one-dimensional caramel malt . very vanilla . m- mouth is unrefined and rough in the way i would expect from good ol bmc . sweetness lingers in an unpleasant and sticky way .
great looking beer !  i will admit that i did not like the mouthfeel very much . too bubbly .

a : very dark brown color that does n't allow you to see through .  the smell reminds me of anchor liberty ale , only slightly less pungent . watery body , with some caramel notes . theres a citrus hop flavor in there too , but there is also a tannic `` spent hops '' flavor which is not so good . it lacks some bitterness too .
simply great to look at .  it 's low in carbonation and a little thin and watery , which is a real shame .
appearance : pours a black color with a huge light tan head .  m : thin and watery , very little carbonation , too thin to be cloying , but i 'd rather this beer be full bodied .

aroma is rich : sweet chocolate , vanilla , with strong whiskey notes . overall a decent beer , but somewhat a let down .  perhaps age will remedy.. m : explosive mouthfeel upon drinking , but the body is very light , with the alcohol evident .

into a large tulip glass , there 's an instant dispersion of foam billowing in the glass , even with the slightest trickle from the bottle . swirling the glass whips it into a pruneish tan meringue . like a cumulonimbus cloud , the foam defies gravity and pushes above the rim , forming irregular peaks and crags . it coats the glass like suds from a bubble bath , sticking in fluffy 3-dimensional shapes all around the edges .  mouthfeel was stingy and watery .

they share the same appearance if poured into the same glass , and the head is excellent . the taste is almost identical , with the can version being perhaps a little more bitter . i think these nitro cans are a great invention .  the taste was simple and good , but part of me thinks it was overshadowed by the dominant carbonation .

pours a rich black midnight color with a soft tan head and lacing . moderate viscosity . good head retention and lacing through out the tasting .  mouthfeel - this is where this one lets me down . feels very thin for a porter , very watery .

a brown top with long legs to match . awesome . a beer that is overpowered and buttered with palo santo wood is one that attacks the palette . not a fan of the hints of sweetness here either . mouthfeel was average , but feeling over carbonated for this suite of flavors .  the taste is cloyingly sweet , viscous , the aromas transfer , and turn very bready on the finish , the middle has cherries candies , almost medicinal the mouth feel is vaguely reminiscent of cough syrup , but watered down . there is no bitterness and even less carbonation .

brownish black pour , good head . pretty beer .  m : dammit , i hate porters like this . light , watery body , slightly oily , and slick on the palate . this would have been so much better with more body to it .
nice white , foamy head with great retention .  medium body . nearly flat .

phenomenal appearance - golden with just a little haze and a large , lacey , and well-retained white head .  mouthfeel is lacking as was expected . all in all this one is a step above the macro light brews .

huge four fingers of bright white , soapy head .  i feel like i have now experienced the true port/lost abbey experience , this is the first one i 've had that is flat ... a : pours dark brown with caramel highlights , zero head even after stiff pour , some clarity s : nose is predominantly oak and vanilla , some char quality in there , stout base takes a back seat t : vanilla and bourbon again dominate , some ashy character in there along with light notes of leather and tobacco , a bit of of boozieness on the finish mf : low carbonation is an understatement , medium body o : good flavors here , the lack of carbonation takes away from the quality a bit , for the premium price tag , i would expect carbonation .

it pours a pretty red color , crystal clear , slightly malty nose & it has a smooth taste .  taste : decidedly like its nose , only more so ; large notes of bittersweet chocolate and espresso rule the roost , here ; not nearly as sweet as you might imagine ; total lack of carbonation left the impression of a somewhat light , thin mouthfeel .

poured into a new belgium snifter a - a beautiful clear dusk sunset color , 2 finger head that lingered and lacing through and through and awesome tiny bubbles for days s - pine , citrus , malt , floral , cotton , sweet , grains and maybe a bit toasty t - very nice bitter sweet , pine , orange , melon , pineapple , very hoppy and yet super bitter sweet malty m - coats the mouth a bit with some super bitter sweet lingering .  the herbal hops will become medicinal with traces of alluminum and will become a bit less appealing as it goes from a zippy feel to rather stagnent . a flat and bitter hop flavor is the finish .

looks great on a goblet . amazing retention and lacing .  high carbonation and a continental hop aroma mixed with corn . light , watery body with a vegtable-grainy taste . dry , crisp finish . strictly unsatisfying .
opaquely dark with a thick , creamy , fluffy mocha-shaded head . a very luxurious beer , whether it 's really a stout or not .  mouthfeel is thin , almost no carbonation .
enjoyed from snifters and beer a gift from the brewer himself ... ap : deep dark body , roasted brown head , awesome retention .  the mouthfeel is watery with medium carbonation .
a- pale translucent body with thick white head . great head retention . leaves behind plenty of lacing .  very , very foamy in the mouth .
nitro-can encouraged frothy tan head , superb retention , some lace , almost opaque hue .  it is very thin like any us macro , making it very drinkable like water .
pours a beautiful clear golden orange with a plentiful fluffy head and excellent sticky lacing .  mouthfeel : bad , fizzy foamy body , hot finish drinkability : meh
a - moderately vigorous pour yields an over the top , dense , styrofoam khaki-colored head . decent sticky legs , too . impressive !  mouthfeel is very thin and weak .
dark brown color with a smooth , silky , creamy , long lasting head of white foam .  the carbonation sort of ruins the mouthfeel from the can and hides the taste .

the aroma is very deep -- anise , fennel , mocha , coffee and a burning alcohol nose -- awesome . really a marvel . strange .  mouthfeel was light in body and watery in texture with a flat carbonation .

visually stunning with a clear red-amber hue , plentiful off-white head and lace , and carbonation bubbles that seem to be in slow motion as they rise to the surface .  the mouthfeel is this beer 's weakest point . also , it feels a bit heavy on the palate and is almost syrupy .

22 oz bomber poured into a pint glass a- hazy orange with a fluffy three finger head s- not as strong of a smell as i would like it to be , some malts and very little hop aroma for a 100 ibu double .  mouthfeel is very thin and overly carbonated .

almost black with a cream colored head measuring maybe one finger . i love pouring it out of the gan into a pint glass and watching it mix and cascade turning from the color of mud to the color of .  mouthfeel : thin and watery ( or slim-bodied , which sounds more positive ) , medium-low carbonation ( too low for the style ) .

11.2 oz , 2007 bottle a : deep brown , not quite black under a nice sized tan head . excellent lace and retention .  mouthfeel this one was clumsy and , worst of all , lacked the fluffy character of a good hefe weizen .

pours a cloudy amber brown into a wine glass with two fingers worth of frothy , white head . the lacing clings to the inside of the glass for dear life , and is quite exquisite .  on top of that , the beer tasted a bit flat and felt thin .

impressive thick , dark brown , almost red head . intimidating looking , with an enormous presence in the glass . fantastic appearance .  the taste is similar , just a little sweeter , with more wateriness and less hops . i could n't get over how watery this beer tasted and felt . maybe i 'm rating it a little low because of that , but it has a lot of strikes against it : watery , bland , and definitely not a bargain .

outstanding retention and lace , strong carbonation . looks beautiful in the glass and the lace is breathtaking , but the flavor just falls short of expectations .  the flavor is closer to my expectations , but the body is way too light for an oatmeal stout -- there 's no chew . the carbonation , which is on the high side , does n't help .

this beer looks perfect . pretty gold color , with a nice big fluffy head .  mouthfeel : the carbonation is very high , way too high , for a milk stout . the body is thin . drinkability : just an ok beer , the mouthfeel also hurts the drinkability .

bottle poured into a dogfish head signature glass it pours clear copper color . a fluffy eggshell white head is very long lasting and intricate lacing across the glass .  mouthfeel - super watery overall - the only thing this beer has going for it is the aroma which is misleading .

bottle opened with a nice hiss and poured a solid black with a smallish tan/brown head that lasted forever .  i really like a strong flavor from my beer ... or food for that matter m : watery . with the cloudy , opaque look of this stuff i was expecting ( and hoping for ) a little creamier or more substantial mouthfeel .
if this beer is to live up to its awesome appearance ( and awesome name ) , it needs to be much more robust in all departments , especially mouthfeel .  dissapointing , watery mouthfeel .

a thick , delightful malt smell dominates the nose , with elements that are clearly fruity ( but not acidic ) shining noticeably through . this smell perfectly prepares the drinker for a sweet , although not cloying , wave of maltiness which has very pronounced toffee , caramel , and bread-like flavors .  m : this was the most dissapointing . aside from the lingering dry finish this was a very thin porter .
on-tap at tustin a : the beer pours a clear amber color with a frothy off-white head . excellent lacing all the way down the glass .  the mouthfeel was a bit thin and watery .
looks great , but that does n't translate to mind blowing .  empty , chalky mouthfeel , not much going on here .

excellent . t- sharp hop bitterness with a floral blanket overall . slightly sticky d- smooth , smells great and tasts great .  mouthfeel is overly fizzy , making an already light beer even fluffier . overall , this is an interesting beer that could be very refreshing if less carbonated .

a : solid black body topped with three full fingers of rich , dense , medium-brown head that just barely poke above the rim of the glass ; incredibly persistent retention and a practically solid sheet of lacing .  mouthfeel is thin .
appearance : pours a crystal clear dark orange color with a huge 3 '' + fluffy head that lasts a long time .  m : watery , very light-bodied , body of a light lager .

a - nice slightly tan head that could have better retention , but leaves excellent lacing . beer is a deep reddish brown color . looks great .  mf : too smooth and wet . watery even , but not creamy .

poured into a stemmed tulip : finger of foamy , smooth , beige head over a russet body with some nice , maroon highlights . visibly nucleation , lots of tiny bubbles . leaves some nice bars of lacing .  the carbonation and the bitterness overpower the toasty flavors .
( a great place ) poured a wonderfully rich yellow color . it was cloudy with a half inch of creamy white head . nice lacing with this beer .  mouthfeel is very thin , again very soda like .

appearance : creamy froth deep dark brown , nearly ebony color smell : deep dark roasted coffee and subtle dark chocolate and some nice cinnamon spice aroma taste : a heavy dose of black coffee , zero alcohol burn , lacked power though , you have to like coffee to liek this beer . mouthfeel : light bodied for a stout drinkability : a solid stout and interesting pumpkin pie aspect  mouthfeel is painfully carbonated . light bodied , way way to much carbonation .

s= huge spices like a fruitcake , or maybe like a spiced vanilla tea . the lovely scents simply do n't follow through in the taste .  it 's piercing , almost . the nose lands itself squarely on the tongue , unadulterated . what you are left with is a diminished , pale , watery finish . this , fortunately , leads to high quaffability .

a-pours a really attractive hazed-out , bright orange with a firm and lasting two inch , bone white head that brought about nice sticky ribbons of lace .  the flavor was both too light and 'way too bitter for a pils . it was watery and lacking in aroma . not much foam - what there was disappeared quickly . the word i 'd use to describe this beer is `` insubstantial . ''
this beer pours with a lot of carbonation - almost too much - an absolutely massive head barreling over the top of the glass a la snow-cone .  mouthfeel was very light bodied and again , watery .

served at a few degrees below fridge tempeature in a tulip glass . the color is a gleaming orange , and the lacing is setting up with unbelievable sticky cling . superb ! smell- a bold metallic smell booms out from the glass , incredibly phenolic and overpowering the malts and hops .  m surprisingly watery for the body ; slightly carbonated with a light , watery finish . my major complaint is with the mouthfeel , the watery texture really detracts from its drinkability in my book .
poured a deep thick black with a nice dark tan head that dissipated quickly .  flavor is good and somewhat spicy , but fades too quickly because body is too thin and watery .
black as the abyss with a dark sticky head .  high gravity beer , this one is king . drink alot of water when drinking or a major headache occurs . so drink with caution .
s - nice aroma . some sweet vanilla and oak notes are punctuated by earthy and herbal hop .  mouthfeel is way watery and i feel like it is slightly udnercarbonated .

reviewed 11/1/2009 ( bottle coded 8899 ) : pours a clear brown color body , with a big tan foamy head , very lasting .  m : very overly carbonated to the point where it was difficult to drink early on , mild acidity , medium-bodied .

the aroma is filled with dried dark fruits , apricots , honey , and wheat toast . overall a good beer , that will become a great beer over time .  the mouth is super thin . the thinnest mouth i 've ever had on an ipa . d= the thin mouth makes me go for sips more often and the flavor does n't linger long ... great flavor on this one no doubt .

very little head to speak of , thin collar of dense white bubbles s : deep notes of dark chocolate , carob , molasses , and a hint of coffee . the flavors are very mellow but well integrated . t : the taste does n't translate into being as good as the smell suggested , the smooth chocolate is there , but turns into a slightly sharp flavor by mid palate and has a slightly metallic finish .  i 'm no fan of bud , and probably have n't had a bmc beer in 2 years , but this is not one of the worst 50 beers in the world . it 's far better than many of the cheap , crappy pale lagers in many parts of the world . although it had little taste to speak of , it was exceedingly easy to drink , which , for bmc swill , ai n't that terrible .
the aroma is of chocolate milk , or maybe the chocolate chips used for cookies .  one thing about this beer is it feels extremely watery .
really delicious . 5 t : malty chocolate with some tangy fruit character from the blueberry .  m - weak and thin . lifeless .

marzen-fest 2010 continues with a 12 oz into a pint a - pours a very clear , almost perfectly brown color . head formation is strong , frothy , egg shell white .  the body was water and medium light .

while i 'm sure this beer is a fine representation of the belgian sour , i have to say i could barely drink it . in my purely subjective estimation , it was just far too sour for me to enjoy . in a blind taste test , i would have said this was champagne , not beer -- and i hate champagne . obviously , there must be something to this beer to garner all the great reviews it has from people more knowledgeable than myself .  watery mouthfeel .
refreshingly bright . taste : hoppy and full of citrus . not quite as balanced as the smell but it 's just as refreshing . the malts definitely bring some yang to the hops yin .  watery mouthfeel .

the nose had a very fresh floral hop aroma .  i must admit i was suprised to see this new offering from coopers as i have never heard of it , it pours a pale golden see thru champagne colour with a nice frothy one finger head , sparkling carbonation and bubbly clingy lacing , it has a green , grassy hop aroma with a malty background , it has a thin mouthfeel even thinner for the style for my liking and the taste isnt as pleasant as it looks it has tastes of watery hops with a feint grainish aftertaste not as great as i was hoping for but definately better than the other macro swill out there .
smells amazing . the pine and citra form a wave of hoppy goodness .  2.5 m thin , with only the grain tastes and the slightest stickiness keeping it from being water itself .
a - deep cherry red with a pretty pink head that left a really nice lacing .  m : a very thin and watery beer .
gorgeous dark burgendy like ribena syrup . redy brown highlights , good head retention but minimal lace .  almost no body present .

poured into a 20oz pint glass has a hazy , cloudy straw colored body with a thick , just-off white head that leaves beautiful lacing .  the flavor echoes the aroma , but the mouthfeel is n't quite up to scratch - weirdly thin and watery , which does no favors to the toasty , nutty , tea-like , and hoppy notes that are all individually assertive but harmonious and balanced in tandem , like a good jazz band .

pours out to a lightly hazy light orange-amber ( not bottle conditioned ) , forming a tall & whipped off-white head with very good retention and lacing .  the body is very thin -- like there was a lot of adjuncts added .

a : huge three finger head , constant carbonation , brown oil color .  better than expected , but as someone who despises ab products + light beer i was n't expecting much trouble is , within the same can it tasted like lemonade in some sips , water in others . giving it a 4 on drinkability because it 's light , so one could drink a lot of these if they chose to .

that settles into a nice thick lace covering most of the glass yes it 's a chocolate stout and the aromas defiantly back it up lots of sweet chocolate aromas some earthiness to it along with some hint of roasted malts flavor 's of dark chocolate are dominate not overly sweet with a coffee backbone it 's got this mocha thing going on the mouthfeel is medium to thin would have liked it a little thicker this is really one of the great chocolate stout 's especially for under $ 5 a bomber well worth the experience  mf- watery and too light bodied for a red ale . mouthfeel lacking .

bottle poured into my darkness glass ... a dark brown , just not yet turned black . a nice big creamy mocha head of at least three fingers , good retention and great lacing .  mouthfeel is very thin with low carbonation , almost watery , drinkability is poor , huge bitterness and watery mouthfeel is a disappointment .
pours beautiful dark brown with red edges , almost black with a huge tan head that sticks around and leaves walls of creamy lace .  carbonation is way too high .
pours an opaque thick looking black , with a fat beige head . very attractive .  it 's drinkable , but the body and carbonation are really lacking .

the brew pours a slightly darker golden color with a huge , creamy , rocky white head that sticks around for a while .  really fizzy ( like coca-cola fizzy ) on the tongue , with a metallic finish , not really what i was hoping for , dissapointing .
